<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxing Federation Is Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- One of boxing's three major sanctioning  
organizations is being investigated by a federal grand jury 
examining whether it sold rankings and arranged fights in return 
for kickbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Lee, president of the International Boxing Federation,  
denied the allegations Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The more than yearlong probe by the U.S. attorney's office in  
Newark focuses on the IBF and has so far led to subpoenas demanding 
financial records from promoters, a source familiar with the 
investigation told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The payments were made by fighter managers, sometimes disguised  
as consulting fees, to promoters and sanctioning groups, according 
to unnamed sources cited by The Star-Ledger of Newark, which 
disclosed the investigation in Thursday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors in the U.S. attorney's office, citing Justice  
Department policy, declined to confirm or deny the existence of 
such an investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The IBF, based in nearby East Orange, also came under scrutiny  
this week from law enforcement agencies in New York following the 
controversial draw in the March 13 heavyweight championship bout 
between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis. Of the three judges, 
only the IBF-picked judge had Holyfield winning the fight many 
believed Lewis dominated. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctioning groups -- the IBF, World Boxing Association and  
World Boxing Council -- by their rules and rankings, play a large 
role in determining whom a boxer fights. Boxers who defy the groups 
risk losing the chance to be declared a champion and earn large 
purses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've done nothing improper. And we'll let the facts be  
brought out by the committee investigating and we'll respond to 
them,'' Lee said Thursday. He said he had not been called to 
testify before the grand jury, but declined extensive comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee had told The Star-Ledger, however, that the grand jury has  
begun calling witnesses. The probe was aimed at ``investigating 
mostly boxing overall'' and how the IBF ``approves fights and ranks 
fighters,'' he told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was no secret to the boxing world, said lawyer  
Patrick English, who regularly represents boxing promoter Dino Duva 
and his Main Events company in northern New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a big thing for a while,'' English said  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit he filed against the IBF in 1996 on behalf of one-time  
heavyweight champion Michael Moorer raised similar corruption 
allegations. It was settled for an undisclosed sum. 
</P>
<P>
	English said neither he nor his clients have been subpoenaed and  
is unsure if his lawsuit sparked the federal inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would think so, but I don't know. I don't think this is the  
only complaint they ever got,'' English said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee is a former New Jersey boxing commissioner removed from  
office in 1985 after a state panel ruled he violated ethics 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The current commissioner, Larry Hazzard Sr., said the state  
Athletic Control Board has no authority over sanctioning 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	It does regulate boxing promoters, however, and Hazzard said  
that if a promoter told him that he was being shaken down by a 
sanctioning body, Hazzard would report that to law officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the way, no one has ever come to me with a complaint like  
that,'' Hazzard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
