<DOCNO> APW19990318.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 11:22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Albanians Sign Deal, Serbs Refuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The ethnic Albanian delegation at the Kosovo peace  
talks unilaterally signed a U.S.-sponsored peace accord today. But 
the Serbs still refused to sign the deal, and the talks appeared 
headed toward collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo Albanian delegation said it was leaving after the  
signing with some members heading to Brussels, Belgium, site of 
NATO's headquarters, some to Washington and others to Kosovo, where 
Yugoslav forces were massing and NATO has threatened airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	It remained unclear whether this second round of talks would be  
suspended or ended completely. There were signs the Serbs would be 
given a few days to consider their position. 
</P>
<P>
	``The agreement is there now,'' chief talks spokesman Phil  
Reeker told The Associated Press. ``We are waiting for the Serbs to 
do the same thing, to take a step for peace and a future for 
Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first round ended inconclusively in Rambouillet, France,  
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The co-chairs of the talks, French Foreign Minister Hubert  
Vedrine and his British counterpart, Robin Cook, are to be briefed 
by mediators later today, France's Foreign Ministry said. Then they 
will report to the rest of the six-nation Contact Group that is 
sponsoring the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision on the future of the peace conference was expected  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting has claimed more than 2,000 lives in the past year in  
Kosovo, a province of Serbia and the dominant of two remaining 
republics comprising Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Tens of thousands of people have fled their homes amid renewed  
fighting in recent weeks. About 90 percent of Kosovo's 2.2 million 
people are ethnic Albanians, and most favor independence. 
</P>
<P>
	In a low-key ceremony, the ethnic Albanians inked the accord at  
the Paris conference center near the Arc de Triomphe where the 
talks have been held. It was also signed by two of the three 
mediators -- Christopher Hill of the United States and Wolfgang 
Petritsch of Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Russian mediator, Boris Mayorsky, did not sign. Russia  
is an ally of Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic, although today 
the Russian foreign minister urged Milosevic to give in and sign 
the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs have said a unilateral signing is meaningless.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in a phone  
call to the ethnic Albanians, praised their decision to sign and 
asked that they ``stay unified,'' said State Department spokesman 
James P. Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	``The signing by the Kosovo Albanians in the face of continued  
Serb intransigence makes it clear that nothing more can be done 
here,'' Rubin told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Serbs are refusing to make a decision for peace. There are  
consequences to that situation that NATO officials have spoken 
of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin was referring to the threat of NATO strikes at Serbian  
targets -- a threat that so far has failed to spur Milosevic into 
accepting a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs adamantly refuse to allow a NATO-led force into Kosovo  
to police an accord, a key element of the peace plan that mediators 
insist is inseparable from the political part. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few days, the Serbs also have raised objections to  
the political part, which sets the terms for broad autonomy that 
would be granted to the ethnic Albanians but keeps Kosovo within 
Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo Albanians finally agreed to sign the deal earlier  
this week, although it denies them the independence they seek. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's official news agency, Tanjug, assailed the Paris  
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been no real talks or dialogue in Paris, just  
threats and pressure,'' the agency said. It said the signing by the 
ethnic Albanians alone is meaningless ``because there is no 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, NATO's commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, arrived today in  
Macedonia to visit the alliance's fast-growing contingent of 
troops. The peace proposal calls for enforcement by 28,000 NATO 
troops --including 4,000 from the United States. About 12,000 troops 
have been assembled in Macedonia so far this month. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Wednesday that Milosevic also should realize NATO is  
ready to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon's top military commanders warned during Senate  
hearings today that NATO airstrikes could bring heavy U.S. 
casualties because Yugoslav air defenses are sophisticated and dug 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a distinct possibility we will lose aircraft in  
trying to penetrate those defenses,'' said Gen. Michael Ryan, the 
Air Force chief of staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
