<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Eyes Endangered Carcass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Smithsonian Institution was happy to  
accept $20 million from former NFL team owner Kenneth E. Behring 
and would like to take a more controversial gift from him as well -- 
the remains of one of the world's most endangered animals. 
</P>
<P>
	Smithsonian scientists have asked for a waiver to the Endangered  
Species Act to import the carcass of a bighorn sheep that Behring 
shot on a 1997 big game hunting trip in the former Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's premier public museum complex is thus doing a favor  
for its leading donor by lending his trophy hunting the legitimacy 
of scientific research, the Humane Society of the United States 
charged Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The sheep, known as the Kara-Tau argali, would be added to the  
120 million specimens in the Smithsonian's National Museum of 
Natural History. Behring's $20 million donation will go in large 
part to renovate that museum, and its main mammal exhibit hall will 
be renamed in his honor this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Natural History Museum is giving this guy a credible  
defense for an activity that is repugnant and counter to any 
sensible principle of conservation,'' Humane Society vice president 
Wayne Pacelle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just nonsense,'' countered Robert W. Fri, director of  
the Natural History Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sheep is a very rare creature, and is therefore very rare  
in museum collections,'' Fri said. ``Museums are in the scientific 
business of maintaining life on Earth,'' and will seek rare items 
when they properly can, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about 100 of the Kara-Tau animals remain in the wild,  
Russian scientists estimate. Behring noted in a statement issued 
through a spokesman that Russian scientists accompanied his hunting 
party to do field research on the animal and that he had a valid 
hunting permit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was certainly not encouraged by any museum to hunt them or  
offer them the specimens or donate the specimens to any museum,'' 
Behring said. 
</P>
<P>
	But while it was legal to kill the sheep, Behring could not get  
the creature into the country without the Smithsonian's help, 
Pacelle charged. 
</P>
<P>
	A few weeks after the hunting trip, the Smithsonian announced  
the $20 million gift from Behring, former owner of the Seattle 
Seahawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no connection,'' Fri said. He denied the museum is  
doing Behring any favors, and said Behring has not asked for any 
special treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Humane Society maintains that Behring is using the  
museum to burnish his image as an accomplished game hunter. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's even more prestigious for him to have this trophy  
exhibited in the Smithsonian's hall, with that hall named after 
him, than to have it in his personal collection in his home,'' 
Pacelle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Museum spokesman Randall Kremer said the animal would only be  
used for research and would not be displayed for the public at all. 
Visitors to the renamed hall will have no idea that Behring gave 
the Kara-Tau or any other specimen to the museum, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fri said that to avoid an appearance of impropriety, he  
stipulated at the time of the donation in November 1997 that the 
museum not accept any specimens from Behring ``that were alive as 
of November'' of that year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kara-Tau and other animals shot on the same trip were  
already dead. 
</P>
<P>
	At the moment, the argument over the Kara-Tau is academic  
because the carcass is in limbo in a Canadian taxidermy shop. The 
Fish and Wildlife Service has not granted the Smithsonian's 
request, in part because it requested additional documentation from 
the animal's native Kazakstan. 
</P>
<P>
	Kremer said the museum is trying to get the requested material.  
</P>
<P>
	If the Smithsonian does not want the sheep and other animals, or  
cannot win the necessary waiver, Behring plans to donate the 
animals to a Spanish museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:45:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Approves Reform Platform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Despite pressure for independent  
oversight, the International Olympics Committee president said he 
will control the reform process himself -- drawing a stinging attack 
from a powerful U.S. critic. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after the unprecedented expulsion of six members in the  
Salt Lake City bribery scandal, the IOC on Thursday approved a 
change in the selection process for the 2006 Winter Games and 
created special commissions to police its members and reform 
itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``The steps that we have taken send a very clear message -- we  
are doing what we promised,'' IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch 
said. ``We promised to clean the house. We did it. We promised 
reforms. We did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was not convinced.  
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC's actions today fall short of the reforms needed to  
bring transparency and accountability to the organization,'' McCain 
said. ``Nothing I have witnessed provides any substantive movement 
in that direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although critics blame the 78-year-old Spaniard for the  
atmosphere that produced the million-dollar gift-giving scandal 
stemming from the selection of Salt Lake for the 2002 Winter Games, 
Samaranch said he would be the chairman and pick the participants 
for the major reform vehicle -- IOC 2000, with a mandate to change 
the committee for the next millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the president of the IOC,'' Samaranch said at a news  
conference. ``This commission must be presided by the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said it was ``worrisome at best'' that Samaranch would  
hand-pick the members. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the reform process lacks credibility, then the entire  
future of the Olympic movement will be in jeopardy,'' he said in a 
statement issued in Washington. ``If the purpose of the new panel 
is to truly restore the integrity of the organization, it must be 
completely independent, and its recommendations must be binding. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is true of any initiative for reform anywhere in the  
world,'' he said. ``The integrity of the Olympic movement is at 
stake. We must see meaningful reforms now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain will open Senate hearings April 14 on the Olympic  
scandal. Senators are proposing legislation to strip the IOC of its 
tax-exempt status, limit sponsors' tax deductions and reroute U.S. 
TV rights money to the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC gave a more positive assessment of the IOC's resolve.  
</P>
<P>
	``They have done what they said they were going to do,'' USOC  
president Bill Hybl said. 
</P>
<P>
	Added USOC executive director Dick Schultz: ``I think it's  
another step along the road to recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC launched the reforms to appease Olympics sponsors, and  
their first reactions were positive. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's Corp. called the IOC's proposals ``a step in the  
right direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have very high expectations that these problems will be  
resolved,'' David Green, a senior vice president for international 
marketing at McDonald's, said in a statement. He said McDonald's 
would like to see the focus shift back to ``the true spirit of the 
games as personified by the hard work and commitment of the 
athletes and the international competition itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-based United Parcel Service, a sponsor since 1994, felt  
the IOC's actions showed ``there is a clear intent on the part of 
the IOC to change itself,'' spokeswoman Susan Rosenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our expectations are met for this meeting. We didn't think  
they would come out of this meeting with a blueprint'' of all the 
changes they planned to make, she said. ``I think it's a start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said he would appoint members of the reform panel by  
the end of the month. The committee will be composed of 20-24 
members, half from the IOC and half from outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the group will study radical reforms to the  
structure and running of the IOC, including the possibility of 
elections, term limits and age restrictions for members. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the panel would include ``eminent personalities'' with  
knowledge of sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has already announced that Giovanni Agnelli, head of  
the Fiat auto empire, has agreed to serve on the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel will submit a preliminary report at the next IOC  
general assembly in June in Seoul, South Korea. The commission 
would present its final recommendations at another extraordinary 
IOC session in December or early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said he will also appoint the members of a so-called  
``independent'' ethics commission, which will enforce a 
code-of-conduct for IOC delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	This panel will have eight members, a majority from outside the  
committee. IOC executive board member Kevan Gosper, a major 
proponent of the ethics panel, said IOC vice president Keba Mbaye 
will be the chairman and that Swiss IOC member Denis Oswald will be 
among the members. 
</P>
<P>
	After months of fending off calls from outside the IOC for his  
resignation, Samaranch was emboldened by Wednesday's overwhelming 
vote of confidence from the membership. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said he was surprised at the extent of the support --  
86 votes in favor and only two against. He said he had expected up 
to 15 ``no'' votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the margin was even greater than when he was  
elected IOC president on the first ballot in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the vote will push me to work harder so that the IOC  
will recover the prestige we had a few weeks ago very, very soon,'' 
he said. ``It gives me a great responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said he plans to serve out the rest of his term until  
2001, but again left open the possibility of an early departure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what can happen in the future,'' he said. ``After  
the vote of confidence, my proposal is to go until the end of my 
mandate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch said the Sydney Games in 2000 ``will make the world  
see that what has happened in the last few months was only an 
incident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The world needs the Olympics Games,'' he said. ``It is the  
most important event in the world, not just in sports. The youth of 
the world deserve the Olympic Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the 2006 games, the IOC approved a plan to have the host  
chosen from two finalists decided by a 15-member selection panel. 
The IOC members will retain their final vote, however. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is designed only for the selection of the 2006 site,  
which concludes June 19 in Seoul. But the IOC has promised 
permanent changes after more review. 
</P>
<P>
	The change is not as radical as what was first proposed --  
stripping of the vote from the general membership. That plan 
produced an uproar from delegates who said they were being punished 
for the corrupt acts of a few colleagues. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Macho' Roles Lead Best Actor Nods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A clownish death camp victim, an infantry  
captain, a director of horror films, an alcoholic cop, an American 
neo-Nazi -- these diverse roles have brought five accomplished 
actors, one Italian, one English, three American, to consideration 
as the best film actor of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them will stand on the stage of the Los Angeles Music  
Center March 21 and receive the Academy Award, the movie world's 
highest prize. For four of them, it's the first time. If the award 
goes to the fifth, Tom Hanks, he will have scored a rare triple, 
having won for ``Philadelphia'' in 1993 and ``Forrest Gump'' in 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The varied roles of the best-actor nominees might seem to  
indicate a trend away from the macho heroics that epitomize 
mainstream movie fare in the 1990s. Alas, no. With the exception of 
Tom Hanks and ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the nominees appeared in 
``special'' films. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Benigni is in ``Life Is Beautiful,'' a foreign-language  
movie; the other three performances are in what could be considered 
art films -- small-budget projects dealing with racism, 
homosexuality and alcoholism, and destined for select audiences. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at the nominees:  

</P>
<P>
              	 *ROBERTO BENIGNI, ``Life Is Beautiful''    	
</P>
<P>
	As Charlie Chaplin did with ``The Great Dictator'' in 1940,  
Benigni chose to depict Nazism with comedy. While Chaplin applied 
ridicule to Hitler and Mussolini, Benigni showed invented moments 
against the horrific backdrop of a German concentration camp. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a daring feat to portray an Italian Jew using humor to  
shield his young son from the Holocaust trauma. Benigni drew 
criticism, but audiences were moved by the poignancy of the 
father's act. ``Life Is Beautiful'' became an international hit, 
especially in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Benigni appears in public as exuberant as he is on the screen.  
Before his film was premiered in Israel, he pranced about the stage 
and chirped, ``I kiss you on the mouth, everybody!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, he defended the film against critics who thought it  
trivialized the Holocaust: ``I felt in my mind I was sincere -- I am 
a man, and I know what is sorrow. This was the best I could do with 
my soul, my mind and my body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benigni's triple play -- nominations for writing, directing and  
acting in ``Life Is Beautiful'' -- has been accomplished three times 
in the past. Orson Welles did it with ``Citizen Kane'' in 1941, 
Woody Allen with ``Annie Hall'' in 1977 and Warren Beatty with 
``Reds'' in 1981. 

</P>
<P>
                	 *TOM HANKS, ``Saving Private Ryan''    	
</P>
<P>
	For his role as a captain leading a squad of GIs through German  
lines to rescue a soldier, Hanks could merely have shown up for the 
first day of filming. Instead, he chose to join other lead actors -- 
most of them a decade or more younger -- in a grueling six-day boot 
camp in which they camped on the ground, ate field rations, carried 
60-pound packs and slept three hours a night. 
</P>
<P>
	After the fourth day, the younger actors mutinied. Hanks, then  
41, argued them out of it. His perseverance contributed to his 
soldiers' respect for him as a leader, and as a superstar who 
required no special treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the heroics of Capt. Miller and his squad, Hanks viewed  
``Saving Private Ryan'' as an antiwar film: ``The first 25 minutes 
are set on Omaha Beach, and it's purely hell on Earth. By the time 
they start gunning down Germans trying to surrender, you honestly 
don't want to see anybody kill anybody again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Hanks wins, he will join an elite group of triple-winners:  
Ingrid Bergman, Walter Brennan and Jack Nicholson. Katharine 
Hepburn holds the record with four. 

</P>
<P>
                	 *IAN McKELLEN, ``Gods and Monsters''    	
</P>
<P>
	English-born James Whale brought distinction to the  
suspense/terror genre with his 1930s films, ``Frankenstein,'' ``The 
Old Dark House,'' ``The Invisible Man'' and ``The Bride of 
Frankenstein.'' He was adept at musicals and dramas as well, but 
retired in 1940 to devote himself to painting. In 1957, he drowned 
in his swimming pool in mysterious circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Lions Gate Films bought Christopher Bran's novel about Whale's  
later life, ``Gods and Monsters,'' which fictionalized a failed 
affair with a gardener (Brendan Fraser in the film) that led to the 
director's suicide. Sir Ian McKellen, one of England's great 
classic actors, was chosen to play Whale. 
</P>
<P>
	After learning of his nomination, McKellen remarked: ``When  
people give you a wonderful script, they say it has Oscar written 
all over it. By which they mean it's a good script, and you don't 
really believe a word more. But then when you start to get awards, 
you think, 'My dear, I wonder if I'm going to get nominated?' Now 
it's come true.'' 

</P>
<P>
                   	 *NICK NOLTE, ``Affliction''    	
</P>
<P>
	``It was a small ... $6 million budget picture to gather this  
much attention,'' commented Nolte after his nomination. ``One 
doesn't anticipate that. You make those kinds of films for the sake 
of making them. You can't really lose money on them, but it's just 
the love of filmmaking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Affliction,'' Nolte plays a small-town cop bedeviled by  
drink and an abusive father (James Coburn, nominee as supporting 
actor). It's the kind of small but challenging film Nolte has been 
seeking after 20 years as a high-voltage star. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going broke, compared to the lifestyle I was living,'' the  
actor has said. ``The biggest paydays I get now are $250,000, half 
a million. I used to make $6 or $7 million. But that was a terrible 
trap for me. I hated those experiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of those high-paid experiences, Barbra Streisand's ``The  
Prince of Tides,'' earned Nolte's first Academy nomination, for 
best actor of 1991. 

</P>
<P>
               	 *EDWARD NORTON, ``American History X''    	
</P>
<P>
	After a long search for an actor to play a murder suspect in  
``Primal Fear,'' the producers decided on an unknown, off-Broadway 
player, Edward Norton. His chilling performance in ``Primal Fear,'' 
his first movie, brought him an Academy nomination as supporting 
actor, and a Golden Globe. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the Brad Pitts and Leonardo DiCaprios, Yale  
University-educated Norton did not seek to cash in on his new fame. 
He played lesser roles in Woody Allen's musical ``Everyone Says I 
Love You'' and Milos Forman's ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``American History X'' continued his search for the offbeat. He  
plays a skinhead -- a tattooed American Nazi. 
</P>
<P>
	Norton has said his urge to act came from seeing a performance  
of ``Cinderella'' and Ian McKellen's one-man show, ``Acting 
Shakespeare.'' After the nominations were announced, McKellen 
commented: 
</P>
<P>
	``What's very encouraging is to see Edward Norton's nomination.  
He said to me I was the reason he became an actor. I hope I'm the 
reason he doesn't win an Oscar.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
