<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs Ulcer Drug for Horses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Horses get ulcers, too? It turns out they do --  
quite often and quite bad. The government is riding to the rescue, 
approving the top-selling human ulcer drug to help racehorses, farm 
horses, even foals. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug is called omeprazole, sold as Prilosec pills to humans.  
The equine version will be sold as GastroGard, a paste in a 
cinnamon flavor horses find yummy. 
</P>
<P>
	Its approval Thursday by the Food and Drug Administration  
provides the first treatment for horses with ulcers. 
</P>
<P>
	Only recently, in fact, did veterinarians discover the  
seriousness of equine ulcers -- thanks to new, 6-foot-long 
endoscopes that let them peer into a horse's stomach. They 
experimented with other human drugs, but found that a horse not 
only requires a lot of Pepto-Bismol, it didn't work very well. 
</P>
<P>
	So horse lovers are excited about GastroGard, which will begin  
selling, by prescription only, within a few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``These ulcers are very painful and impact the horse's  
performance, his overall health and well-being,'' said Bill White, 
a veteran trainer at Miami's Calder Race Course. ``It's a problem 
more prevalent than most people may think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why? Mostly because of the way horses' stomachs are designed.  
But stress is a major underlying factor, said the FDA's Dr. Linda 
Wilmot. That means racehorses and performance horses are at extra 
risk, and so are foals, who can experience stress from infant 
illnesses or weaning. 
</P>
<P>
	According to GastroGard manufacturer Merial Limited, up to 1.8  
million performance horses may have ulcers. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug ``should have a tremendous impact,'' Wilmot said.  
</P>
<P>
	Contrary to popular belief, stress does not cause human ulcers --  
a bacterium called H. pylori is the main culprit. People's ulcers 
are treated with antibiotics to kill the germs and anti-acid drugs 
such as Prilosec that shut down gastric acid production so the 
stomach has time to heal. 
</P>
<P>
	But H. pylori hasn't been found in horses. Instead, the top  
lining of horses' stomachs is particularly sensitive to acid 
because it's made of the same extra-delicate tissue of a human 
esophagus. Any person who's ever had heartburn, when acid rubs that 
sensitive esophagus skin, can empathize. 
</P>
<P>
	The horse developed as a grazing animal, and grass neutralizes  
the acid. But whenever horses stop eating, the stomach still 
produces acid that bubbles against that sensitive tissue, explained 
Dr. Michael Murray of Virginia Tech's Equine Medical Center in 
Leesburg, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Even barnyard Mr. Eds get ulcers. Unlike people, horses in  
stressful environments or places where they can't eat often -- like 
training sessions or travel -- have a higher risk. Symptoms include 
decreased appetite, colic, poor hair coat, poor body condition and 
decreased performance. In foals, symptoms also may include 
intermittent nursing. 
</P>
<P>
	A test of GastroGard in 300 horses found a once-a-day treatment  
for 28 days healed or reduced ulcers' severity in 99 percent of 
treated horses. Treatment costs about $40 a day. Because 
in-training horses often suffer recurrences, Merial recommends a 
``maintenance dose'' after the initial 28-day treatment until 
training ends. 
</P>
<P>
	Horses with ulcer symptoms should be checked by endoscopy, a  
process that requires sedating the animal for 15 to 30 minutes, 
Murray said. Not all veterinarians can do that, but the drug seemed 
to have no side effects so some may rely on symptoms alone to 
prescribe, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA did, however, warn the drug shouldn't be used by  
pregnant or lactating mares, because there's no proof it's safe for 
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
