<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. To Probe Starr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court cleared the path  
Thursday for the Justice Department to investigate the tactics of 
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr in the Monica Lewinsky case. 
</P>
<P>
	The special court that appoints independent counsels dismissed a  
challenge by Landmark Legal Foundation, a conservative group that 
sought to block the Justice Department from investigating Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge court said it would not intervene because ``we  
are without power to act on the Landmark petition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office contended that Landmark could not be injured by  
the investigation and therefore had no legal grounds to sustain a 
lawsuit. The Justice Department argued that the Ethics in 
Government Act did not give the court the power to intervene. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both are correct rationales,'' the court said. ``We have no  
jurisdiction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In order to sustain a case, the applicant must show ``a concrete  
and actual or imminent injury in fact,'' the court said. ``We find 
nothing in Landmark's motion that could even remotely be considered 
an injury to itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The court also said it could not go beyond the powers set out in  
the Ethics in Government Act or review the attorney general's 
actions involving an independent counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said in a statement that the ruling was consistent with  
the position of his office that ``third parties, regardless of the 
merits of their complaints, have no standing to challenge the 
attorney general's actions under the statute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This office fully accepts the court's resolutions of this  
issue,'' Starr added. 
</P>
<P>
	Landmark President Mark R. Levin brushed off the ruling, saying  
his group's primary goal in pursuing the litigation ``was to make 
public an issue that the Justice Department never wanted to see the 
light of day. Mission accomplished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said, ``We're pleased  
the court agreed with us that it did not have jurisdiction to 
review the attorney general's actions in this matter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The department is investigating allegations of irregularities by  
Starr's office, including the initial handling of information on 
the Monica Lewinsky matter; Starr's request to the department for 
jurisdiction to investigate Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with 
President Clinton; and Starr's conduct during the investigation, 
including the initial meetings between the counsel's office and Ms. 
Lewinsky in January 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	One issue is the offer by Starr's deputies to Ms. Lewinsky of an  
immunity deal conditioned on her not discussing it with her 
original lawyer, Frank Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department rules prohibit government prosecutors from  
discussing immunity deals with defendants outside the presence of 
their lawyers. Starr's office is required to follow these rules 
unless doing so would undermine the purpose of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr has denied any impropriety in his office's dealings with  
Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision comes at a time that several key lawyers are  
leaving Starr's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The opinion was handed down by U.S. Circuit Judge David Sentelle  
and senior appellate judges Peter Fay and Richard Cudahy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
