<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greeks Have Stock Market Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- If the breeze is right, the gamy smell  
from the open meat market wafts over the main doors of Athens' 
stock exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love it. It puts me in the mood: Blood and guts,'' sniffed  
Aris Makroyiannis, pausing for a moment at the market's crimson 
facade before racing to the gallery for a good seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with a calculator and binoculars, the 45-year-old shop  
owner is a new recruit in the army of investors laying siege to the 
exchange -- currently Europe's hottest trading floor and the world's 
No. 2 performer last year in terms of percentage increase. At about 
85 percent, it was only slightly behind South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Each business day, the small visitors section fills up. The  
cadre of private investors bite their nails, scribble on pads and 
peer through binoculars at the trading board and general index 
ticker, flanked by images of the goddess Athena and the sea king 
Poseidon. 
</P>
<P>
	Most often these days, investors end up counting their gains  
rather than moaning their losses. The exchange's general share 
index set another record Thursday -- its 21st ceiling-busting day 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is trying to cash in,'' stock broker Peter Spartalis  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greece's booming market has an odd blood line, born out of  
fiscal clutter. 
</P>
<P>
	Chronic inflation, crushing public debt and a host of other  
economic woes kept Greece from joining the first group of the 
European Union's single currency club. 
</P>
<P>
	But Premier Costas Simitis has so far managed to stay focused on  
the drive to meet EU standards and enter the euro group by 2001. 
Inflation has nose-dived. Interest rates have been cut. Plans have 
advanced to sell off money-losing state companies. A flurry of 
mergers and acquisitions are being discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	Greece, once the economic backwater of the EU, has earned  
applause from influential observers, including Moody's Investors 
Service. 
</P>
<P>
	And the stock market -- especially the banking sector -- sprang to  
life last year. 
</P>
<P>
	For investors, it's a prime chance to catch a ride on an EU  
economy apparently chugging toward the single currency zone. 
Similar bull markets occurred in Italy and Spain as they made their 
euro transformations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the feeding frenzy atmosphere is more pronounced in smaller  
and poorer Greece. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 1 million Greeks -- about one-tenth of the population --  
are believed to own shares. A decade ago, investing in the market 
was virtually unknown outside an elite circle. More than 100 
companies are awaiting regulatory approval to join the nearly 300 
listed firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see this market cooling off for a while,'' said  
Spartalis. 
</P>
<P>
	The optimism is so high that some people have taken out bank  
loans at 20 percent interest to buy stocks, according to media 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is sheer madness,'' warned an editorial in the respected  
Kathimerini newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Faith in the market can lead to foolish moves, analysts warn.  
Some small investors may throw their money at any company expecting 
sizable returns. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are many, many unsophisticated investors racing to get  
into this market,'' said Chris Elafros, an analyst at Telesis 
Securities in Athens. ``These people may not be as prudent and may 
unwittingly take some unwise risks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Greek stock market has been quite resilient on its upward  
climb. 
</P>
<P>
	It dipped by more than 7.5 percent in one day last month during  
the political upheaval following Turkey's arrest of Kurdish rebel 
leader Adbullah Ocalan, who had been secretly sheltered by Greek 
officials in Kenya. But the market regained almost all its losses 
the following day. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts predict the Greek stock market may eventually  
mature and take on an Italian character -- where political 
developments don't necessarily shake up investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would be positive,'' said Petros Katsoulas, an emerging  
market specialist at Credit Suisse First Boston in London. ``This 
market will go down and some investors will be scared ... It can't 
keep up like this forever. It's the law of physics.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
