<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diabetes Drug Debate Intensifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The number of liver-related deaths linked to  
the diabetes drug Rezulin is much greater than previously 
announced, the Los Angeles Times reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 155 Rezulin patients have died since the drug went on  
the market in March 1997, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert Co., the maker of the drug which helps control  
blood-sugar levels, disputed the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokesman Stephen Mock said there were 35 serious  
incidents since the introduction of Rezulin, including 28 deaths 
and seven patients who needed liver transplants because of 
complications stemming from the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said some of the patients had other health conditions,  
including stroke, cancer and heart attacks, that could have 
contributed to or caused their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert maintains that while there are ``hundreds'' of  
adverse drug reports that must be reported to the Food and Drug 
Administration, those cases do not always result in authorities 
finding a direct link to Rezulin, Mock said. 
</P>
<P>
	FDA spokesman Larry Bachorik said Thursday the agency would not  
release official numbers nor confirm the numbers given by 
Warner-Lambert. The agency will present results of a review of the 
drug during an advisory meeting next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Bachorik said the agency doesn't expect the numbers to be  
dramatically different from early December, when published reports 
attributed about 33 deaths to the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin is among the biggest-selling diabetes drugs, taken by  
more than 1 million people. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
