<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sooners' Sampson's Latest Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- When Kelvin Sampson looks at Oklahoma's game  
with top-seeded Michigan State in the NCAA Midwest Regional, he 
sees more than All-America guard Mateen Cleaves and a team that 
pounds opponents on the backboards. 
</P>
<P>
	He also sees Texas and Missouri and Oklahoma State -- teams his  
Sooners beat on the road during the regular season when no one else 
gave them much of a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampson always says he looks at challenges as opportunities, and  
that will be the case again Friday night in the regional 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The questions are always the same,'' Sampson said Thursday.  
``Last week, it was how are you going to guard Jason Terry? Now, 
it's how are you going to guard Mateen Cleaves? 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't overrespect. When you get this far, you're capable of  
winning and we've proven that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That mindset has carried 13th-seeded Oklahoma (22-10) this far  
for the first time since the Sooners' run-and-gun days of 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma upset No. 4 seed Arizona and beat fifth-seeded North  
Carolina-Charlotte last weekend by playing outstanding defense, 
rebounding well and shooting 3-pointers. The Sooners made 10 3s 
against Arizona, 13 against UNCC. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State coach Tom Izzo said he's concerned about the long  
rebounds that result from long-range jumpers. 
</P>
<P>
	``That can be an advantage or disadvantage,'' he said. ``If we  
get them, it can help our fast break. If we're not getting them, 
then it can create some problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans (31-4) have won 20 straight games, the Big 10  
regular-season and tournament titles, and showed their mettle last 
week by surviving a second-round scare against Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk about Michigan State always begins with Cleaves, with good  
reason. He averages 11 points and seven assists per game, and 
presents problems with his strength. 
</P>
<P>
	While Arizona's Jason Terry was quick and smooth, Cleaves ``is  
kind of a sledgehammer point guard,'' Sampson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He dominates his position. He plays physically strong. I  
watched eight games where I thought he was the main reason they won 
at the end. He has an infectious enthusiasm about him. I think it's 
important for a point guard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans' leading scorer, Morris Peterson, doesn't even  
start. Antonio Smith averages 8.4 rebounds per game but gets plenty 
of help from his teammates, especially at the offensive end. 
Michigan State has grabbed 18 offensive rebounds per game, about 
twice as many as its opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	That could be where the game is decided. Oklahoma has been a  
good offensive rebounding team, but doesn't compare to the 
Spartans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes the plays don't always work,'' Smith said. ``We do  
have some great offensive rebounding. Sometimes we do have a kind 
of ugly offense, but it's called getting the ball in the basket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma has gotten contributions from throughout the lineup in  
the first two tournament games. But if they are to have a chance 
Friday, the Sooners must get a big game from bruising forward 
Eduardo Najera. He had 17 points and 13 rebounds against Arizona 
and followed with 20 points and 15 rebounds against North 
Carolina-Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	``I watch a lot of college basketball throughout the season. I  
was very impressed (with Najera),'' Cleaves said. ``He has a 
passion for the game. He plays hard. It seems like he plays every 
game like it's his last.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will be one team's last game of this season. A Michigan State  
loss would be considered a big upset, although Spartan players said 
it would be an upset in seedings only. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is tough to play a team people considered the underdog,''  
Smith said. ``But we never look at people as underdogs. No. 1 seed, 
No. 13 seed, that's nothing but a number. We're not good enough to 
look past anyone.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
