<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:59:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Bankers Leave Bank Rates Alone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Despite the arrival of weaker than  
expected economic data, European Central Bank policy-makers kept 
interest rates unchanged at 3 percent at their regular meeting 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	While the bankers did not act Thursday, many economists expect  
them to lower the key refinancing rate in the 11 nations that share 
the euro, the new single currency, to 2.75 percent later in the 
second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Thursday, a German think tank, the Ifo institute,  
reported that business confidence in western Germany was less 
optimistic in February than January. 
</P>
<P>
	The Munich-based Ifo tracks sentiment and prospects in the  
manufacturing, construction and wholesaling sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure was the latest in a series of weak economic data that  
should persuade the central bank to lower rates, said Stefan 
Pelgrim, an analyst at Commerzbank. ``They're so weak that there's 
need to act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bank, in its March monthly report released Wednesday, ruled  
out any near-term action, saying that the current economic picture 
did not suggest a need to change rates. The report noted that the 
outlook for inflation -- the bank's key monetary goal -- remained 
``favorable,'' and that the risks of rising prices were ``broadly 
unchanged on balance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Taken together, all these factors argue in favor of an  
unchanged monetary policy stance,'' the central bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	The sudden resignation of German Finance Minister Oskar  
Lafontaine last week removed the main political proponent of 
lowering rates, diminishing any suggestion that a rate change would 
be politically influenced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:24:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supporting Actors Have Also Starred </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Academy Award nominees for best  
supporting actor of 1998 share one thing in common: All five have 
also played leading roles. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, actors have challenged the taboo against stars  
accepting less than major roles in movies. The conventional wisdom 
insisted that stars who did so would send a signal that their 
careers were on the slide. 
</P>
<P>
	Nowadays, you never know who will turn up for a brief turn in a  
movie. Robin Williams, Robert De Niro, George Clooney, John 
Travolta, Bill Murray, Bruce Willis, Brad Pitt, Al Pacino and Sean 
Connery are among those who have played lesser roles for a fraction 
of their usual salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it's a trend, because some of the best roles are  
supporting roles,'' says nominee James Coburn. ``It doesn't really 
matter to me. It's a pleasure to be supporting somebody who has to 
carry the picture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The supporting actor nominees:  

</P>
<P>
                  	 *JAMES COBURN, ``Affliction''    	
</P>
<P>
	Coburn's two-week job as Nick Nolte's boozing, abusive father in  
``Affliction'' was enough to bring his first Academy nomination. He 
has been in films since 1959 and has starred in Sam Peckinpah's 
``Pat Garrett and Billy the Kid'' and the James Bond spoofs ``Our 
Man Flint'' and ``In Like Flint.'' His busy career came to a 
near-halt in the 1980s when he was stricken with crippling 
arthritis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't quit acting, but I could only take jobs where I  
didn't have to do very much,'' he says. ``That lasted for about 12 
years.'' He recovered and has been more active in the past five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Coburn, recently seen in an amusing supporting role alongside  
Mel Gibson in ``Payback,'' said he had no second thoughts about 
accepting ``Affliction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There was such quality to it that I had no doubts at all,''  
says the actor. ``When you're playing with Nick (Nolte), Sissy 
(Spacek), Mary Beth (Hurt) and working with (director Paul) 
Schrader, that's not anything you could turn down without having a 
hole in your head.'' 

</P>
<P>
                 	 *ROBERT DUVALL, ``A Civil Action''    	
</P>
<P>
	Duvall is a veteran of Academy action, having been nominated six  
times, half as a leading actor, half for support. The leads were in 
``The Great Santini'' (1972), ``Tender Mercies'' (1983), for which 
he received an Oscar, and last year's ``The Apostle,'' which he 
also wrote and directed. 
</P>
<P>
	His first two supporting nominations came for ``The Godfather''  
(1972) and Apocalypse Now'' (1979). In ``A Civil Action,'' he plays 
Jerome Facher, a high-level but homespun attorney who defends a big 
corporation against a class action suit brought by another lawyer, 
played by John Travolta, over pollution of small town's water 
supply. 
</P>
<P>
	After stage training off-Broadway and in summer stock, Duvall  
made a brief but memorable film debut as Gregory Peck's 
feeble-minded neighbor in ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' (1964). With 
``The Godfather,'' he became one of Hollywood busiest actors, both 
in leads and as supporting actor. He has played Dwight D. 
Eisenhower in the television movie ``Ike'' and won praise in TV's 
``Lonesome Dove.'' 

</P>
<P>
                  	 *ED HARRIS, ``The Truman Show''    	
</P>
<P>
	For the second time, Harris has been nominated for playing a  
take-charge commander in a control room, surrounded by banks of 
video monitors. The first time came in 1995 for his role as Gene 
Kranz, in charge of bringing a crippled space capsule back to Earth 
in ``Apollo 13.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In ``The Truman Show,'' he appears as the demonic producer of a  
television show about the real life of a young man (Jim Carrey) who 
doesn't know he is being filmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Tenafly, N.J., Harris played football at Columbia  
University, studied acting at Oklahoma State University and 
graduated in fine arts from the California Institute of the Arts. 
After a few minor film roles, his career was boosted when he played 
astronaut John Glenn in ``The Right Stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harris has starred in films such as ``Walker'' and ``Paris  
Trout.'' In recent years he has co-starred with Clint Eastwood in 
``Absolute Power,'' with Sean Connery and Nicolas Cage in ``The 
Rock,'' and with Julia Roberts and Susan Sarandon in ``Stepmom.'' 

</P>
<P>
              	 *GEOFFREY RUSH, ``Shakespeare in Love''    	
</P>
<P>
	The question about Geoffrey Rush this year was not whether he  
would receive a nomination, but for which picture. The Australian 
gave outstanding performances in both Elizabethan movies -- as 
Walsingham, the bloodthirsty adviser to the queen in ``Elizabeth,'' 
and as Henslowe, the harried theater manager in ``Shakespeare in 
Love.'' Academy voters chose the latter. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Australia's leading stage actors, Rush achieved immediate  
international fame as the stammering piano virtuoso in ``Shine.'' 
His performance won the 1996 Oscar as best actor. 
</P>
<P>
	Rush was asked if he was more at ease with his second  
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``No,'' he replied firmly. ``It's a different project and I'm  
two years older, but you don't get used to something like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His feelings now? ``Terror.''  

</P>
<P>
               	 *BILLY BOB THORNTON, ``A Simple Plan''    	
</P>
<P>
	Good ol' Arkansas boy Thornton burst onto the movie landscape  
two years ago with his nomination as best actor for his gripping 
portrait of a mentally retarded man in ``Sling Blade.'' He also 
wrote and directed the film and won the Oscar for original 
screenplay. 
</P>
<P>
	Most filmgoers had never heard of Thornton before, but he likes  
to remind people, ``I've been around for 20 years.'' He was 
nominated this year for his role as Jacob Mitchell in ``A Simple 
Plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thornton has made a specialty of playing country boys, sometimes  
good ones, sometimes not so good. Among his films: ``One False 
Move'' (which he wrote and starred in), ``Dead Man,'' ``The 
Winner,'' ``Armageddon,'' ``Primary Colors'' and ``U-Turn.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
