<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Calls `Vitamin O' Ads Deceptive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- A ``Vitamin O'' dietary supplement  
advertised in USA Today and other newspapers as a cure for cancer 
is nothing more than bottled salt water sold for $10 an ounce, the 
government says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission is asking a federal judge here to  
bar two Washington state companies from making what the FTC says 
are false and unsubstantiated claims about the product. A hearing 
is set for April 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC ultimately wants to force Kettle Falls-based Rose Creek  
Health Products Inc. and The Staff of Life Inc. to refund 
customers' money. 
</P>
<P>
	An ad that ran in USA Today claims Vitamin O ``has helped  
eliminate everything from breathing problems and lack of energy to 
life-threatening diseases'' such as cancer and heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	An Food and Drug Administration lab analyzed the liquid and  
found it to be nothing more than salt water, said Eleanor Durham, 
an FTC attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald L. Smyth, owner of both Rose Creek and The Staff of Life,  
did not return a call Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC has several pending complaints against producers of  
dietary supplements that purport to cure various ailments. Such 
products are frequently advertised in alternative medicine 
publications and can be sold without approval from the FDA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vitamin O case is unusual because the product has recently  
been promoted in newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
