<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank To Raise More Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest  
commercial bank, plans to raise 6 billion marks, or about $3.37 
billion, to expand in Europe and finance its purchase of Bankers 
Trust. 
</P>
<P>
	The money, which is one-third more than Deutsche previously said  
it would raise, is needed to take full advantage of opportunities 
to penetrate the European market, chairman Rolf Breuer said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there was a possibility of making acquisitions or  
forming alliances. 
</P>
<P>
	When it first announced the $10.1 billion takeover Bankers  
Trust, Deutsche Bank had said it would need to raise about 4 
billion marks on the capital market. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite lawsuits by Holocaust victims, Breuer said he expects  
Deutsche Bank's acquisition of Bankers Trust to be completed by 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Bank is one of many German companies facing  
class-action suits in the United States filed by Holocaust 
survivors, accusing them of profiting from slave labor or the Nazi 
expropriation of Jewish assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuits could delay regulatory approval of the takeover.  
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Bank also announced that net profits more than tripled  
to 3.38 billion marks, or $1.9 billion, last year from 1.02 billion 
marks in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings were boosted by extraordinary gains from a special  
bonus dividend paid out by DaimlerChrysler last year. Deutsche Bank 
has a 12 percent stake in DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial crises in Russia, southeast Asia and Latin America  
pushed trading profits down nearly 4 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
