<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diabetes Drug Debate Intensifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Liver-related deaths linked to the diabetes  
drug Rezulin increased dramatically last year, despite claims by 
the manufacturer that there had been fewer fatalities, the Los 
Angeles Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin was listed as a contributing factor in the deaths of 65  
people last year -- more than four times as many as in 1997, the 
newspaper reported, citing federal records. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first six weeks of 1999, 12 liver-related deaths were  
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 155 Rezulin patients have died since the drug went on  
the market in 1997. About 60 percent of the patients showed signs 
of liver damage. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the federal records, some of the patients had other  
health conditions, including stroke, cancer and heart attacks, that 
could have contributed to or caused their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert Co., whose sales of Rezulin have topped $1  
billion, assured the FDA in a letter dated Dec. 31 that 
liver-related deaths associated with the drug had declined 65 
percent over the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin helps control blood-sugar levels. The same FDA advisory  
panel that approved Rezulin in 1996 is expected to vote March 26 on 
whether to restrict or ban the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials declined to comment specifically on the  
deaths, saying only that the drug's risks should be weighed against 
its benefits in treating adult-onset diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert spokesman Stephen Mock last December that he  
wasn't aware of a Rezulin-related death since July. The Times said 
FDA records show the company reported 31 deaths to federal 
officials between July 28 and Dec. 17. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
