<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Neilson Suspended Two Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Flyers coach Roger Neilson was  
suspended for two games and fined $10,000 Thursday for throwing a 
stick onto the ice in Tuesday's loss in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson will miss Sunday's game against Detroit and Monday's  
game in Toronto. Craig Ramsey will coach the team in Neilson's 
absence, with Neilson watching the games but prohibited from 
communicating with the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson tossed the stick in the direction of referee Bill  
McCreary to protest the lack of a penalty call on which St. Louis 
scored. He narrowly missed linesman Lonnie Cameron. 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson said he was not trying to hit Cameron but rather get  
McCreary's attention at the 6:47 mark of the third period in a 5-2 
loss to the Blues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a reaction and protest to what we thought was a  
non-call and I fired a stick,'' Neilson said. ``There's not too 
much you can say about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson and Flyers general manager Bob Clarke had a conference  
call Thursday with NHL disciplinarian Colin Campbell and vice 
president Jim Gregory. 
</P>
<P>
	A referee's report acknowledged there was no intent on Neilson's  
part to hit one of them, Clarke said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just an emotional outburst and he fired the stick out  
onto the ice,'' Clarke said. ``Now he's got to pay the price ... 
We're obviously glad it's only two games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension comes with the Flyers in the midst of a  
team-record 12-game winless streak. 
</P>
<P>
	The team had Thursday off and will resume practice Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Neilson has said he's been ejected from several games during his  
coaching career but never suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	On the disputed play, St. Louis' Terry Yake appeared to hold  
Jody Hull's stick. That gave Chris Pronger a clear path to set up 
Pavol Demitra for the goal that gave the Blues a 3-1 lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
