<DOCNO> APW19990318.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:24:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LA Philharmonic Leader Is Dramatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- With his boyish good looks, quick smile and  
deep eyes, Esa-Pekka Salonen could be mistaken for a Hollywood 
actor. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, he does frequent the hall where the Academy Awards  
are held. 
</P>
<P>
	But Salonen works with a score, not a script, as the  
internationally respected conductor of the Los Angeles 
Philharmonic. 
</P>
<P>
	With Salonen at its podium, the Los Angeles Philharmonic has  
emerged as one of the world's leading progressive symphonies. The 
orchestra specializes in performing the music of contemporary 
composers, and is considered a leading venue to premiere new work. 
</P>
<P>
	The 40-year-old Finnish native, who could pass for half his age,  
says he wanted to be a composer and became a conductor by accident. 
As a music student in the late 1970s, Salonen and his friends used 
to play each other's compositions. But someone had to conduct the 
sessions, and Salonen seemed to have a knack. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then he became good at it. And the rest is history,'' said  
longtime friend Tapani Lansio. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1979 -- only 21 and still in music school -- Salonen made his  
conducting debut with the Finnish Radio Symphony Orchestra. Six 
years later, the young maestro became music director of the Swedish 
Radio Symphony Orchestra and also was made principal guest 
conductor of the Philharmonia in London. He took the Los Angeles 
Philharmonic's baton in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting in the lobby of the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion on a  
recent afternoon, Salonen stared into a paper cup of coffee and 
tried to explain why he was so good at conducting orchestras. He 
only does what comes naturally, he says, and really can't explain 
further. It just happens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just try to study the music until I feel I have something to  
say, and then I convey it,'' Salonen said. ``That, more or less, is 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as he discussed his passion for conducting, Salonen said he  
``can't imagine life without being a composer,'' and a good-natured 
grin begins to form at the corners of his mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has redefined the maestro myth,'' says the Philharmonic's  
symphony violinist and principal concertmaster, Martin Chalifour. 
``He is really able to command respect and authority while seeming 
like one of the troops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jorma Panula, a respected composer and former teacher at the  
Sibelius Academy in Helsinki, where Salonen studied for seven 
years, says he spotted the young man's talents immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Salonen's good humor is one of his strongest assets; ``He's able  
to laugh at some of the mistakes he made during the early stages of 
his conducting career,'' said Panula. ``His openness saves him. 
He's still a normal young man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But even though he wields a conductor's baton like a magic wand  
and brings inexhaustible energy to his work, Salonen holds as much 
passion for composing. As he jets around the world to conduct, 
Salonen balances a laptop computer on his knees and works on his 
compositions. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1986, he told an Associated Press reporter in Helsinki that  
he wanted to take a break from conducting to compose. And next 
year, he finally will. He plans to write an opera, and is 
deliberate and cautious when he talks about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like seeing a building from a distance -- a big building,  
like a cathedral. I can see the shape but the details are still too 
far away,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He is working under a deadline -- the premiere is scheduled for  
the summer of 2001 at the Aix-en-Provence music festival in France. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the premiere may be in Europe, the music will be  
decidedly Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you can hear in my music that I have been here for a  
few years, and I don't mind it,'' he says. ``In fact, that is the 
whole point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salonen is largely responsible for establishing the  
Philharmonic's identity as an orchestra that premieres new 
composers, and whose repertoire includes a lot of 20th-century 
music. And it is not an easy niche to carve. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a measure of trust that has to be built between the  
music director and the community,'' said Grace Chang of the 
American Symphony Orchestra League in Washington D.C. If the 
audience is disappointed by modern compositions they find too 
difficult to enjoy, they are not likely to be back. 
</P>
<P>
	But Salonen sees spreading new music as a function of the  
orchestra -- to be as much a part of the Los Angeles scene as film, 
television and the visual arts. 
</P>
<P>
	``A symphony has to tap into the soul of its environment, and we  
try to produce programs which deal with life in Southern 
California,'' Salonen said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a recent production of Stravinsky's ``The Story of a  
Soldier,'' the characters were switched to contemporary 
Hispanic-American immigrants, and half of the story was performed 
in Spanish. The somewhat risky approach to the production was 
well-received by critics. 
</P>
<P>
	And his best-regarded work to date is titled ``L.A.  
Variations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he talks about his feelings for Los Angeles, he begins to  
fidget on his chair and his hands start to move as if he is 
conducting his own thoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are those (composers) who never change -- Schonberg came  
to L.A. to live and didn't change one bit. Stravinsky came here and 
changed a lot, and right away,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he raises his hand, as if to call a halt, and says with a  
grin, ``but I mean no comparison here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salonen finds some aspects of working in Los Angeles tough.  
Among the hardest, he says, is the general decline in music 
appreciation in local schools. And he notes that American 
television rarely broadcasts classical music. 
</P>
<P>
	``The natural sources from which a teen-ager would get a glimpse  
of classical music have dried up,'' he said. ``Even the background 
music of cartoons -- in the '60s and '70s you would have heard a 
symphony orchestra. Now, if you watch a cartoon, you hear a 
synthesizer or technopop in the background.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salonen himself picked up his interest in playing music on his  
own. His father was a businessman, who enjoyed but never played 
music. Salonen entered music school as a French horn student. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still keep an old one in the bottom of a closet of my summer  
house in Finland,'' he says, as a dimpled grin takes over his face. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take it out once a year and use it just to scare away  
crows,'' he laughed. ``I make an awful noise.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:35:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gambling Addiction Report Debated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 20 million Americans have or could  
develop gambling problems, but the economic impact of that is 
``relatively small,'' concludes a study likely to further enflame 
the debate over legalized wagering. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey conducted for the National Gambling Impact Study  
Commission found that more than 5 million Americans are 
pathological or problem gamblers and an additional 15 million are 
at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	A second report, also released Thursday as the commission began  
two days of meetings in Washington, estimated that 1.8 million 
Americans suffer severe ``pathological'' gambling each year. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission has three months to finish a wide-ranging report  
on gambling for Congress, and the extent of compulsive gambling in 
the country is just one of several open issues. Yet gambling 
addiction is the most contentious topic, and the report on the 
survey conducted for the commission only widened the chasm between 
the two sides. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank J. Fahrenkopf, Jr., president of the American Gaming  
Association, alleged that an earlier draft of the report was 
retooled to exaggerate the dangers of gambling through sensational 
language and changes in conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he noted that the report ``confirms that the economic and  
social benefits of gaming far outweigh the costs to society of 
pathological and problem gambling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report's classification of 15 million Americans as ``at  
risk'' for developing a gambling problem was criticized by 
Fahrenkopf and some commission members. 
</P>
<P>
	Survey participants who said they gambled just once to relieve  
uncomfortable feelings were put in the ``at risk'' group, said 
commission member John Wilhelm, general president of the Hotel 
Employees and Restaurant Employees International Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Other members were troubled by the report's finding that the  
economic cost of problem gambling is ``relatively small'' -- about 
$5 billion a year in legal fees for divorce, court and jail costs 
for arrests, lost wages and bankruptcy. That compares with $72 
billion for smoking, $166 billion for alcohol abuse and $71 billion 
for motor vehicle crashes, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	James Dobson, president of Focus on the Family and the panel's  
most outspoken opponent of gambling, said the $5 billion estimate 
of gambling's cost is far too low. He wondered how to calculate the 
costs of child abuse or spousal abuse committed by a gambling 
addict. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody on the commission has really struggled with this:  
How do you estimate the social cost?'' said commission Chairwoman 
Kay James. ``It's very difficult to do. At best, I think what we 
can say at this point is we really need more research, we need more 
information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cornerstone of the commission's work on the topic, the  
national survey, was conducted by the National Opinion Research 
Center at the University of Chicago in collaboration with other 
researchers. It is the first widespread survey since the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The report found that 2.5 million Americans are ``pathological''  
gamblers, a disorder codified in 1994 by the American Psychiatric 
Association, and another 3 million are problem gamblers. 
</P>
<P>
	Combining telephone surveys with interviews at casinos, the  
report concluded that people are about twice as likely to be 
problem or pathological gamblers if a casino is within 50 miles of 
their home. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Horn, spokesman for the National Coalition Against  
Legalized Gambling, said he was stunned at the finding that 6.4 
percent of casino patrons interviewed were pathological gamblers 
and 4.6 percent were problem gamblers. 
</P>
<P>
	``That means more than one in 10 people in a casino need  
psychiatric help,'' Horn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The second study, by the National Research Council -- part of the  
National Academy of Sciences, an independent organization chartered 
by Congress to advise the government -- says pathological gamblers 
are far more likely to commit crimes, run up large debts, damage 
relationships and kill themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Pathological gambling is ``a significant enough problem'' to  
warrant funding ``a more sustained, comprehensive and scientific 
set of research activities than currently exists,'' the study says. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission has just started discussing what steps to  
recommend to Congress. One mentioned Thursday would require 
casinos, state lotteries, the horse racing industry and other 
gambling outlets to help fund prevent and treatment programs for 
problem gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission member Richard C. Leone, president of the Twentieth  
Century Fund and a former state treasurer of New Jersey, said he 
worries that the nation is becoming one big compulsive gambler, 
with states battling it out to see who can capture the most dollars 
through casinos, lotteries, video poker and other outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I view it as a kind of national psychosis,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 15:37:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Strike Eases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Taxi drivers began withdrawing their  
blockades Thursday after Ecuador's president annulled a gasoline 
price increase to defuse a bitter standoff that paralyzed cities 
for three days. 
</P>
<P>
	Private cars circulated freely and most striking taxi and bus  
drivers went back to work. Long lines of cars formed at gas 
stations to buy the cheaper gas. 
</P>
<P>
	The main demand of striking drivers had been that President  
Jamil Mahuad revoke a decree doubling gasoline prices they argued 
would bankrupt them. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is good news. I'm going back to work. But the drivers are  
still cautious. We'll shut the country down again if Mahuad tricks 
us,'' Quito taxi driver Antonio Puertas said. 
</P>
<P>
	While many strikers went back to work, others stayed at their  
barricades of burning tires and fallen trees after the taxi union 
said the government's offer was not enough. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to lowering gas prices, union leaders said they  
wanted the government to freeze gas prices at the lower levels for 
two years and release 68 strikers detained by police during 
protests. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to cause chaos, but we will continue the strike  
if we don't get our demands,'' taxi union leader Samuel Egas said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news conference at the presidential palace, Mahuad  
announced an agreement with leftist and center-left parties in 
Congress to pass vital economic austerity measures in exchange for 
annulling the price rise and ending a 60-day state of emergency he 
declared last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this I call on the country to return to normality and  
peace,'' Mahuad said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahuad last week ordered the banks closed to prevent a financial  
meltdown and announced a package of spending cuts and tax increases 
to rescue the South American nation from bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Furious leftist-led unions, students and Indian groups had vowed  
to force Mahuad to back down. 
</P>
<P>
	The new coalition agreed to approve tax increases and leave in  
place a controversial decree partially freezing bank accounts for 
six months to a year, Mahuad said. The partial freeze was to 
prevent a run on bank deposits. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic crisis was set off by last year's El Nino floods,  
which caused $2.6 billion in damage, and low world prices for oil, 
Ecuador's major export. 
</P>
<P>
	The government this year has had to bail out seven of Ecuador's  
39 banks. Its currency, the sucre, has lost more than 40 percent of 
its value, and inflation is at nearly 50 percent, the highest in 
Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement followed days of intense negotiations between  
Mahuad and opposition leaders after the Social Christian party, his 
former conservative ally, said it would not support most of the 
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	The rupture of relations had cast doubts on Mahuad's ability to  
pass the reforms and led to calls for Mahuad, who took office seven 
months ago, to step down. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of food and fuel had doubled under the measures,  
increasing the hardship of already poor Ecuadoreans. Many people 
had supported the striking drivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
