<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation All but Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inflation all but disappeared -- again -- in  
February, allowing increased wages to flow directly into more 
purchasing power for American workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Price Index edged 0.1 percent higher last month,  
for the third consecutive month, despite a few scattered trouble 
spots such as meat, oranges, school books and airline fares, the 
Labor Department said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	World economic weakness continued to deliver dividends to U.S.  
buyers, with prices falling for clothing, cars and computers, 
reflecting the influence of imports manufactured in countries with 
devalued currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the department said average weekly earnings for  
American workers, adjusted for inflation, jumped 0.7 percent in 
February, the biggest increase in 18 months. During the past year, 
they have risen 3.6 percent to $452.49, before inflation, and 1.9 
percent after inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Increased imports have had a positive effect on the economy by  
keeping prices down, and real consumer purchasing power up,'' said 
economist Dave Huether of the National Association of 
Manufacturers. ``There is no inflation-creep in sight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The seasonally adjusted inflation rate for the first two months  
of the year was just 1.1 percent, compared with a 12-year low of 
1.6 percent for all of 1998. That means Federal Reserve 
policy-makers meeting March 30 probably will feel comfortable 
leaving short-term interest rates unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``Low inflation will keep the Fed on hold throughout 1999,''  
said economist Stan Shipley of Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy costs were unchanged last month, with declines for fuel  
oil and gasoline offsetting increases for electricity and natural 
gas. Energy is down 5.7 percent from a year ago, but analysts 
warned recent big increases for crude oil mean prices at the pump 
will head higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll probably see a 3 percent to 4 percent increase in  
gasoline prices. ... It will be noticed but it won't be huge,'' 
said economist Donald Ratajczak of Georgia State University. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices, meanwhile, rose only 0.1 percent after a  
substantial 0.5 percent increase in January. Fruit costs went up, 
pushed by a 5.3 percent increase for oranges on top of a 24.1 
percent gain the previous month, reflecting a December freeze in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef rose 1.3 percent, the most in six years, and pork, 1.4  
percent. Still, pork remained 5.3 percent cheaper than a year ago 
and vegetable costs fell 3.4 percent, pulled down by a 20 percent 
drop for tomatoes, the most in almost three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices excluding the volatile food and energy components edged  
up 0.1 percent in February. Airline fares jumped 2.4 percent. 
Hospital services and textbooks rose, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Further airfare increases probably will appear in the March  
price index, due out next month. Over the weekend, the airline 
industry raised business fares about 1 percent and leisure fares by 
about 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	However, clothing costs fell 0.2 percent in February, and new  
cars and trucks, 0.3 percent. Computer prices declined 2.8 percent 
and were 34.6 percent lower than a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, tobacco costs declined 1.4 percent but were still 33.5  
percent higher than a year earlier, reflecting tobacco companies' 
efforts to recoup the cost of multimillion-dollar liability 
settlements. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:24:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Dismisses Count Vs. Hubbell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday dismissed a  
criminal count against presidential friend Webster Hubbell in a 
fraud indictment that makes references to Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The count accused Hubbell of scheming to conceal work done by  
him and Mrs. Clinton, his former law partner, on a failed Arkansas 
land deal. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge James Robertson agreed with Hubbell that the  
allegations in the count were too vague. 
</P>
<P>
	``The charging language ... alleges no specific act or acts of  
concealment by 'trick, scheme or device' and no specific 'false, 
fictitious, or fraudulent statements or representations,'' the 
judge said, citing specific language of federal law. ``It is 
non-specific.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr had obtained a 15-count  
indictment of Hubbell last November in connection with a land deal 
known as Castle Grande. Federal regulators said the deal was 
riddled with ``insider dealing, fictitious sales and land flips.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson dismissed Hubbell's motions to throw out other counts  
in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was referred to 36 times in the original indictment  
against Hubbell, signifying that her name could be brought up 
repeatedly in the trial set to begin June 14. She could be called 
to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's witness list is not due until April 14, lawyers said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons' Whitewater partner, the late James McDougal, tried  
to sell off pieces of Castle Grande to prop up his collapsing 
savings and loan. 
</P>
<P>
	The dismissed count charged that from March 1989 through  
December 1995, Hubbell tried to cover up the true nature of his and 
Mrs. Clinton's relationships with Hubbell's father-in-law, Seth 
Ward; with McDougal's Madison Guaranty bank and the land deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell also was accused of making ``false and fraudulent''  
statements and representations to two U.S. banking regulatory 
agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hubbell argues that Count 1 is a 'catch all' count that fails  
to inform him clearly of the precise offense of which he is accused 
so that he may prepare his defense,'' Robertson wrote in 18-page 
opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	``He points out reasonably that a jury might convict if it  
unanimously accepted the generality of the charge of 'scheming,' 
although split on which (if any) of the many acts alleged ... 
(that) Hubbell actually committed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office maintained that the count was ``sufficiently  
specific'' and that it was not necessary for that count ``to set 
forth precisely the false statements and acts of concealment upon 
which it depends ...,'' the opinion said. The independent counsel 
contended the concealment scheme was the offense, rather than any 
specific act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 12:43:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Encourages Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- McDonald's will distribute 13 million booklets  
about the importance of reading with its Happy Meals this fall in 
an educational campaign announced Thursday by Hillary Rodham 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The booklets will ``explain to parents the importance of  
nourishing their children's minds as well as their bodies,'' Mrs. 
Clinton told members of the Association of American Publishers at 
the group's annual meeting. ``This is a great way to reach out to 
families who, running for a fast-food meal, like all the rest of 
us, are trying to get from one place to the next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's will work with the AAP and the Education Department  
on the effort, which begins October. 
</P>
<P>
	The AAP also will sponsor a ``Get Caught Reading'' campaign to  
help spark interest among people ages 18 to 34, whom the first lady 
called a ``critical age group because it includes, obviously, the 
parents of very many young children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign will feature posters in major bookstores and  
various print advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's message that reading is cool will be aired by celebrities  
like Whoopi Goldberg and Rosie O'Donnell, who are going to be among 
those 'getting caught,''' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hoping that the 'Get Caught Reading' ads will have enough  
of a rebellious twist to encourage people who might otherwise not 
be caught dead reading to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said not all parents realize that reading to  
children can help build vocabularies, develop imaginations and 
improve their reasoning skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``We kind of take it for granted if you come from a family that  
loves books or if you've been read to as a child that that is 
something that's constantly going on in homes and families, but I 
learned early on that that's not the case,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The AAP is a national trade group that represents about 200  
commercial book publishers, including university presses and 
scholarly societies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
