<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co. To Refund Termite System Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumers who took the bait that a termite  
removal system would prevent pests from infesting and damaging 
their homes can get their money back under a settlement announced 
Thursday by the maker of the product and government regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	United Industries Corp., which manufactures Terminate, has  
agreed to refund customers and modify advertising for its termite 
bait system. The Federal Trade Commission, the District of Columbia 
and nine state attorneys general had charged that the company's 
claims about the use and effectiveness of Terminate was deceptive 
and unsubstantiated. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the complaint, the company, based in St. Louis,  
advertised Terminate as ``the first do-it-yourself termite home 
defense system.'' The promotional materials imply that users only 
have to place bait stakes in the ground around their home and 
Terminate would do the rest, the complaint charged. 
</P>
<P>
	But the commission said consumers must actually inspect the bait  
stakes every two to three months or more frequently, add additional 
stakes where termite activity exists and replace or remove the 
stakes every nine months, the complaint said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also failed to let consumers know that bait stakes  
do not work against drywood termites, the FTC said, and that 
professional pest control services are recommended for homes with 
active infestation or in areas with drywood or Formosan termites. 
</P>
<P>
	``Termites cause serious damage and consumers spend serious  
money trying to deal with it,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of 
FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection. The commission has the 
authority to regulate truth in advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Terminate is sold through national home improvement stores and  
regional chains for $60 to $100. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement filed in U.S. District Court in Baltimore,  
the company will not make any such claims without reliable 
scientific data to support them. The company must also disclose in 
its advertising that the product is ``not recommended as sole 
protection against termites, and for active infestations, get a 
professional inspection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said adding this statement is consistent with its  
past communications. 
</P>
<P>
	``This agreement does not change the overall message that we  
have been sending since the product's launch. It does, however, 
make some clarification in these communications,'' said Jim Olsen, 
general manager of termite products for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Terminate label lists four steps consumers should  
take in addition to using the product to reduce the risk of 
infestations. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers may seek a refund within 15 months of purchase of the  
product. 
</P>
<P>
	The order also requires the company to pay the District of  
Columbia and the following nine states $40,000 each for 
investigation and litigation expenses: Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, 
Maryland, Ohio, New Jersey, North Carolina, Texas and Virginia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
