<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Priceline.com Files for IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Priceline.com, the Internet travel  
company that allows consumers to name their price for airline 
tickets, disclosed plans Thursday to sell 10 million shares in an 
initial public offering that would raise about $80 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the  
company said it expects the shares to start selling at between $7 
and $9. The company has applied to trade on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 
</P>
<P>
	With ``Star Trek'' actor William Shatner as its pitchman,  
priceline.com has become familiar to consumers since it launched 
its service last April. 
</P>
<P>
	The company says it has sold more than 237,000 airline tickets  
by allowing customers to name the price they want to pay, then 
searching for a major airline willing to release seats on flights 
where they have unsold space. No match, no tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	The company offers similar buying services for hotel rooms,  
mortgages and new cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel industry analysts predicted strong demand for the  
company's stock. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably the most advertised Web site on radio that I've  
ever seen in my life,'' said Tom Parsons, editor and publisher of 
Bestfares.com magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The company originally filed in December but had not said how  
many shares it would offer or given its estimate on the initial 
selling price. 
</P>
<P>
	In its amended filing Thursday, the company said sale of the 10  
million shares represents a 8 percent stake in the company. 
</P>
<P>
	In its filing, the company said it sold 135,000 airline tickets  
in 1998, with revenue of $35 million. In the first 60 days of 1999, 
it sold 102,700 tickets, with revenue of $21 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
