<HEADLINE> Train Crash a Nightmare for Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NESBIT, Miss. (AP) -- Rainey and Lacey Lipscomb wanted to spend  
the night on the train with their hometown friends, the ones who 
had joined them on a spring break trip to Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Cindy Lipscomb saw her two oldest daughters was  
when they kissed her goodnight Monday and headed to the front 
sleeper car of Amtrak's City of New Orleans train to join June 
Bonnin, 46, and her granddaughter, Jessica Whitaker, 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than an hour later, the train plowed into a tractor-trailer  
loaded with steel and derailed. Leaking diesel fuel erupted in 
flames. Dazed but unhurt, Ms. Lipscomb searched frantically for 
10-year-old Rainey and 8-year-old Lacey. The three girls and Ms. 
Bonnin, all from this suburb of Memphis, Tenn., were dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to die when I saw the flames because I knew,'' Ms.  
Lipscomb told The Commercial Appeal of Memphis. ``It was either lay 
down and die or pray, and I just sat down and prayed. It just felt 
like my heart was ripped out of my chest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lipscomb's youngest daughter, Jesse Anne, 5, was unhurt.  
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have not officially released the names of those  
killed in the crash. More than 100 people were injured, including 
Ashley Bonnin, Ms. Bonnin's 8-year-old daughter, who lost part of a 
leg. 
</P>
<P>
	``She thought she might be a bit able to do more to get my wife,  
June, out of that car,'' Max Bonnin said Wednesday. ``We assured 
her that she did everything that she possibly could.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheena Johnson Dowe, a senior at Tougaloo College in suburban  
Jackson was also among the fatalities, WLBT-TV in Jackson reported 
Wednesday. Dowe, her sister and three children were returning home 
after a trip to visit their mother in Chicago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
