<HEADLINE> Rep. Weygand To Run for Chafee Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Rep. Robert Weygand, a two-term  
Democrat, announced Thursday he will run for the Senate seat that 
will be vacated next year by Republican John Chafee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sticking my neck out to run for this,'' said Weygand,  
noting that he probably would have little difficulty getting 
reelected to his seat in the House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm doing it because I really believe that there are  
things I can do for Rhode Island in the Senate that I can't do in 
the House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chafee, 76, announced Monday that he would not seek a fifth  
Senate term. On Tuesday, his son, Warwick Mayor Lincoln Chafee, 
announced he would run for the seat in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Weygand, 50, is the first Democrat to declare his candidacy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
