<HEADLINE> Credit Lyonnais, Mellon in Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French bank Credit Lyonnais is in talks with Mellon  
Bank Corp. about an alliance in asset-management services. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been talking with Mellon Bank, for whom we have a lot  
of respect,'' Credit Lyonnais Chairman Jean Peyrelevade said 
Thursday at a news conference to present the bank's 1998 results. 
``But we don't know if these talks will lead anywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An agreement between Mellon and Credit Lyonnais, though far from  
certain, would mark the latest in a string of overseas 
asset-management alliances for Pittsburgh-based Mellon. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past year, Mellon has entered asset-management  
alliances with banks in Brazil, Chile, Hong Kong, Japan and 
Singapore. 
</P>
<P>
	Mellon's mutual-fund companies have about $390 billion in assets  
under management. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Dishart, a spokesman for Mellon, declined to comment,  
but said, ``We continue to see opportunities for leveraging our 
investment management capabilities overseas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The talks come as the French government on Sunday opened the way  
for Credit Lyonnais' privatization, setting the stage for a core 
group of institutional investors to acquire an equity stake 
totaling 33 percent in the privatization's first stage. 
</P>
<P>
	The government will then sell around half of the shares on the  
stock market before the end of June, market conditions permitting. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of European banks and insurers have already signaled  
their interest in joining the initial shareholders group, including 
Caisse Nationale du Credit Agricole, Societe Generale, Paribas and 
Axa of France, and Allianz of Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Lyonnais also said Thursday that its net profit tripled  
in 1998 to 165 million euros ($149 million), largely surpassing 
analysts' expectations. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
