<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nike Third-Quarter Earnings Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) -- Third-quarter earnings at Nike Inc. rose  
70 percent, partly on the strength of cost-cutting efforts that 
included a cutback on NBA endorsements, as the sneaker giant 
handily beat Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Beaverton-based company earned $124.2 million or 44 cents a  
share, compared to $73.1 million, or 25 cents a share, for the 
year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue for the three months ended Feb. 28 was $2.18 billion,  
down 2 percent from $2.22 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had projected earnings of  
38 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman Phil Knight said the effort to hold down expenses would  
continue because domestic demand remained weaker than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite continued softness in the U.S. athletic footwear and  
apparel retail market, we are beginning to see signs of increased 
consumer demand for our footwear,'' Knight said. ``While we are 
encouraged by these early indicators, we remain cautious on our 
prospects for near-term growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Future orders for athletic footwear and apparel has fallen, with  
orders scheduled for delivery between March and July 1999 down 4 
percent to $3.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders fell 6 percent in the United States and 16 percent in  
Asia but increased 8 percent in Europe, which has repeatedly been a 
strong market for Nike. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the company performed a little better than they  
expected, but they remain concerned about the next several months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Near term the outlook isn't as rosy as the long-term  
outlook,'' said Josie Esquivel of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in New 
York. ``They're not going to rebound the way they did in 1995.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said Nike stock prices may have been a little high recently,  
but the company has shown a strong recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're definitely on their way back,'' Esquivel said.  
</P>
<P>
	The results were released after the markets had closed Thursday.  
Shares of Nike fell $2.37 1/2 to close at $55 in trading on the New 
York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
