<HEADLINE> IBF Judge Filed for Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- The IBF judge who came under fire for her  
scoring of the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight filed for 
protection from creditors under the U.S. Bankruptcy Code earlier 
this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugenia Williams of Atlantic City filed a Chapter 7 bankruptcy  
petition on Jan. 25, court officials confirmed today. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about it, she told the New York Post, which first reported  
the story, ``I don't know what you're talking about. They told me 
not to answer any more questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She would not say to whom she was referring.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams, a 10-year veteran of judging who works as a  
$39,200-a-year accounts clerk for the city, scored the fight 
115-113 for Holyfield, even though many who saw the 12-round 
heavyweight title fight at Madison Square Garden and others who 
watched on pay-per-view felt Lewis dominated. 
</P>
<P>
	The WBA judge at ringside, Stanley Christodoulou of South Africa  
scored it 116-113 for Lewis and WBC judge Larry O'Connell of 
Britain scored it a 115-115 tie. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was to testify today at a hearing in New York City  
called by New York state senate investigators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
