<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Grants Top Exec Stock Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. granted top executive Alan R. Mulally  
a multimillion stock deal that could exceed $27 million by mid-2008 
to keep him from becoming chief executive of another company, 
reveals a proxy statement being filed by the company today. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of the package, which includes restricted stock and  
stock options, hinges on how Boeing stock fares over the next 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulally headed Boeing Information, Space &AMP; Defense Systems when  
the agreement was negotiated last year. A couple of months later, 
he was promoted to president of Boeing Commercial Airplane Group, 
the company's bread-and-butter jetliner manufacturing arm and 
source of most of the company's recent problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on condition of anonymity, a senior Boeing executive  
said Thursday that Mulally negotiated his stay-at-home deal after 
being offered the top position at a competing company. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive would not identify the company. The Seattle  
Post-Intelligencer and The Wall Street Journal reported last year 
that Mulally rejected an offer from Raytheon Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The proxy statement prepared for filing today also showed Boeing  
chairman Philip M. Condit received more than $2.8 million in 1998. 
More than $1.8 million came from exercising previously awarded 
stock options and the rest was from salary and other direct 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	President Harry C. Stonecipher, Boeing's chief operating  
officer, received $956,577 in pay and other compensation last year. 
He did not exercise any stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	Condit and Stonecipher announced last month they would forgo  
their bonuses for 1998 because of Boeing's poor performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing has endured billions of dollars in losses and tumbling  
stock prices in 1997 and 1998 because of production line snarls, 
parts shortages, late aircraft deliveries and costly fixes on 
new-model 737s. Economic turmoil has cut orders from Asian 
countries, and tens of thousands of jobs are being cut after a 
costly buildup to boost aircraft production rates. 

</P>
</TEXT>
