<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Euro; Down Vs. Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the euro Thursday as  
poor German economic data kept the new European currency on a 
downward path. The dollar slipped against the yen after an early 
rally fizzled. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0970, down  
from $1.1007 on Wednesday. The dollar was quoted at 117.45 Japanese 
yen, down from 118.01 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro hit a three-week high against the dollar during the  
European trading session. But the brand new currency, on a downward 
track almost since it was launched in January, quickly fell after a 
widely watched indicator of German business sentiment marked a 
sharper drop in February than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``That really did put a damper on the euro's ability to break  
away from that down trend,'' said Kathleen Stephansen, a senior 
economist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	During Asian trading, the dollar rallied against the yen as  
Tokyo's main stock index fell 3.4 percent. But the U.S. currency 
got caught in that country's economic cross-currents. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese companies are selling foreign assets and bringing home  
yen to enhance their balance sheets before the end of the Japanese 
fiscal year on March 31, a trend that tends to push the yen upward 
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4575 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4509, and 1.5182 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5215. The British 
pound fell to $1.6297 from $1.6305. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7828 German 
marks, up from 1.7768; 5.9809 French francs, up from 5.9595; and 
1,763.67 Italian lire, up from 1,760.56. 
</P>
</TEXT>
