<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> C-Span Marks 20 Year Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When C-Span debuted on March 19, 1979, the  
cable TV network had four employees, a $450,000 budget and one 
telephone line to yield calls from creditors and viewers alike. It 
operated only during business hours because the satellite it shared 
showed sporting events at night. 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades later, the network boasts gavel-to-gavel coverage of  
Congress, a staff of 250 and a $33 million budget. But ask chairman 
Brian Lamb to describe other differences between then and now and 
he'll say the Cable-Satellite Public Affairs Network he founded 
remains virtually unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other than the fact we offer a lot more programs, the mission  
is exactly the same,'' Lamb said in an interview. ``And the 
product, by and large on most days, is exactly the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	C-Span premiered with funding from the cable industry and to  
fears about the impact of televising proceedings in Congress. But 
the now-24-hour network soon became so popular among political 
junkies that senators began to complain about all the attention 
going to their House counterparts. Thus, the debut seven years 
later of C-Span 2 to telecast live sessions of the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamb said he always knew he'd find an audience for his network.  
C-Span has attracted a small but loyal group of viewers who crave 
more news than a 30-second sound bite. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 74.6 million households can view C-Span on their cable  
or satellite TV systems, a 1997 survey by Statistical Research Inc. 
estimated that just 22 million people watch C-Span each week. But 
nearly all of them -- 94 percent -- were registered to vote and did 
so in the last general election. C-Span viewers also were more 
likely to contact lawmakers, volunteer in campaigns and make 
political contributions, the survey found. 
</P>
<P>
	The audience can be a somewhat fanatical bunch: Tune in at 7  
a.m. on the East Coast to the network's daily ``Washington 
Journal'' program hosted by Lamb and it wouldn't be unusual to hear 
from a wide-awake caller from California. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a certain percent of the public, a thinking public and  
voting public that wants the discussion, that wants the challenge, 
that wants the information,'' said Lamb, a stolid presence who 
could be called the Joe Friday of cable TV. 
</P>
<P>
	His unemotional, ``just the facts'' interviewing style has  
helped make Lamb, 57, the most recognizable personality on the 
deliberately anti-personality C-Span. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamb served as a Pentagon spokesman during the Johnson  
administration and as a press secretary for Republican Sen. Peter 
Dominick of Colorado. He is a former reporter for UPI Audio and a 
past Washington bureau chief for CableVision magazine, which is 
where he was working when he came up with the idea for C-Span and 
its gavel-to-gavel coverage of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Using simple, stationary camera angles, C-Span attempts to  
provide the most neutral view of every event it telecasts. In 
addition to sessions on the House floor, the network also shows 
congressional hearings, speeches at the National Press Club and 
press briefings by federal agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The only cameras C-Span cannot control are the ones in the House  
and Senate chambers -- the network must tap into a government feed -- 
but they are consistent with the network's speaker-and-podium 
style. 
</P>
<P>
	C-Span offers Americans a more realistic look at politicians  
than the usual polished image supplied by evening news clips and 
Sunday TV talk shows. 
</P>
<P>
	If anything, C-Span has shown American that Congress consists of  
``flawed human beings,'' said John Pitney, a government professor 
at Claremont McKenna College. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not every member is 'Mr. Smith Going to Washington.' The House  
is noticeably short of Jimmy Stewarts,'' Pitney said of the famed 
movie. Like many college instructors, Pitney uses C-Span 
extensively in class. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Levinson, a communications professor at Fordham University,  
recalled the shock of watching members of the Senate Judiciary 
Committee during the confirmation hearing for Supreme Court Justice 
Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here they were considering very important issues -- should this  
man become a Supreme Court Justice, and sexual harassment,'' he 
said. ``Just the expressions on some of the faces of the senators, 
yawning and looking uninterested. It was something I don't think 
anyone had seen before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Frantzich, co-author of ``The C-Span Revolution,''  
agreed that the network has affected the way the public sees its 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's set up this kind of expectation that, hey, we ought to be  
doing things in public, that there's a sense of illegitimacy if 
it's done behind closed doors,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
