<DOCNO> APW19990318.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:39:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Sex Basic-Training Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a battle of the sexes, lawmakers are  
clashing over a congressional commission recommendation that men 
and women train together at military boot camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Roscoe Bartlett, R-Md., argued Wednesday during a House  
subcommittee hearing against maintaining mixed-gender basic 
training in the Army, Air Force and Navy. Now, only the Marines 
separate the sexes in the first 12 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The forces, except for the Marines, are forced to worship at  
the altar of political correctness,'' Bartlett charged, suggesting 
men and women may be sexually tempted if kept at close quarters 
when they first enter the services. ``The sexual dynamic is both an 
attraction and a distraction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., countered that there's no  
turning back from integrating women throughout the military so the 
sexes should learn to work together from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's this attraction ... when do we integrate the  
troops?'' she asked. ``If we follow what Mr. Barlett said, we would 
never have women in the military.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez discounted Bartlett's argument that during 5,000 years  
of military history, no civilization has successfully trained men 
and women together during boot camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because maybe it didn't work for the Romans or the  
Israelis doesn't mean it can't work here in the United States,'' 
said Sanchez during a polite, but pointed exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartlett said he supports women in the military, where 14  
percent of the 1.4 million active duty force is female, and is only 
against mixing the sexes during the ``short period of intense 
resocialization'' that is basic training. 
</P>
<P>
	``Men and women are different,'' he said. ``They're physically  
different and emotionally different.'' In training together, 
``Either you're not going to begin to challenge the average man or 
you're going to overstress the average women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House moved last year to require separate basic training for  
men and women, but the measure didn't pass in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate before the House Armed Services Committee's panel on  
military personnel centered on findings of the Commission on 
Military Training and Gender-Related Issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Panel chairman Rep. Stephen Buyer, R-Ind., said he asked for the  
study because of questions raised about training after several sex 
scandals, including with drill instructors at Aberdeen Training 
Ground, Md., and at Fort Leonard Wood, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon did its own study in the wake of the scandals, but  
Defense Secretary William Cohen rejected his committee's 
recommendation to separate sexes during basic training. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Cohen announced in June that male and female recruits  
would continue training together in the Army, Air Force and Navy, 
but would sleep in separate, more secure quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	All the service chiefs agreed with keeping mixed training, which  
began as an experiment during the late 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, reflecting divisions on the subcommittee, had  
deeply mixed feelings, too. Six of 10 members approved keeping 
mixed training. The rest abstained or voted ``no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even the abstainers said they want to change the system.  
</P>
<P>
	Anita Blair, chairwoman of the commission who abstained, held up  
Marine Corps basic training as the model. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force trainers ``told me the Marine Corps has the best idea.  
The Marine Corps does it right,'' Blair said. 
</P>
<P>
	But former Pentagon official Frederick Pang, vice chairman of  
the commission, said the mixed training was working and the sexual 
scandals ``grew out of instances of failure ... not out of any 
fundamental breakdown that we could find.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, consisting of retired members of the military,  
educators and social scientists, is scheduled to deliver its final 
report in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Buyer, surprised commission members had not visited Fort Leonard  
Wood while investigating alleged training problems, suggested they 
should before completing their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charges vs. First Lady Were Drafted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Kenneth Starr's top deputy testified  
Thursday that he had questioned the truthfulness of President 
Clinton and the first lady inside the prosecutor's office and had 
even drawn up a draft indictment of Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he had ever referred to the Clintons as ``crooks and  
liars,'' W. Hickman Ewing Jr. said, ``I believe I made that 
statement in-house ... (but) I don't believe I used the L-word or 
the C-word. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly expressed internally that I had problems with some  
of their answers,'' Ewing said. 
</P>
<P>
	Subpoenaed as the leadoff defense witness at the trial of Susan  
McDougal, one of the Clintons' former Whitewater partners, Ewing 
revealed some of the inner workings of Starr's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, on trial for refusing to answer grand jury  
questions, is trying to demonstrate that prosecutors wanted to use 
her to get to the Clintons, whether there was sufficient evidence 
to charge them or not. 
</P>
<P>
	She is charged with criminal contempt and obstruction of  
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. McDougal's lawyers called Ewing to the stand in an  
effort to focus on the conduct of the Independent Counsel's office, 
his testimony is the type of attention the first lady would like to 
avoid as she tests the waters for a possible Senate bid in New York 
in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said that at dinner one evening with other Starr staffers,  
he graded the president and first lady on their responses to 
questioning by Whitewater investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said the president was about a 'C' and Mrs. Clinton about an  
'F,''' Ewing testified. Ewing said his remark followed his 
observing her answers during a July 1995 deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing testified that he made the statement after Mrs. Clinton  
said ``'I don't recall' about 50 times'' during the deposition in 
July 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he drafted the proposed indictment against the first  
lady sometime after September 1996. Early that year, Mrs. Clinton's 
long-sought law firm billing records mysteriously surfaced in the 
White House, revealing that she had worked on a failed land 
development that James McDougal was trying to use to prop up his 
failing S&AMP;L. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said it was not unusual for a federal prosecutor to draft  
an indictment whether or not a charge is ever brought. He didn't 
say what charge the draft might have included. 
</P>
<P>
	As a prosecutor, he said, ``You're always thinking about ...  
what possible crime could it be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he showed the draft to ``a couple of people in the  
office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Kendall, Mrs. Clinton's private lawyer, scoffed at Ewing's  
revelation, saying ``the mere fact that this prosecutor's office 
drafted a frivolous indictment three years ago has no significance 
whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until the emergence of the billing records -- which had vanished  
after the 1992 presidential campaign -- Mrs. Clinton never revealed 
that she had done any work on the McDougals' Castle Grande 
development, which federal regulators said was riddled with fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the billing records were turned over, the inspector  
general's office at the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. concluded 
that Mrs. Clinton created a real estate document that was used to 
deceive federal regulators. Castle Grande ended up costing the 
McDougals' S&AMP;L nearly $4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1995 interviews with Starr's prosecutors, Mrs. Clinton  
was questioned under oath about the work her law firm had done for 
the McDougals' S&AMP;L. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was in conflict with interviews we had already done with  
several people in the Rose Law Firm,'' Ewing said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted the president's changing responses to questions  
about whether he had asked Whitewater partner James McDougal to 
hire Mrs. Clinton's law firm to represent Madison Guaranty, the 
McDougals' savings and loan, in the mid-1980s. Clinton was Arkansas 
governor at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	James McDougal said Clinton made the request, and during the  
1992 presidential campaign, Clinton denied it. But in sworn 
testimony to Starr's investigators in 1995, Clinton said ``I don't 
recall'' whether McDougal's account was accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing made a number of concessions under questioning by McDougal  
attorney Mark Geragos. For example, he acknowledged that 
prosecutors hadn't told the grand jury that James McDougal kept 
changing parts of his story as Starr's office zeroed in on 
Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	And Geragos focused on the fact that even though prosecutors  
knew James McDougal had changed his story, Starr told U.S. District 
Judge George Howard on the day McDougal was sentenced that he had 
testified ``truthfully'' and had ``substantially aided our search 
for the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under cross-examination by one of his own prosecutors, associate  
Independent Counsel John Barrett, Ewing explained why the Starr 
team was so intent on getting Mrs. McDougal's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``They needed a witness without baggage,'' Ewing testified. ``If  
they've been convicted, that's baggage. If they've given previous 
conflicting testimony, that's baggage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing noted that while Mrs. McDougal had been convicted of four  
felonies in her 1996 trial, she had not testified at that trial. 
James McDougal had testified, and later changed his account of 
whether Clinton knew about a fraudulent $300,000 loan to Mrs. 
McDougal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
