<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:35:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains Down; Soybeans Mostly Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures were lower and soybeans mostly  
higher in dealings Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures fell sharply, pressured by reports of moisture  
moving across growing regions in the United States, as well as news 
that the dry Chinese wheat belt got rain Wednesday night. Traders 
also absorbed news of low net export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and corn futures also fell amid dimmed hopes that the  
government could orchestrate an acreage set-aside this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were mostly higher with talk of positive overnight  
export business. Likewise, recent rumors of a last-minute acreage 
set-aside by the government were dismissed by most market 
participants. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn finished lower despite hitting 9 1/2-week highs earlier in the  
day. The losses were limited by solid weekly export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery was off 4 cents to $2.73 3/4 a bushel; May  
corn was off 1 1/2 cent to $2.24 1/4 a bushel; May oats were off 1/2 cent 
to $1.11 a bushel; May soybeans were up 3/4 cent to $4.82 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and feeder cattle futures were mostly higher on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, as were lean hogs and pork bellies. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle futures rose 0.28 cent to 67.15 cents a pound;  
March feeder cattle were unchanged at 72.00 cents per pound; April 
lean hogs were up 1.30 cent to 42.27 cents a pound; and May pork 
bellies were up 0.43 cent to 50.90 cents per pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
