<DOCNO> APW19990318.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:45:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Denies Spy Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Chinese diplomat on Thursday denied  
allegations his country stole nuclear weapons designs from a U.S. 
laboratory. The official blamed a Cold War mentality and 
``political atmospherics'' for the furor that has prompted FBI and 
Energy Department investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the State Department, responding quickly, said the United  
States remains ``deeply concerned about reports of China's attempts 
to illegally acquire sensitive U.S. technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That concern is ``shared widely by both branches, the executive  
and legislative branches of government, by both political 
parties,'' said James P. Foley, the deputy spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no division there. The Chinese should not read our  
concern over espionage as a partisan matter or a matter that's 
manufactured by opponents of U.S.-China relations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese diplomat, He Yafei, a minister-counsel at the  
Chinese Embassy, insisted ``the Sino-U.S. relationship has become 
the victim of party politics in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Citing the Monica Lewinsky scandal, He said: ``You all know how  
party politics play, especially when you're nearing a major 
election. You have seen the outcry or the big media coverage on the 
Lewinsky issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The diplomat accused critics of harboring Cold War instincts.  
</P>
<P>
	``They are sorry there is no more Soviet Union and they don't  
know how to act,'' said He, referring to those accusing China of 
espionage at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in the 1980s to 
help modernize Chinese nuclear warheads. 
</P>
<P>
	Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born American engineer at the New Mexico  
facility, is the focus of the investigation. He was fired last week 
for violating security regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee has not been charged with any crime and Energy Secretary  
Bill Richardson said he did not know if Lee would be prosecuted. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson told Congress on Wednesday he planned to tighten  
security at the nation's nuclear weapons laboratories. Former CIA 
Director John Deutch is to help decide whether too many foreign 
visitors are admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think strengthening the security of labs is right,'' He said  
at a news conference in the embassy ballroom. ``Nothing wrong with 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, asserting the two nations and the world benefit from  
scientific exchanges, the Chinese diplomat cautioned: ``Don't go 
too far so that normal scientific exchanges are affected. It will 
not only hurt other countries, but it will hurt U.S. interests, 
too, because in the long run any advance in science and technology 
is not dependent on scientists of one country alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the dispute could harm improving relations between  
Washington and Beijing, and that some Chinese scientists were 
questioning whether to continue scientific exchanges ``to advance 
our knowledge of nuclear science.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongii due here next month, He  
said ``there are some people in the United States who do not want 
to see progress in the Sino-U.S. relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever there is improvement in the Sino-U.S. relations,  
whenever there is an important summit that is going to happen, you 
will see ... these anti-China waves, undercurrents, whatever. Human 
rights issues, nuclear issues and other issues; it will come up,'' 
He said. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not identify anyone, and specifically excluded Sandy  
Berger, the president's national security adviser who supports 
closer ties with China. On Sunday, Berger said ``there's no 
question'' China benefited from important information leaked from 
the Los Alamos laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the allegations of espionage and theft, He replied  
that ``nothing of this sort has ever happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``China never benefited from anything that is illegal,'' the  
diplomat said. ``We have normal exchange programs. Of course each 
side will benefit from these exchange programs, otherwise it will 
be meaningless. But it has nothing to do with nuclear military 
technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Repeatedly, He returned to his central theme, that U.S.-Chinese  
relations generally and scientific cooperation specifically were in 
jeopardy from people opposed to progress between the two countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't let Chinese-U.S. relations become hostage to that,'' He  
implored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  2006 Olympic Bidding Different Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The cursor dragged across the  
computer screen, offering a 3-D vision of the jagged peaks off the 
lake in Klagenfurt, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	That is as close as the IOC members will get to six bidding  
cities ahead of their June decision on the host of the 2006 Olympic 
Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the members can no longer come to us, we have to do it this  
way,'' said Dr. Dieter Kalt, the general manager of the Klagenfurt 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Breaking with years of wining and dining, lavish gift-giving and  
other pampering by bid cities, the IOC members decided Thursday to 
outlaw visits to reduce any risk of corruption, which is at the 
heart of the worst scandal in Olympic history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Visits are unnecessary and public perception of them is just  
too bad,'' said executive board member Jacques Rogge, who prides 
himself in keeping away from candidate cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The bidding war between the cities has been suspended since  
December when the Salt Lake bribery scandal broke. It will now be 
resumed under new, stricter rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were waiting like lions in a cage. Tomorrow we will be let  
out again,'' said Lance Kelly, international relations coordinator 
for Switzerland's Sion bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the bid cities criticized the new limits as unfairly  
favoring Sion, which already was visited by most IOC members during 
previous bids. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they had told us one year ago, we would have though twice  
about bidding,'' said Marco San Pietro of Italy's Turin bid, 
echoing complaints from the other five bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	The other cities bidding are Helsinki, Finland; Zakopane,  
Poland; and Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of showing IOC members around, the cities are belatedly  
changing strategies, pumping more funds into an avalanche of 
paperwork, videos and CD-roms. 
</P>
<P>
	Even that is running into IOC restrictions forcing bid cities to  
submit their material to IOC headquarters before it can be sent on 
to the members. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is Soviet-style censorship. It is ridiculous,'' said  
Evelina Christillin, head of the Turin bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Members will be snowed under paperwork ahead of the June 19  
selection in Seoul, South Korea. There, a 15-member panel will trim 
the six hopefuls for 2006 down to a final pair, which will be 
immediately sent to the general assembly for a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The bidders will have an hour-long presentation for the members  
there, a do or die session where more money will now be poured 
into. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the budgets of bidding cities hover around $10-12  
million and some said around $700,000 was earmarked for the IOC 
visitors. Critics of Thursday's decision said that if the IOC was 
so intent of protecting their members from potential corruption, it 
should pay for the visits itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC should arrange travel and pay everything and after the  
visit we get to pay them,'' said Kalt, eager to show that 
Klagenfurt's three nation bid of Austria, Italy and Slovenia is 
really quite compact. 
</P>
<P>
	Saarikangas agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a question of showing your product. Not a question of  
bribing,'' he said, comparing it to the difference between testing 
a car and browsing through a glossy leaflet. 
</P>
<P>
	The cities were allowed to come to the IOC meeting to compensate  
for the loss of exposure to IOC members. But IOC members were 
elusive as the general assembly devoted most of its time to 
expelling six members for corruption and centering on much-needed 
reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nearly impossible to talk to them here. Sometimes they  
drop by to try our chocolates,'' San Pietro said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  2006 Olympic Bidding Different Now </HEADLINE>
