<DOCNO> APW19990318.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Concerned Over Clot-Buster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government says hospitals are again  
experiencing shortages of the clot-busting drug Abbokinase, as the 
manufacturer investigates viral contamination in the factory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration said Abbott Inc. found  
``reovirus'' in three bulk lots of Abbokinase, ingredients mixed up 
and awaiting heat-pasteurization before sale. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not cause for alarm, said FDA's Dr. David Feigal. At most,  
reovirus causes mild cold or gastrointestinal symptoms, and 
pasteurization should kill it, he said. Abbott stressed that 
testing has found no reovirus in finished Abbokinase that was sold. 
Further sales await FDA's approval once additional testing is 
complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the Abbokinase lots were supposed to be sterile,  
so the reovirus illustrates a safety breakdown in manufacturing, 
Feigal said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be asking Abbott to looking at manufacturing methods to  
create the conditions that these types of contaminations don't 
occur,'' he said. In a notice issued late Tuesday, the FDA alerted 
hospitals that ``this is going to create another time period of 
shortage,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Abbokinase, known chemically as urokinase, is one of many drugs  
used to dissolve blood clots. It is made from kidney cells taken 
from foreign newborns who have died. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospitals experienced shortages last fall when the FDA  
temporarily suspended Abbokinase sales, saying Abbott failed to 
ensure the kidney cells were infection-free. No contamination was 
found, so the FDA allowed some sales to resume in January but urged 
doctors to use alternative clot-busters whenever possible. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer group Public Citizen reiterated its call Wednesday  
for an Abbokinase recall until the product is proven sterile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
