<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 21:52:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> America West Airlines May Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- A four-year dispute over wages was coming to a  
head today as America West Airlines prepared for a strike by its 
flight attendants that could begin tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless an agreement is reached, flight attendants could strike  
as early as 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday, a minute after the end of a 
30-day cooling-off period set by the National Mediation Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2,300 attendants have been working without a contract since  
voting to unionize in 1994, three years after America West filed 
for bankruptcy protection and employees took pay cuts designed to 
help the company get back on its feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the company has become profitable, posting record  
earnings in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of America West's flight attendants earn the  
top-scale salary of $23,800. Top-scale flight attendants at rival 
Southwest Airlines earn $41,200. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight attendants also want the same daily expenses as  
pilots receive, $1.80 an hour away from their base city. Currently, 
flight attendants get no per diem allowance. 
</P>
<P>
	Most passengers at Sky Harbor International Airport in Phoenix  
were well aware of the looming strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw this coming,'' said Laura de Leon, who was returning to  
San Jose Thursday with her husband Arnold and 10-month-old daughter 
Amelia. 
</P>
<P>
	Before booking their return flight, de Leon said she checked on  
an Internet Web site to make sure it wouldn't be affected by a 
possible strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``It turned out that we didn't have to change our flight, but we  
definitely made sure,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone was aware of the strike threat.  
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Hemwall of New York was flying to Albuquerque Thursday and  
planned to travel back through Phoenix via America West next week. 
He said he hadn't heard anything about the flight attendants' 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just take my chances. I'm sure something will happen by  
then. Really, I don't want to have to get involved,'' Hemwall said. 
</P>
<P>
	America West serves 53 domestic destinations overall and eight  
cities in Mexico and Canada. The nation's ninth-largest carrier has 
hubs in Phoenix, Las Vegas and Columbus, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Lines at the America West ticket counter were long at Sky Harbor  
on Thursday, but travel agents say their customers are wary of 
booking America West. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're pretty much avoiding America West at all costs and  
trying to go with other airlines,'' said Amy Wright, of Bell Travel 
in Sun City, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if America West has a lower published fare, people are  
tending to buy a more expensive ticket because they don't want to 
be caught in that predicament,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Van Epps of Moon Valley Travel in Phoenix said he's seeing  
the same trend for flights in the next couple of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``But further into the summer, people are still booking America  
West. They figure a strike would be over by then,'' Van Epps said. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel agencies reported a steady stream of America West  
customers trading in electronic tickets for paper tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	America West on Thursday recommended the switch, saying it can  
more easily re-accomodate passengers holding paper tickets to other 
airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's flight attendants say they will stage a series of  
random, unannounced work stoppages -- dubbed CHAOS for ``Creating 
Havoc Around Our System.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has threatened to shut its entire operation down if  
CHAOS begins and has reportedly said it will fire flight attendants 
who participate in the strike. 
</P>
<P>
	America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack said, ``America West will  
not tolerate employees who engage in acts the flight attendants 
describe as CHAOS. If there is a disruption in airline service like 
that the company will take action appropriate to the 
circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Association of Flight Attendants have used a CHAOS strike  
just once before in 1993 against Alaska Airlines. Despite only 
seven flights being canceled, the strike succeeded in driving away 
passengers. Alaska Airlines fired six or seven flight attendants, 
but the courts ordered the airline to give them back their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Zack, a spokesman for the union, said the union has been  
informing members of the possibility of being fired during a 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that happens, we're confident they'll get their jobs  
back,'' Zack said, calling the company's threat illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	America West flight attendants conducted dry run strike  
procedures Thursday and announced that in just seven minutes they 
can successfully prevent any flight from leaving Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Zack said the time includes passing through security, informing  
people at every gate that they're being struck, and reconvening. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
