<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:24:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Lock, Stock' Star Enjoys the Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Some people in England shy away from stardom. But  
not Nick Moran. 
</P>
<P>
	At 30, the once-unknown lead of ``Lock, Stock, and Two Smoking  
Barrels'' speaks happily of leaving anonymity behind, courtesy of a 
cheeky gangland comedy that has had Britain laughing -- and 
cowering. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, he says with a smile over coffee at a south London  
cafe, ``I go to auditions, and they make tea and they polish your 
shoes. Before, people would say, `Who is that upstart? Get out!' 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I could carry a film, but I didn't know I could  
actually, legitimately,'' he says. ``But with `Lock, Stock,' it's 
written in black and white: Can Carry A Film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moran has every right to be likably immodest, given the  
phenomenon that ``Lock, Stock'' has become in Britain since its 
late-summer opening. 
</P>
<P>
	A loopy East End thriller that is funny and knuckle-busting in  
turn, the film struck a particular chord with Britain's youth 
culture, making stars of its little-known quartet of leads, as well 
as a local hero out of Londoner Guy Ritchie, its first-time 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	The film's broader appeal will be tested March 19, when ``Lock,  
Stock'' opens wide in the United States, following an acclaimed 
premiere in January at the Sundance Film Festival in Utah, and 
critical openings in New York and Los Angeles earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	After that, Moran's killer cheekbones may be more than simply  
British tabloid fodder. With three further movies awaiting release 
in 1999, Moran is ready for the big time -- and excited by it as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a No. 1 movie in my own country,'' says Moran, not so  
much warming to a theme as devouring it, well, lock, stock, and 
barrel. ``There are very, very few people who can say that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moran's performance as Eddie, the hapless if charming card shark  
whose misadventures set in motion a Byzantine underworld face-off, 
is the linchpin of a densely plotted scenario. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie's sort of like my flash alter ego,'' Moran says. ``I  
always looked at it as if Eddie was a better-looking version of 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the actor acknowledges that the movie itself -- an ensemble  
piece -- was greater than any individual player, which may explain 
why he was chosen for the role and not Stephen Dorff and Ethan 
Hawke, who were originally mentioned. (The film's biggest names are 
Sting, who took a tiny role because wife Trudie Styler is a 
co-producer, and, in his acting debut, Vinnie Jones, one of the 
``bad boys'' of English soccer.) 
</P>
<P>
	``What's great is that `Lock, Stock' is so full of people  
discovering their own abilities,'' Moran says. ``I don't think Guy 
knew he was an absolutely brilliant director until he made an 
absolutely brilliant film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The oldest of three boys, Moran grew up in what he calls a  
``really heinous'' council estate -- Britain's equivalent of 
low-income housing -- in the north London suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	And while many British actors have parents in the profession,  
Moran says his background was more likely to land him a job at the 
local supermarket. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, ``someone had told me about these mythical places  
called drama schools which I never knew existed. I lied about my 
age, got in, and was just 20 when I left. I did the course and 
inadvertently learned how to act properly,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	It took a decade before ``Lock, Stock'' came, accompanied by  
serious recognition. Before that, Moran spent a year on the West 
End in the musical ``Blood Brothers'' and did a little-seen film, 
``Hard Days, Hard Nights,'' about a Liverpool band that was not the 
Beatles. 
</P>
<P>
	Since ``Lock, Stock'' came out in Britain, Moran has won acclaim  
for a London play, Nick Grosso's ``Real Classy Affair,'' which 
co-starred Joseph Fiennes of ``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And among his upcoming movies, he speaks highly of ``New  
Blood,'' in which he plays John Hurt's son, and a cameo role, again 
with Fiennes, in ``Rancid Aluminum,'' playing a dress-wearing 
schoolboy who deals cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood remains an untapped market that Moran is eager to  
test, but he says he's unlikely to choose a project simply because 
of the budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to do good stuff, not cheesy stuff,'' he says. ``I  
don't have to be in a $50 million or $100 million movie. Something 
like `Lock, Stock' will do me, you know what I mean?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
