<DOCNO> APW19990318.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:35:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Mixed; Wheat, Coffee Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Oil prices were mixed Thursday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange, with crude futures erasing early gains amid some doubts 
about proposed output cuts by most of the world's top producers. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, wheat prices dropped sharply and coffee prices  
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	April crude oil surged to a 5-month high for a second straight  
day on growing confidence that the world glut that has depressed 
prices will soon be alleviated. But the gains were erased late in 
the session as some uncertainty crept into the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuwait was the latest country to indicate it will go along with  
proposed production cuts, telling customers that deliveries will be 
reduced beginning in April. That came one day after Saudi Arabia 
announced plans to cut production by 580,000 barrels a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Arabia, Iran, Venezuela and Mexico last week reached  
agreement on a plan to cut production. The agreement still must be 
formally approved at the meeting of the Organization of the 
Petroleum Exporting Countries next week in Vienna, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	But some market participants are skittish about the plan, said  
Ed Kevelson, a vice president at Paribas Futures Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of countries still haven't detailed their cuts.  
Venezuela's comments have been shaky at best,'' Kevelson said. 
``Venezuela is always the wild card.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevelson pointed out that while oil prices have rallied lately,  
the market remains bearish compared to previous years. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil for April delivery fell 5 cents to $15.00 a barrel.  
April heating oil rose .02 cent to 39.70 cents a gallon; April 
unleaded gasoline fell .17 cent to 47.03 cents a gallon; April 
natural gas fell .61 cents to $1.687 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in May  
rose 10 cents to $13.37 per barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, grain futures were lower and soybeans mostly  
higher in dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were sharply lower, pressured by moisture moving  
across growing regions in the United States, as well as news that 
the dry Chinese wheat belt got rain Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants also digested news of low net export sales.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and corn futures tumbled on dimmed hopes that the  
government could orchestrate an acreage set-aside this year, which 
had been rumored. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were mostly higher with talk of positive overnight  
export business. Likewise, rumors of a last-minute acreage 
set-aside by the government were dismissed by most market 
participants, which weighed on prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just physically can't happen (this year) and I think the  
trade started to realize that today,'' said Don Roose of U.S. 
Commodities Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn finished lower despite hitting 9 1/2-week highs earlier in the  
day. Losses were limited by solid weekly export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery was off 4 cents to $2.73 3/4 a bushel; May  
corn was off 1 1/2 cent to $2.24 1/4 a bushel; May oats were off 1/2 cent 
to $1.11 a bushel; May soybeans were up 3/4 cent to $4.82 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee experienced its biggest decline in about a month after  
the end of a strike by truckers in Colombia, the world's 
second-largest grower. U.S. warehouse inventories are already 
brimming, meaning depressed prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee for May delivery fell 4.55 cents to $1.0265 a pound on  
the Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
