<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Revive Campaign Funding Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats, preparing for possible  
Republican delaying tactics, said Thursday they are launching a 
signature drive to force the House to take up legislation to change 
campaign funding laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, said that by getting 218  
signatures, a majority of House members, on their ``discharge 
petition,'' they could bring the issue to the House floor by late 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the effort are the ``Blue Dogs,'' a group of 29 moderate  
and conservative House Democrats, and Democratic freshmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would do a terrible disservice, not only to our  
constituents, but also to future generations, if we fail to take 
advantage of this window of opportunity,'' said Rep. Brian Baird, 
D-Wash., president of the 23-member Democratic freshman class. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, then-Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., agreed to bring  
campaign finance bills to the floor only after a similar discharge 
petition neared the 218-signature mark. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP leadership, which opposed campaign spending limits, was  
unable to stop the August passage, by 252-179, of a major campaign 
funding bill sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and 
Martin Meehan, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shays-Meehan bill would ban federal ``soft money'' --  
unlimited and unregulated donations to political parties. It also 
would restrict issue ads, which seek to influence elections under 
the guise of educating voters, and expand disclosure requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar measure in the Senate, sponsored by Sens. John McCain,  
R-Ariz., and Russ Feingold, D-Wis., had 52 supporters but was 
unable to garner the 60 votes needed to bring it to a final vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Stenholm said Shays-Meehan again would be the base bill under  
their petition, but that others, including the Republican 
leadership, could offer alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has said he would allow floor  
time this year for the campaign spending issue. But he has not 
responded to a letter from the Democrats seeking a more definite 
date. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala., said he talked to staff in the  
Speaker's office Wednesday, but got no commitment of a time for 
debate. ``We will not be denied this opportunity,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stenholm and other supporters are concerned the debate would get  
pushed back to year's end, when the upcoming election season will 
complicate matters and time might run out for both House and Senate 
consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
