<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Nurses Bill Clears Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A limited number of foreign-trained nurses  
would be allowed to work in short-staffed American hospitals in 
poor, rural and inner-city areas under a proposal that cleared a 
House subcommittee Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The nurses would be allowed to work in U.S. hospitals for up to  
five years. Visas would be capped at 500 per year over the 
four-year life of the program. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Judiciary Committee's immigration panel approved the  
bill by voice vote, sending it to the full committee for further 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospitals must meet certain criteria in order to hire foreign  
nurses. They must be short of nurses, have at least 190 acute care 
beds, a Medicare population of 35 percent and at least 28 percent 
of the patients on Medicaid. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bobby Rush, D-Ill., the primary sponsor, said that while  
there was no nationwide nursing shortage, many hospitals lack a 
sufficient number of health care professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also contains safeguards to protect the jobs of  
American nurses. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar measure passed the House last year but died in the  
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 441.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
