<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Source: Driver Tried To Beat Train  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- A motorist who claims to have been  
directly behind the truck involved in the deadly Amtrak collision 
said the driver tried to snake through lowered crossing gates and 
beat the train, a high-level federal source told The Associated 
Press today. The National Transportation Safety Board source, who 
spoke on the condition of anonymity, said investigators believe the 
motorist is credible and had a clear view of the accident. Monday's 
crash killed 11 people. The engineer in the locomotive has claimed 
the truck driver had tried to zigzag his tractor-trailer through 
the crossing gates after they had come down. 

</P>
<P>
	Arabs Won't Support Iraq  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Arab foreign ministers today again turned  
down Iraq's demands to condemn U.S.-British airstrikes on the 
country, declaring instead that Iraq should comply fully with U.N. 
resolutions. In a joint statement issued at the end of their 
two-day meeting, the ministers only demanded ``a halt to any action 
against Iraq outside the mandate of the related (U.N.) Security 
Council resolutions.'' The statement did not refer directly to the 
airstrikes or name the United States and Britain. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Orders Analysis of Lab Threat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today ordered an analysis of  
the security threat at U.S. nuclear labs in the wake of suspicions 
that China stole weapons designs. Clinton directed the President's 
Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board to conduct a review. Former 
Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., the head of the panel, will lead the 
investigation. ``I am determined to do all that is necessary to 
protect our sensitive national security information and to prevent 
its diversion to foreign countries,'' Clinton said in a statement. 

</P>
<P>
	Missile Defense Bill Passes House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Closely following Senate approval of a  
missile-defense bill, the House today passed its own version of a 
system to protect the 50 states against limited ballistic missile 
attacks. ``We have no defense today against any missile system. It 
is a national priority that this Congress needs to address,'' Rep. 
Curt Weldon, R-Pa., chief sponsor of the legislation, told 
colleagues. The bill, approved 317-102 by the House, would commit 
the Pentagon to building the system. 

</P>
<P>
	Balloonists Set Course for Africa  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Two weary balloonists reached the  
skies over the Atlantic Ocean today and have made it three-quarters 
of the way around the world in their attempt to conquer one of 
aviation's most elusive goals. Bertrand Piccard of Switzerland and 
Brian Jones of England headed out over the Atlantic Ocean, hoping 
for a possible Sunday morning landing in northwest Africa. By this 
afternoon, Jones, a 51-year-old balloon instructor, and Piccard, a 
41-year-old physician, had traveled 21,985 miles of the 26,000-mile 
odyssey that began with a March 1 liftoff from the Swiss Alps. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Hits 10,000 But Closes Under  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average today posted a  
record close of 9,997.62, up 118.21 points, after cracking 10,000 
six times but pulling back each time. On Tuesday, the Dow briefly 
traded as high as 10,001.78 before slipping back. A spark for 
today's advance was the report that consumer prices rose 0.1 
percent last month. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,559-1,390. 
The Nasdaq rose 33.99 to 2,462.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Addresses Privacy Problem  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. offered two free software  
programs on its Internet site today to strip out an identifying 
number that could be used to trace the authorship of some 
electronic documents. One program is a small patch to repair the 
problem and prevent the number from being planted in such 
documents. The second removes the number from existing documents. 
Microsoft confirmed earlier this month that its latest version of 
Windows generates a unique serial number for each computer. That 
number partly is planted within some documents created with its 
popular collection of Office 97 business programs, which include 
Word and Excel. 

</P>
<P>
	Boxing Judge Discusses Controversy  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The judge at the center of the controversial  
Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield draw said today that her view of the 
fight was obscured at times by photographers. Testifying at a New 
York state Senate hearing, Eugenia Williams also said that after 
watching a tape of Saturday's heavyweight unification fight, she 
would have scored it a draw, instead of 115-113 for Holyfield. That 
scoring wouldn't have changed the ultimate outcome of the bout, 
though. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
