<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temple Preps for Purdue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- There's a four-letter word Temple coach John  
Chaney doesn't want his players to utter, and it begins with ``D.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If you guessed ``Duke,'' you would be right. Just try not to  
mention the name of the top-ranked team to the Owls again until 
after sixth-seeded Temple's East Regional semifinal game Friday 
against 10th-seeded Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some guys who look too far ahead make a lot of blunders. I  
just want them to win today, just win now,'' Chaney said before his 
team departed Philadelphia on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	If Temple (23-10) beats Purdue (21-12), they could face  
top-seeded Duke, assuming the Blue Devils defeat 12th-seed 
Southwest Missouri State in Friday's other semifinal at the 
Meadowlands in East Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect to convince my team that the most important thing  
that happens to you is what happens today, not yesterday, not 
tomorrow,'' Chaney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that his players need much convincing in the first place,  
especially with last year's 82-52 first-round loss to West Virginia 
still lingering in their minds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Karcher, who sat out last season because of academics,  
remembers watching the game on television. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still can't believe (I'm here). I remember last year I was  
home watching the game with my grandmother. It was a bad feeling,'' 
said Karcher, who leads Temple in scoring with 13 points per game. 
``The whole time I was watching, I was saying to myself, `Man, I 
wish I was playing.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Karcher hopes to step up his shooting against Purdue. After  
scoring in double figures for 15 straight games, the 6-foot-5 
forward has managed just 11 points on 3-for-12 shooting in the 
first two tournament games and has been hampered by foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes down to fundamentals,'' Chaney said. ``The guys who  
make a lot more errors, the guys who try to hit home runs, the guys 
who concentrate on the small things, don't make it. We always go 
back to A-B-C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Boilermakers have been up and down all season, entering the  
tournament having lost four of five games. But upset wins over 
Texas and Miami in the NCAA tournament have Purdue on the upswing 
again, with Purdue's man-to-man defense holding second-seeded Miami 
to a season-low 32.9 percent shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Temple's matchup zone keys their play. The Owls have  
limited opponents to 37.8 percent shooting, including 36 percent 
from 3-point range. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside, Temple's 6-10 forward Lamont Barnes, who has averaged  
13.5 points in the tournament, might be able to take advantage of 
Purdue's front line, which has no starter taller than 6-8. Pepe 
Sanchez has averaged 14.5 points the last two games, but the point 
guard is even more essential in keying the Owls' defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Purdue) is a physical team, and they play great defense,''  
said Temple sixth man Quincy Wadley, who is still nursing a bruised 
hand but is expected to play Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``But defense has been our philosophy, too. Our defense -- that's  
been the key to our success,'' Wadley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
