<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 25.53 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were higher at midday as investors  
reacted to another positive report on inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
25.53 at 9,904.94. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher as well, with the Standard  
&AMP; Poor's 500 index up 7.00 at 1,304.82, and the technology-heavy 
Nasdaq composite index up 9.82 at 2,438.79. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Dow fell 51.06 to 9,879.41 after briefly  
crossing 10,000 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose this morning after the Labor Department reported  
consumer prices rose a tiny 0.1 percent last month, a signal that 
inflation is under control. That news boosted prices in the bond 
market, where the 30-year Treasury bond was up 9/32 point and its 
yield, which moves opposite the price, was at 5.48 percent, down 
from 5.5 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were unfazed by a separate report from the Commerce  
Department that the nation's trade deficit shot up 21 percent in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	They were also undisturbed by the continuing rise in oil prices,  
which longer-term could prove inflationary. ``Oil is turning the 
corner,'' said Gregory Nie, a technical analyst at Everen 
Securities in Chicago, ``but there will be a proving period over 
the short term where you get a correction in crude that will take a 
little starch out of this move up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were higher today, with Dow member Exxon up 1 at 75 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
	Dow components were also led higher by financial services  
stocks, which reacted positively to a report that Chase Manhattan 
Corp. is looking for a merger partner. Chase shares were up 1 1/16 
at 83 7/16. American Express was leading the Dow components higher 
and was up 3 5/16 at 124 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest Inc. of  
Hartford, Conn., said Friday's triple expiration of options and 
futures contracts lent a slightly positive bias to stock prices 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Shaughnessy said, ``the fundamentals of the market  
remain solid. Inflation is benign, the economy is in good shape, 
profits will start to pick up this quarter.'' He predicts the Dow 
will rise to 10,600 by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues edged out decliners by 1,422 to 1,345 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 364.53 million 
shares, up from Wednesday's pace of 337.61 million. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
