<DOCNO> APW19990318.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 00:32:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Department, Bosnia Links Eyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In contacts under federal investigation,  
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott's brother-in-law received 
thousands of dollars from an associate of accused war criminal 
Radovan Karadzic around the time he tried to arrange the Bosnian 
fugitive's surrender, according to lawyers and government 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott's brother-in-law, Cody P. Shearer, is now telling  
authorities he has received mail threats from Bosnian figures who 
claim he took the money in 1997 with promises to win leniency for 
Karadzic on the war crimes charges, and demand that he pay 
Karadzic's family $1 million or risk ``tragedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shearer's lawyer denies those claims and says the money his  
client received was reimbursement for expenses he incurred while 
helping the Karadzic associate. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before Shearer reported the threats, the State Department  
inspector general and the FBI had begun investigating whether he 
misrepresented his ties to the Clinton administration in his 
dealings with the Bosnian figures, several government officials 
told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The contacts include a meeting Shearer had with Karadzic's  
family, a letter he received from the accused war criminal, his 
efforts to introduce a Karadzic associate, physicist Dragan 
Hajdukovic, to the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague, 
Netherlands, in 1997 and his efforts to assist Hajdukovic's 
advocacy of a Bosnia peace plan, according to documents and 
interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Karadzic was indicted by the war crimes tribunal in 1995 for  
geonicide in the massacre of thousands of Muslims after Bosnian 
Serb forces captured Srebrenica, which had been designated as a 
U.N. ``safe zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Documents show U.S. officials knew that Shearer was dealing with  
Hajdukovic to arrange a possible surrender by Karadzic as early as 
summer 1997. A senior U.S. official, who spoke on condition of 
anonymity, said Talbott was told about it at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	A year later when reports surfaced that Hajdukovic was promoting  
a plan that would undo the 1995 Dayton peace accords for Bosnia, 
Talbott sent a letter to Shearer suggesting such contacts were 
better left to the U.S. special emissary for the region, Robert 
Gelbard. 
</P>
<P>
	Shearer's lawyer, William Murphy, said his client received  
payments of less than $25,000 from Hajdukovic in fall 1997 and the 
money was used as reimbursement for expenses and a donation to a 
group Shearer runs. Murphy said Shearer paid phone and living 
expenses for Hajdukovic as the physicist promoted his own peace 
plan for Bosnia and later tried to arrange Karadzic's surrender. 
</P>
<P>
	Karadzic, who led the Bosnian Serbs during 3 1/2 years of civil war  
that left 200,000 dead, remains at large. 
</P>
<P>
	One issue for investigators is how Shearer, who visited Bosnia  
as a journalist and head of a tax-exempt peace organization, 
represented his ties to his diplomat brother-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	In a February 1996 letter, for instance, Shearer wrote  
Hajdukovic claiming the Bosnian had played a ``an unheralded, 
critical role in bringing peace to Bosnia'' and securing the 
release of a U.S. journalist and French pilots held captive there. 
</P>
<P>
	Shearer wrote that Talbott had been ``absolutely amazed at your  
work and contacts'' and suggested he had talked to Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright, then the U.N. ambassador, and President 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Hajdukovic says Shearer invoked the names of Clinton and  
Talbott. ``He said, 'If you can show to my big friends, meaning his 
brother-in-law and president, that you can offer a serious line of 
negotiation, military action to capture Karadzic would not 
happen,''' Hajdukovic said in a telephone interview from Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy demurred. ``Cody always made it clear to Mr. Hajdukovic  
that he was not an official representative of the United States nor 
would he act as an emissary to representatives of the U.S. 
government,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past month, Hajdukovic and other Bosnians sent at least  
eight letters to Shearer and his lawyers alleging he had reneged on 
promises to ``moderate'' or ``abolish'' the war crimes charges 
against Karadzic and claiming the money he received came directly 
from Karadzic's family, Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyer said Shearer never was told the money had come from  
Karadzic or had any connection to the war crimes case. 
</P>
<P>
	``The letters that Mr. Shearer recently received were troubling  
and prompted us to forward all of them to the FBI so that they 
might investigate whether Mr. Shearer is the victim of an attempted 
extortion,'' Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hajdukovic acknowledged sending some of the letters and said  
Shearer had been paid substantially more than the $25,000. He would 
not say how much. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I ask is not to blackmail, I simply ask that he repay the  
funds he received, nothing less and nothing more,'' Hajdukovic 
said. Hajdukovic declined to say where the money came from. 
</P>
<P>
	Shearer is the brother of Brooke Shearer, who is married to  
Talbott. Shearer's brother, Derek, was Clinton's ambassador to 
Finland. 
</P>
<P>
	When the contacts were first disclosed last fall by former GOP  
congressional investigator David Bossie, U.S. officials said Cody 
Shearer was not acting on behalf of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
the State Department's present assessment is that Karadzic tried to 
use the Hajdukovic-Shearer connection to claim influence with 
Talbott and Clinton and ``sow seeds of discontent'' among Bosnian 
Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents reviewed by the AP indicate that Shearer met with  
Karadzic's mother and brothers in Montenegro in 1997, then received 
a letter from the fugitive indicating he was willing to consider a 
surrender to the Hague tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of any risky acts, I am ready to cooperate in ... a  
resolution of the Hague problem,'' Karadzic wrote Shearer. ``I 
don't know how the Hague problem is going to be resolved. I am not 
concerned with my destiny, nor am I afraid from what may happen to 
me but I do have a good case, since I did not do anything wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shearer forwarded the letter to his brother, the former  
ambassador. His fax, dated Aug. 25, 1997, stated he had met 
Karadzic's mother and brothers in Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	His family and others said that if Karadzic died in a military  
capture raid, ``the Serb part of Bosnia will go up in flames and 
Dayton (peace accords) will be killed forever,'' Shearer reported 
to his brother. 
</P>
<P>
	Shearer requested that a ``responsible U.S. official'' contact  
Hajdukovic. Shearer's fax was forwarded to a State Department 
lawyer who reports to Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	According to both Hajdukovic and an associate close to Shearer,  
who spoke only on condition of anonymity, Shearer introduced 
Hajdukovic to a lawyer at the war crimes tribunal in late summer 
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
