<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Awarded $14.5M in FB Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A boy who suffered brain damage while  
playing high school football has won a roughly $15 million jury 
award from the company that made the boy's helmet. 
</P>
<P>
	After six hours of deliberation Wednesday, federal jurors  
awarded $11.45 million to Joe Rodriguez, a former Los Fresnos High 
School football player, and his mother, Raquel Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	Pre-judgment interest currently puts the total award around  
$14.5 million, plaintiffs lawyer Arnold Aguilar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago-based Riddell Sports Inc. has promised to appeal the  
decision. Riddell is the biggest producer of football protective 
equipment and supplies helmets and pads for the NFL. Revenue for 
last year topped $186 million. 
</P>
<P>
	During the six-day trial, the plaintiffs argued that Riddell  
could have provided a safer, more-padded helmet than the one 
Rodriguez was wearing. The company had, in fact, made such a helmet 
but chose not to sell it, Aguilar argued. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had the materials to make a better helmet,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Riddell lawyers argued that Rodriguez could have had a previous  
medical problem, such as a brain aneurysm, that was aggravated by 
the blow he took to the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez was 19 in August 1995, when he was thrown to the  
ground and landed on his head during a scrimmage. He walked to the 
sideline and collapsed minutes later. Today, he is in a vegetative 
state and is fed through a tube. Doctors expect him to live only 15 
more years, and his medical bills run about $125,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors listened to six days of conflicting testimony from expert  
witnesses, including doctors and engineers who disagreed on whether 
the helmet Rodriguez was wearing or an improved helmet would have 
prevented his injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyer Bob Guerra, who represented Riddell, declined comment  
Wednesday and didn't return a phone call from the Associated Press 
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell officials in Chicago also did not return a phone call,  
but in a statement said that even if the verdict stands, it is 
responsible for only $750,000 in damages. The rest is covered by 
its insurance, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We disagree sharply with the verdict and plan to aggressively  
appeal this case,'' the statement said. ``The facts, in our view, 
are not consistent with the verdict that was rendered.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
