<DOCNO> APW19990318.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Movies Revisit Cold War Over Kazan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Time has done nothing to quell the  
hurt and anger felt by those on Hollywood's blacklist toward the 
people who named their names. 
</P>
<P>
	At a raucous news conference Thursday, blacklisted screenwriters  
displayed ads bought in Hollywood trade papers denouncing a special 
Oscar going to director Elia Kazan, who identified Communist Party 
members during infamous hearings nearly 50 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``His actions did enormous damage to the motion picture  
industry, as well as established throughout the country a climate 
of fear which suppressed creativity and silenced dissent,'' says 
the ads to appear today in the Hollywood Reporter and Variety. 
</P>
<P>
	The ads were unveiled by members of a group called the Committee  
Against Silence. At the event, interrupted by a heckler shouting 
``Communism is evil!,'' writers, entertainment union members and 
others said Kazan's testimony in 1952 denied many of his colleagues 
the opportunities for the same accomplishments he is being honored 
for. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ruined and destroyed their careers, their families, their  
lives,'' said Norma Barzman, a 78-year-old blacklisted writer whose 
name was restored this month to the 1953 film ``Luxury Girls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 89-year-old Kazan will receive the lifetime achievement  
Oscar during Sunday night's televised ceremony. His critics have 
called on audience members to refrain from applauding when he 
accepts his award. 
</P>
<P>
	At a separate news conference, Academy president Robert Rehme  
said the award was solely for Kazan's ``body of work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a good side to the protest, it is that it has made  
people aware of that terrible period of our history and the impact 
of that,'' he said. ``But we stand by our award to Mr. Kazan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People who support the award have formed a group called the Ad  
Hoc Committee for Naming Facts, calling on Academy members to wear 
American flag lapel pins to the ceremony. Both sides have promised 
to demonstrate outside the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion. 
</P>
<P>
	Blacklisted actor John Randolph, who has appeared in ``Serpico''  
and ``You've Got Mail,'' said Kazan gave credibility to the 
hearings by the House Un-American Activities Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a question of forgiveness. It's a question of  
remembrance,'' Randolph said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazan has declined to comment on the controversy.  
</P>
<P>
	Kazan, who had once been a member of the Communist Party,  
informed on eight friends from the Group Theater, the best known of 
whom were playwright Clifford Odets and actress Paula Strasberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, the director never issued a blanket apology, but  
made it clear that he agonized over his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Even to his detractors, Kazan has long been considered one of  
the greatest stage and film directors. His debut film, ``A Tree 
Grows in Brooklyn'' in 1945, earned an Oscar for supporting actor 
James Dunn. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, Kazan won a directing Oscar for ``Gentleman's  
Agreement,'' which also was named best picture. His second Oscar 
was for ``On the Waterfront,'' the 1954 film that made Marlon 
Brando a star. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazan also was nominated for ``A Streetcar Named Desire''  
(1951), ``East of Eden'' (1955) and ``America'' (1963). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitewater Defense Gets Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Attempting to put Kenneth Starr's  
tactics on trial, lawyers for Susan McDougal want to call the 
Whitewater prosecutor's top deputy to the witness stand. But a 
judge ruled today the defense must first spell out in more detail 
what questions will be asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting on a request from Starr's office, U.S. District Judge  
George Howard ordered Mrs. McDougal's lawyers to provide a better 
summary of their questions for Deputy Independent Counsel Hickman 
Ewing and told the two sides to try to reach an agreement on 
Ewing's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Court papers filed earlier by Starr's office suggested the  
defense lawyers' summary might be used to fight an appearance by 
Ewing or to try to block some questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal is charged with criminal contempt and obstruction  
of justice for failing to answer questions before Starr's grand 
jury. Her lawyer, Mark Geragos, has portrayed her as a mistreated 
pawn in prosecutors' overzealous pursuit of President and Mrs. 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office argued that federal regulations require that the  
defense must disclose ahead of time what information is being 
sought when a U.S. attorney is called as a witness. 
</P>
<P>
	``We already told them what we wanted to talk to Ewing about,''  
Geragos said outside of court. ``Now they want more detail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to prosecutors, Geragos said he planned to ask Ewing  
about: any conversations he recalled regarding Mrs. McDougal's 
``cooperation'' with the Whitewater grand jury; the circumstances 
surrounding her grand jury appearance; and why prosecutors believe 
she acted with corrupt intent when she refused to answer questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office complained that the letter was too vague and  
``contains only three sentences describing the areas of inquiry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The legal wrangling came as Mrs. McDougal's lawyers prepared to  
call their first witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution rested its case after seven days, ending this  
morning with testimony from an Arkansas banker, Ron Proctor, who 
dealt with the original loan for the Whitewater land development. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing watched from the rear of the courtroom Wednesday as the  
prosecution closed its case by summoning three former members of 
the Whitewater grand jury before whom Mrs. McDougal had refused to 
testify. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the day, Bill Henley, Mrs. McDougal's brother,  
reached through a crowd of reporters and handed Ewing a subpoena, 
saying, ``Hick, I've got something for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt really good,'' Bill Henley said a few moments later.  
``It's about time we got to ask them a few questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said later he didn't think prosecutors would try to block  
his appearance at the behest of the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing to hide,'' Ewing said.  
</P>
<P>
	But he hinted at a possible legal dispute ahead over how far  
afield Mrs. McDougal's lawyers should be allowed to range in 
questioning the Whitewater prosecutor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos would not rule out summoning Starr as well. ``First let  
me deal with Hick Ewing,'' he said. ``One at a time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Making a prosecutor a defense witness was the second unusual  
turn of the day. The first was putting on the witness stand three 
members of the grand jury that indicted Mrs. McDougal after she 
refused to answer their questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said that in 25 years as a federal prosecutor he had never  
seen grand jurors testify at a criminal trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand jury foreman John Washam testified that the death of Mrs.  
McDougal's former husband, James McDougal, in 1998 made her 
testimony even more crucial than it had been before. 
</P>
<P>
	With James McDougal's death, ``one link of the chain was gone''  
of people who knew what went on in Whitewater, said Washam. 
McDougal had been Starr's chief cooperating witness in his 
investigation of the Whitewater land deal in which the Clintons and 
McDougals were partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos focused on the fact that Starr's office didn't tell  
grand jurors James McDougal had changed his story a number of 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wouldn't you have wanted to hear that?'' Geragos asked grand  
juror Marsha High. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' she responded.  
</P>
<P>
	Geragos argues that his client didn't want to answer questions  
because overzealous prosecutors were trying to force her to give 
false testimony against the president and first lady Hillary Rodham 
Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
