<HEADLINE> Report: Louis Farrakhan Is Ailing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan is  
reported to be gravely ill, but the Muslim group's leaders would 
not release any information about his condition Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan, who was treated for prostate cancer several years  
ago, has been ill since early January with an undiagnosed 
condition, according to an article in The Final Call, the Nation of 
Islam's newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan said the current illness ``took me down so fast, that  
it concerned me greatly because, though I'm nearing 66, I have 
never been sick like this in my life,'' the newspaper reported in a 
March 10 update on its Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	During a Feb. 28 speech in Chicago, Farrakhan said he lost 20  
pounds and most of his muscle mass in less than two weeks and had 
``no appetite, night sweats, dealing with the after effects of 
radiation therapy (for prostate cancer) and other things,'' 
according to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls seeking comment Thursday from the newspaper's editors, a  
Nation of Islam spokesman and Farrakhan were not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Final Call scheduled a press conference Friday to ``respond  
to rumors about the Honorable Louis Farrakhan's health.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan has sometimes rankled U.S. officials with his  
outspoken support of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, whom he has 
visited several times, and his negative comments about Jews, 
Christians, white people and the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan reportedly was treated for prostate cancer by  
Gadhafi's doctors after announcing he had the illness in 1991. He 
most recently met with Gadhafi in November -- his fifth visit to 
Libya in three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
