<DOCNO> APW19990318.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 08:15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Hears Airstrikes Briefing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon's top military commanders warned  
today that there could be U.S. casualties if NATO launches 
airstrikes against Serb positions in an effort to pressure Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's air defenses are sophisticated and heavily  
defended, Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff, told the 
Senate Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a distinct possibility we will lose aircraft in  
trying to penetrate those defenses,'' Ryan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is going to be tremendously dangerous,'' Marine Corps  
Commandant Gen. Charles Krulak agreed. Serbian air defense systems 
``are mobile. The terrain is very tough. And the weather cannot be 
underestimated,'' Krulak said. He said there were some 
``bottom-line question'' that still need to be answered: ``What is 
the end game? How long will the strike go on? Will our allies stay 
with us?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony came as the Senate prepared to debate the Kosovo  
issue later in the day, including a move by some members to block 
funds for sending U.S. troops to Kosovo to help enforce a peace 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Dennis Reimer, the Army chief of staff, told the committee  
that the ``current criteria for commitment'' on the ground remains 
a still-elusive peacekeeping agreement. President Clinton has said 
he's prepared to send up to 4,000 U.S. troops to Kosovo as part of 
a 28,000-member NATO peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	``Troops that would be earmarked for that are prepared to do  
that,'' Reimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va., said he was troubled by  
the massing of Serbian forces on the border with Kosovo. ``That 
calculus seems to me to me that they are ready for extensive ground 
operations,'' Warner said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you are correct, Mr. Chairman,'' Reimer said. ``We are  
watching that very closely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony by the military commanders came as peace  
negotiations in Paris seemed on the verge of collapse. Stymied by 
the Serbs, the Clinton administration was seeking to establish 
friendly ties with the Kosovar Albanians, who are trying to wriggle 
free of Yugoslavia's control. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright invited Hashim Thaci and  
other members of the ethnic Albanian delegation here for talks on 
their political goals, and they accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to develop a good relationship with them as they  
transform themselves into a politically oriented organization under 
a Kosovo living in peace,'' said James Foley, the deputy State 
Department spokesman, after disclosing that spokesman James Rubin 
had flown unannounced to Paris to deliver Albright's invitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Rubin's taking on that unusual role, Foley said he  
had developed ``rapport'' with the ethnic Albanians in earlier 
rounds of negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright has also employed Bob Dole, the defeated Republican  
presidential candidate, to deal with the insurgents who gave their 
formal approval to the plan this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-nation plan the Serbs are resisting would give the  
ethnic Albanians control over schools, police and other day-to-day 
activities, but not the independence many have sought and battled 
Serb troops for. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo Liberation Army, a guerrilla group, has spearheaded  
the secession movement in the Serbian province. Its members, under 
the peace plan, would be eligible to be part of the police force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to develop closer and better ties with that  
organization,'' Foley said, referring to the Kosovar Albanians' 
drive for political acceptance. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have sought discussions and assistance from us in this  
regard, with an eye toward their future role under a peace accord 
in Kosovo,'' Foley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration persisted in its drive to persuade  
members of Congress it is a good idea to send U.S. troops to Kosovo 
as part of a NATO peacekeeping force if a settlement somehow is 
concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed  
Services Committee, said he and several other Republicans do not 
believe Americans should be sent into military action to solve 
Europe's civil wars. 
</P>
<P>
	Spence complained that the United States had spent about $10  
billion for troop deployments and military operations in Bosnia and 
will lay out $1.5 billion to $2 billion a year to continue the 
mission, which has no time limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright and other administration officials have threatened the  
Serbs with a NATO attack if they blocked a settlement that had 
Albanian approval and if they broke a cease-fire established for 
Kosovo last October. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, told Congress that  
Serb forces were prepared to resume fighting in Kosovo on a ``very 
large scale'' if no accord was reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright assessed the bleak situation in separate telephone  
calls to French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and Russian Foreign 
Minister Igor Ivanov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 18:03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Recruiting Is Hampered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Military recruiting efforts are being hampered  
by parents and teachers who view the armed forces as a ``last 
option'' for students unable to get into college or find good jobs, 
recruiters told lawmakers Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have parents out there that forget what made America  
America,'' Army Sgt. Monica Duncan-Boney of St. Louis told a House 
Armed Services subcommittee. ``We have a lot of walls to break 
down. We have to show the military is a No. 1 option.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Navy Petty Officer Dahlia Clow of San Antonio said teachers and  
principals believe they have failed if they don't get students into 
college and they don't consider the educational benefits of the 
military, which provides schooling, training and university grants. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is with the attitude of educators,'' Clow said.  
``The military to them is the last option for their students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force Sgt. Robert Austin, a recruiter from Oklahoma City,  
said high schools often provide college representatives with lists 
of seniors but decline to give the names and phone numbers to the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision on whether to allow military recruiters on campus is  
left up to individual school districts and principals, Austin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that if they're federally funded, they shouldn't be  
able to tell us we can't come into the school,'' Austin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers on the House Armed Services Committee's military  
personnel panel didn't indicate whether any of them would propose 
mandatory recruiter access to high schools that receive federal 
funds. Nearly all public high schools receive some form of federal 
funding. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hawaii Rep. Neil Abercrombie, the ranking Democrat on the  
subcommittee, said, ``I think that's a good idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress in 1994 approved legislation denying military grants  
and contracts to colleges that barred recruiters. Two years later, 
lawmakers increased the penalty to ban federal student aid to 
universities that did not allow military officials on campus. 
</P>
<P>
	Abercrombie also said he was pleased that Army Secretary Louis  
Caldera is looking at accepting more non-high school graduates as 
long as they have their GED equivalent certificates and pass 
entrance tests. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., who chaired the subcommittee  
hearing, said he and many other Republicans are opposed to 
accepting more recruits without high school diplomas or lowering 
other standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that further reductions to recruit quality standards  
present a very costly and dangerous risk to military readiness that 
must be avoided,'' Graham said. ``Quality recruits are essential to 
maintaining the warrior ethos so essential to combat readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Defense Secretary William Cohen and other Pentagon  
officials haven't endorsed Caldera's GED acceptance proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	All the recruiters representing the services except the Army  
rejected a proposal by Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman 
John Warner, R-Va., to shorten some military enlistments from 
several years to 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner made the proposal in a letter to the military chiefs,  
saying the plan might attract recruits who don't want to serve four 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army already has a two-year program. But Navy, Air Force and  
Marine officials argue it would be too difficult and costly to 
train people for high-tech military jobs without a four-year 
commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would lead to a higher turnover,'' Austin said, making  
recruiting an even tougher job as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, at least 90 percent of Army recruits must have high school  
diplomas, a standard set by the Defense Department. The Navy, faced 
with more than 20,000 job vacancies, also has recently begun 
accepting more recruits who don't have a high school diploma. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Corps and Air Force, which historically have had the  
least trouble recruiting, have been adding recruiters and boosting 
advertising so they won't face large shortfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera said he expects the Army to fall short of its goal of  
recruiting 74,000 soldiers this fiscal year. The Navy, which fell 
6,900 short this year, also is heading toward a shortfall, as is 
the Air Force. The Marine Corps is expected to be the only service 
to make its recruitment quota for fiscal year 1999, which ends 
Sept. 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
