<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Touches 10,000; Ends at 9,997.62 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average cracked 10,000  
six times today but pulled back each time, finishing a nail-biting 
session less than three points below the mark. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip index ended at 9,997.62, up 118.21 points on the  
day. It was the second day that the Dow crossed 10,000 but failed 
to hold its gains -- on Tuesday, the index briefly traded as high as 
10,001.78 but slipped back and closed with a loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad market indexes made substantial gains as well today,  
indicating a broader and perhaps more durable advance in the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 18.73 to 1,316.55 , and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 33.99 to 2462.96. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-8 margin on the  
NYSE, with 1,559 up, 1,390 down and 613 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 827.39 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
749.79 million the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 6.96 to 617.61, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index declined 0.97 to 714.86. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.12 to 399.55.  
</P>
<P>
	But while the broader indexes showed Wall Street had some brawn,  
advancing issues still barely edged out decliners on the New York 
Stock Exchange, and volume was moderately heavy. 
</P>
<P>
	The immediate spark for today's advance was a Labor Department  
report this morning that consumer prices rose a tiny 0.1 percent 
last month. That was a confirmation that inflation remains in check 
and a signal that the Federal Reserve is unlikely to raise 
short-term interest rates anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer price report boosted prices in the bond market,  
where the 30-year Treasury bond was up 3/8 point and its yield, which 
moves opposite from its price, fell to 5.47 percent from 5.5 
percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders also attributed the advance to Friday's triple  
expiration of futures and options contracts, which added a layer of 
excitement and volatility. 
</P>
<P>
	But the momentum for Dow 10,000 has been building for a long  
time with an extraordinary alignment of positive events, including 
low interest rates, a very strong U.S. economy that is prompting 
consumers to buy everything from stocks to socks, and the recent 
perception that the world's economic trouble spots are recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the real prime mover is the obliteration of  
inflation expectations and successful completion of a conflict, the 
Cold War, and with that finished, changing dynamics in the world 
economy,'' said Joseph Battipaglia, chairman of investment policy 
at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``These fundamental drivers are critical to 
attracting ... money'' into the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors seemed bent on driving the blue-chip index above the  
benchmark figure. They were unfazed by a separate report from the 
Commerce Department that the nation's trade deficit shot up 21 
percent in January. 
</P>
<P>
	They were also undisturbed by the continuing rise in oil prices,  
which longer-term could prove inflationary. ``Oil is turning the 
corner,'' said Gregory Nie, a technical analyst at Everen 
Securities in Chicago, ``but there will be a proving period over 
the short term where you get a correction in crude that will take a 
little starch out of this move up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, higher oil prices today fed the advance of oil stocks.  
</P>
<P>
	Dow components were also led higher by financial services  
stocks, which reacted positively to the drop in interest rates and 
a report that Chase Manhattan Corp. is looking for a merger 
partner. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
