<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The head of the Episcopal Church has rebuffed a  
protest from other national branches in the Anglican Communion over 
the Americans' liberal policy on homosexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	Last August the world's Anglican bishops voted 526-70 for a  
declaration that homosexual acts are ``incompatible with 
Scripture.'' But the Episcopal Church, the U.S. branch of 
Anglicanism, has allowed each bishop to decide, and several endorse 
gay and lesbian clergy and same-sex couples. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter dated Feb. 26, the leaders of Anglican branches in  
Kenya, Rwanda, Tanzania, Australia, the Middle East, South America 
and Southeast Asia wrote Presiding Bishop Frank T. Griswold, asking 
all U.S. bishops to comply with the declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	Griswold replied that divergent opinions exist in the United  
States and other Anglican branches. ``We therefore find ourselves 
in a process of discernment and 'testing the spirits','' he said. 
He invited the complainants to visit and talk personally with 
homosexuals and bishops who support them. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Episcopal priest evicted    	
</P>
<P>
	BROCKTON, Mass. (AP) -- An Episcopal priest has been evicted from  
church grounds in a dispute over gay rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The court order came after a long-running feud between members  
of a conservative congregation, St. Paul's Church, and a liberal 
diocese led by Bishop Thomas Shaw. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may have lost access to our church building, but we have  
not lost faith,'' the Rev. Thomas Morris said. ``In the end, Jesus 
wins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris' followers claim they have been at odds with church  
officials since earlier in the decade, when the diocese elected to 
sanction same-sex marriages and ordain homosexuals as priests. St. 
Paul's then began withholding fees it was bound to pay the diocese. 
</P>
<P>
	A Superior Court judge granted a preliminary injunction against  
Morris, forcing him to vacate the building. But Judge Charles J. 
Hely wrote in his decision the issue was not religion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The defendants have no legal authority whatsoever to ownership  
or control of the real and personal property of St. Paul's 
Episcopal Church,'' he wrote, adding, ``The undisputed facts of 
this motion do not require the court to attempt to resolve any 
religious doctrine controversy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Edward W. Rodman, a diocese spokesman, said the diocese  
embraces homosexuality because it is ``inappropriate to single out 
any group of people or sin as being worse than any other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Episcopal bishop resigns    	
</P>
<P>
	SOMERSET, N.J. (AP) -- The bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of New  
Jersey is taking a leave of absence before the end of June and will 
resign in September 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``I looked on the one hand at the battered and beleaguered  
diocese, and on the other hand I looked at the progress that has 
been made. ... In doing so, I came to the conclusion that I am in 
the way,'' Bishop Joe Morris Doss said in announcing his 
resignation at an annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics in the diocese that covers central and southern New  
Jersey disapprove of Doss' leadership style, and some mistrust him. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop Clayton Matthews, an official with the national church,  
said the resignation was highly unusual. He said an interim bishop 
will be appointed to head the diocese until September 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Doss said his role has been as a lightning rod  
and his tenure incited controversy because he brought deep-rooted 
problems to the surface. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters have said his liberal stance on social issues  
including homosexuality are too much for conservatives in the 
diocese. The Rev. Alan French, president of the Diocesan Standing 
Committee and a Doss critic, said the problems stem from Doss' 
leadership style. 
</P>
<P>
	``It had nothing to do with ideology,'' French said. ``I think  
that's totally unfounded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Lutheran bishop vows rural aid    	
</P>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The Evangelical Lutheran Church wants to do  
something to ease the farm crisis in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop H. George Anderson, who leads more than 5 million  
Lutherans nationwide, said his church will try to listen and 
administer to the needs of farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson spoke at ``Sowing Seeds of Hope,'' a church conference  
of Great Plains pastors and lay leaders called to discuss the rural 
crisis. The Evangelical Lutheran Church is trying to understand how 
it can be most effective in helping people survive the crisis, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Nebraska, the church has set aside $500,000 for a national  
``rural concerns desk'' that, among other things, could lobby for 
changes in laws that affect the agricultural community. 
</P>
<P>
	Gretchen Ritola, an assistant to Nebraska Bishop Richard Jessen,  
said some congregants feel that if the church truly stands for 
justice, it must fight for economic justice for family farmers and 
ranchers. 
</P>
<P>
	At its highest level, she said, the church would deal with  
everything from overseas trade issues to corporate farming. 
Locally, pastors need to understand the marketplace and signs that 
lead to losing the farm. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *'A Taste of Passover' on PBS    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- ``A Taste of Passover'' on PBS is a musical  
offering that producer Gerald Slavet hopes will nourish not just 
the souls of Jews but those of other religions. 
</P>
<P>
	The concert was filmed before an audience at the New England  
Conservatory of Music in January and will be presented March 21 as 
a public television special, 10 days before Passover. 
</P>
<P>
	It features a gospel choir singing traditional Jewish songs, a  
klezmer band, and a demonstration of how to make the perfect matzo 
ball. Broadway actor Theodore Bikel is host. The show also features 
humorist Moshe Waldoks and Yiddish language expert Harriet Chasia 
Segal. 
</P>
<P>
	Slavet said he chose the conservatory's gospel choir to perform  
because he feels gospel music expresses the spirituality of the 
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love Hasidic music, it comes from deep in the soul and  
gospel music comes from deep in the soul,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Passover is an eight-day holiday celebrating the Jewish exodus  
from Egypt and escape from slavery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
