<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Precious Documents Get Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Viewed by more than a million visitors a year,  
the charters on which Americans base their independence, run their 
government and protect their rights are in line for new display 
cases to secure them for the centuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Already more than two centuries old, the Declaration of  
Independence, the Constitution and the Bill of Rights have survived 
invading armies, thoughtless and prolonged exposure to direct 
sunlight and attempts at reproduction that may have sapped the ink 
directly from the parchment on which they are written. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the National Archives showed off the manufacturing  
model of a titanium, aluminum and tempered-glass case intended as 
part of a display system that will encase all pages of the founding 
documents by the end of 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Work on the casing system is to run in tandem with the  
restoration of the Archives building on Pennsylvania Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Every viewer can see that the Declaration, especially, is badly  
aged and faded. But its value to the nation has remained unaltered. 
</P>
<P>
	John Carlin, the archivist of the United States, told an  
audience of officials and preservation experts in the Archives 
rotunda that the importance of the three documents cannot be 
overstated. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are touchstones of truth,'' he said. ``They verify the  
original words and the original signatures, attesting to the 
validity of the foundations of our governance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They are, he said, ``the physical reality of the instruments  
through which we asserted our nationhood, created our government 
and defined our rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Archivists have long been concerned that the current arrangement  
is inadequate for the long-term preservation of fragile documents 
already damaged by rough handling and exposure to excessive levels 
of light during their early years. 
</P>
<P>
	The glass that has pressed against the historic parchment since  
1952 is beginning to deteriorate even though the fragile documents 
themselves are reported to be in no immediate danger. 
</P>
<P>
	Archivists also have been frustrated in that the present system  
totally seals the documents from outside intervention, preventing 
physical examination or contact checks for possible deterioration. 
</P>
<P>
	The display system now in use allows only the first and last  
pages of the Constitution to be shown. The new arrangement will 
display all four of that document's pages as well as the single 
pages of the Declaration and Bill of Rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The three documents have been on display since 1952 in a bronze  
and marble-columned shrine inside the Archives rotunda. Each 
evening the documents are lowered into a vault of steel and 
reinforced concrete. The process is reversed each morning when the 
encased documents are returned to their marble display units. 
</P>
<P>
	The extreme care with which the United States has shielded the  
three documents in recent years contrasts with the often casual 
preservation efforts of the past in which they were carted from one 
temporary home to another, rolled and unrolled, and displayed for 
years on end under the destructive glare of unfiltered light. 
</P>
<P>
	When the British army burned Washington in August 1814, the  
Declaration of Independence and the other documents were hastily 
bundled into linen bags and trundled into rural Virginia in a cart. 
</P>
<P>
	When interest in seeing exact copies of the Declaration became  
irresistible a few years later, printers made reproductions by 
methods that probably soaked the original iron gall ink directly 
out of the parchment. 
</P>
<P>
	When World War II threatened, the three charters were placed  
under Secret Service guard to the U.S. gold depository at Fort 
Knox, Ky., where they remained until the government offered 
assurances in 1944 that all possibility of an attack on Washington 
was at an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
