<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:52:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNC Exec To Use Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The incoming co-chairman of the Democratic  
National Committee is pledging to ``make the party of high hopes 
the party of high-tech,'' with standardized files to target voters 
and $1 million in software improvements for state parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Andrew, in a speech to be delivered Friday when he formally  
takes his position, lays out his vision to harness technology for 
expanding the reach of the party and keying on the concerns of 
individual voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just as businesses across America are changing the way they  
operate, we will electrify, digitize, and personalize the way we do 
politics in every election,'' says Andrew, President Clinton's 
choice to run the DNC's day-to-day operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC, working with state parties, will create a National  
Voter File to profile and target voters across the country. With 
this information, campaigns can deliver a tailored message to 
voters, Andrew says. 
</P>
<P>
	``The National Voter File will allow us to slice and dice  
information to reach voters with the one-to-one customized message 
that will move them to the polls and move them to vote 
Democratic,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Andrew details a plan to spend $1 million to  
equip state parties with the voter file and upgrade their software. 
He said the money will create a network connecting state parties 
and the DNC to exchange information and ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC also intends to establish a Democratic Internet Center,  
hiring staff and buying new equipment so party members use the 
latest tools of technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``We Democrats must always be the party of what's next,'' he  
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
