<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:35 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dow Ends at 9,997.62  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average cracked 10,000  
six times today, but pulled back each time, finishing at a record 
high close of less than three points below the mark. The blue-chip 
index ended at 9,997.62, up 118.21 points. On Tuesday, the Dow 
briefly traded as high as 10,001.78, but slipped back. The spark 
for today's advance was a Labor Department report that consumer 
prices rose a tiny 0.1 percent last month. On the New York Stock 
Exchange, advancers led decliners 1,559-1,390. the technology-heavy 
Nasdaq composite index rose 33.99 to 2462.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Industry Wins Case in Ohio  
</P>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- A federal jury handed the tobacco industry a  
big victory today, rejecting a $2 billion lawsuit brought by union 
health funds to recover the costs of workers' smoking-related 
illnesses. The jury ruled for the industry on all counts in the 
first of about 12 such lawsuits around the country to go to trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Aide Drafted 1st Lady Charges  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Kenneth Starr's top deputy testified  
today that at one point in the Whitewater investigation he drafted 
a proposed indictment of Hillary Rodham Clinton and showed it to 
others in the independent counsel's office. W. Hickman Ewing Jr., 
called as the lead-off defense witness in Susan McDougal's trial, 
said he drafted the indictment against the first lady sometime 
after September 1996 and was not more specific. He added it was not 
unusual for a federal prosecutor to draft an indictment whether or 
not a charge is ever brought. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians Sign Peace Deal  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The ethnic Albanian delegation at the Kosovo peace  
talks unilaterally signed a U.S.-sponsored peace accord today, but 
the Serbs still refused to sign the deal, and the peace talks 
appeared headed toward collapse. The Albanian delegation said it 
was leaving after the signing, with some members going to 
Washington and others returning to Kosovo, where Yugoslav forces 
were reported to be massing and NATO has threatened airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon Warns of U.S. Casualties  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon's top military commanders today  
warned that U.S. casualties may occur if NATO launches airstrikes 
against the Serbs in order to pressure Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to accept a peace accord on Kosovo. Their testimony came 
as the Senate prepared to debate a move by some members to block 
funds for sending U.S. troops to the province to help enforce the 
agreement. The deal would give ethnic Albanians control over 
schools, police and other day-to-day activities, but not 
independence. 

</P>
<P>
	China Denies Spy Charges  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Chinese diplomat today denied allegations  
his country stole nuclear weapons designs from Los Alamos National 
laboratory. He Yafei, a minister-counsel at the Chinese Embassy, 
blamed a Cold War mentality for the furor that has prompted FBI and 
Energy Department investigations. A Taiwan-born American engineer 
who was fired from his job at the lab last week is the target of 
the investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Possible Amtrak Witness Surfaces  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- An investigator said today a potential  
witness has come forward who claims to have seen the crash of an 
Amtrak passenger train that rammed a truck Monday night, killing 11 
people. The person contacted Amtrak late yesterday and the National 
Transportation Safety Board will try to interview the witness in 
detail later today, member John Goglia told a news briefing. 
Investigators ``believe that this witness has valuable 
information'' and is credible, Goglia said, declining to elaborate. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Clears Way for Probe of Starr  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court cleared the way today  
for the Justice Department to investigate the official conduct of 
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. The special court that names 
independent counsels dismissed a challenge by Landmark Legal 
Foundation, a conservative group that sought an order to block the 
Justice Department investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Africans, U.S. in Economic Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today led the first-ever  
meeting of ministers from 46 African countries and U.S. government 
officials, generating an agreement to increase the continent's role 
in the global economy. They also pledged to cooperate more closely 
in such areas as AIDS prevention and treatment. During sessions 
yesterday, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told the ministers their 
nations will benefit from extensive debt forgiveness that the 
United States has proposed only if they enact broad economic 
reforms. 

</P>
<P>
	Joe Torre Undergoes Prostate Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The surgeon who removed New York Yankees  
manager Joe Torre's cancerous prostate gland today believes the 
disease hasn't spread, and said the prognosis is ``excellent.'' Lab 
tests on the removed gland and surrounding lymph nodes won't be 
complete for a few days. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
