<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Preparing To Borrow Billions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., which just acquired cable TV giant  
Tele-Communications Inc., is about to go on a borrowing binge with 
the planned sale of at least $6 billion in bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a new look for a company that has long been the most widely  
held stock in America. For generations, Americans have bought and 
held shares in the company they regarded as reliable old Ma Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning next week, investors can purchase a piece of AT&AMP;T's  
debt as well. But will investors who have coveted AT&AMP;T for its 
stability and steady profits be so quick to embrace a security 
based on debt? 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Thursday they expect the cachet of the AT&AMP;T name  
to make the bond offering a hot ticket, perhaps stimulating the 
entire $2.4 trillion U.S. corporate bond market. While the company 
plans to offer $5 billion to $6 billion in bonds, outsiders say the 
deal could easily balloon to $8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	That would surpass the $6.10 billion of debt taken on in August  
by upstart rival WorldCom Corp. as it gobbled up MCI Communications 
to become MCI WorldCom Inc. The biggest corporate bond issue ever 
was by RJR Holdings Capital, which sold $6.11 billion in May 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T needs the money to foster its growth in a booming, highly  
competitive industry, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``AT&AMP;T's goals take vision, money and execution,'' said Jeffrey  
Kagan, an independent industry analyst in Atlanta. ``They have the 
vision and can certainly execute their plans. They just need 
money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T officials said proceeds from the offering will first be  
used to help pay for its recently completed $42 billion purchase of 
TCI and its $4 billion stock buyback program. 
</P>
<P>
	Next, AT&AMP;T will need the funds to help convert TCI's cable lines  
into local phone lines, a cornerstone of AT&AMP;T's plan to move back 
into local service. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond sale isn't AT&AMP;T's first foray into selling debt.  
Spokeswoman Eileen Connolly said the company has moved in and out 
of the bond market for years, although the last offering was a 
relatively paltry $300 million in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The time is right for borrowing by big business. Interest rates  
are low. In addition, as federal surpluses grow, the government is 
cutting back on its borrowing and the bond market is able to absorb 
more debt from businesses without pumping up interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good time for us to get back into it,'' Connolly  
said, citing the TCI deal. By contrast, the mid-1990s featured the 
sale or divestiture of AT&AMP;T's credit card assets, Lucent 
Technologies Inc. and NCR Corp., which left the company flush with 
cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The strength and competitiveness of rivals like MCI WorldCom  
have spurred AT&AMP;T to keep growing and keep spending, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an expensive time for all the phone companies,'' Kagan  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond offering will allow AT&AMP;T to pay for its deals without  
dipping into cash on hand or issuing more stock, which would dilute 
earnings. Just Wednesday, the company's board approved a 3-for-2 
stock split, effective April 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper Petagna, president of American Municipal Securities in  
St. Petersburg, Fla., said shareholders shouldn't necessarily be 
scared off by the prospect of debt. While corporate bonds are more 
frequently purchased by institutional investors, individuals can 
buy them as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``A company can really enhance its value by borrowing to finance  
growth,'' he said. ``It all has to do with the way the business is 
managed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This week, as AT&AMP;T began a push to attract institutional  
investors to the bonds, company executives emphasized their 
intention to protect AT&AMP;T's credit rating. That's an important 
gauge for any investor, Petagna said. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's long-term debt now receives stellar reviews from  
credit-rating agencies like Standard &AMP; Poor's and Moody's Investors 
Services Inc. Tim Caffrey, an S&AMP;P analyst who covers AT&AMP;T, said the 
big new bond offering isn't likely to affect the company's 
creditworthiness. 
</P>
<P>
	``If an offering of this size came as a surprise, that would be  
a problem,'' Caffrey said. ``But AT&AMP;T has always kept us pretty 
well-informed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AT&AMP;T fell $1.87 1/2, or 2 percent, to close at $82.12 1/2 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
