<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top 4 Percent Guaranteed at UC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- For years, graduating at the top of the  
class didn't mean high school students would be eligible for 
admission into California's prestigious public university system. 
</P>
<P>
	That's about to change. In an attempt to reward high-performing  
students from low-performing schools, the Board of Regents is 
backing a plan to ensure eligibility to the University of 
California to students who graduate in the top 4 percent of their 
class. 
</P>
<P>
	``It says we understand that some schools are better than  
others, but that is not the student's fault. All the student can do 
is do as well as humanly possible,'' said Gov. Gray Davis, 
president of the Board of Regents. 
</P>
<P>
	The change is not expected to significantly change minority  
enrollments, which plunged after the state stopped using 
affirmative action in the admissions process. But it will bring in 
more rural and poor students and, supporters hope, could serve as a 
morale booster for schools that traditionally send few students to 
the university. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 4 percent admissions program will say to every student in  
every high school, `Keep dreaming big dreams, keep working hard. If 
you really excel, we will reward your effort,''' Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	The change, recommended Thursday by a 13-1 committee vote, is  
expected to be approved by the full board today and would take 
effect in fall 2001. Students still have to take required college 
board tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of who gets into the university has been hotly  
debated since 1995, when regents voted to drop affirmative action -- 
a vote taken under the supervision of then-Gov. Pete Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ban went into effect last fall, admission of black and  
Hispanic students dropped about 10 percent across the system, with 
much steeper declines at the prestigious campuses of Berkeley and 
UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters later banned affirmative action at all state colleges by  
passing Proposition 209. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he supported affirmative action, Davis says the 4  
percent plan is not an attempt to get around Proposition 209. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the plan would affect relatively few students. A pilot  
study found that of the 10,200 estimated students in the 4 percent 
pool, two-thirds were already eligible for UC. That left 3,600 
students, of whom about 2,000 were white. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those supporting the plan was Regent Ward Connerly, who  
led the move to drop race as a factor in admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this proposal can hold the promise of sending two or three  
students to UC without a basketball scholarship, then it is worth 
it,'' said Connerly, who is black. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 15:37:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Ethnic Clashes Kill 43 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Ethnic groups armed with knives and  
swords clashed for a second day Thursday in a remote area of Borneo 
known for its brutal communal violence. At least 43 people have 
been killed, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 houses were burned, and several people were  
dismembered in the fighting, which began Wednesday and involved 
four ethnic groups that ganged up on a fifth one, officials and 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	One man was decapitated, his head paraded through a village by a  
screaming crowd, a witness said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 400 people from the outnumbered ethnic group, immigrant  
farmers from the island of Madura, boarded boats to flee the 
fighting, said Lukman Hakim, a local district official. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and troops rushed to the Tebas and Pemangkat districts  
near Indonesia's border with Malaysia, 450 miles northeast of 
Jakarta, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	A resident said the fighting had stopped by late Thursday but  
the situation remained tense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very scared. We can still see some houses burning. No  
one wants to go out,'' said the resident, who identified himself 
only as Djusan. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting on Borneo involved the latest outbreak of violence  
between rival ethnic and religious groups in Indonesia, a country 
struggling with one of its worst economic and political crises in 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 people have been killed since January in weeks of  
clashes between Christians and Muslims in the Maluku Islands in the 
country's east. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people fear that such violence could escalate as the  
world's fourth most populous nation prepares to hold its most open 
parliamentary election in 45 years on June 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballot is regarded as crucial to a democratic process that  
began when authoritarian President Suharto quit in May amid riots 
and protests against his 32-year rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Stability also is needed to help Indonesia recover from its  
position as the worst victim of Asia's 19-month economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	A local police chief, Chaherul Rafidi, said 43 people were  
killed in the two districts of Borneo in fighting involving 
indigenous Malay, Bugis, Dayak as well as ethnic Chinese people on 
one side and Maurese immigrants on the other. 
</P>
<P>
	A national police spokesman, Brig. Togar Sianeapar, said the  
violence was prompted by a dispute over an unpaid bus fare by a 
Madurese immigrant on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hakim, the district official, said it began when passengers  
discovered that the Madurese had boarded the bus with a hidden 
weapon, in violation of an agreement that his ethnic group and 
Dayaks had recently reached to reduce tensions between them. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, at least 300 people were killed when Dayak tribes  
fought with Madurese farmers, who had been relocated to the area by 
Indonesia's government in an effort to ease population growth 
elsewhere. At that time, there were reports of cannibalism by 
indigenous tribesmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
