<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't. Opposes Food Co. Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department filed a lawsuit  
Thursday to block Suiza Food Corp. from acquiring Broughton Food 
Co. on grounds the deal could result in higher milk prices for 
Kentucky school districts. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's antitrust division also sought a temporary  
restraining order to prevent the deal from closing until the court 
rules on a motion for a preliminary injunction to block the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza, based in Dallas, and Broughton, based in Marietta, Ohio,  
agreed not to oppose the restraining order. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed in U.S. District Court in London, Ky.  
</P>
<P>
	Suiza and Broughton compete for school milk contracts in dozens  
of south central Kentucky school districts. Their merger would 
create a monopoly on milk bids in more than 20 school districts 
there, the government said. In another 30 districts, the deal would 
reduce bidders from three to two. 
</P>
<P>
	``This transaction would substantially lessen competition for  
school milk business and result in higher prices and poorer 
services to schools and school children in Kentucky,'' said 
Assistant Attorney General Joel I. Klein. ``If allowed to proceed, 
the merger would eliminate the chief source of school milk 
competition in the region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the affected school districts have a large percentage of  
students entitled to participate in the U.S. Department of 
Agriculture's school lunch program. As a result of paying higher 
milk prices, south central Kentucky school districts would have 
less money to spend on other food provided by that program, the 
division argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Suiza owns and operates 37 fluid milk processing plants in this  
country; it had net sales of $1.8 billion in 1997. Broughton owns 
and operates three fluid milk processing plants in the United 
States and had 1997 sales of $87.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The department noted that the school milk industry in Kentucky  
has a history of collusion, although it did not involve Suiza or 
Broughton. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, two other companies pleaded guilty to criminal  
bid-rigging charges involving milk sold to Kentucky schools over 10 
years. Suiza and Broughton each later acquired a processing plant 
from one of the offending companies. The government said the 
history shows that school milk markets are conducive to collusion. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
