<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temple's Sanchez Has Unlikely Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- If you think Purdue making it to  
the Sweet 16 is surprising, consider Pepe Sanchez's road to Temple. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-sport athlete growing up in Argentina, Sanchez chose  
basketball over soccer. He made his country's national junior team 
and then found his way to Philadelphia after Temple coach John 
Chaney was impressed with what he saw of him on a videotape sent by 
a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Since arriving three years ago, Sanchez has started every game  
for the Owls and just might be the most important person on the 
court Friday night when sixth-seeded Temple (23-10) takes on 
10th-seeed Purdue in the semifinal of the East Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner will play either No. 1 and top-seeded Duke (34-1) or  
12th-seeded Southwest Missouri State (22-10) on Sunday in the 
regional championship that everyone expects Duke to win. 
</P>
<P>
	The Purdue-Temple matchup pits teams with veteran coaches who  
stress defense and a more deliberate style of play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think whoever gets the lead will have some control,'' Purdue  
coach Gene Keady said. ``We really don't care about the pace. I 
think the main thing is to control Temple's offense with our 
defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That ultimately means controlling Sanchez, who was spectacular  
in victories over Kent State and third-seeded Cincinnati. He played 
77 of a possible 80 minutes, and had 29 points, 10 assists, eight 
rebounds, seven steals and three turnovers. He was also the focal 
point of the Owls' matchup zone defense that limited the Bearcats 
to 34.7 percent shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I play a game, my goal is not to be the star of the  
game,'' said Sanchez, an All-Atlantic 10 first-team selection this 
year and its defensive player of the year last. ``My goal is to be 
the most regular person on the floor and to have balance and to be 
cool thinking about what I am doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``A perfect game is scoring between 10 and 15 points, six or  
eight assists, stealing balls and getting rebounds and not turning 
the ball over,'' Sanchez added. ``If I score 30 points, something 
is wrong and we're probably not going to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue guard Jaraan Cornell said Sanchez just doesn't make a lot  
of mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to have to make him work and not try to let him  
make the easy pass and try to contain him,'' Cornell said. ``He 
leads the team in steals so I am going to have to protect the ball. 
It's going to be a challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that might help Purdue is to avoid what Cincinnati  
did, which was to try to attack Sanchez's side of the zone. Going 
the other way might be easier. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue, though, seems to have found answers in the NCAA  
tournament that were missing at the end of the Big Ten season. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the beginning, there were a lot of people that doubted  
whether we would be here since we lost five of our last six 
games,'' forward Brian Cardinal said. ``But we're proving people 
wrong now and showing them that we do deserve to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What has changed is the Boilermakers' defense, which has gotten  
a lot tougher. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we figured out the problem, I started to like our team  
much better,'' Keady said. ``I don't like guys with bad attitudes 
because they are going to make you fail. I don't want to be a 
failure. I want to be the best I can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue edged Texas 58-54 in the opening round of the tournament  
and surprised second-seeded and 10th-ranked Miami 73-63 behind a 
20-point performance by Cardinal. The Boilermakers also got a great 
defensive effort from Alan Eldridge, who limited Johnny Hemsley to 
13 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
