<HEADLINE> Holyfield Regrets Calling Lewis KO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Evander Holyfield regrets his prediction that he  
would knock out Lennox Lewis in the third round of their 
heavyweight title unification bout, which ended in a draw. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was wrong by even saying that, even though I felt I would  
take him in three rounds,'' Holyfield told The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``By saying that, I made it hard, and I refused to turn from it.  
I apologize for that,'' said Holyfield, who lives in suburban 
Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The IBF and WBA champion said he watched a tape on Sunday of  
Saturday night's fight at Madison Square Garden, but did not try to 
score it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're both champions,'' he said of himself and Lewis, the WBC  
heavyweight champ. ``I could see why the judges thought neither of 
us took the fight from the other guy. The judges said it was a 
draw. Realistically, he didn't knock me out, and I didn't knock him 
out. It's all based on a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even with the punch stats, people say, `Well, this man hit you  
600 times.'' But if he hit me that much, why didn't I fall? How 
come I was never staggered or hurt? Obviously, because a lot of 
times he was tapping me,'' Holyfield said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was trying to get Lewis close to him ``so that I  
could nail him with a big shot. But it didn't work. When boxers 
don't do what they're supposed to do, it falls into the judges' 
hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield confirmed remarks by his attorney, Jim Thomas, who  
said that the fighter did not feel well just before the fight. He 
said he had a ``difficult camp,'' alluding to a virus and other 
ailments, including leg cramps during the Lewis fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things happen. But when things happen, I don't go looking for  
excuses. Lennox fought a good fight,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield said he is ``willing to be flexible'' in negotiations  
for a rematch with Lewis, and he might fight for a lower guarantee 
than the $50 million he earned Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	About the rematch, Holyfield said, ``He can't beat me the same  
way. Don't think that I'm going to come back and be the same. What 
he did was very effective. I've got the bruises to show that he was 
effective. I got punished enough.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
