<HEADLINE> NCAA Appeals Judge's Rejection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The NCAA on Thursday appealed a federal  
judge's refusal to give it more time to revamp its freshman 
eligibility requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Ronald Buckwalter declined Tuesday to  
issue a stay which could have delayed enforcement of his court 
order striking down Proposition 16, which mandated that freshmen 
attain a minimum standardized test score to play in Division I 
athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA on Thursday asked for another stay from the 3rd Circuit  
of the U.S. Court of Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	In his initial ruling last week, Buckwalter declared that  
minimum score requirements have ``an unjustified disparate impact 
against African-Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA has said that without more time to develop new  
requirements, there will be chaos among the 302 Division I schools 
because they will be without a critical recruiting guideline. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Proposition 16, students scoring less than 820 on the SAT,  
or 16 on the ACT, could not participate in athletics, regardless of 
their other academic credentials. 
</P>
<P>
	Buckwalter's ruling on Proposition 16 only struck down using  
such tests as minimum requirements, but did not outlaw altogether 
the use of standardized tests, which many educators have long said 
are racially and culturally discriminatory. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA has said the earliest it could establish new guidelines  
is October, since it has to consult its member schools before 
instituting new rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
