<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monthly Trade Deficit Biggest Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's trade deficit jumped to its  
highest monthly level in history, a $17 billion imbalance that is 
certain to boost a growing movement in Congress to erect trade 
barriers to protect American industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21 percent widening in the January deficit -- up by $2.9  
billion from December -- reflected a booming U.S. economy's strong 
demand for foreign products and global recessions that have 
seriously undercut exports by American farmers and manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's worse-than-expected Commerce Department report on the  
trade deficit in goods and services came one day after the House, 
by a lopsided 289-141 vote, passed a bill that would impose stiff 
limits on imports of foreign steel. The Senate has not yet 
considered the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Protectionist pressures are likely to increase in coming months.  
Economists believe last year's record $169 billion trade gap could 
easily swell to $200 billion this year as recessions in one-third 
of the world hurt American exporters and imports continue to flood 
into the United States because of strong domestic demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States remains an oasis of prosperity in the global  
economy,'' said Michael Fenollosa, economist at John Hancock in 
Boston. ``Unless our economy tanks or the rest of the world makes a 
miraculous recovery this year, this deficit is going to get worse, 
much worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is worried that rising protectionist  
sentiment in this country could trigger new financial turmoil in 
developing countries by signaling the United States is no longer 
willing to serve as an importer of last resort for troubled 
economies. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House has threatened to veto the steel import bill,  
arguing it would violate World Trade Organization rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only is the bill WTO inconsistent, it could send a  
chilling message to the rest of the world at a time when our 
economy is doing very well,'' Commerce Secretary William Daley told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Other reports Thursday showed that despite America's trade  
troubles, the U.S. economy continues to turn in a stellar 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation, helped by the flood of cheap imports and falling  
world oil prices, rose by only 0.1 percent in February, while the 
number of Americans filing for unemployment benefits remained below 
the 300,000 level for the seventh straight week, something that 
last occurred 25 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents of the administration's free trade policies are  
unswayed by the good overall economic performance, saying that is 
little comfort to workers laid off by import competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``An unemployed steel or textile worker will tell you the trade  
deficit does matter,'' said Rep. Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. factories have cut 337,000 jobs in the past year and  
farmers are suffering through their worst times since the recession 
of the early 1980s because of lost export sales and falling world 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had been forecasting the January deficit would widen  
but the size of the gap caught them by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Stan Shipley, economist at Merrill Lynch, said he expected trade  
would cut 1.5 percentage points off economic growth in the current 
quarter, although he said the gross domestic product would still 
expand at a healthy 4 percent annual rate. 
</P>
<P>
	By country, America's deficit with China widened sharply to $4.9  
billion as U.S. exports to China fell to the lowest level in more 
than two years. Daley said this poor showing highlighted the need 
for China to do more to eliminate trade barriers if it wants to 
gain entry into the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	America's deficit with Japan narrowed by 22 percent to $4.7  
billion, but the deficit with all Pacific Rim countries, the region 
hardest hit by the financial crisis, widened by 7.8 percent to 
$12.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	And in a sign of coming problems, the U.S. surplus with Latin  
America, one of the few areas where the trade flow is in America's 
favor, was cut in half to $671 million in January, reflecting that 
region is now falling victim to the global turmoil that has hurt 
Russia and Asian countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge in the January deficit came as exports fell by 1.4  
percent and imports rose 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.1 billion drop in exports was led by falling demand for  
farm goods including corn, oil seeds and cotton and manufactured 
products including oilfield drilling equipment, farm machinery, 
aircraft and autos. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.8 billion rise in imports included monthly records in  
shipments of foreign autos, food and consumer goods, led by a $425 
million increase in shipments of pharmaceutical products into the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	The deficit would have been even worse expect for the fact that  
Americans continue to benefit from falling world oil demand, which 
pushed the average price of imported crude oil down to $9.19 per 
barrel, the lowest level in 25 years. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
