<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Urged on Corporate Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Nasdaq for corporate bonds?  
</P>
<P>
	As Wall Street bond dealers try to head off a government  
mandate, lawmakers are prodding securities regulators to act to 
make price data on corporate bonds as clearly available as 
information about stocks and government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Greater numbers of ordinary investors have started buying  
corporate bonds, which now have a U.S. market of $2.4 trillion -- 
nearly twice the size of the municipal bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate bonds are considered integral to the stock market's  
performance, because it would be difficult to make sound judgments 
on a company's stock without accurate data on its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their rapid growth, lawmakers and federal regulators  
believe corporate bonds have fallen behind stocks and other bond 
markets in the openness of their prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time has come ... to illuminate this needlessly dark  
corner of our capital markets,'' Arthur Levitt, chairman of the 
Securities and Exchange Commission, testified Thursday at a hearing 
of the House Commerce subcommittee on finance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly the technology now exists to gather transaction  
prices, distribute them and interpret them in a timely, accurate 
and an efficient fashion,'' Levitt said. ``Incomplete information 
leaves investors vulnerable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To spur the SEC, the subcommittee began considering a proposal  
that would order the agency to adopt new rules governing price 
disclosure in the corporate bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an important goal for our markets and investors,''  
said Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the full Commerce 
Committee, who challenged the SEC and the bond market last fall 
``to get going and clean this market up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone using the bond market to save for retirement or  
education will benefit from it,'' Bliley said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt, who began pushing for better price disclosure in  
corporate bonds in a speech last September, said Thursday the new 
proposal ``creates a greater sense of urgency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following an SEC review of bond markets, the National  
Association of Securities Dealers agreed last year to adopt rules 
requiring dealers to report all corporate bond transactions to the 
NASD and develop systems for real-time disclosure of buying and 
selling prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASD, a self-policing group that operates the Nasdaq Stock  
Market, also has said it will improve its efforts to detect fraud 
in corporate bond trading. While the SEC review found that the 
overall bond market was running smoothly, it uncovered anecdotal 
evidence of possible insider trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike stocks, the vast majority of bonds are not traded in a  
central market. They are bought and sold over the telephone by a 
relatively small group of dealers that includes major brokerages 
such as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bond Market Association, which represents the dealers, has  
disputed claims that they are impeding the development of 
electronic trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The group is offering its own system for reporting prices at  
which dealers buy and sell bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``In less than six months, the industry has made substantial  
progress toward implementing a system that will enhance corporate 
bond price transparency,'' Micah Green, the association's executive 
vice president, testified at Thursday's hearing. ``Our commitment 
to improving transparency is serious, and we are making it 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the price-reporting system being developed by the dealers  
only covers investment-grade corporate bonds, not the popular 
high-yield ``junk'' bonds, and details of the new system ``are 
still unclear,'' Levitt told the lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edolphus Towns of New York, the subcommittee's senior  
Democrat, said, ``I hope we are not being asked to anoint any one 
system at this point.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
