<DOCNO> APW19990318.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 04:15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ACLU To Defend Festival Organizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The American Civil Liberties Union and state  
Sen. Tom Hayden said police overreacted when they used force to 
disperse a crowd at a hip-hop festival last month. 
</P>
<P>
	ACLU Executive Director Ramona Ripston said Wednesday that the  
organization will represent Asia Yu, the festival organizer who has 
been charged with inciting a riot. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police treated this as a riot, but there was no riot,''  
Ripston said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Feb. 28 scene became chaotic after police marched in wearing  
riot gear, wielding batons and aiming guns at the seemingly 
peaceful crowd, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be very frightened if I saw police in riot gear aiming  
guns at me,'' said Ripston. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayden, whose son attended the festival and videotaped it,  
issued a statement saying he had viewed the tape and ``I am of the 
opinion that the LAPD overreacted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The confrontation began simply enough with police arresting  
someone spray-painting graffiti on a wall,'' Hayden said. ``This 
led to a handful of people throwing bottles and/or rocks at police 
vehicles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hayden said police escalated the situation by calling a citywide  
tactical alert. Officers also occupied the Venice area for several 
hours, used excessive force in making arrests and pointed weapons 
at the crowd, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Hayden's statement, police spokesman Lt. Anthony  
Alba said, ``That's a private citizen's opinion. I was there and I 
witnessed individuals throwing rocks and bottles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yu, 28, a professional hip-hop dancer, could receive a year in  
jail and a $1,000 fine if convicted of inciting to riot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
