<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 15:37:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Albanians Seek Peace, Await War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIKOVAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The red Albanian flag flutters over  
the ruins of Likovac, and the devastated village that serves as 
Kosovo Liberation Army headquarters swarms with black-uniformed 
fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	They're ready for more war, yet they seek peace.  
</P>
<P>
	As the battle for Kosovo heads into its second year, even  
hardened KLA commanders are ready to suspend their struggle for 
independence and settle for autonomy, as laid out in the 
U.S.-sponsored peace accord signed Thursday by ethnic Albanian 
delegates in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Even KLA supreme commander Sulejman Selimi says he's happy to  
hang up his gun and become ``a free civilian'' in an autonomous 
Kosovo, where democratic rights would be policed by the world 
powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Outgunned by the Yugoslav army and in need of Western support,  
Selimi and many other rebels are now willing to accept the world's 
vision of NATO-enforced autonomy for Kosovo within Serbia, the main 
Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Independence for the ethnic Albanian-majority province remains  
their ultimate goal. But there is a growing recognition among rebel 
ranks that time is on their side -- that they can achieve that 
objective through other means than fighting heavy tanks with 
submachine guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the Serbs' superior firepower, Kosovo's Albanian rebels  
seem to hold the better cards. 
</P>
<P>
	If Serbs refuse to sign the internationally endorsed peace plan,  
they risk being bombed into compliance by NATO. If the Serbs do 
sign, the bet is that in a province where ethnic Albanians are a 90 
percent majority, autonomy is bound to mutate into independence 
over the next few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not how you fight the war, it's whether you win it that  
counts,'' a gap-toothed fighter who identified himself only as Remi 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few days, reinforced Yugoslav army and Serb police  
forces have driven a wedge between guerrilla areas north of 
Pristina and the rebel region of Drenica, southwest of the 
provincial capital. Dirt roads are dotted with tractor-pulled 
trailers carrying weeping women and children fleeing homes left 
unprotected by retreating rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Selimi, in his first interview since he was appointed supreme  
commander last month, said the Serbs want to ``cut Kosovo and take 
a piece of it'' before any possible NATO strike. They then hope to 
hold on to the mineral-rich north in any negotiations over the 
future of the province. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Yugoslav army also wants to seize control of the  
rugged mountain region between Drenica and the north to set up 
anti-NATO air defenses there. 
</P>
<P>
	His fighters in the Cicavica Mountains have already seen  
antiaircraft missiles being unloaded from Yugoslav army trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon says 16,000 to 21,000 Yugoslav army troops are now  
on the perimeter of Kosovo, and an additional 14,000 to 18,000 are 
deployed inside. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old commander says his fighters are ready to  
surrender their weapons under a Kosovo autonomy agreement that 
foresees the withdrawal of most government troops and the 
stationing of 28,000 NATO forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Serb forces withdraw, we no longer need our guns,'' he  
said Wednesday in his heavily guarded home. He said Serbs who 
stayed out of the conflict ``will have no problems'' in an 
autonomous Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Selimi was a friend of Adem Jashari, the guerrilla movement's  
founder who was killed in a clash with Serb police in a Drenica 
village in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	As an armed aide served cups of red tea to visitors under the  
flicker of a generator-driven light bulb, Selimi described himself 
as ``part of a generation that suffered a lot of pain'' under Serb 
rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA, he vowed, will ``fight until the last soldier dies'' if  
the autonomy plan goes awry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 15:37:24 </DATE_TIME>
