<DOCNO> APW19990318.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:55:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Regulator Warns of Fraud Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) -- Retirees, recent immigrants and other  
investors are losing hundreds of millions of dollars as 
off-exchange currency fraud reaches ``epidemic proportions,'' the 
outgoing chairwoman of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission 
warned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooksley Born, in a speech before futures and options industry  
participants, urged Congress to give her agency authority to 
regulate the estimated $70 trillion over-the-counter derivatives 
market, calling a current lack of supervision dangerous to the U.S. 
and world economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Institutional supervisors focus on the tree; market regulators  
see the forest,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress should provide ``clear and unequivocal enforcement  
authority to pursue off-exchange foreign currency fraud imposed on 
the retail public, which has reached epidemic proportions,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers have indicated they intend to undertake a  
comprehensive review of the Commodity Exchange Act as they decide 
whether to reauthorize the CFTC by Sept. 30, 2000. Currently, 
foreign currency trades are exempted from most oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	Born, who is scheduled to step down at the end of her term on  
April 13, has for years urged lawmakers to give the commission the 
same policing powers it has over the U.S. futures and options 
exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Securities and Exchange Commission have argued  
they should control oversight of over-the-counter markets, while 
those firms have argued their self-policing activities should be 
enough to prevent fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	But Born said ``bucketshops'' operating in New York, Washington,  
D.C., Florida, Arizona, Nevada and California have fleeced 
thousands out of their retirement money by promising to invest it 
in foreign currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they put the money in offshore accounts where it cannot  
be recovered and have virtually no fear of federal action, she 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mother Studied As Fire Killed Baby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A 17-year-old mother was working toward a  
high-school equivalency degree when her apartment caught fire, 
killing her infant son who was alone at home, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and an official at the school where Tiffany Bennett was  
studying said she was taking classes to meet welfare requirements, 
a claim disputed by state welfare officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Melvin Rudolph III died of smoke inhalation Wednesday -- a week  
short of his first birthday -- in a second-floor bedroom of the 
apartment in suburban Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Allegheny County coroner classified the death as accidental.  
The fire began in an electrical cord leading to a space heater, 
Deputy Fire Marshal Thomas Hitchings said. 
</P>
<P>
	His mother was at the Pittsburgh Job Corps Center. She left the  
boy home with the space heater on in the bedroom to keep him warm, 
police said. The child was not in a crib. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bennett was questioned but no decision on charges had been  
made Thursday afternoon, said Sgt. Lee Torbin, a county homicide 
investigator. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was very much a preventable death,'' Fire Marshal Robert  
Full said. ``Earlier detection of the fire could have saved this 
baby's life. ... We know the baby was left unattended. We know it's 
a tragic loss of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bennett had performed well in classes toward her general  
equivalency degree, said Allen Crawford, the center's acting 
director. Classes, which run from 7:50 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. daily, 
were required so Ms. Bennett could receive benefits from the state 
Welfare Department, Crawford said. 
</P>
<P>
	Department spokeswoman Mary Ellen Fritz said Ms. Bennett was not  
on the state's cash assistance program, and she added that the 
state provides child care for parents whom the program requires to 
attend vocational training or classes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a case of welfare reform gone astray. In no way  
was this woman required to go to school as part of a 
cash-assistance program. This is something she chose to do,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A smoke alarm outside Ms. Bennett's apartment did not have a  
battery. Her landlord, Al Smith, said he tested the smoke alarm 
when Ms. Bennett moved in January. He said she had not told him 
about the dead battery since then. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbor Diane Green smelled smoke, heard a first-floor smoke  
alarm, called an emergency dispatcher and pounded on the door. She 
fled after getting no response. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:24:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Via Dolorosa' Is Masterful Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Most playwrights reveal themselves through their  
work. David Hare is no exception. 
</P>
<P>
	But the British writer, author of ``Plenty,'' ``Racing Demon,''  
``Skylight'' and other works, has done one better. He has put 
himself on stage in ``Via Dolorosa,'' a masterful meditative 
monologue on his 1997 visit to Israel and the Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a fascinating journey, not only for what it reveals about  
Hare, but for what it says about a situation that has defied 
solutions for thousands of years. 
</P>
<P>
	At Broadway's Booth Theater, Hare paints his picture from scores  
of interviews with Jews and Palestinians alike. It is a fragmented, 
often surreal portrait, made up of contradicting ideas hurled at 
him with a ferocity that could make one despair for any resolution 
of the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	The 51-year-old Hare, a gangly gentleman casually dressed in a  
white shirt and charcoal gray slacks, is no actor. ``I've always 
tried to get Judi Dench to do this sort of thing,'' he says of the 
profession he abandoned at age 15 after a school production of ``A 
Man for All Seasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet his slow, almost stiff delivery contributes to the  
effectiveness of the evening. His speech is deliberate, carefully 
measured as he moves across the nearly barren stage of the Booth, 
which is filled only with a wooden playing area, two desks and two 
chairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The author reveals that he finally has discovered the subject of  
his many plays (there are more than a score). Faith, the need for 
belief, dominates most of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Israel is, first and foremost, a cause ... the cause being a  
patch of land ... lying like a small brown anchovy set down on a 
school atlas,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause has created intractable conflict, battles that are  
championed by an astonishing parade of characters in ``Via 
Dolorosa.'' The author re-creates some vivid interviews in his 
90-minute lecture. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare starts in Israel, visiting settlers in Hebron, a Jewish  
settlement surrounded by Arabs. He stays with Danny and Sarah 
Weiss, American Jews who came to Israel to reconnect with their 
spiritual values. As for their living on disputed land, Danny 
contends Israel must have roots. ``It has to be the place where 
life goes right down deep into the soil,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	That soil is claimed just as defiantly by the Palestinians,  
although there are as many shades of opinion among the Arabs as 
there are in Tel Aviv. 
</P>
<P>
	Haider Abdel Shafi, the most popular politician in Gaza,  
declares, ``Our most urgent task is to reform ourselves.'' Shafi 
laments the lack of principles in his society and criticizes Yasser 
Arafat for being ``a man who buys peoples' allegiance,'' creating a 
corrupt society. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone has an opinion, including Hare who celebrates the  
argumentative environments in which he finds himself. He discovers 
joy in the fact that people stand for something, unlike folks in 
his own country. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare chides British Prime Minister Tony Blair for being ``all  
things to all men'' and thus not letting people know what he really 
stands for. 
</P>
<P>
	The title of the evening comes from Hare's need to walk the Via  
Dolorosa in Jerusalem, ``to follow the Stations of the Cross, which 
represent the steps on Christ's journey to his death.'' The 
playwright is bewildered by the narrow unimpressive walkway, its 
postcard shops and the hordes of ``American evangelicals dressed in 
shell suits and baseball caps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wants more, but gradually realizes it is not the stones that  
are important but the ideas they represent that matter, ideas that 
have led to the life-and-death struggle in the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare has become something of a growth industry on Broadway. Last  
year, New York saw ``The Judas Kiss,'' the author's drama about 
Oscar Wilde starring Liam Neeson. Earlier this season, Nicole 
Kidman, riding waves of publicity, sold out in ``The Blue Room.'' 
Next month could be the best of all, Dench, returning to Broadway 
after more than 30 years, in ``Amy's View.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But for now, we have the playwright in the flesh, courtesy of  
Lincoln Center Theater. ``Via Dolorosa'' makes a plea for 
understanding or, at the least, attempting to understand. It is a 
lively, literate evening that like the rest of Hare's plays, 
celebrates belief, even if no agreement is in sight on what belief 
is the one true faith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:29:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Terrapins, Red Storm Go High-Octane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Coach Mike Jarvis wants the St. John's  
Red Storm to enjoy what he calls a fantastic voyage. For Maryland, 
taking in the sights just won't do anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	The Terrapins are in the round of 16 for the fourth time in six  
years. Getting this far is no longer a thrill for a program that 
hasn't been to a regional championship game since 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the focus is reaching the first Final Four in Maryland's  
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maryland definitely is on the cusp of greatness this year,''  
senior Laron Profit said. ``We feel this is our opportunity. There 
is a sense of urgency, not only for Maryland basketball, but we're 
being selfish. This is our last time around. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel this is our opportunity to go out and do well and win  
and be remembered in Maryland as the team that got us there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second-seeded Terrapins (28-5), who already have the most  
wins in school history, must get past third-seeded St. John's 
(27-8) tonight in the first South Regional semifinal at 
Thompson-Boling Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Top-seeded Auburn plays No. 4 Ohio State in the second game.  
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis is trying to pass along some of the excitement of playing  
in the semifinals in his first year coaching the Red Storm. He 
knows how fleeting success can be since he took George Washington 
to a regional semifinal in 1993, only to fall short three other 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing I asked them to do ... is no matter how much they  
want to win a game and no matter how far they want to go, to enjoy 
the experience and have some fun because these things don't happen 
very often for many people,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans could have the most fun from a semifinal that features two  
teams that love to push the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Storm can nearly match Maryland, the nation's  
fifth-highest scoring team this season with an 85.6 average, 
point-for-point on offense. Jarvis has five starters scoring in 
double figures, with the Red Storm averaging 79.3 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Williams, one victory short of 400 for his career, said he  
hopes both teams play at the level that got them to the round of 
16. But he won't be picky. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll take an ugly game ... if we win,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Terrapins are used to being quicker than most opponents, an  
advantage they won't have against St. John's. Williams said 
preparation will be the key, but that doesn't mean major changes 
for Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to go out and play Maryland basketball,'' Maryland  
guard Terrell Stokes said. ``That's what got us 28 wins, so I don't 
think we should change anything at this point of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland basketball this season has meant defense as much as  
balanced offense. The Terrapins already have a school-record 423 
steals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Storm has shown some versatility in the tournament.  
</P>
<P>
	St. John's, making its first appearance in the round of 16 since  
1991, switched from its preferred man-to-man defense to a zone 
against Indiana, despite the players' reservations. The result was 
an 86-61 victory, the worst tournament loss in Indiana's history. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his Red Storm will need to play with the same kind of  
discipline to keep up with Maryland and contain Steve Francis (17.2 
points). That doesn't mean playing tentatively. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this stage of the game, unless you're Duke, you better play  
attack and you better play disciplined; otherwise, you're going 
home,'' Jarvis said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 17:05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow 10k Party Will Have To Wait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The party hats will have to wait for another  
day. 
</P>
<P>
	A gleeful celebration was cut short at the New York Stock  
Exchange Thursday as the Dow Jones industrial average edged past 
the 10,000-point mark -- again -- just as the closing bell was rung, 
then dipped below as late trades were settled. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior exchange officials cheered from an observation platform  
above the trading floor as a retiring member of the exchange, 
William Schnurr, slammed the final gavel together with Peter Kann, 
chairman and chief executive officer of Dow Jones &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Kann and NYSE Chairman Richard A. Grasso began flinging out blue  
baseball caps emblazoned with the words ``Dow 10,000'' as it 
appeared that the market's best-known indicator would close above 
the historic benchmark just two days after piercing it for the 
first time. 
</P>
<P>
	But they stopped just seconds later as the ticker board  
indicated that the average was falling below the magic number, 
ending at 9,997.62, up 118.21 points on the day and less than three 
points shy of the mark. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was more than a close call -- we were there,'' said Robert  
B. Fagenson, vice chairman of the exchange and a managing director 
of a specialist firm. ``But then it ticked back. It just gives us 
an a opportunity to do it again tommorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange had prepared thousands of the hats to give away on  
the day that the average closed above 10,000, and several officials 
were standing at the ready Thursday with bags of the hats on the 
trading floor just in case. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Grasso and Kann on the platform above, the officials began  
handing out the hats as the closing bell was rung, but then stopped 
again just a minute later as the indicator dipped back below 
10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, well.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are plenty more hats,'' Fagenson said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:29:11 </DATE_TIME>
