<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 22:53:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unions Lose Case Vs. Tobacco Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- The embattled tobacco industry has picked up  
a big win in federal court, with jurors rejecting a $2 billion 
lawsuit accusing cigarette makers of unfairly targeting blue-collar 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury sifted through three weeks of testimony and thousands  
of documents before concluding Thursday that the tobacco industry 
hadn't concealed the dangers of smoking from the public since 1954. 
</P>
<P>
	``This jury's verdict should send a loud message that these  
lawsuits have no factual basis,'' said Gregory Little, a lawyer for 
Philip Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	The class-action lawsuit was brought by 114 Ohio union health  
funds in an attempt to recoup the costs of treating workers' 
smoking-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first of at least 14 such lawsuits around the nation  
to go to trial. Two similar lawsuits are set to go to jury trials 
this year in Washington and New York, Little said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Coughlin, attorney for the union health funds, said he  
was disappointed by the jury, which deliberated for two days before 
ruling for the tobacco industry on all counts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to understand how somebody could look at all that  
activity and then say that's all right or that didn't impact 
millions and millions of people,'' he said. ``It's tough to lose 
this case, but there will be more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several similar cases have been thrown out around the country,  
with some judges saying the unions have no legal standing unless 
they file separate lawsuits on behalf of every smoker. 
</P>
<P>
	The tobacco industry came to a $206 billion legal settlement  
with states in November, but cigarette makers still face 
class-action lawsuits and individual lawsuits by smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has been ordered to pay damages in only four  
liability cases brought by smokers, and three verdicts were thrown 
out on appeal. The fourth, a $51.5 million award last month for a 
former three-pack-a-day smoker in California, is being appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Enough is enough. It's time to stop kicking the tobacco  
industry. Smokers make their own choices in they way they choose 
their lifestyles,'' said Robert Weber, a lawyer for R.J. Reynolds, 
another defendant in the Ohio case. 
</P>
<P>
	The health funds were led by Iron Workers Local Union No. 17  
Insurance Fund, which brought the case in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry was accused by the health funds of using  
promotional gimmicks and images such as Joe Camel and the Marlboro 
Man, ``aware that people with lower incomes and less education are 
more susceptible to the advertising,'' said Mike Withey, lead 
attorney for the plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The tobacco companies contended there was nothing illegal about  
their ad campaigns and disputed the idea that blue-workers were 
more likely to be swayed by them. 
</P>
<P>
	Liggett Group chief executive Bennett LeBow testified during  
that trial how he broke ranks with other companies by admitting 
publicly that nicotine is addictive, smoking causes cancer and 
cigarette makers target adolescents with their advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Liggett was dropped as a defendant in the lawsuit after the  
company settled out of court and agreed to testify for the 
prosecution. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:54:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Counsel Funds Mulled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With little support for renewing the  
independent counsel law, Democrats who once favored the statute 
want not only to let it expire but also to cut off money this year 
for Kenneth Starr and other outside investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic amendment by Sens. Robert Torricelli of New  
Jersey and Tom Harkin of Iowa would shift the investigations to the 
Justice Department at the end of the year. But with no Republican 
sponsors, it has little chance of being approved. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about restoring confidence in those investigations,''  
Torricelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to give them six months to get their stuff together  
and turn it over to the Justice Department,'' Harkin added. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic measure would cut off federal money for Starr's  
investigation of President Clinton and for four other independent 
counsels on Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Several senior Republican officials who demanded anonymity said  
there was no desire among Senate GOP leaders to change and renew 
the law when it expires June 30, despite a push by a small group of 
moderate senators of both parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Simply allowing the law to expire as scheduled would permit  
Starr and other special prosecutors to continue their 
investigations until they are finished. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a draft of their bill, the Democratic sponsors  
would cut off federal funding of investigations by independent 
counsels appointed before June 30, 1996, which would include Starr, 
who still has several areas of unfinished business relating to the 
Clinton investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not our intention by ending these appropriations to end  
these investigations,'' Torricelli said. ``They should continue 
professionally and thoroughly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, battered by Starr's five-year probe, and others in his  
administration who once supported the independent counsel law have 
joined Republicans in advocating its death. Attorney General Janet 
Reno on Wednesday became the latest member of the administration to 
advise Congress to let the Justice Department handle probes of 
high-level officials. 
</P>
<P>
	But even though she was arguing a position widely held among  
lawmakers in both parties, Reno met with skepticism Wednesday from 
Republican senators who believe the Justice Department can't 
investigate members of its own administration with credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	'' If you appoint a special counsel, as long as you are the  
appointing authority, isn't there at least a perception of a 
conflict of interest that is harmful to public confidence?'' asked 
Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I have come face to face with, senator, is that the  
conflict exists in the act now,'' replied Reno, who has been 
accused of protecting Clinton in her decisions on whether to seek 
outside probes. 
</P>
<P>
	Having seen the statute's structure ``probably closer up than  
anybody in American history,'' Reno told the Senate panel she has 
given up looking for ways to fix the statute -- and the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Removing the attorney general from the independent counsel  
process would be unconstitutional, she said, so the Justice 
Department is the right place for such probes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't figure out how to avoid a conflict and still have  
constitutional muster,'' she told Collins. Having the Justice 
Department conduct such probes would be an imperfect system, Reno 
allowed. But, she added, ``It can't get any worse, senator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several members of the panel took issue with that statement,  
pointing out the ``Saturday Night Massacre'' in which President 
Nixon fired special prosecutor Archibald Cox, who was investigating 
the Watergate scandal. That incident inspired the independent 
counsel law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:53:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Witness Is Subpoenaed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Attempting to put Kenneth Starr's  
tactics on trial, lawyers for Susan McDougal reached an agreement 
today to question the Whitewater prosecutor's top deputy on the 
witness stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Independent Counsel Hickman Ewing was served a subpoena  
Wednesday at the back of the courtroom where Mrs. McDougal is on 
trial for refusing to answer questions before Starr's grand jury 
investigating Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors raised questions today about what Ewing would be  
asked but agreed not to fight the subpoena after the judge ordered 
Mrs. McDougal's team to provide more details about the planned 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The questioning will be limited pretty much to the  
investigation of Susan McDougal,'' prosecutor Mark Barrett said. 
After talking to defense lawyers, ``We think we all are on the same 
page.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulations require that the defense disclose ahead of  
time what information is being sought when a U.S. attorney is 
called as a witness, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos, contends she refused to  
answer grand jury questions because she felt prosecutors were 
pressuring her to give false testimony against President and Mrs. 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos also says prosecutors withheld information from the  
grand jurors who indicted Mrs. McDougal that would have decreased 
the credibility of other witnesses, including Mrs. McDougal's 
former husband, James. 
</P>
<P>
	She is charged with criminal contempt and obstruction of  
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	The legal wrangling came as Mrs. McDougal's lawyers prepared to  
call their first witnesses, beginning with Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution rested its case after seven days, ending this  
morning with testimony from an Arkansas banker, Ron Proctor, who 
dealt with the original loan for the Whitewater land development. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Ewing watched from the rear of the courtroom as  
the prosecution closed its case by summoning three former members 
of the Whitewater grand jury before whom Mrs. McDougal had refused 
to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the day, Bill Henley, Mrs. McDougal's brother,  
reached through a crowd of reporters and handed Ewing a subpoena, 
saying, ``Hick, I've got something for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt really good,'' Bill Henley said a few moments later.  
``It's about time we got to ask them a few questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos would not rule out summoning Starr as well. ``First let  
me deal with Hick Ewing,'' he said. ``One at a time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Making a prosecutor a defense witness was the second unusual  
turn of the day. The first was putting on the witness stand three 
members of the grand jury that indicted Mrs. McDougal after she 
refused to answer their questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said that in 25 years as a federal prosecutor he had never  
seen grand jurors testify at a criminal trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand jury foreman John Washam testified that the death of Mrs.  
McDougal's former husband, James McDougal, in 1998 made her 
testimony even more crucial than it had been before. 
</P>
<P>
	With his death, ``one link of the chain was gone'' of people who  
knew what went on in Whitewater, said Washam. McDougal had been 
Starr's chief cooperating witness in his investigation of the 
Whitewater land deal in which the Clintons and McDougals were 
partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos focused on the fact that Starr's office didn't tell  
grand jurors James McDougal had changed his story a number of 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wouldn't you have wanted to hear that?'' Geragos asked grand  
juror Marsha High. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' she responded.  
</P>
<P>
	Geragos argues that his client didn't want to answer questions  
because overzealous prosecutors were trying to force her to give 
false testimony against the president and first lady Hillary Rodham 
Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
