<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Basket Maker Dies of Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, Ohio (AP) -- David Longaberger, who developed his  
family's basket weaving tradition into a $700 million-a-year 
business bearing his name, has died of cancer. He was 64. 
</P>
<P>
	Longaberger, who had been battling kidney cancer for nearly two  
years, died Wednesday at his central Ohio farm. 
</P>
<P>
	He founded The Longaberger Co. in 1973 with five weavers. Today  
the company employs more than 7,000 people and 47,000 independent 
sales associates who sold 8.3 million baskets in 1998. He had 
remained chairman of The Longaberger Co. during his illness, but 
promoted his daughter, Tami, as president and chief executive in 
July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Longaberger's father owned a basket company and taught all of  
his 12 children to make the baskets. But business waned as 
cardboard and paper sacks began to replace baskets and the business 
closed in 1955. 
</P>
<P>
	David Longaberger owned a restaurant and grocery store in nearby  
Dresden, where he grew up, when he founded his company. In 1978, 
Longaberger decided to sell the baskets exclusively through home 
shows, which have since spread throughout the United States 
</P>
<P>
	Longaberger turned the 20-mile stretch between the corporate  
office and Dresden into a destination place for basket lovers, some 
of whom have bought so many that they had to add rooms to their 
homes. The baskets are popular collectibles. 
</P>
<P>
	Longaberger was an unlikely success story. He spent two years in  
the first grade and three years in the fifth. He stuttered so badly 
as a child that he took a job as a door-to-door salesman when he 
got out of high school to improve his speech. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
