<HEADLINE> Brazil Ford Unit Suspends Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The Brazilian subsidiary of Ford Motor  
Co. is suspending production for two weeks because of a scarcity of 
parts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of difficulties in obtaining parts and components we  
will stop production between March 22 and April 5,'' a company 
spokeswoman said Thursday, refusing to give further details. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leader Alfredo Cavalcanti said Ford's troubles were due to  
the recent devaluation of the country's currency which has made 
imported parts more expensive. He did not know what percentage of 
the parts used by Ford were imported. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency, the real, has lost 35 percent of its value since  
it was devalued on Jan. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Cavalcanti said that because of the lack of parts, Ford has been  
unable to complete about 3,000 unfinished vehicles at its plant in 
the industrial suburb of Sao Bernardo do Campo on the outskirts of 
Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford is negotiating with local auto parts suppliers who are  
also having trouble because of the devaluation'', Cavalcanti said. 
``Hopefully the situation will be normalized by April 5.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
