<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Bomb Probe Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The outside police chief  
charged with overseeing the probe into the assassination of a 
Catholic lawyer has arrived in Northern Ireland to begin work, amid 
cries for the province's predominantly Protestant force to 
completely sever itself from the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the family of Rosemary Nelson, killed earlier this  
week by a bomb rigged in her silver BMW, planned to bury her today 
in her hometown of Lurgan, 30 miles southwest of Belfast. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Nelson, 40, successfully represented a number of  
high-profile Irish Republican Army suspects, including one charged 
with killing two police officers, and had a harassment complaint 
pending against the Royal Ulster Constabulary at the time of her 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to public outrage, Sir Ronnie Flanagan, the RUC's  
chief, took the unprecedented step of calling in an outside officer 
-- David Phillips, chief constable in the English county of Kent -- 
to supervise the murder investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips arrived Wednesday night to begin preliminary  
consultations. 
</P>
<P>
	An anti-Catholic terror group calling itself the Red Hand  
Defenders has claimed responsibility for Mrs. Nelson's death, which 
appeared to be aimed at ensuring the formation of Northern 
Ireland's new Protestant-Catholic coalition government remains 
stalled. 
</P>
<P>
	But many Catholics have called for the RUC to completely cede  
the investigation to outside authorities, accusing members of the 
force of colluding in her death. 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights groups, too, have questioned the appropriateness of  
the RUC force playing a role in the hunt for her killers, 
especially after Mrs. Nelson said before her death that officers 
made a number of death threats against her. 
</P>
<P>
	``The investigation must be seen to be above reproach,'' said  
Maggie Beirne of the Committee on the Administration of Justice, a 
Belfast-based group. ``RUC officers will still be gathering 
forensic evidence and doing other front-line work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions have run high in Northern Ireland since Mrs. Nelson's  
death. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night, several people were injured, including a  
police officer, when Protestants and Catholics clashed in 
Portadown, the town near Lurgan where Mrs. Nelson was representing 
Catholic residents in their contentious fight to block a Protestant 
march through their neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Police responded to a barrage of Molotov cocktails and stones by  
firing plastic bullets in an attempt to quell the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, a former leading member of the Red Hand Commando, a  
Protestant paramilitary group observing a cease-fire, was shot dead 
in west Belfast. The motive was not immediately clear, but 
authorities believed fellow Protestants were behind the killing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
