<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Budget Films No Oscar Recipe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Advice to actresses with Academy Award  
ambitions: Stay out of the mainstream. 
</P>
<P>
	The evidence is there. Of the past six winners, only one -- Helen  
Hunt in last year's ``As Good As It Gets'' -- appeared in a 
big-budget film released by a major studio. 
</P>
<P>
	Take a look at the nominees for best actress of 1998. Only  
perennial nominee Meryl Streep starred in a major studio release, 
Universal's ``One True Thing,'' and it was modestly budgeted. Three 
of the other films were made independently in England, one came 
from Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shakespeare in Love,'' for which Gwyneth Paltrow was  
nominated, was originally developed by Universal Pictures. Casting 
and other problems made the studio drop it, and Miramax Films 
snapped it up. Universal retained an interest in the film, which 
turned out to be an immense success. 
</P>
<P>
	A glance at the nominees for best actress in a leading role:  

</P>
<P>
                  	 *CATE BLANCHETT, ``Elizabeth''    	
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth I of England must be the most portrayed monarch in  
film history. Her filmography dates back to Sarah Bernhardt in the 
1912 ``Queen Elizabeth.'' Other Elizabeths have included Bette 
Davis (twice), Flora Robson (twice), Florence Eldridge, Agnes 
Moorehead, Jean Simmons and Glenda Jackson (in ``Mary, Queen of 
Scots'' and a TV series). 
</P>
<P>
	And now in the 1998 Academy nominations, a young Elizabeth, Cate  
Blanchett in ``Elizabeth,'' and an older one, Judi Dench in 
``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Geoffrey Rush, who portrays the queen's unscrupulous  
promoter, Miss Blanchett emerged from the Sydney theater, having 
graduated from Australia's National Institute of Dramatic Arts in 
1992. After appearing in television dramas and a couple of feature 
films, she attracted international attention in Gillian Armstrong's 
``Oscar and Lucinda'' with Ralph Fiennes. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Academy nominees luncheon, Miss Blanchett was asked how  
she managed to speak like an English queen. Her reply: ``I think 
the Australian sound sits between the English and the American. We 
have been so inundated by British and American television that we 
know what both accents sound like.'' 

</P>
<P>
             	 *FERNANDA MONTENEGRO, ``Central Station''    	
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilian actress has charmed reporters with her effusive  
comments about her nomination: ``I'm not young, I'm not beautiful, 
but this is so exciting. ... I'm like a child, I play like a child. 
...'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Montenegro is a veteran of the Brazilian stage and of  
Brazilian TV and films, having appeared in more than 50 plays and 
dozens of movies and soap operas. Among the titles: ``They Don't 
Wear Black Tie,'' ``Hour of the Star'' and ``See This Song.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 71st Oscar nominations mark the first time two in the  
leading actor and actress categories gave non-English-speaking 
performances. Miss Montenegro spoke Portuguese in ``Central 
Station,'' Roberto Benigni Italian in ``Life Is Beautiful.'' Only 
one lead has won the Oscar in a foreign language: Sophia Loren in 
``Two Women'' in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Central Station,'' Miss Montenegro plays Dora, a woman who  
makes her living in an airport by writing letters for travelers. 
One of her clients is a woman with a small boy. When the woman is 
killed in a traffic accident, Dora forms a relationship with the 
boy. 

</P>
<P>
             	 *GWYNETH PALTROW, ``Shakespeare in Love''    	
</P>
<P>
	If ``Shakespeare in Love'' had stuck to plan, Julia Roberts  
would have played Viola, the playwright's fictional lover and 
inspiration for ``Romeo and Juliet.'' But two years ago the 
producers were stymied in their search for a young, romantic Will, 
and filming was postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	When the film was reorganized, another American, Gwyneth  
Paltrow, was cast as Viola. ``She was our first choice,'' says 
producer Donna Gigliotti. ``I had done a picture with Gwyneth 
called 'Emma.' I had loved her since the first time I saw her at 16 
with her mom in the theater.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Los Angeles, Miss Paltrow grew up in movies and theater,  
her mother being the actress Blythe Danner, her father film 
producer Bruce Paltrow. As a teen-ager, she appeared with John 
Travolta in ``Shout.'' A chance meeting with Steven Spielberg led 
to her casting as Wendy in his grown-up version of Peter Pan, 
``Hook.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an adult, she has appeared in ``A Perfect Murder'' opposite  
Michael Douglas, ``Seven'' with Brad Pitt, ``Great Expectations'' 
with Ethan Hawke and ``Jefferson in Paris'' with Nick Nolte. 

</P>
<P>
                 	 *MERYL STREEP, ``One True Thing''    	
</P>
<P>
	The question wasn't whether Meryl Streep would be nominated as  
best actress; it was which picture she would be cited for: ``One 
True Thing'' or ``Dancing at Lughnasa.'' The voters chose ``One 
True Thing,'' in which she plays a small-town housewife devoted to 
her home and club life. She faces death by cancer with the same 
orderliness she has insisted on in her married life. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the late 1970s, Miss Streep has been nominated 11 times,  
tying with Jack Nicholson (Katharine Hepburn holds the record with 
12). Her Oscars came for a supporting role in ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' 
in 1979 and lead in ``Sophie's Choice,'' 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Educated at Vassar College and the Yale Drama School, Miss  
Streep made her film debut as Jane Fonda's society friend in 
``Julia.'' Her second movie, ``The Deer Hunter,'' brought her first 
Oscar nomination as supporting actress. During the 1980s and 1990s 
she has reigned as the premier actress of American films. 

</P>
<P>
                	 *EMILY WATSON, ``Hilary and Jackie''    	
</P>
<P>
	Besides Meryl Streep, only Emily Watson has been nominated  
before among the best actress nominees -- for ``Breaking the Waves'' 
two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Watson plays the British cellist Jacqueline du Pre, whose  
brilliant career was ended by multiple sclerosis in 1987. The movie 
traces the often stormy relationship of du Pre and her older sister 
Hilary (played by Rachel Griffiths). It was based on the book by 
Hilary and her brother Piers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hilary and Jackie'' became engulfed in controversy when famed  
classical musicians, including violinists Itzhak Perlman and Yehudi 
Menuhin, wrote a letter to the London Times condemning the 
portrayal of their late colleague as ``selfish, spoiled and 
manipulative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the Jacqueline du Pre that we, as her friends and  
colleagues, knew,'' they wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	When Miss Watson appeared at the recent nominees luncheon, she  
dismissed the complaint as ``a spot of bother.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
