<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains Lower; Soybeans Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures were mostly lower and soybeans  
mixed in early dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk of overnight export business was supportive to soybeans,  
but generally the trade was uninspiring. Likewise, rumors of a 
last-minute acreage set-aside by the government this year was 
dismissed by most market participants. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures fell as traders digested news of low net export  
sales. Reports of problems with the Chinese winter wheat crop were 
supportive. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn was mixed at the open after rallying Wednesday on news the  
United States may lift its ban on agricultural sales to Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery was off 2 1/4 cents to $2.75 1/2 a bushel; May  
corn was off 1/2 cent to $2.25 1/4 a bushel; May oats were unchanged at 
$1.11 1/2 a bushel; May soybeans were up 3/4 cent to $4.82 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and feeder cattle futures were mostly higher on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs and pork bellies were 
also higher. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle futures rose 0.38 cent to 67.25 cents a pound;  
March feeder cattle were off 0.05 cent to 71.95 cents per pound; 
April lean hogs were up 0.65 cent to 41.62 cents a pound; and May 
pork bellies were up 0.43 cent to 50.90 cents per pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
