<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:59:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Producers Seek Federal Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 100 independent oil and natural gas  
producers have fanned out across Washington this week, clamoring 
for federal help for an industry battered by low crude oil prices 
stemming from a worldwide glut. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond seeking tax relief and other legislative help, the  
marginal producers and their allies on Capitol Hill are calling on 
the Clinton administration to change its policies toward Iraq. 
Under a U.N. policy supported by the United States, Iraq is allowed 
to sell up to $10.4 billion of oil a year in order to purchase food 
and medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House is assembling a task force, to be headed by  
presidential economic adviser Gene Sperling, to examine the state 
of the oil industry and possible relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic producers have seen their industry shrink by 50,000  
jobs in the last year and seen more than 136,000 oil wells shut 
down since November 1997. They contend the oil-for-food program is 
serving mainly to aid Saddam Hussein while harming U.S. interests. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our rights are being violated by politicians taking care of  
the Middle East,'' complained Ruben Ramirez, a 34-year oil industry 
veteran from Kermit, Texas, who has been laid off amid the 
industry's current woes. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the oil-for-food program, Iraq can use $600 million a year  
to rebuild its oil infrastructure and drill new wells, adding to 
the current oversupply and potentially handing Iraq a tool to 
destabilize oil markets, producers said at a Capitol news 
conference Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not want to argue against ... some kind of relief for  
the Iraqi people,'' said New Mexico producer George Yates, chairman 
of the Independent Petroleum Association of America. ``But what 
we're saying is that the oil-for-food program is skewed. It is 
government at work, it is not the market at work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing before Senate committees Wednesday, Energy Secretary  
Bill Richardson said Iraq's 2.5 million barrel-a-day production has 
a negligible impact on U.S. oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	But that view was dismissed by the chairman of the Senate Energy  
and Natural Resources Committee, Sen. Frank Murkowski of Alaska, 
who noted oil prices rose sharply when OPEC last week proposed 
production cuts of 2 million barrels a day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to recognize that old reality that charity begins at  
home,'' Murkowski said at Thursday's news conference, organized by 
IPAA. ``We've got to support our domestic petroleum industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IPAA, which represents thousands of marginal producers, is  
backing legislation that would provide tax credits and return 
inactive wells to production. IPAA members met Tuesday at the White 
House with Vice President Al Gore, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, 
Richardson and other top administration officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Marginal producers account for 20 percent of domestic production  
-- a large share for a nation that depends on foreign oil for more 
than half of its energy needs, the independents note. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message has to be that the administration will not let  
this industry collapse,'' Yates said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 01:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Army General Hale Is Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LEWIS, Wash. (AP) -- A retired Army general who admitted to  
adulterous affairs with the wives of four subordinates has been 
reprimanded and fined -- and will not spend any time behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Maj. Gen. David Hale, 53, was ordered to pay a $10,000  
fine and forfeit $12,000 of his $75,744 annual pension for one 
year. He had faced up to 11 years in prison and prosecutors had 
wanted him jailed. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale, who tearfully apologized in court, did not meet with  
reporters after Wednesday's hearing. Donald Mancuso, the Defense 
Department official who oversaw the investigation, said the 
sentence was enough to send a warning to other officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Such high-profile cases ``do in fact cause officers to think  
twice,'' Mancuso said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was the highest-ranking Army officer to face court-martial  
since 1952. His case led to allegations the Pentagon had a double 
standard for dealing with sexual misconduct when it came to 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was allowed to retire with honor last year despite claims  
of improprieties he committed while he was a top NATO commander in 
southern Europe. The resulting furor led the Pentagon to change its 
rules to bar top officers from retiring while facing allegations of 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale had faced up to 56 years in prison before prosecutors  
dropped nine charges in exchange for his guilty pleas to seven 
counts of conduct unbecoming an officer and one count of making 
false official statements. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale's civilian lawyer, Frank Spinner, said his client was ``not  
pleading guilty to any non-consensual sexual offenses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations concerned relationships Hale had from 1996 to  
1998 when he held the NATO post in Turkey. He and his wife 
separated in 1995 and divorced in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was forthright in admitting guilt.  
</P>
<P>
	He told of how he ordered two Caesar salads and a bottle of wine  
to a Connecticut hotel room, then had sex with Donnamaria Carpino 
Madden. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon afterward, the two shared a flight to Turkey, where they  
were met at the airport by Col. Everett Madden -- the woman's 
husband and Hale's chief of personnel and administration. Hale did 
not tell him of their relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Court-martial judge Col. Stephen Saynisch asked whether that  
constituted unbecoming conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sir, it's an understatement,'' Hale replied, adding he was  
ashamed, embarrassed and unable to look the colonel in the eye. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Mrs. Madden who sparked Mancuso's investigation with  
public complaints that Hale had forced her into a four-month sexual 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale testified that his life unraveled after his 29-year  
marriage ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``I let my compassion overrule my sense of propriety,'' he said,  
describing gifts of money to help another subordinate's recently 
divorced wife rebuild her life. He had sex with her in a Las Vegas 
hotel room. 
</P>
<P>
	At times, he said, his relationships with the women overlapped,  
but maintained all intimate acts grew out of friendship. He 
socialized with the women in scuba diving clubs, bowling clubs and 
on shopping trips. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot express how sorry I am, how embarrassed I am, for the  
pain I have brought on the U.S. Army, my fellow soldiers and my 
family and friends,'' he said, reading from a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Maj. Michael Mulligan recommended a jail sentence  
``to send a message there is no difference ... between the lowliest 
private and a general.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Spinner said the embarrassment was enough. And even Mrs.  
Madden -- who also has filed a civil action against the Army and Air 
Force officials, alleging they tried to discredit her in the 
investigation -- suggested the sentence was an adequate deterrent. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale ``is now forever a convicted felon and proven liar,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``While some may debate whether the sentence appropriately  
matches the crimes, I am very pleased to see that not even a 
two-star general is above the law,'' Mrs. Madden said. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other case in which an Army general faced court-martial  
since Congress enacted the Uniform Code of Military Justice in 1951 
was in 1952, when Maj. Gen. Robert Grow, military attache in 
Moscow, was tried on charges of dereliction of duty. 
</P>
<P>
	He was reprimanded and suspended from command for six months.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Sgt. Maj. Gene McKinney, then the Army's  
highest-ranking enlisted man, was reduced in rank and reprimanded 
after he was convicted of obstruction of justice in a sexual 
misconduct case. He was acquitted of 18 counts alleging sexual 
harassment of six military women. 
</P>
<P>
	In another case, Air Force Lt. Kelly Flinn, the nation's first  
and only female B-52 pilot, was given a general discharge after 
being charged with adultery for having an affair with the husband 
of a female airman in North Dakota. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
