<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDX Earnings Up; Stock To Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The parent company of Federal Express  
Corp. posted better-than-expected profits Thursday despite the drag 
of $90 million spent on preparing for a strike. FDX also announced 
a 2-for-1 stock split. 
</P>
<P>
	FDX earned $78 million, or 52 cents per share, in its third  
quarter ended Feb. 28, exceeding Wall Street forecasts by a wide 
margin. In the same period a year ago, FDX earned $18 million, or 
12 cents a share, including one-time acquisition costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Third-quarter revenues totaled $4.1 billion, a 3 percent  
increase from year-ago levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong showing boosted FDX shares, which closed up $5.18 3/4,  
or 6 percent, to $98.12 1/2 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest earnings data reflects contingency expenses related  
to a threatened pilot walkout during the Christmas season. 
</P>
<P>
	FDX spent $90 million leasing planes and crews from other  
companies in preparation. The strike was averted when negotiators 
for the two sides reached an agreement in early December. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding one-time factors, per-share earnings for the  
just-ended quarter amounted to 87 cents, up from 65 cents in the 
same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Express founder and chairman Frederick Smith said the  
company is benefiting with more businesses sending smaller 
shipments frequently to keep inventory down. 
</P>
<P>
	He also cited an increase in business-to-business electronic  
commerce and ``supply chain reengineering,'' which aims to move an 
order from manufacturer to customer quicker with fewer go-betweens. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDX board of directors authorized a stock split in which FDX  
investors of record on April 15 will receive two shares for every 
one they hold. The split will take effect on May 16. 
</P>
<P>
	FedEx, based in Memphis, Tenn., is the world's largest cargo  
airline. It has 145,000 employees worldwide and ships more than 3 
million items to 211 countries each day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
