<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets fell Thursday after a 3.3  
percent drop in the region's largest market, Tokyo, prompted 
investors elsewhere to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, shares fell after a strong rally this week that had  
propelled the blue chips to an eight-month high. The U.S. dollar 
was lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 550.19 points,  
or 3.38 percent, to finish the day at 15,717.92. On Wednesday, the 
average rose 1.22 percent -- its highest close since July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors bailed out after the Dow Jones industrial average  
fell overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest in Japanese stocks among foreign investors remained  
strong, but the market has shot up so sharply that some selling 
seemed natural, said Sachio Ishikawa of Chuo Securities in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On currency markets, the dollar bought 118.52 yen in afternoon  
trading, down 0.12 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its 
late New York level of 118.01 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares fell after a steady rise over the past  
seven weeks, plunging 2.6 percent on the losses in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index shed 280.75 points to close at  
10,659.32. The index rose 0.3 percent on Wednesday and gained 
nearly 18 percent over the past month. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was mainly affected by Japan,'' said Andrew To of  
Tai Fook Securities, Co. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares fell amid consistently weak corporate earnings  
reports. The Straits Times Index fell 4.09 points, or 0.27 percent, 
to 1,466.07. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rose 1.7 percent on late buying of banking  
stocks. The SET index rose 6.11 points at 362.91. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose slightly on selective buying of blue  
chips, despite anticipation of more dismal corporate earnings. The 
Composite Index was up 3.49 points, or 0.67 percent, at 515.34 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rose on foreign buying of Philippine Long  
Distance Telephone Co. The PSE Index rose 41.26 points, or 2.1 
percent, at 2,024.05. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares fell 3.6 percent as investors cashed in on recent  
gains. The KOSPI fell 21.54 points at 578.98. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares fell on worries that the main market index might  
have reached its short-term peak. The All Ordinaries index fell 
10.1 points, or 0.3 percent, to 2,967.7. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares rose on buying in semiconductor, plastics, and  
paper-related stocks. The Weighted Price Index rose 137.94 points, 
or 2 percent, to 6,895.01. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares fell on a late sell-off led by Telecom Corp.  
of New Zealand Ltd. The benchmark NZSE-40 capital fell 28.48 
points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,141.43. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Markets were closed for a public holiday.  

</P>
</TEXT>
