<HEADLINE> LA Tries To Get NFL Groups Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A day after NFL owners voted to give Los  
Angeles a new franchise, two competing groups were being urged to 
get together behind one proposal that would have the team play at a 
renovated Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Richard Riordan was said to be trying to broker  
cooperation between the two investment groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Coliseum is head and shoulders above any other venue,''  
Riordan said. ``We're going to have a team here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riordan has already talked to members of both camps and is  
setting up meetings intended to end competition, the Los Angeles 
Times reported today, citing sources it did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our door is open,'' said Eli Broad, a leader in the coliseum  
bid said Wednesday. ``We'd be delighted to get together and talk 
about it. I would hope that we would end up with a unified bid 
behind the Coliseum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Hollywood dealmaker Michael Ovitz, who heads the group  
backing a stadium in Carson, said it was too soon to determine if 
his group would be willing to give up its original plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to assess that right now,'' he said. ``We're  
thrilled that L.A. is in the running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NFL team owners voted 29-2 Tuesday to award Los Angeles the  
league's next expansion franchise. But they made it a conditional, 
six-month offer. If no acceptable stadium and franchise proposal is 
produced by Sept. 15, it's back to the drawing boards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz's group wants to build a new stadium in Carson, about 18  
miles south of downtown Los Angeles. The other group, led by real 
estate developer Ed Roski wants to overhaul the downtown Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Magic Johnson, one of Ovitz's partners, said Wednesday it may be  
time for his group to merge with the Coliseum effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's the Coliseum, I'm for that,'' he said. ``What I want  
is football, and it sounds like the Coliseum may be the way to get 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coliseum appears to be the owners' choice, but with  
reservations. The main question they seem to have is how much 
money, especially public money, would be available for redoing the 
Coliseum and the area around it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
