<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Lab Threat Analysis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Moving to counter congressional complaints of  
lax security, President Clinton is ordering a review at the 
nation's nuclear weapons laboratories even as relations with China 
falter over espionage suspicions. 
</P>
<P>
	Brushed aside in the clamor were urgent appeals from Beijing to  
maintain the strong ties Clinton has championed in six years in the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``China has become -- or rather the Sino-U.S. relationship has  
become -- the victim of party politics in the United States,'' a 
Chinese diplomat told reporters here Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am determined to do all that is necessary to protect our  
sensitive national security information and to prevent its 
diversion to foreign countries,'' Clinton said in a statement a few 
hours later. 
</P>
<P>
	The review will be undertaken by his Foreign Intelligence  
Advisory Board, a bipartisan and independent panel headed by former 
Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese diplomat, He Yafei, a minister-counsel at the  
Chinese Embassy, denied his government stole nuclear secrets at the 
Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico. He said the 
allegations were rooted in Cold War thinking and ``political 
atmospherics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China's prime minister, Zhu Rongai, has called the allegations a  
``fallacy'' and part of an ``anti-China wave.'' He is due here next 
month for talks designed to reinforce the administration's policy 
of good relations with Beijing and to reinforce China's bid to join 
the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu said this week he expected critics to ``vent anger'' at him.  
Clinton, meanwhile, hopes the review and Energy Secretary Bill 
Richardson's plans for tightened security at the laboratories will 
dampen the political firestorm touched off by suspicions that Wen 
Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born American engineer, helped China in the 1980s 
to learn the design of an advanced nuclear warhead. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence  
Committee, this week complained that security at Los Alamos and at 
other facilities has been ``too loose too long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice chairman, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., also was critical,  
saying of security measures, ``I no longer have confidence we are 
doing it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, in a joint letter to Sandy Berger, the president's  
national security adviser, the two senators complained about the 
way the administration was briefing congressional intelligence 
committees. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton acted on Berger's recommendation in ordering the review.  
Some Republicans have called for Berger's resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	The president asked Rudman for a report within 60 days. The  
inquiry will be conducted by the former senator and four other 
members of the 12-member board. 
</P>
<P>
	Two were identified Thursday as Anthony S. Harrington, a  
Washington lawyer, and Dr. Sidney D. Drell, a professor and deputy 
director of the Stanford University Linear Accelerator Center. The 
two other members have not been named. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also asked Rudman to consult with Congress before  
conducting his review, and then to share his findings with Congress 
and the public. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're under no illusions about China or any other country that  
tries to acquire our sensitive technologies, whether friend or 
foe,'' David Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council, 
said. ``What we need to do is be vigilant to protect our secrets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle, making his first major foreign  
policy speech as a potential presidential candidate in 2000, 
criticized the Clinton administration for removing the link between 
human rights and trade policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``President Clinton has consistently supported granting China  
most-favored nation status, no matter how egregious the human 
rights abuses documented by his own State Department,'' Quayle 
charged in a speech prepared for delivery today in Los Angeles to 
the World Affairs Council. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department spokesman, James Foley, said, meanwhile, that  
concern about the espionage reports was deep and ``shared widely by 
both branches, the executive and legislative branches of 
government, by both political parties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no division there. The Chinese should not read our  
concern over espionage as a partisan matter or a matter that's 
manufactured by opponents of U.S.-China relations.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
