<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Flies 3rd Group To Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq sent a third -- and possibly last --  
group of pilgrims to Saudi Arabia today aboard a Russian-made cargo 
plane, violating U.N. sanctions against air travel in and out of 
Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The Il-76 took off this afternoon with 124 ``elderly and sick  
men and women pilgrims,'' the official Iraqi News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight to Jiddah, Saudi Arabia -- a main dropoff point for  
Muslims performing the hajj, or annual pilgrimage -- would be the 
last, the news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Il-76 plane had flown to Saudi Arabia on Tuesday and  
Wednesday, transporting 221 pilgrims in the two flights. That plane 
was seized Wednesday by Saudi Arabia, which asked the U.N. 
sanctions committee for instructions, diplomats said at the United 
Nations. U.N. sanctions were imposed on Iraq for invading Kuwait in 
1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the committee took no action, Saudi Arabia got the green  
light to release the plane, as it said it would do today, said 
Peter Mollema, a diplomat from the Netherlands, which chairs the 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not been able to reach consensus and as a consequence  
... we understand the Saudis will let the plane go,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraqi officials and an air force pilot at the air base had  
earlier claimed that today's flight was by the same Il-76 that had 
flown on the previous two days. 
</P>
<P>
	But an Iraqi diplomat at the United Nations said it was a  
different Il-76 that flew to Saudi Arabia today. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports also refuted claims by Iraqi officials that the  
country had only one operational civilian plane at its disposal. 
Most of the country's planes have been parked abroad since the 1991 
Gulf War or are not operational. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters were not invited to cover today's departure of the  
plane as they were for the last two trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a Libyan passenger jet said to be carrying Muslim  
pilgrims flew to Saudi Arabia today on a flight that apparently 
also would violate a U.N. embargo. Libya has defied the embargo 
every year since 1994 to ferry Libyans to Saudi Arabia for the 
hajj. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. Security Council imposed limited sanctions on Libya in  
1992 after it refused to hand over for trial two suspects wanted 
for the bombing of a U.S. plane over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988. 
The blast killed 270 people, including 198 Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from those ferried by air, Iraq is sending 18,000 pilgrims  
by land. They are camped at the border post of Arar, waiting to be 
allowed to proceed to the Saudi cities of Mecca and Medina, Islamic 
holy cities where millions of Muslims gather each year for the 
hajj. 
</P>
<P>
	A deal between Iraq and the United Nations to provide each  
pilgrim with $2,000 from the country's oil-for-food money fell 
through on Tuesday because of a disagreement over distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq, a predominantly Muslim nation, says the 8 1/2-year-old  
sanctions infringe its people's religious rights. Islam requires 
every able-bodied person who can afford it to travel at least once 
to Mecca to perform the hajj. The hajj season this year culminates 
at the end of March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
