<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Not Funding Disabled Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The school district in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, had  
already overspent its special education budget by $1 million when 
the Supreme Court ruled it had to pay for one-on-one nursing for a 
student -- adding $30,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Garret Frey, the 16-year-old sophomore on a ventilator because  
of an accident that left him paralyzed, isn't the issue, said 
Superintendent Lew Finch. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is really about the federal government creating rules  
requiring schools to educate children with disabilities, but not 
sending enough money to ensure they can afford it. 
</P>
<P>
	If schools don't get more help, they may need to raise local  
taxes, Finch said. ``This might be the case that opens a lot of 
eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Special education is one of the most emotional issues schools  
face, and one of their fastest-growing costs. States have long 
fought with local schools and the Education Department over costs. 
Now Republicans and Democrats in Congress are debating how much the 
federal government should help. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 6 million children receive special education instruction  
and services costing $60 billion, about $5 billion of that from the 
federal government. About $55 billion comes from states and local 
districts, which follow strict rules stemming from the 1975 federal 
law covering special education. 
</P>
<P>
	States get anywhere from 7 percent to 12 percent of their  
special education money from the federal program. The law allows 
the federal government to contribute up to 40 percent -- or about 
$11 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our first obligation is to fulfill the needs demanded from the  
laws already on the books,'' said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who has 
proposed increasing the federal contribution to at least $9 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In their first education debate this year, Republicans and  
Democrats sparred over a bill that would let schools spend money 
sought by the Clinton administration for new elementary school 
teachers on special education instead. The Senate approved the 
idea, but the House didn't consider it. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, not usually known for increasing education  
spending, have criticized President Clinton's request for a 1 
percent increase in special education funding. Giving the states 
more special education money frees local money for other needs such 
as new computers, new teachers and new school buildings, Gregg 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats want federal money spent on the teachers and other  
early education programs that they say could help reduce the number 
of children classified as learning disabled, the biggest category 
of special education students. 
</P>
<P>
	If budget restraints were gone, the administration would support  
more special education money, said Judith E. Heumann, who runs the 
Education Department's special education programs. But states also 
should manage their own dollars better, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heumann, who is in a wheelchair, says of Republicans: ``They are  
scapegoating disabled kids. We have serious concerns that one group 
should be pitted against the other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the federal special education law was passed in 1975, there  
were approximately 4 million children who needed special education, 
approximately 8 percent of school-age children. Nearly 2 million of 
them, some with severe disabilities, were excluded from financially 
strapped public schools, and the law was passed to ensure they were 
educated. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, 5.8 million special-needs children nationwide  
representing 12 percent of the school-age population. 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics suggest schools are placing into special education  
more students who simply can't read well, who speak another 
language or who have behavior differences that prevent them from 
fully functioning in a classroom setting. 
</P>
<P>
	The National School Boards Association estimates that 17,000  
children nationwide have high-cost needs. The Education Department 
says 600 to 2,000 need ventilators like Frey. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cedar Rapids, for example, the average expense per special ed  
child is $7,800 -- $3,800 above its average for non-special-needs 
children. The district has about 50 severely disabled students who 
cost at least $15,000 each a year to educate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe in the rights of those students, but we're getting  
to the point that we're not always protecting the rights of other 
children who are not disabled,'' said Dolorita Reandeau of the 
South Kitsap schools in western Washington state, which recently 
paid a $20,000 legal bill in a due process hearing for one student. 
``Our hands are tied.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parents of special ed students say they and their children are  
paying, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheryl Watson of Harrisburg, Pa., has spent years struggling  
with her district over the cost of services, such as tutoring and 
computer software, for her 13-year-old son, who has Tourette's 
syndrome and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is you have to look at the severity of the  
impact on the child's learning,'' Watson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
