<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Condor Found Shot to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- A California condor, released in  
northern Arizona as part of a reintroduction program, was found 
shot to death in Grand Canyon National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildlife officials said they learned of the shooting Monday.  
``This isn't being taken lightly,'' said Jeff Humphrey, a spokesman 
for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Condors were granted federal protection under the Endangered  
Species Act in 1967. Among the most ancient of North America's 
birds, condors were nearly extinct when biologists launched a 
recovery program in the late 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Condors were first reintroduced to Arizona in 1996. There are  
over 100 condors in the wild in California and Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Intentionally killing an endangered species is punishable by up  
to a year in jail and $100,000 fine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
