<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bucs' Martin Might Be Odd Man Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates are trying to  
wedge four outfielders into three positions, and it looks more and 
more like the odd man out is Al Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, nearly traded to Arizona last month, now seems to have  
definitely lost his left fielder's job to Brian Giles. He 
apparently won't unseat Jose Guillen in right field, either. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Gene Lamont confirmed Thursday that Martin likely will  
be on the bench when the season starts, barring an unexpected 
injury or trade before the Pirates play the Montreal Expos on April 
5. 
</P>
<P>
	Giles would start in left, with Brant Brown in center and  
Guillen in right field despite missing more than two weeks of 
spring training in a visa dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Martin's status following the Pirates' 7-6 victory  
against the Philadelphia Phillies, Lamont said, ``We got two guys 
(Giles and Brown) in trades and Guillen drove in 84 runs last year. 
If Guillen is ready, he'll probably start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates initially were concerned that Guillen's late arrival  
might force him to start the season at Triple-A Nashville to make 
up the time he missed in camp. But he has swung the bat well during 
his first seven days in camp and had two hits in his first 
exhibition start Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's looked fine. He's come out swinging, and that doesn't  
really surprise me,'' Lamont said. ``I think he'll be fine when the 
season starts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen was hitless in two at-bats Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Martin admittedly fretted after being demoted to a platoon role  
while batting a career-low .239 in 1998, and his offseason was 
equally unsettled as the Pirates tried unsuccessfully to trade him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates were within minutes of dealing him to Arizona until  
Diamondbacks outfielder Bernard Gilkey declined to rework minor 
contract language that would allow the trade to go through. 
</P>
<P>
	But Martin said he is tired of worrying where he will be on  
opening day -- in left field, on the bench -- or in another city. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I'm just trying not to think about it very much,''  
Martin said. ``Whether I'm in the lineup or not, if I worry about 
it I'll get upset or mad, so I'll just let it go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin has not talked to general manager Cam Bonifay to  
determine if any other teams have shown interest in a .280 career 
hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't heard anything,'' Martin said. ``Everybody's just  
going about their business and ... well, I don't know, I'm tired of 
worrying about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his own undefined role, Martin said the addition of five  
veteran position players -- even the one who has taken his job -- has 
created a more major-league attitude in the Pirates' clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin likes not having to be a nursemaid, confidante and big  
brother to a platoon of inexperienced players, as he was last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely more major league,'' Martin said. ``Last year  
was a lot different, just telling guys how to act. This year, it's 
much more of a big league atmosphere, and that's half the battle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other half? Perhaps it's returning to the lineup as an  
everyday player. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things could surely change during the season if one of them  
isn't swinging well,'' Lamont said. ``These things usually have a 
way of sorting themselves out.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
