<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 11:24:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Friends Toast John Glenn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- For a change, John Glenn wasn't in  
a parade, wasn't getting a medal, wasn't even being praised as the 
great geriatric hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he was among old friends and fellow astronauts, and the  
mood was anything but reverential as they toasted him -- not just 
for his space-shuttle flight last October, but for the 37th 
anniversary of his first rocket ride. 
</P>
<P>
	Gene Cernan, the last man to walk on the moon, portrayed Glenn  
in a skit as a feeble-minded old geezer bound for space. ``I hear 
they're going to let me preboard,'' Cernan deadpanned. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Mercury astronauts Scott Carpenter, Wally Schirra and  
Gordon Cooper took aim at the recently retired senator's squeaky 
clean image. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Larry Flynt report on John Glenn shocked the public  
today,'' Schirra intoned. ``Mr. Flynt revealed that he has 
photographs of the astro-senator using his salad fork on his steak 
and confirms sightings of John wearing white shoes after Labor 
Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn, who became the oldest person in space at age 77, aboard  
the shuttle Discovery, plunged right into the spirit of things. 
</P>
<P>
	``Space could well be an old folks' home,'' he told 550 guests  
who paid up to $1,000 each to attend the charity fund-raiser at a 
Walt Disney World hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you spill food, it doesn't go on your tie or anything.  
You don't need a cane or a walker or a wheelchair, you just float. 
Drive in no traffic and leave the turn signal on, it doesn't make 
any difference. Balance? Who cares, you're upside down anyway. No 
falls, no broken hips. If you can't sleep, don't worry about it, 
night will be coming along in about 45 minutes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn got his first taste of celebrity in February 1962, when he  
became the first American to orbit the Earth. Reaction to his 
second trip, aboard Discovery, was just as intense. Wherever he 
goes -- Majorca, Barcelona, Rome, Osaka, Kyoto, Disney World -- he's 
recognized. Whenever he stops, he's mobbed by well-wishers. 
</P>
<P>
	He says he never expected it, isn't courting it, and isn't sure  
why it's happening. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it's because of age, or his Senate background, ``or the  
fact that we were the first orbital flight, or whatever 
combination,'' the former Democratic lawmaker tells reporters, 
almost apologetically. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe you can give me a better analysis of it than I can give  
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astronaut Hall of Fame near the Kennedy Space Center  
collected more than 40,000 notes to Glenn between September and 
March, enough to fill 21 books. 
</P>
<P>
	He's one of this year's winners of the Ellis Island Medal of  
Honor, along with Hillary Rodham Clinton and Chief Justice William 
Rehnquist. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City gave him a ticker tape parade, and he's the first  
astronaut to have a NASA center named after him. The Lewis Research 
Center in Cleveland is now the John H. Glenn Research Center at 
Lewis Field. 
</P>
<P>
	He has signed with Bantam Books to write his autobiography, due  
out this fall, and he celebrated Christmas two months late because 
of post-flight obligations and his departure from the Senate after 
24 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn and his six much younger crew mates went on a world tour  
and were feted by prime ministers and chancellors, even a king and 
queen. (One crew member is from Spain, another from Japan.) 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone figured we were in 11 different hotels in 13 days, so  
it wasn't exactly a pleasure trip,'' Glenn says. ``I was recognized 
most places,'' he adds. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn says he's indifferent to the spotlight: ``I don't run to  
cameras. I don't run away from cameras. I just try and live my 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors at Johnson Space Center in Houston are still studying  
Glenn to see what they can learn about geriatrics in space, and the 
tests will continue until about May. 
</P>
<P>
	Unusual for an astronaut, Glenn suffered no motion sickness or  
other ailment during his nine days in orbit. The moment he got 
back, though, nausea struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning astronauts often suffer dizziness and stiffness. In  
Glenn's case it lasted only a day. By the fourth day after his 
return -- and every day since -- he has felt completely normal, he 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn plans to spend his retirement working with students at  
Muskingum College in his hometown of New Concord, Ohio, and at Ohio 
State University. His goal is to encourage young people to go into 
public service. 
</P>
<P>
	He'd love to go back into space but doubts his wife, Annie,  
would approve. His two children certainly wouldn't. 
</P>
<P>
	His family gave him a stack of books for Christmas figuring  
reading ought to keep him on the ground. And his colleagues, as 
demonstrated at the roast, will keep his ego in check. 
</P>
<P>
	But Glenn had the last laugh.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no truth whatsoever to the fact that NASA refused to  
let me have a spacewalk because they were afraid I'd wander off 
someplace,'' Glenn said. ``And there's also no truth to the claim 
that I was the first 77-year-old to leave Florida in something 
other than a Winnebago.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
