<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 14:55:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Helps High-Speed Internet, Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Companies that provide high-speed Internet and  
data services would be helped by action Thursday by federal 
regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission agreed to tighten rules  
making it easier for companies to install equipment at major local 
phone companies' central offices to provide high-speed services. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised rules should take effect in one or two months.  
</P>
<P>
	The order would help companies, including Covad Communications  
and NorthPoint Communications, which provide connections letting 
businesses access information from computers at speeds considerably 
faster than regular phone lines. It also would help other companies 
that want to provide just local phone service. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's order is designed to make it cheaper and faster for  
companies that compete or want to compete against the nation's five 
Bell companies, GTE and other major local phone providers to put 
equipment inside the major companies' offices in order to provide 
competing services. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies need to do that to provide their own competing  
phone, data or Internet access services. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said the order should spur more  
competition for all these services. 
</P>
<P>
	The order, among other things, lets the competing companies  
install a wider range of equipment than previously allowed in those 
offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The order also gives the competing companies, for the first  
time, the option of being able to rent a tiny amount of space, 
rather than being forced to rent a 10-foot by 10-foot fenced 
enclosure, which can be expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, it lets competing companies that have been denied space to  
inspect the major companies' offices for verification. 
</P>
<P>
	Covad said the FCC's order could help the company provide  
services to more areas by ``reducing some of the bureaucracy and 
cost'' of installing equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth does not believe the revised rules are necessary,  
saying it already offers rivals some of the options. Bell Atlantic 
said it needs to study the details of the FCC's order before taking 
a position on the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the FCC proposed licensing rules for companies that  
want to provide telephone and data services by satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC said it has enough airwaves space to accommodate all  
nine companies -- including Iridium, Globalstar and Boeing -- that 
have expressed interest in getting a license. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also said it would look into whether licensed companies  
should have to provide 911 service that lets emergency dispatchers 
know the location of callers. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC hopes to have a final licensing plan by the fall or  
winter and would start licensing companies shortly after that. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 12:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Neb. Firefighters Declare Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THEDFORD, Neb. (AP) -- Hundreds of exhausted firefighters  
declared victory today over flare-ups from a massive prairie fire 
that has consumed more than 50,000 acres of range land. They also 
mourned one of their own. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas County Attorney Warren Arganbright said 45-year-old  
Charles J. Vodak, a volunteer firefighter from nearby Dunning, died 
of an apparent heart attack while battling the flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Vodak, who was single, died at 9:20 p.m. CST Tuesday at the Reed  
Hamilton Ranch headquarters, about nine miles north of the 
junctions of State Highways 83 and 2. 
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy was being done today in Kearney.  
</P>
<P>
	Another firefighter suffered smoke inhalation and several other  
minor injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The good news after two nearly-sleepless days for hundreds of  
firefighters was that all flare-ups were declared under control or 
out by 8 p.m. CST Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, it looks like a done deal,'' said Duane Morrow of  
the Nebraska Emergency Management Agency. ``We're just doing a 
little mop-up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said all fires were out this morning. They revised  
the number of acres burned to 60,000 to 70,000 acres, including 
2,000 acres that burned late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Carpenter, District Ranger at the Nebraska National Forest  
and the McKelvie National Forest, said his crews, as well as some 
from the Bureau of Indian Affairs and the U.S. Fish and Wildlife 
Service, were patrolling the area today to guard against any 
flare-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the crews consisted of about 19 people using seven grass  
trucks, each of which carry about 300 gallons of water. 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday evening, firefighters had nearly extinguished a  
flare-up about three miles west of Thedford. Flames sent dozens of 
firefighters scurrying in small trucks over the charred hills to 
reengage the blaze. 
</P>
<P>
	Thick black, brown and white smoke obscured the setting sun as a  
wall of fire roared over the Middle Loup River valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Crop dusters from nearby towns -- pressed into service to pour  
water and fire retardant on hot spots -- buzzed the fire like 
divebombers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fanned by gusty winds Tuesday and Wednesday, the fire charred a  
40-mile long swath of north-central Nebraska grassland about 300 
miles northwest of Omaha. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 300 people were evacuated in and around Thedford before  
emergency managers declared victory over the blaze Wednesday 
morning. Wind gusts up to 45 mph caused problems soon after. 
</P>
<P>
	Winds diminished at sunset, and scores of firefighters swarmed  
local gas stations and stores for much-needed refreshments. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Mike Johanns declared a state of emergency to make state  
resources available to help fight the fire. National Guard members 
were alerted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen some prairie fires, but this was truly incredible,''  
Johanns said. ``That ranchland is burned up, and it's not going to 
grow back for a while. Any cattle and calves that got in the way of 
that fire in all likelihood are lost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johanns said some $2 million in state emergency funds could be  
available. The state also established a hotline for people 
interested in helping ranchers who lost stores of feed in the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the fire, believed to have started Tuesday, was not  
immediately known. The governor said a charred -- and apparently 
abandoned -- farmstead 10 miles north and five miles west of Mullen 
appeared to be the starting point. 
</P>
<P>
	The starting point was five miles east of a ranch owned by media  
mogul Ted Turner, who raises bison in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The path of the fire was up to 10 miles wide in places. One  
rural house was destroyed and officials said an unknown number of 
cattle perished in the sparsely settled region. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Westover of the Nebraska Forest Service said the estimated  
damage made the fire Nebraska's second largest. The first also 
started near Mullen in 1972. Satellite images showed that fire 
burned about 75,000 acres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
