<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Jury To Get Fight Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight is  
over. The investigations into the result are just beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	While a district attorney is already looking into possible  
criminal activity surrounding the bout, many of the principals 
involved in the bout were due to testify today at a state Senate 
hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau has convened a  
grand jury to issue subpoenas and gather testimony about the 
controversial draw at Saturday's heavyweight championship 
reunification fight at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgenthau's spokeswoman, Barbara Thompson, declined Wednesday  
to discuss what illegalities, if any, he thinks were involved in 
the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	One source close to the investigation, who asked not to be  
identified, said: ``We could be looking at tampering or illegal 
payments. Then again, maybe we're looking at lousy judging, which 
is not a crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among those to appear in New York City at a hearing of the state  
Senate Committee on Investigations are promoters Don King and Dino 
Duva, Lewis' American promoter; Bob Lee, the IBF president; referee 
Arthur Mercante Jr., and Eugenia Williams, the IBF-picked judge who 
had Holyfield winning the fight many believed Lewis dominated. 
</P>
<P>
	Slated to testify by phone were Larry O'Connell of England, the  
WBC judge who scored the fight a draw; Stanley Christodoulou of 
South Africa, the WBA judge who declared Lewis the winner; and WBC 
president Jose Sulaiman. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's hearing was expected to focus on the judging of  
Saturday's fight, the relationships between the sanctioning bodies 
and the boxing industry and health issues involving fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer canceled a public hearing  
scheduled for Friday involving many of the same people who were to 
appear today and will offer Morgenthau's investigators ``any and 
all assistance in their attempt to pursue a criminal case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New York state Athletic Commission is also investigating the  
Holyfield-Lewis draw. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who sat ringside at the bout,  
said Wednesday that state athletic commissions must take the lead 
in reforming professional boxing and not wait for the federal 
government to step in. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, the IBF president, defended the work of Williams, the judge  
his organization selected for the bout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am sure they aren't going to find anything irregular at  
all,'' he said. ``It is a subjective viewing of a fight and you 
can't tell these judges what to see or what not to see. All I tell 
them is, `Do the best you can.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, a $39,200-a-year municipal employee in Atlantic City,  
N.J., filed for bankruptcy on Jan. 25, according to a story in 
today's New York Post. 
</P>
<P>
	When Williams was asked about the filing she said, ``I don't  
know what you're talking about,'' according to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Jersey, the Star-Ledger of Newark said federal  
investigators are looking into allegations of corruption in 
professional boxing, including kickback schemes between fighters 
and promoters. 
</P>
<P>
	The probe also is investigating whether the International Boxing  
Federation and Lee sold rankings and arranged for fights in return 
for kickbacks from fighters and their promoters, according to the 
Star-Ledger. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, a former New Jersey boxing commissioner removed from office  
in 1985 after a state panel ruled he violated ethics regulations, 
confirmed that the investigation exists, but denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't done anything wrong,'' Lee said in today's editions  
of the newspaper. ``We try to promote the interests of boxing. What 
they are talking about, I don't know.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
