<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Two prison inmates who claim  
they are being held for political reasons doused themselves with 
alcohol and set themselves on fire, officials in the southern state 
of Chiapas said. 
</P>
<P>
	One inmate, Daniel Diaz Perez, suffered first- and second-degree  
burns after setting himself on fire Wednesday, said Febronio 
Tovilla, medical director at Cerro Hueco prison in Tuxtla 
Gutierrez, the state capital. The other inmate, Jose Cruz de la 
Porte, suffered less serious burns, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men are charged with kidnapping and arms trafficking.  
They have denied the accusations and claim they are being held 
because they are activists in a group that promotes indigenous 
rights. They have been on a hunger strike for a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Tovilla said the men's relatives had brought the alcohol into  
the prison. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela and Iran agreed Thursday to  
swap some oil customers in Europe and the Americas, hoping to cut 
transportation costs and boost profits for both countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, announced by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal  
Kharrazi, Iran will distribute oil to some of Venezuela's customers 
in Europe. In return, Venezuela will supply some of Iran's 
customers in the Americas. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the two countries are to meet March 21 in London  
to work out details of the agreement, Venezuelan Energy and Mines 
Minister Ali Rodriquez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for Venezuelan oil hit a 12-year low in recent months,  
helping provoke economic troubles that include a $9 billion fiscal 
deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Kharrazi, in Venezuela for a three-day visit, and Venezuelan  
Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel also signed an accord to 
strengthen Iranian-Venezuelan relations. On Wednesday, Kharrazi 
said Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez has accepted an invitation to 
visit Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's Congress voted Thursday to  
approve a financial transactions tax seen as key to the success of 
the government's fiscal reform program. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, which slaps a 0.38 percent tax on all banking  
transactions, passed the Chamber of Deputies 357-125 with one 
abstention. The measure was approved by the Senate earlier this 
year and should go into effect in 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The government expects the tax to yield about $4.8 billion this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax was the last piece of a broad government fiscal program  
that formed the backbone of an agreement with international lenders 
for $41.5 billion in aid. Approval of the tax should pave the way 
for release of a second tranche of funding, worth about $9 billion, 
in early April, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement between Brazil and the IMF requires stiff  
austerity measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
