<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:32:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders Balk at Kosovo Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration warned that ``NATO  
will act'' against Serb targets if Yugoslav leader Slobodan 
Milosevic doesn't accept the peace accord ethnic Albanians signed 
in Paris on Thursday. Those warnings drew a skeptical response on 
Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Serbs will be responsible for the consequences,'' said  
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	But Senate Republican leaders, unhappy with the administration's  
depiction of developments, late Thursday demanded a face-to-face 
meeting with President Clinton on Friday to discuss the escalating 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were not satisfied with what they heard'' at a  
closed-door briefing for senators by Albright and other top 
administration officials, said John Czwartacki, spokesman for 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. He said both Republican 
and Democratic senators had voiced their frustrations at the 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	He said sentiment in the GOP-ruled Congress had changed from  
``qualified support'' for administration policy ``to real serious 
debate over whether we should be heading into a long, drawn-out 
campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president agreed to see the leaders at 10:30 EST Friday, a  
White House spokesman said late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll be making clear that the United States has a clear  
national interest in preventing a wider war from spreading in 
Kosovo,'' said spokesman David Leavy. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the Air Force's chief of staff, Gen. Michael Ryan, said  
Milosevic's forces are well-prepared and well-equipped for a U.S. 
airstrike. ``There is a distinct possibility we will lose 
aircraft,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan and other top military commanders testified at a Senate  
hearing as negotiators on the Albanian side of the Kosovo dispute 
signed a peace agreement in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the talks teetering on the verge of collapse because of  
the Serbs' refusal to sign the accord, Yugoslav forces appeared to 
be mobilizing for all-out war. The ethnic Albanian-run Kosovo 
Information Center reported large movements of Yugoslav army and 
police forces throughout Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, press secretary Joe Lockhart warned that  
``NATO will act if President Milosevic and the Serbs, through their 
intransigence at the talks or through further aggression, resist 
finding some political settlement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of a Serbian buildup of troops along the Kosovo border, Lockhart  
said, ``Any buildup is of concern. Any further aggression here we 
would view as a grave mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Albright, speaking with reporters as she prepared to brief  
senators on the latest developments, said she had a message for 
Milosevic: ``NATO stands ready to take whatever measures are 
necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate had been poised to debate a move by Sen. Kay Bailey  
Hutchison, R-Texas, to sharply restrict funds for any U.S. military 
operation in Kosovo. But Senate leaders late Thursday postponed the 
debate until Monday after hearing from the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would be binding and would deny funds for any  
U.S. involvement in a peacekeeping operation unless approved by 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, emerging from the closed-door briefing, said he continues  
to have ``significant reservations'' about the possibility of NATO 
airstrikes followed by possible U.S. ground troops in Kosovo. ``We 
need to be advised what the risks are. And the American people need 
to have a better understanding what the United States national 
security interests are, if any.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchison told reporters, ``I am more convinced than ever that  
this is a mistake at this time.'' She said she would move ahead to 
try to get a Senate vote on whether the United States should become 
involved again militarily in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said she had spoken to Kosovo's Albanian leaders by  
phone, ``and I congratulated them for their courage and vision in 
signing the agreement negotiated in Paris.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, she said, ``the Serbian negotiators have gone  
backwards,'' refusing to even discuss the possibility of a NATO 
peacekeeping force in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, there can be no agreement if the Serbs do not sign,  
and right now there is no sign that the Serbs will agree,'' 
Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation is as clear as it could be. The Albanians have  
said yes to the accords and the Serbs are saying no,'' she added. 
She said if Belgrade doesn't reverse course, ``the Serbs will be 
responsible for the consequences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's air defenses are sophisticated and heavily  
defended, Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff, told the Senate Armed 
Services Committee earlier Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``These guys are very good. So taking on these defenses with air  
power will not be easy,'' he said. ``There is a distinct 
possibility we will lose aircraft in trying to penetrate those 
defenses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan said that the air-defense capability ``not just in Kosovo  
but within the whole Yugoslav land mass'' includes many 
surface-to-air missiles and other weaponry capable of shooting down 
U.S. warplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This defense array is much more substantive than'' in Bosnia  
by a factor of two or three times, Ryan said. Airstrikes helped 
bring about peace talks in Dayton, Ohio, which in 1995 helped end 
civil war in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is going to be tremendously dangerous,'' Marine Corps  
Commandant Gen. Charles Krulak agreed. Serbian air defense systems 
``are, in many instances, mobile. The terrain is very tough. And 
the weather cannot be underestimated. That can be a show-stopper in 
many ways,'' Krulak said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said some ``bottom-line questions'' still need to be  
answered: ``What is the endgame? How long will the strike go on? 
Will our allies stay with us?'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has threatened airstrikes against Serbian positions if the  
Albanian side in the peace talks signs the proposed peace 
settlement and Milosevic's Serbian delegation does not -- the 
current situation. 
</P>
<P>
	While first strikes would likely be sea-launched and  
air-launched missiles, warplanes flown by pilots probably would 
have to eventually go in, the military commanders suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	Adm. Jay Johnson, chief of naval operations, told the panel,  
``We should be under no illusions that this would be easy. The risk 
is high, in my view.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
