<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil TV Host Snarls Ransom Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- He is Brazil's answer to Jerry  
Springer, a TV ``shockmeister'' who thrives on the outrageous. But 
now, Carlos Massa may have gone too far. 
</P>
<P>
	Massa is accused of thwarting the release of a kidnapping victim  
by going on national TV with an offer to create a telephone hotline 
to help raise money for the ransom. After Massa got involved, the 
kidnappers upped their demand -- from $300,000 to $2 million -- and 
sent a piece of the victim's ear to back it up. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident pushed the kidnapping of Wellington Camargo, the  
brother of Brazilian country music star Zeze di Camargo, from the 
crime page to the front page of Brazilian newspapers. The case has 
drawn the attention of top Cabinet ministers and raised a debate 
about media ethics. 
</P>
<P>
	Camargo, who is paraplegic, was kidnapped in December near his  
home in the midwestern state of Goias. Negotiations between the 
kidnappers and Camargo's relatives had dragged on for months, 
until, the family says, a ransom of $300,000 was finally agreed on. 
</P>
<P>
	Then last week, Massa -- known to millions of TV viewers by his  
stage name ``Ratinho,'' Portuguese for Mouse -- got involved, 
calling on his viewers to make donations toward the ransom. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw that, I said: It's all gone down the drain,'' Zeze  
di Camargo said in a radio interview. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as the program aired, the kidnappers left a note outside  
a TV station with their new ransom demand -- and the piece of ear 
inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Massa's meddling sparked a national outcry.  
</P>
<P>
	An editorial in the Rio newspaper O Globo said Massa's actions,  
``in addition to breaking the law, violates the code of ethics of a 
TV announcer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Communications Minister Jose Pimenta da Veiga called the  
proposal ``hasty, inopportune and irresponsible.'' Justice Minister 
Renan Calheiros said he would study ways to punish Massa. 
</P>
<P>
	Camargo, accompanied by his brother and singing partner Luciano,  
met Thursday with Pimenta da Veiga and Senate President Antonio 
Carlos Magalhaes in Brasilia, the capital, where they reportedly 
discussed a new law with tougher rules on media ethics. 
</P>
<P>
	Massa said he has apologized to Camargo but felt the outcry was  
exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made a mistake, but it was involuntary,'' Massa said in a  
radio interview. ``It's tremendously unfair to blame this whole 
kidnapping thing on a TV show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camargo said the family was waiting for the kidnappers to get in  
touch again -- and praying they would not make good on their threat 
to cut off his brother's other ear. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just hope the bandits will negotiate, and we'll start all  
over again from zero,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
