<DOCNO> APW19990318.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:47:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Rejects U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Vietnam issued a sharp rebuke Thursday to  
a U.N. report on religious freedom, saying it will no longer allow 
investigations into human-rights issues or religious affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came two days after U.N. investigator  
Abdelfattah Amor reported that Vietnam maintains elaborate controls 
over all religious groups to prevent the emergence of any 
organization that might rival the Communist Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Amor said state interference includes controls over the programs  
of religious organizations, the training and recruitment of clergy, 
the building of places of worship and the printing of religious 
books. 
</P>
<P>
	While welcoming foreigners engaged in business and  
``humanitarian purposes,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Le Sy Vuong 
Ha said outside investigators were not welcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vietnam does not accept any individual or organization going  
to Vietnam with the intention of carrying out an investigation... 
because it interferes into Vietnam's internal affairs,'' he told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement comes amid concern about a conservative backlash  
in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissident Nguyen Thanh Giang was arrested March 4 for allegedly  
possessing anti-communist documents, a move that some Western 
diplomats saw as a warning to authors of recent letters criticizing 
the party for alleged corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Amor said despite government guarantees of access to anyone he  
wanted to see, he was prevented from meeting some leaders of 
unsanctioned religions. 
</P>
<P>
	Any religion not officially recognized by the Vietnamese  
government is considered superstition that must be stamped out. 
That includes unsanctioned sects of Buddhism and other religions. 
</P>
<P>
	For its part, Vietnam claimed Thursday that Amor had unfettered  
access. It called his 30-page report, which is to be presented next 
week to the U.N. Human Rights Commission, ``not objective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights groups say church leaders have been jailed because  
of their religious practices. Officials deny they hold any 
religious or political prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Buddhism is the primary religion among Vietnam's 78 million  
people. Important minority religions include the Roman Catholic and 
Protestant churches, and the indigenous Cao Dai and Hoa Hao. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations with the Vatican thawed slightly last year. The  
Vatican's deputy foreign minister, Celestino Migliore, wraps up a 
five-day visit on Friday that has been aimed at establishing 
diplomatic relations and paving the way for a pope visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 00:52:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wood Has Always Feared Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Kerry Wood had been dreading this since he  
was 12 years old, when replays of Dave Dravecky's chilling injury 
flashed over and over on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	While vendors sold spring training programs with Wood's picture  
on the cover, his season is over after just 26 spring training 
pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	If he's lucky, he'll be back early in 2000. If he's not -- well,  
there's no telling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've thought about this from the first time I saw the video --  
I can't remember his name now -- he threw one pitch and his arm 
broke,'' Wood said, remembering Dravecky's injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood's teammates were on the field, getting ready to play the  
Arizona Diamondbacks. Wood, in blue jeans and a cap as black as the 
Cubs' mood, was up in a luxury suite, talking about how doctors 
will take a ligament from his left wrist and transplant it into his 
right elbow to replace the one he tore Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year-old right-hander, the NL Rookie of the Year, is not  
even sure if he'll return for the start of the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't even had the surgery yet. It's too early to think  
about when I'm going to be back,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His 95 mph fastball, the one that delighted baseball last  
summer, the one that enabled him to strike out a record-tying 20 
against Houston last May, might never come back. He talked about 
how it was the work ethic of the individual that would make the 
difference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've played with guys who had the surgery,'' he said.  
``Sometimes guys were throwing harder and pitching better than 
before they were hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rehabilitation usually takes about a year, but sometimes it's  
less and sometimes it's more. He's had elbow pain since high 
school, but refused to blame the injury on his coaches, amateur and 
pro. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's safe to say it was inevitable,'' he said. ``From the time  
my velocity picked up and I started to throw harder, I felt it 
could happen on any given day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood had only 13 of the Cubs' 90 wins last season, but he  
brought excitement to Wrigley Field and everywhere he went. He was 
the next Nolan Ryan, the next Roger Clemens, a flamethrower from 
Texas who grabbed headlines with his heater. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the day he pitched, you'd go to the ballpark with an extra  
bounce in your step,'' Cubs president Andy MacPhail said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood will get a second opinion, just to make sure he needs the  
transplant, then choose Dr. Lewis Yocum, the Anaheim Angels team 
physician, or Dr. James Andrews to put his elbow back together. 
</P>
<P>
	When he comes back, he'll have to change his delivery some more,  
taking stress off the reconstructed elbow. The Cubs had tried to 
get him to stop throwing across his body, to plant his left foot 
another seven or eight inches toward the middle of the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough to change when you're throwing the ball good,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came his first warmup pitch before the second inning  
against Anaheim at Tempe. It was about 10 feet above the ground. 
Wood knew something was wrong but kept on pitching, still throwing 
95 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't something that startled me or gave me a great deal  
of pain,'' he said. ``Pitchers have kinks early in the spring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The kink turned out to be a major breakdown, a torn ulnar  
ligament. 
</P>
<P>
	With opening day nearly three weeks away, Wrigley's bleachers  
bums already had reason to cry in their beers. 
</P>
<P>
	For a franchise searching for its first pennant since 1945 and  
its first World Series title since 1908, Wood was the hope. Yes, 
Sammy Sosa provided the power, but pitching wins. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Cubs fans are ready to write off the team for the rest of  
the century, not surprising given its history. Wood says they 
shouldn't give up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because one player goes out, to say the whole season is  
shot, that's not fair,'' he said. ``We have a great team and I 
think we're going to bounce back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
