<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar, Gold Move Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mostly lower against other  
major currencies in European trading Thursday. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.1011, up from $1.0979 Wednesday, and  
the British pound was quoted at $1.6296, up from $1.6274. Later, in 
New York, the euro was trading at $1.0990. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 117.90 Japanese yen, down from 118.48.  
In midday New York trading, it was quoted at 117.53 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Wednesday included 1.4496  
Swiss francs, down from 1.4546; and 1.5180 Canadian dollars, down 
from 1.5200. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth: 1.7763 German marks,  
down from 1.7814; 5.9573 French francs, down from 5.9747; 2.0014 
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0072; 1,758.49 Italian lire, down from 
1,763.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $282.90 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$284.10 on Wednesday. In Zurich, the bid price was $282.80, down 
from $284.80. Gold rose 30 cents in Hong Kong to $284.35. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.04 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.01. 
</P>
