<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Theft Costs Companies $4B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. businesses lose an estimated $4 billion  
annually due to high-tech theft, according to the most far-reaching 
study yet released on the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	But increased security by the industry's largest high-tech  
manufacturers firms has dramatically reduced their losses in recent 
years, said the study released today by an electronics trade group 
and a consortium of high-tech executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The large firms, including Texas Instruments Inc. and Intel  
Corp., are taking steps that range from improved background checks 
of employees to more discreet packaging of products in transit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trends are going in the right direction,'' said Mike  
McQuade, a senior vice president of the American Electronics 
Association. ``It's pretty good news, although the problem has not 
gone away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The electronics association and the International Electronics  
Security Group sponsored the two-year study, which was carried out 
by Santa Monica, Calif. think tank Rand Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Rand surveyed 95 high-tech manufacturers that together account  
for 40 percent of sales volume in the computer, semiconductor, hard 
disk drive and cellular telephone industries. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nine months ending June 1998, the 95 firms reported 1,704  
thefts of equipment and parts worth nearly $35 million globally, 
including more than $17 million worth of losses in the United 
States. The incidents ranged from truck hijackings to thefts from 
the companies' offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on that data, the study estimated that $125 million worth  
of high-tech goods is stolen annually in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	The study then projected that high-tech theft costs American  
businesses $4 billion annually. The total includes the value of 
lost goods as well as indirect costs including insurance, security 
and lost sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The study did not include data on theft of consumer goods from  
homes or stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, high-tech firms have begun to tighten security in recent  
years, researchers noted. Improvements include more television 
cameras and secure doors on loading docks, better inventory 
controls and more discreet packaging for shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Instruments, for example, in the last year began checking  
the backgrounds of contractors before hiring them, said Skip 
Williams, vice president of worldwide security. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also recently brought together risk management,  
security, legal and logistics departments to study how to better 
protect semiconductors in transit, said Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've taken a few losses of our own, mostly in transit,'' said  
Williams. ``We have worked with carriers and transporters to change 
the methods in which they handle our product both at warehouses as 
well as aboard airplanes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A single shipment of semiconductors -- the components that are  
critical to making cellular phones and other electronics goods -- 
can be worth several million dollars. Thefts of such goods in 
transit has been a growing problem for the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredible how this property is treated. It should be  
treated like cash, but it's treated like a can of peas,'' said Rich 
Bernes, executive director of the nonprofit Technology Theft 
Prevention Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Following security improvements and other changes including more  
attention to the problem by law enforcement, 18 large firms in the 
study cut theft losses 75 percent in one year. Losses cost $80 
million in 1996 and only $21 million a year later, the study 
reported. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
