<HEADLINE> Derby Favorite Exploit Is Retired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- A third Kentucky Derby victory for  
trainer Bob Baffert would be quite an exploit. 
</P>
<P>
	If it is achieved, however, it will be without one of his best  
3-year-old prospects, Exploit. 
</P>
<P>
	The early favorite for the Derby has been retired because of a  
bone chip in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he had surgery it would be eight or nine months before he  
could come back, and after knee surgery they don't come back as 
good,'' Baffert said Wednesday. ``He's worth more money at 
breeding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The injury occurred Saturday when Exploit finished second to  
Prime Timber, another Baffert-trained Derby hopeful, in the San 
Felipe at Santa Anita. It was Exploit's first loss in six starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert, who won the 1997 Kentucky Derby with Silver Charm and  
last year with Real Quiet, said that after the colt walked Tuesday 
morning, a filling was discovered in the knee. X-rays disclosed the 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Exploit, owned by Bob and Beverley Lewis, won all four starts as  
a 2-year-old and began his 3-year-old campaign by winning the San 
Vicente on Feb. 6 at Santa Anita. Two of his victories at 2 were in 
the Iroquois and the Kentucky Jockey Club at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert also trains two other Derby hopefuls -- Straight Man,  
also owned by the Lewises, and General Challenge. Straight Man is 
unbeaten in two career starts. Top 3-year-old fillies 
Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting also are trained by Baffert. 
Neither is headed for the Derby at this time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
