<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hughes Invests $1.4B in Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Hughes Electronics Corp.'s $1.4  
billion Spaceway satellite system, scheduled to debut in 2002, will 
give consumers access to inexpensive, high-speed computer links, 
including Internet and video conferencing. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers will be able to transmit and receive data, voice,  
video, audio and multimedia via a pair of satellites orbiting Earth 
but only pay for the amount of bandwidth needed to communicate with 
high-speed corporate networks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be as easy as picking up your telephone today,''  
Hughes chairman Michael T. Smith said Wednesday during a telephone 
news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers will no longer have to go through a retransmission  
service or hub but will be able to communicate directly via 
satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Spaceway ``the most advanced satellite platform in the  
world,'' Smith said users will see a 20 percent to 30 percent cost 
reduction over current land-based systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Spaceway will provide access for everyone from large businesses  
to home office users to two-way, high speed applications including 
desktop video conferencing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Large businesses, telecommuters, small office, home office or  
solo users and consumers will have easy access to two-way, 
broadband multimedia applications such as desktop 
videoconferencing, interactive distance learning, commuter 
networking and many other intra- and internet services,'' said 
Pradman P. Kaul, chief operating officer of Hughes Network Systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, through its Hughes Network Systems unit, will develop  
terminals and ground infrastructure. Another subsidiary, PanAmSat, 
will operate the telemetry and Hughes-owned DirecTV will market 
several data services to subscribers. DirecTV has about 4.5 million 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Two operational Spaceway satellites and one spare, built by  
Hughes in El Segundo, will be placed in geosynchronous orbit in 
late 2001, Kaul said. The launch site has yet to be announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The first system is expected to begin in North America in 2002  
and eventually be marketed in regions worldwide. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
