<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 12:43:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Approves New Phone Rate Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a few clicks of a computer mouse,  
telephone customers could scan the Internet for the current prices 
that long-distance companies charge for their services. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission, in a 4-1 vote Thursday,  
adopted rules that eventually could require AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom, 
Sprint and other long-distance carriers to post such information on 
their corporate Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The major long-distance companies say they already voluntarily  
provide information about rates on their Web sites. But the FCC 
plan, assuming it takes effect, would force them to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's requirement would cover a wide range of services, from  
domestic long-distance calls to calling-card calls to directory 
assistance. It would not include information on international 
calls. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers should be able to do comparison shopping for  
long-distance service just as easily as they can do it in the 
grocery store,'' FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies would have to provide information on domestic  
rates -- including the terms and conditions of service -- in a timely 
manner and updated regularly. 
</P>
<P>
	If rates or services are changed, that would have to be posted,  
too. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond that, the FCC would not specify when information must be  
posted, how often it must be updated or where it would appear on 
the companies' corporate Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth, who dissented, said  
long-distance companies ``don't need any federal mandates to say, 
`If you don't do this you'll be in big trouble.' ... They want to 
tell consumers what their prices are because that's what consumers 
demand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's requirement goes hand-in-hand with a 1996 order, which  
never took effect, intended to free long-distance companies from 
having to file federal tariffs outlining their rates or service 
changes to the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, long-distance companies continue to file that  
information with the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's action Thursday does not affect that 1996 order, which  
is being challenged by MCI WorldCom and others in federal court 
here. But the public disclosure requirement would not take effect 
unless the court upholds the FCC's 1996 order involving federal 
tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Consumers Union's Washington  
office, said the public disclosure requirement would help make 
consumers more aware of rate changes. But he noted it would not 
help those who do not own computers. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, the FCC also required long-distance companies to  
post current rate information in some of their offices. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T said they are not opposed to the public  
disclosure, but repeated their opposition to getting rid of federal 
tariffs. Sprint, however, doesn't like the disclosure requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the century-old doctrine, long-distance companies may  
charge only the rates for services they have filed with the FCC. 
The tariff trumps all other agreements with customers, verbal or 
otherwise. Some critics contend the arrangement lets companies slip 
rate changes by customers. 
</P>
<P>
	But MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T contend that in the absence of  
tariffs, companies would have to enter into some other contract 
with customers each time rates or services were changed. 
</P>
<P>
	That would make it harder for them to offer new discount plans  
or promotions featuring free or cheap calls, they note. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kimmelman and other critics said that consumers would be  
better served by posting rate information online than by putting it 
in tariffs, which the average long-distance customer does not see. 
</P>
<P>
	Assuming the court upholds the FCC on its decision to eliminate  
tariffs, officials contemplate that long-distance companies 
voluntarily would move toward a more ``contractual relationship'' 
with customers -- along the lines of credit-card companies that 
provide notice in the mail when terms change. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 15:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Questions Farm Disaster Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, appearing  
before exasperated lawmakers Thursday, defended an expected 
eight-month delay in getting $2.3 billion in emergency disaster aid 
to farmers. ``We're doing the best we can,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman informed Congress last week it would probably be June  
before the money could be distributed to farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers, who included the money in a $6 billion emergency  
disaster aid package passed in October, were openly frustrated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress wrote the nation's farmers and ranchers a check,''  
said House Agriculture Committee chairman Larry Combest, R-Texas. 
``Mr. Secretary, when are you going to cash it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not rocket science. This is not splitting the atom.  
This is something the department has done before,'' Combest said. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Rep. Bill Barrett, R-Neb., ``There's a lot of hurt out  
there. I think USDA is adding to that hurt and this is 
disappointing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Glickman said the massive aid package, which  
included provisions for everyone from dairy to grain farmers, was 
``complex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have liked to have gotten the money out in January,''  
Glickman said. ``We created a program from scratch. We're doing the 
best we can under these circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the criticisms, many GOP lawmakers said they were open  
to the possibility of another disaster package this year. The low 
prices that plagued the agricultural economy last year are expected 
to continue through much of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem hasn't gone away,'' Combest said. He said the  
situation was as bad or worse than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last year, prices for commodities like soybeans and corn  
have slipped to record lows while livestock prices have also 
lagged. Hog prices, for instance, at one point fell to $8 per 
hundred pounds -- the lowest in four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA distributed $2.8 billion in payments to compensate for low  
prices shortly after the package was passed. But distributing the 
disaster payments, which cover disasters and disease, has become a 
more complex task, Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	One complication is that the emergency package covered farmers  
who have suffered crop losses over several years before 1998 or who 
had losses only in 1998 -- a provision that has taken an enormous 
amount of time to compile, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the disaster package included seven new programs,  
including aid for livestock and dairy farmers, Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	As lawmakers debated the delay, a few Republicans were trying to  
draw attention to the problems in agriculture in hopes of pushing 
even more reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Thune of South Dakota, along with Reps. Jo Ann Emerson  
of Missouri, Rick Hill of Montana and Wes Watkins of Oklahoma, have 
been lobbying GOP leaders for a series of steps to help farmers, 
including price supports that could cost billions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the agitators,'' Thune said at a news conference  
Thursday. ``You've got to start somewhere when you want to start a 
revolution.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Who's Eligible for Low Income Break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Major eligibility qualifications to claim the earned income tax  
credit, which can reduce or eliminate federal income taxes. This 
year's maximum credit is $3,756. 

</P>
<P>
 *You can claim the credit if:    	
</P>
<P>
	--You have earned income from a job or self-employment.  
</P>
<P>
	--Your earned income and modified adjusted gross income are less  
than $10,030 with no children; $26,473 with one child or $30,095 
with two or more children. Investment income must be $2,300 or 
less. 
</P>
<P>
	--Your children meet these rules: 18 years or under; 23 years or  
under if a full-time student; any age if permanently and totally 
disabled; must live with you in your home. 
</P>
<P>
	--You, your spouse and children have Social Security numbers.  
</P>
<P>
	--You do not file separate tax returns if married.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
