<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Scores With Instant Replay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Maybe commissioner Paul Tagliabue was watching ESPN last month  
and saw the Pro Bowlers' Tour using instant replay. 
</P>
<P>
	Or he might have been one of the few tuned in to NHL games and  
saw them go to the tape to see if a skate was in the crease. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the case, the NFL has finally brought back instant  
replay. It was long overdue. 
</P>
<P>
	The league abandoned it after the 1991 season because the system  
didn't work smoothly and games were lagging. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was a poor year for officiating, and everyone agrees  
they need instant replay,'' said Fox analyst John Madden. ``What 
surprises me with all the people and all the brains, they haven't 
come up with a system that works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe they should have called PBA commissioner Mark Gerberich.  
</P>
<P>
	The PBA implemented instant replay in the mid-1990s and used it  
in February's Columbia 300 to correctly determine that one of its 
bowlers fouled by crossing the line before releasing the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to use everything possible to make the right  
decision,'' Gerberich said. ``We have also used it to see if a 
pinsetter caused a pin to fall or if it fell on its own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL began using it the same year it was removed from the  
NFL. It wasn't without faults, but instead of giving up on the 
system, they altered it. 
</P>
<P>
	When it first began, the referee was the only one allowed to  
decide whether to review a goal. This year, the video goal judge, 
stationed upstairs, also has the authority to decide to look at the 
tape. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL's decision came at least one year too late, but it's  
nice to see that the NFL is finally placing the game's integrity 
ahead of its length. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CLEANING UP:* HBO's Lou DiBella isn't saying that boxing's  
sanctioning bodies have taken money. But in the wake of the 
controversial draw between heavyweights Evander Holyfield and 
Lennox Lewis, he says reform is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sport doesn't stink, but the governance of the sport  
does,'' said DiBella, HBO Sports' senior vice president. ``The 
problem is with the sanctioning bodies and the promoters, who 
license the judges. The selection has to change. It's dirty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiBella also believes Eugenia Williams should never judge  
another fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not saying she took a check, but there is no way a  
competent person could judge the fifth round to Holyfield.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JIM OF ALL TRADES:* No matter what the sport, Jim Nantz  
continues to shine as the anchor of CBS' sports coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	He nearly single-handedly kept the NFL pregame show afloat  
despite working with three rookies, all of whom have been either 
reassigned or fired. 
</P>
<P>
	After the AFC championship game in mid-January, Nantz worked the  
golf beat for most of February. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked only four college basketball games with Final Four  
partner Billy Packer prior to the NCAA tournament, but hasn't 
missed a beat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think at a very young age, he's about the best I've ever  
been involved with,'' Packer said. ``He's a consummate professional 
and there are very few guys that can do what he has done -- maybe 
Bob Costas and Dick Enberg.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* ESPN and ESPN2 will broadcast all eight NCAA  
women's semifinal games Saturday. ... TBS has added the 
Lakers-Portland game on April 21 to its schedule. ... CNN/SI 
football insider Peter King has signed a three-year extension. ... 
HBO will replay the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield fight Friday at 
10 p.m. EST and will examine baseball's economic future Monday at 
10 p.m. on ``Real Sports''. ... Kevin Kennedy has jumped from ESPN 
to become a baseball commentator at Fox Sports Net. ... Van Earl 
Wright will replace Steve Lyons as host of ``Rewind'' on April 5 
because Lyons is working full time on the Fox Sports Net nightly 
sports show. ... Two-time Indy 500 winner Arie Luyendyk will make 
his TV analyst debut for Fox's Indy Racing on March 28. ... ABC's 
Parker Johnson makes his debut on the premiere of the CART racing 
series Sunday at 4 p.m. in Miami. ... Utah coach Rick Majerus will 
join Greg Gumbel and Clark Kellogg for CBS' coverage of the NCAA 
tournament on March 20-21. ... CBS' average national rating through 
the first weekend was 5.6, down 5 percent from last year. 
</P>
