<DOCNO> APW19990318.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:24:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Oscar' Likes Character Actresses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Is the character actress making a comeback in  
the Academy Awards? Nominations for best supporting actress of 1998 
suggest just such a trend. 
</P>
<P>
	When the awards for supporting players were introduced in the  
ninth Academy Awards in 1936, the Board of Governors sought to 
reward those actors who contributed greatly to films but were 
overshadowed by the stars. The first 10 awards went to such 
polished veterans as Alice Brady, Fay Bainter, Hattie McDaniel, 
Jane Darwell, Mary Astor and Ethel Barrymore. 
</P>
<P>
	That has changed over the years. In the past decade, the award  
has been presented to relative newcomers: Whoopi Goldberg, Marisa 
Tomei, Anna Paquin, Mira Sorvino, Juliette Binoche, Kim Basinger. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for Rachel Griffiths, this year's nominees represent  
decades of experience in films, theater and television. 

</P>
<P>
                 	 *KATHY BATES, ``Primary Colors''    	
</P>
<P>
	The only Oscar winner among the five and the only native-born  
American, Kathy Bates was nominated for her portrayal of Libby 
Holden, the blunt talking, pistol-packing adviser to Clintonesque 
candidate John Travolta in ``Primary Colors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Bates has been in movies since 1971 when she appeared in  
``Taking Off,'' Milos Forman's first American film. She kept busy 
in character roles in movies and theater, then in 1990 achieved her 
triumph with ``Misery.'' Her startling performance as the wacko who 
imprisons her favorite author (James Caan) won her the Oscar as 
best actress in a leading role. 
</P>
<P>
	Her films since then include ``Fried Green Tomatoes,'' ``At Play  
in the Fields of the Lord,'' ``Dick Tracy,'' ``Prelude to a Kiss,'' 
``A Home of Our Own'' and notably, as the unsinkable Molly Brown in 
``Titanic.'' 

</P>
<P>
                 	 *BRENDA BLETHYN, ``Little Voice''    	
</P>
<P>
	A veteran of British theater and television, Brenda Blethyn is  
having her second go at the Oscar; two years ago she was nominated 
as lead actress in ``Secrets &AMP; Lies.'' This year she was chosen for 
her role in ``Little Voice'' as the boozing, man-chasing harridan 
whose relentless put-downs of her willowy daughter (Jane Horrocks) 
have made the teen-ager a recluse. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a desperate woman,'' Miss Blethyn says of her character.  
``She is someone who is lamenting her loss of figure and looks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Miss Blethyn appeared here for the Golden Globes and Oscar  
nominees, onlookers were surprised by how sleek and attractive she 
was. 
</P>
<P>
	``People ask me if I have lost weight,'' she said. ``I haven't.  
They also said I looked so much shorter. I say, 'There's no way I 
could have lost height.''' She'll be able to appear as her own 
lovely self in her next film, ``Night Train'' with John Hurt. 

</P>
<P>
                	 *JUDI DENCH, ``Shakespeare in Love''    	
</P>
<P>
	She was nominated last year as another English queen, Victoria,  
in ``Mrs. Brown,'' and now she plays the aging Elizabeth I. And 
even though the current Elizabeth has bestowed upon her the title 
of dame, there is nothing regal about her off-stage and off-camera. 
``Don't call me Dame Judi,'' she insists. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in the theater in the 1950s, she has played everything  
from Juliet to Lady Macbeth, Portia to Cleopatra, as well as Sally 
Bowles in ``Cabaret.'' Her films include ``Room With a View'' and 
``Henry V,'' and she plays the British secret service chief in the 
James Bond movies. She even appears in the BBC sitcom ``As Time 
Goes By.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Dench's appearance in ``Shakespeare in Love'' may have set  
a record for the least amount of screen time to warrant an Academy 
nomination. She was asked how she managed to make such an 
impression in such brief time. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to make up for it when you've only got eight  
minutes,'' she replied. ``You have to make the best of it. First, 
you get a good costume.'' 

</P>
<P>
              	 *RACHEL GRIFFITHS, ``Hilary and Jackie''    	
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredibly exciting,'' says Rachel Griffiths of her  
nomination, ``especially since I was not on anyone's tip list. Now 
I can have an international career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian beauty is the least known of the five nominees,  
but Oscar magic is likely to change that. She was chosen for her 
role as Hilary, the stable older sister of the erratic, dying cello 
genius Jacqueline du Pre (Emily Watson). 
</P>
<P>
	The real Hilary du Pre and her brother Piers wrote the book on  
which the film was based. Jackie's famous colleagues in the music 
world attacked the film for depicting the cellist as ``selfish, 
spoiled and manipulative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Griffiths is a product of the Australian theater, having  
appeared in ``A Doll's House,'' ``The Sisters Rosensweig'' and 
others. Her most notable films have been ``Muriel's Wedding'' and 
``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' as a Southern belle. 

</P>
<P>
               	 *LYNN REDGRAVE, ``Gods and Monsters''    	
</P>
<P>
	Some of those who viewed ``Gods and Monsters'' without knowing  
the cast credits were astonished to learn that Lynn Redgrave had 
played the role of the loyal, sympathetic housekeeper for the 
homosexual director of horror films, James Whale. Usually glamorous 
in the height of fashion, the actress had transformed into a dowdy 
servant. 
</P>
<P>
	``People ask me how I had done it,'' she says. ``Did I gain  
weight? Did I have a prosthesis on my chin? I did none of that. I 
simply did what I have done many, many times in the theater: I 
became the character with expressions, my posture and my 
attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The actress can call on such techniques as a third-generation  
member of Britain's acting dynasty that includes her parents, 
Michael Redgrave and Rachel Kempson, sister Vanessa and brother 
Corin. She has had a busy 37-year career in theater and films, 
scoring a 1966 Oscar nomination as lead actress in ``Georgy Girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She has been a U.S. citizen for 25 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
