<DOCNO> APW19990318.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 09:35:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Rips GOP Budget Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore today ripped a $1.74  
trillion budget plan offered by Republicans, calling it a rehash of 
bad economic policies that pushed the country into recession a 
decade ago. ``We don't need more Republican retronomics,'' Gore 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the White House to a group of black newspaper  
publishers, Gore said he was disappointed that the House Budget 
Committee approved a plan which he said ``puts risky tax schemes 
first'' ahead of Social Security overhauls. He said that is a 
budgetary tactic straight out of the 1980s -- one blamed in part for 
a recession that did not turn around until Clinton's first budget 
was approved in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've tried this kind of budget before, and it nearly wrecked  
the United States. It drove our economy into the ditch,'' Gore 
said. ``I appeal to the Republican leadership to drop this 
nostalgia for the recessions of the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House panel's 22-18 vote along party lines Wednesday night  
capped a day of political maneuvering on both sides of the Capitol 
as Democrats unsuccessfully sought to put off tax cuts until both 
Social Security and Medicare are overhauled. Republicans argued 
that projected budget surpluses will make it possible to accomplish 
many things. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you think what we're going to do is take away from the tax  
cut -- we're not going to support that,'' said Rep. John Kasich, 
R-Ohio, chairman of the House committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The House and Senate budgets envision unspecified tax cuts of  
$15 billion next year and $778 billion over the next decade. Other 
rejected proposals would have shifted some of that money into 
spending programs Democrats favor, such as Head Start or hiring 
more teachers to reduce class sizes. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the tax cuts, the plans crafted by Kasich and Senate  
Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., would set aside 
$1.8 trillion in projected surpluses over the next decade to ensure 
Social Security's solvency when the huge baby boom generation 
begins retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	That compares to $1.3 trillion over 10 years for Social Security  
in President Clinton's proposed budget, but Clinton's plan also 
would lock up part of the remaining surplus to keep Medicare 
afloat. The popular health program for senior citizens faces a 
financial crunch beginning in 2008. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican budgets, which set overall tax and spending  
limits that are filled in by later congressional action, also would 
boost defense spending to $289 billion for fiscal 2000, $9 billion 
more than this year and $8 billion more than Clinton proposed. They 
would also increase spending for primary and secondary schools by 
more than $2 billion next year, and provide more for some 
agriculture and veterans' programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said they could afford those increases while  
honoring a tight spending limit for next year set by the 1997 
budget-balancing pact. Neither committee provided much detail about 
which programs they would cut to heed that spending ceiling, but 
both chairmen said they could do it. 
</P>
<P>
	But that also imposes some limits on spending priorities.  
Kasich, for example, agreed with the thrust of a Democratic 
amendment to boost spending for research at the National Institutes 
of Health but said the proposal cost too much. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't be all things to all people,'' Kasich said.  
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Democrats said that to afford the GOP's proposed  
increases, the remaining programs affected by the spending limits 
would face 12 percent reductions. That could mean cuts in popular 
programs such as Head Start, food inspections and the FBI, they 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it were an over-the-counter drug, it would have to say,  
'Warning: Could be harmful to elderly, children and working 
families,''' Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said of 
the GOP plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, the Clinton administration threatened to veto a  
GOP proposal to set aside Social Security's vast surpluses over the 
next decade -- before baby boomers start retiring -- for debt 
reduction. 
</P>
<P>
	That proposal, which will move separately from the budget  
resolution, would require that Social Security surpluses be used to 
buy down the debt. Doing otherwise would require votes of 60 of the 
100 senators, a tough hurdle to overcome. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Democratic leaders, Treasury Secretary Robert  
Rubin said the plan could hinder the government from issuing new 
debt if it needed to, threatening its credit rating and perhaps 
requiring it to stop paying Social Security benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 20:31:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Solheim Format To Debut in 2000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The sixth Solheim Cup will be played Oct. 6-8,  
2000 at Loch Lomond Golf Club in Glasgow, Scotland, under a new 
format, the Ping organization announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ping also said LPGA Hall of Famer Pat Bradley would be the  
captain for the American team. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Solheim Cup has become the pinnacle of women's  
professional golf, steeped in tradition,'' Bradley said. ``I want 
to continue the standard of excellence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Long-hitting Laura Davies of England said Bradley, who has won  
31 LPGA Tour titles, exemplifies the successful U.S. teams in the 
cup competition, because she is nearing the end of a great career. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a short history, so the inspirational players are  
still active,'' Davies said about the European LPGA that provides 
the competition for the LGPA. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsored by Karsten Manufacturing Corp. of Phoenix, which makes  
Ping golf equipment, the Solheim Cup is a match-play event that has 
featured four four-ball groups and four foursomes playing on the 
first two days of competition, with 12 singles matches on the 
concluding Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the format calls for eight foursomes the first day,  
six four-ball matches the next and then the 12 singles-matches at 
the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	The change was made primarily to increase the available hours of  
daylight and help everyone finish, Ping CEO John Solheim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
