<DOCNO> APW19990318.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 00:22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Learns Lesson About Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two young computer entrepreneurs made a pretty  
profit off Steve Forbes by beating the millionaire publisher and 
presidential candidate to his own name. 
</P>
<P>
	They reserved the Internet domain name ``www.forbes2000.com''  
back in 1997 as Forbes was preparing a second consecutive campaign 
for the White House. So before he launched his campaign Tuesday 
with a splashy announcement on that Web site, Forbes first had to 
obtain it. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Segal, a Cincinnati-based Internet marketer who represented  
the Forbes campaign, said he purchased rights to three Web sites -- 
including ``www.forbes2000.com'' -- for a total of $6,500. He said 
the price was ``extremely reasonable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the sellers, Greg Trangmoe, said the agreement with  
Forbes prevents him from revealing how much money was paid. 
</P>
<P>
	But Trangmoe last year turned down five-figure offers from  
prospective buyers and says now that he does not regret that 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good investment,'' he said, ``definitely a good  
investment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The practice of ``cyber-squatting'' -- reserving names that  
others might need -- is going strong in politics. The speculation is 
fairly low-risk, since rights to a ``domain name'' are available 
for $70 for two years. The Forbes case shows there is money to be 
made. 
</P>
<P>
	And even technologically savvy politicians are prone to make a  
www.mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore is a technophile who drew chuckles last  
week by claiming he ``took the initiative in creating the 
Internet.'' He's been a likely candidate for president in 2000 for 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he lost the race to ``www.gore2000.com'' to Market Vision  
Inc. of Kansas City, Mo., which uses the site to sell political 
memorabilia, including the ``Gore 2000 Election Kit'' -- a bumper 
sticker and six buttons for $20. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospective candidate best prepared for the Internet seems  
to be Texas Gov. George W. Bush, whose exploratory committee 
controls ``www.bush2000.com'' as well as ``www.georgewbush.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Elizabeth Dole is trying to attract support with  
``www.edole2000.org'' but does not have control over 
``www.dole2000.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trangmoe and Brian Keys, partners in Adega LLC, are auctioning  
off several other domain names. 
</P>
<P>
	They are asking $4,000 for ``www.alexander2000.org,'' even  
though Republican Lamar Alexander is already on the Web at 
``www.lamaralexander.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They are asking $1,000 for ``www.bradley2000.org,'' although  
Democrat Bill Bradley already has a site up and running at 
``www.billbradley.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And they are testing the market to see how high the bids might  
be on ``www.mccain2000.com,'' a site that could come in handy for 
Republican Sen. John McCain of Arizona, even though McCain already 
has ``www.mccainforpresident.org.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is some risk in having a Web site fall into hostile hands.  
Adega underscored the threat for a time last year by linking the 
``www.forbes2000.com'' page to three other sites -- one of them 
pro-Forbes, the other two anti-Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	As she considers whether to run for Senate in New York, first  
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton might be unsettled to learn that 
``www.hillary2000.com'' is in the hands of a Republican. But Chris 
Hayden, a California environmental consultant, says he reserved the 
site in hopes of making money rather than trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd use it to try to sell items, as opposed to say anything  
bad about her or good about her,'' said Hayden, who added he would 
entertain offers from a Hillary Clinton campaign interested in 
buying the site. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, also considering a bid for  
Senate, probably would prefer that ``www.whitman2000.com'' be 
controlled by someone other than Dan Parisi, a New Jersey computer 
entrepreneur known for establishing a raunchy pay site at a Web 
address similar to the official one for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	But Parisi said he voted for Whitman and would let her use the  
site if she wants it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 23:24:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Tires Make Andretti Optimistic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOMESTEAD, Fla. (AP) -- Michael Andretti can't get over a  
statistic that his public relations representatives recently 
brought to his attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that we led only 31 fewer laps than Alex Zanardi, but  
finished seventh in the points, indicates that we had more 
opportunities to win or at least finish higher in the 
championship,'' Andretti said. 
</P>
<P>
	The last two CART seasons have been very frustrating for the  
36-year-old former series champion. He has begun each of those 
years with victories in the Marlboro Grand Prix of Miami and gone 
the rest of the season without a win. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, he has had terrible luck -- crashing while leading,  
breaking while running near the front and generally falling into a 
miserable rut by the middle of each season. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday, he will try to make it three in a row on the 1 1/2-mile  
oval at Miami-Dade Homestead Motorsports Complex. More important, 
Andretti says he expects this season to be far better to the end of 
the 20-race schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	A big reason for his optimism is the Newman-Haas team's recent  
switch from Goodyear tires to Firestones. Teams racing with 
Firestone radials dominated the Champ Car series last year, with 
only Andretti winning on Goodyears. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very difficult decision to make, Andretti said.  
``Goodyear has been great supporters over the years, and they are a 
company that is going to get it right. But it is probably going to 
take them 10 races to catch up, and we don't have the time to wait 
right now. We have to look out for ourselves and our sponsors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti fully expects to be a contender for the PPG Cup title  
that is up for grabs since Zanardi, who won the last two titles for 
Target-Chip Ganassi Racing, returned to Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is 25-year-old Dario Franchitti who is generally  
considered the man to beat for the 1999 championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care if they label me a championship contender or no  
hope,'' Franchitti said. ``One thing I learned last year is that 
you have to be consistent over the course of the season. It's a 
balancing act between being aggressive and using your head. I'm 
just happy to be considered a championship possibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti is hardly alone as a title contender, though. At  
least eight drivers are considered legitimate threats to replace 
Zanardi at the top of the standings. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Franchitti, the name mentioned most is Zanardi's former  
teammate, Jimmy Vasser, who hopes to give Ganassi's team its fourth 
straight series championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``The competition, it's there and it's deep,'' the 1996 series  
champion said. ``There's built-in pressure just to perform at the 
highest level that you can, to keep your team and your sponsors 
happy and to keep your job. 
</P>
<P>
	``So there's not really any more pressure because there is a  
fourth championship possible for our team. I think we may have a 
shot at it, but it's just going to take a little while for the 
whole scenario to unfold.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Franchitti being the man to beat, Vasser said, ``Anybody  
would be an idiot not to consider Dario Franchitti a championship 
contender. He won three races last year, and the fashion in which 
he won them, the consistency and the speed he had, that was 
impressive. But he's going to have to get it done on the racetrack. 
Nobody is going to give him anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Franchitti, Vasser and Andretti, the drivers expected to  
challenge for the title include Greg Moore, Adrian Fernandez, Bryan 
Herta, Gil de Ferran and, the driver who was fastest in winter 
testing, Patrick Carpentier. Among them, all are on Firestones 
except de Ferran. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore agrees winning the title will be an uphill climb, but  
said, ``You can't look at any of those guys and say there's no way 
they are going to win the championship. But, hopefully, I'm at the 
top of it. Dario and all those guys can fight for second.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Skiers Get Tropical Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- The United States' top skiers won't have  
to worry about chapped lips and frostbitten fingers during the 
national Alpine and Freestyle Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, unseasonably balmy weather in the Utah mountains could  
change the nature of competition for an American team finishing a 
season marked by retirements and injuries in its ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	The temperature reached 60 degrees under mostly clear skies on  
Thursday as the U.S. Ski and Snowboard Association announced a 
lucrative long-term extension of its sponsorship deal with Chevy 
Trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninety minutes north at Snowbasin Ski Resort, the second day of  
training concluded on the Bernhard Russi-designed downhill course 
which will be used in competition for the first time Friday. 
Snowbasin will be the site of downhill competition in the 2002 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Olympic venues at Snowbasin, Park City Mountain Resort  
and Deer Valley Resort will all be used over the six days of 
events. It's the first time Salt Lake City's new Olympic ski venues 
will be featured in a multi-sport event. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to give our athletes any advantage we can, and  
one thing we can do is take advantage of the facilities here,'' 
USSA president Bill Marolt said. ``Any experience we can give our 
skiers on the Olympic courses will pay off down the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To combat the annoyingly beautiful weather, the downhill  
competitions on Friday will begin 2 1/2 hours earlier than previously 
scheduled to take advantage of early morning snow conditions. The 
snow softening that occurs with each passing hour slows the racers 
considerably. 
</P>
<P>
	The fastest downhill training runs on Thursday were turned in by  
Megan Gerety of Anchorage, Alaska, who finished eighth in the 
downhill World Championships at Vail last month, and developmental 
program skier Travis Svensrud. 
</P>
<P>
	Russi, the 1972 Olympic champion who has designed practically  
every major modern downhill course, will be on hand to study the 
skiers' reaction to his latest creation. The course has received 
high marks from both skiers and coaches during training, but the 
real tests will come Friday in competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't like the way it was set, but the course is awesome,''  
said Chad Fleischer, who finished second at last month's World Cup 
downhill finals in Sierra Nevada, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some great sections. If they remove a couple of  
gates to provide for some big, sweeping turns, it'll be a better 
race, but the course will be a lot of fun with some steeps, some 
air (jumps), all the good stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of the top U.S. alpine and freestyle skiers will take part  
in the competitions -- or rather, all of the top skiers still 
healthy and competing. The ranks of American skiing have been 
thinned considerably in the last year, but the national 
championships could be a stage for new faces to emerge. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic gold medalist Picabo Street, still recovering from  
injury, will miss her second straight U.S. Championships. Gold 
medalist Tommy Moe leads the list of skiers who have hung up their 
skis recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of young skiers on both teams who are looking  
for an opportunity to shine, and they could have that here,'' said 
four-time national champion Kristina Koznick, who won her second 
World Cup slalom race this season. ``Of course, the old ones like 
me are still going to try to hang on to our titles, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The national championships are back in Utah for the first time  
since 1995, when the alpine events were held at Park City and on 
Snowbasin's previous downhill course. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, the races received scant attention from the  
local community and suffered from organizational problems, not the 
least of which was an infamous information tent near the bottom of 
the Snowbasin runs which blew over several times during the events. 
</P>
<P>
	Much has changed. Over 350 community volunteers will be working  
at Snowbasin alone during the first dry run for the Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 01:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Leaders Consider Pay Raise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top House leaders are weighing a plan to help  
lawmakers to a cost of living increase, a boost that could add 
about $5,000 to an annual salary of $136,673. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., raised the issue at a meeting  
earlier this year with Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt, 
according to aides to the two men. 
</P>
<P>
	John Feehery, Hastert's spokesman, noted that under current law,  
members of Congress are entitled to an annual cost of living 
increase. The speaker, he said, ``is in favor of having that law 
continue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt, D-Mo., was noncommittal, according to an aide, Laura  
Nichols. She said any proposal to increase compensation would have 
to be aired in the party caucus, and be subject to a vote in the 
full House. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Congress last received an increase two years ago,  
after the Republican and Democratic leadership agreed not to make a 
political issue of the subject. In other years, lawmakers have 
voted to stop the increase from taking effect. 
</P>
<P>
	While there was no noticeable public backlash against the 1997  
pay increase, some lawmakers objected at the time. The issue would 
almost certainly provoke debate on the House floor again this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1989 law, lawmakers are entitled to a cost of living  
increase that is pegged to the pay raise the president proposes 
each year for federal workers. President Clinton recommended a 4.4 
percent increase for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. A 4 
percent increase in congressional pay would amount to more than 
$5,400 and raise the salary to more than $142,000. 
</P>
<P>
	While aides said a cost of living hike stands a good chance of  
taking effect, a separate proposal for an increase in compensation 
seemed to be faltering. 
</P>
<P>
	The suggestion, floated by Rep. Bill Thomas of California, would  
allow most lawmakers to claim a $125 per day allowance to defray 
their living expenses in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The allowance could be claimed for any day the House meets, to  
be paid from the funds set aside for office expenses. Thus, any 
money the lawmaker claimed personally would have to come from staff 
salaries or other expenses such as equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Congress met for little more than a third of the year,  
lawmakers would be eligible for more than $14,000 in increased 
compensation -- an increase of more than 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas has suggested making the change administratively by a  
vote of the House Administration Committee, which he chairs, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several senior aides, as well as some lawmakers, said Thomas'  
proposal had attracted interest among the members, particularly 
from lawmakers who received a similar benefit when they were 
members of state legislatures. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hastert distanced himself from the proposal during the day.  
``There are a lot of proposals out there and the speaker does not 
endorse this one,'' said Feehery. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas issued a written statement late in the day saying the  
panel would consider the proposal ``only at the request of the 
House leadership. ... The House Administration Committee, appointed 
by the speaker and the minority leader, would be responsive to the 
leadership,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other aides and lawmakers noted that any lawmaker could force a  
vote on the proposal when the regular spending bill covering 
congressional expenses goes to the floor, regardless of what action 
the House Administration Committee took. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, a cost-of-living increase has greater appeal to  
some lawmakers than the suggested per diem. Congressional pensions 
are calculated on the basis of pay, and one official, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity, said some veteran lawmakers would rather 
have a cost of living increase than the per diem allowance, even 
though it would cost them money in the short run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
