<DOCNO> APW19990318.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 00:22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campaigns Explore Cyberspace, Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- In Missouri's U.S. Senate race, they  
were the mouse clicks that roared. 
</P>
<P>
	It started last week, when Daryl Duwe was surfing Democratic  
Gov. Mel Carnahan's new taxpayer-funded Web page for children. The 
state Republican spokesman thought he had struck political gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a few mouse clicks from the children's page, with no  
warning, was a chat room that was definitely not for youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans were gleeful about linking the raunchy site to  
Carnahan, the leading challenger to freshman GOP Sen. John Ashcroft 
in next year's election. Duwe rushed with his finding to The 
Associated Press, which asked Carnahan about the links. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's office immediately ordered the links severed,  
Carnahan said, ``because you don't want inappropriate material out 
there that children might reach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It certainly didn't stop there.  
</P>
<P>
	In a statement calling the two-term governor ``Sexman  
Carnahan,'' Steve Law, executive director of the Republican 
Senatorial Campaign Committee, suggested Carnahan had ``hired Larry 
Flynt as his campaign manager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remark infuriated backers of Carnahan, who is a Southern  
Baptist deacon, husband of 44 years, grandfather and children's 
advocate untouched by even a whisper of sexual impropriety in 
nearly four decades in public office. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnahan's campaign consultant, Marc Farinella, decided to  
strike back. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent hours on Ashcroft's publicly financed Senate Web page  
and the senator's political action committee page last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Through a link from both sites that led to the Washington, D.C.,  
chapter of the Log Cabin Republicans, a gay and lesbian political 
club, Farinella made his way to a homosexual online newspaper with 
explicit personal ads, contacts for escorts and offers of phone 
sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Farinella also clicked from Ashcroft's sites to a ring of  
conservative Web pages about sniper training, militias and white 
separatists. 
</P>
<P>
	The consultant sent a letter to Ashcroft about the links, asking  
whether the senator was ``prepared to meet the same standard that 
you have set for Governor Carnahan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All outside links were dropped from Ashcroft's sites the day the  
letter arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashcroft hasn't offered any public comment. But the senator's  
spokesman, Steve Hilton, said Wednesday that the links were shut 
down because of a ``routine review'' that started before what he 
dismissed as Farinella's ``all-night mouse click-a-thon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That research upset many backers of Ashcroft, a gospel-singing  
son of an Assemblies of God minister, a new grandfather married for 
more than three decades and one-time presidential favorite of 
Christian conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Others are either amused or irritated that the clash of  
Missouri's most popular politicians has gone so negative so early. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both of them are squeaky clean,'' said Ken Warren, a Saint  
Louis University political scientist professor who has tracked the 
careers of Carnahan and Ashcroft since the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither one could conceivably be guilty of anything associated  
with illicit sex, so these allegations from both camps are bogus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton, the Ashcroft spokesman, said his boss deserves credit  
for offering an on-screen warning when a visitor is about to leave 
the Senate site for the wide-open paths of cyberspace. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnahan's site had no such warning, but it is being discussed.  
</P>
<P>
	Greg Johnson, chief programming analyst for the computer system  
at the University of Missouri-Columbia, scoffed at the notion that 
screen warnings stop the curious from online surfing, including 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just a fig leaf for Ashcroft's protection, not the  
child's,'' Johnson said. ``I think it's an unnecessary step -- a 
mother hen approach that may actually incite a child to look. This 
is like your mom saying don't go to the pool hall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stuart Biegel, director of UCLA's Online Institute for  
Cyberspace Law and Policy, countered that on-screen warnings ``are 
a reasonable thing to ask'' of a government site's offramps to the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``But anybody who knows anything about the Web knows if you  
follow links, you will come to places you hadn't intended to go,'' 
Biegel said. ``Is this really the most important issue that could 
be debated in the Senate race in Missouri?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
