<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota To Open Theme Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Hoping to convince young buyers that Toyotas aren't  
boring cars for their parents, Japan's top auto company is opening 
a theme park with games and rides to show that cars can be fun. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota's $126 million facility is part of a futuristic  
waterfront amusement complex in Tokyo called Palette Town, which 
has a concert hall, adventure rides and a giant Ferris wheel. The 
carmaker's park, which is dubbed Mega Web, opens to the public on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota is hoping that Mega Web will jazz up its image as a staid  
automaker and attract younger car buyers at a time when a stubborn 
recession has been sending auto sales plunging in Japan. In January 
alone, Toyota's production tumbled 14 percent from the same month a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The park includes exhibits of Toyota models from the 1950s, as  
well as Dodges and other makes. Visitors can also try designing a 
car on computers, play with clay models, and take a jaunt in a tiny 
electric car that showcases an automated driving system. 
</P>
<P>
	A test-drive course allows visitors to try out actual Toyota  
models, but one thing you can't do here is actually buy a car. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want people to see, drive and experience our cars,'' said  
Toyota President Hiroshi Okuda. ``One reason we decided on this 
project is the attraction of the waterfront. It's vibrant and a big 
hit with the young.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's waterfront is a favorite dating spot for young Japanese,  
and the raging success of Tokyo Disneyland has shown how effective 
amusement parks can be at attracting children and young couples. 
</P>
<P>
	Some industry analysts, however, have reservations about the  
project. ``It's a very expensive way to go about altering their 
image,'' said Steve Usher, an auto analyst with Jardine Fleming. 
Usher said Toyota still needs to come up with models that appeal to 
young buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mega Web park offers several types of virtual driving  
machines, which resemble arcade games. The ``Mission Triangle'' 
flashes jungle scenes with dinosaurs on a screen as the car dips 
and shakes depending on how you drive. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Future World'' pavilion will feature a high-tech roller  
coaster, but that exhibit wasn't ready for the press tour Thursday. 
Officials said it would open soon. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Toyota, the Palette Town amusement complex also  
gets backing from Mori Building Co. and other companies. The area 
has a bowling alley, restaurants, and a hall for rock concerts. A 
shopping mall opens in the summer, and a colorful Ferris wheel 
offers a view of Mt. Fuji on a clear day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
