<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seating for Oscar Is a Real Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Forget Steven Spielberg, Michael Eisner and  
Michael Ovitz. The most powerful person in Hollywood these days is 
a guy named Otto. 
</P>
<P>
	You know, Otto Spoerri.  
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, yes. I am the most powerful,'' chuckles the  
66-year-old financial controller of the Academy of Motion Picture 
Arts and Sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	It is Spoerri's job to ration out Oscar tickets when the  
ceremony squeezes into the 2,850-seat Dorothy Chandler Pavilion on 
Sunday after the last two years at the cavernous Shrine Auditorium, 
which seats 6,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Let the whining begin.  
</P>
<P>
	``You hear it every year,'' Spoerri says with a sigh. ``You  
know, `My mother is dying of cancer' or `My parents are flying in 
from New Zealand.' I've heard it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For 23 years, Spoerri has decided who gets in, who sits where  
and who gets left out. With fewer than half as many seats available 
this year as in 1998, there's a lot of arm-twisting to get into the 
71st Academy Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just say, `Guess what? Each nominee is offered two  
tickets,''' he says. That means there are 157 people eligible for 
the $250 tickets, and Spoerri is willing to listen to pleas for 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some nominees ask for extra seats for parents, grown-up kids,  
whatever it might be. If you can accommodate them, you do. But it's 
tight this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six staffers handle all ticket-related calls, but Spoerri  
usually becomes the target of the dissatisfied since his signature 
is on each rejection letter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been threatened, but they can get angry and let  
their steam out. I'll listen. I really feel for these people,'' he 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Spoerri admits he was ``pretty awed by the star power'' when he  
first took over the job. Now, denying an A-list phenom is almost 
routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have said `no' to stars,'' he says, refusing to identify  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, ever vigilant  
about interlopers to their ultra-private party, pounces on brokers 
who sell Oscar tickets to non-sanctioned guests. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets found in the wrong hands are traced and offending  
Academy members forever blacklisted from the Oscars. There are two 
or three such expulsions each year. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason is simple: ``If we have a member whose ticket request  
is rejected, then he looks on the TV and sees somebody's 
hairdresser in a seat, they are unhappy,'' Spoerri says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Academy has 6,000 members, yet only 300 seats are dedicated  
for them. Members are picked by lottery and ``people who are a name 
sometimes don't get picked,'' Spoerri says. 
</P>
<P>
	Presenters, of course, get tickets and so do their dates.  
Studios, telecast advertisers, performers, past Academy governors, 
Academy friends and the news media get still more. 
</P>
<P>
	California Gov. Gray Davis, Mayor Richard Riordan and police  
Chief Bernard Parks got tickets this year, as did the mayor and 
fire chief of Beverly Hills. 
</P>
<P>
	Deciding who sits where is yet another ordeal for Spoerri, who  
must decide if guests sit on the more prestigious main floor or in 
the balcony. Separating feuding stars is another headache. 
</P>
<P>
	So where will the most powerful man in Hollywood be Sunday  
evening? 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife and I have tickets,'' he says. ``I can enjoy the show  
once it starts.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:47:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Denies Spy Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Chinese diplomat, flatly denying allegations  
his country stole nuclear weapons data from an American laboratory, 
blamed Cold War thinking and partisan politics for the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are sorry there is no more Soviet Union and they don't  
know how to act,'' He Yafei, a minister-counsel at the Chinese 
Embassy, said of those making the accusations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese diplomat said the dispute could harm improving  
relations between the United States and China, and that some 
Chinese scientists are questioning whether to continue scientific 
exchanges ``to advance our knowledge of nuclear science.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some people in the United States who do not want to  
see progress in the Sino-U.S. relationship,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The official did not identify anyone, and specifically excluded  
Sandy Berger, the U.S. national security adviser, who supports 
closer ties. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the allegations that a Chinese-American scientist  
provided Beijing with sensitive material, He replied that ``nothing 
of this sort has ever happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, FBI Director Louis Freeh said nuclear secrets could  
leak inadvertently and added that the Energy Department is taking 
steps to make sure that a casual e-mail or fax doesn't give away 
sensitive military secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Clinton administration and Congress struggled to close  
holes in the security surrounding the nation's nuclear weapons 
laboratories, top officials said sophisticated spies might not be 
the only outlet for classified information on nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeh told a House hearing Wednesday that the FBI still is  
trying to determine whether a leak to China of weapons information 
from Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico occurred through 
the actual passing of documents or simply from viewing and 
memorizing information that was seen or read. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeh said he could not rule out information getting into  
Chinese hands by ways in which a person ``is not intending to 
transmit secret information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes ``information gets transferred between two scientists,  
and at least one of them ... had no intent at all to transfer top 
secret information,'' making the investigations more difficult, 
Freeh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Security at federal weapons labs has been troublesome for years,  
the FBI chief said. ``The culture has not been a 
security-conscious, or certainly never a counterintelligence 
security-conscious one,'' he said. ``That's been the greatest 
vulnerability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking to change that culture, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson  
imposed new security measures for e-mail and other electronic 
communications from the national weapons labs Wednesday. He also 
ordered an internal investigation of allegations that a department 
official was prevented from briefing Congress on evidence of 
Chinese espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's plenty of blame to go around,'' Richardson told  
reporters following a closed meeting of the Senate Intelligence 
Committee. ``This started during the Reagan-Bush years. ... There 
are also problems on our side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said he had no evidence that secrets have been  
leaking out via e-mail, but he said such a scenario ``is a 
potential problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee was questioning Richardson on how the  
administration responded when it first learned of an inquiry into 
the alleged Chinese theft of top-secret nuclear warhead technology 
from Los Alamos in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``China did get information relating to the (warhead) which is  
damaging to our national security,'' Richardson said. ``The extent 
of that damage is not yet known.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intelligence officials first learned of the apparent security  
breach in 1995 and an FBI investigation began in early 1996. A 
scientist at Los Alamos was fired March 8 after being the target of 
the FBI investigation. He has not been charged with any crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson rejected a proposal by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.,  
chairman of the Intelligence Committee, that the administration 
impose a moratorium on exchange programs involving lab scientists 
going overseas and foreign scientists coming to the labs. But he 
said former CIA Director John Deutch would review the weapons labs' 
foreign visitors program to ensure it ``meets the highest standards 
of security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The foreign visitors program is important to our national  
security,'' Richardson said. ``We want Russian scientists to know 
how they should control their nuclear weapons. ... Let's not get 
hysterical and overreach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby, emerging later from the closed-door meeting, said no one  
was getting hysterical and that the issue was not being 
politicized. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't about Democrats or Republicans,'' Shelby said. He  
questioned whether the security measures imposed by Richardson, 
particularly on e-mail, would provide sufficient protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:39:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> C-Span Marks 20 Year Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When C-Span debuted on March 19, 1979, the  
cable TV network had four employees, a $450,000 budget and one 
telephone line to yield calls from creditors and viewers alike. It 
operated only during business hours because the satellite it shared 
showed sporting events at night. 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades later, the network boasts gavel-to-gavel coverage of  
Congress, a staff of 250 and a $33 million budget. But ask chairman 
Brian Lamb to describe other differences between then and now and 
he'll say the Cable-Satellite Public Affairs Network he founded 
remains virtually unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other than the fact we offer a lot more programs, the mission  
is exactly the same,'' Lamb said in an interview. ``And the 
product, by and large on most days, is exactly the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	C-Span premiered with funding from the cable industry and to  
fears about the impact of televising proceedings in Congress. But 
the now-24-hour network soon became so popular among political 
junkies that senators began to complain about all the attention 
going to their House counterparts. Thus, the debut seven years 
later of C-Span 2 to telecast live sessions of the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamb said he always knew he'd find an audience for his network.  
C-Span has attracted a small but loyal group of viewers who crave 
more news than a 30-second sound bite. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 74.6 million households can view C-Span on their cable  
or satellite TV systems, a 1997 survey by Statistical Research Inc. 
estimated that just 22 million people watch C-Span each week. But 
nearly all of them -- 94 percent -- were registered to vote and did 
so in the last general election. C-Span viewers also were more 
likely to contact lawmakers, volunteer in campaigns and make 
political contributions, the survey found. 
</P>
<P>
	The audience can be a somewhat fanatical bunch: Tune in at 7  
a.m. on the East Coast to the network's daily ``Washington 
Journal'' program hosted by Lamb and it wouldn't be unusual to hear 
from a wide-awake caller from California. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a certain percent of the public, a thinking public and  
voting public that wants the discussion, that wants the challenge, 
that wants the information,'' said Lamb, a stolid presence who 
could be called the Joe Friday of cable TV. 
</P>
<P>
	His unemotional, ``just the facts'' interviewing style has  
helped make Lamb, 57, the most recognizable personality on the 
deliberately anti-personality C-Span. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamb served as a Pentagon spokesman during the Johnson  
administration and as a press secretary for Republican Sen. Peter 
Dominick of Colorado. He is a former reporter for UPI Audio and a 
past Washington bureau chief for CableVision magazine, which is 
where he was working when he came up with the idea for C-Span and 
its gavel-to-gavel coverage of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Using simple, stationary camera angles, C-Span attempts to  
provide the most neutral view of every event it telecasts. In 
addition to sessions on the House floor, the network also shows 
congressional hearings, speeches at the National Press Club and 
press briefings by federal agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The only cameras C-Span cannot control are the ones in the House  
and Senate chambers -- the network must tap into a government feed -- 
but they are consistent with the network's speaker-and-podium 
style. 
</P>
<P>
	C-Span offers Americans a more realistic look at politicians  
than the usual polished image supplied by evening news clips and 
Sunday TV talk shows. 
</P>
<P>
	If anything, C-Span has shown American that Congress consists of  
``flawed human beings,'' said John Pitney, a government professor 
at Claremont McKenna College. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not every member is 'Mr. Smith Going to Washington.' The House  
is noticeably short of Jimmy Stewarts,'' Pitney said of the famed 
movie. Like many college instructors, Pitney uses C-Span 
extensively in class. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Levinson, a communications professor at Fordham University,  
recalled the shock of watching members of the Senate Judiciary 
Committee during the confirmation hearing for Supreme Court Justice 
Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here they were considering very important issues -- should this  
man become a Supreme Court Justice, and sexual harassment,'' he 
said. ``Just the expressions on some of the faces of the senators, 
yawning and looking uninterested. It was something I don't think 
anyone had seen before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Frantzich, co-author of ``The C-Span Revolution,''  
agreed that the network has affected the way the public sees its 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's set up this kind of expectation that, hey, we ought to be  
doing things in public, that there's a sense of illegitimacy if 
it's done behind closed doors,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
