<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3M: Strong Dollar Will Hurt Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAPLEWOOD, Minn. (AP) -- Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing's  
profits will be shy of analyst expectations in the first quarter 
due to the strength of the dollar against currencies in Europe and 
Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials told analysts Wednesday that the dollar's  
increasing strength against other currencies in the first two 
months of the quarter have cut earnings from sales by about 1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong dollar hurts American exporters by making U.S. products  
more expensive in other currencies and making foreign revenues less 
valuable when converted into dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	3M, best known as the maker of Scotch brand tape and Post-It  
Notes, makes more than half of its sales abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of 3M fell $2.31 1/4, or 3 percent, to $74.06 1/4 by early  
Thursday afternoon on the New York Stock Exchange. The profit 
update by 3M came after the close of trading on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 3M struggled throughout 1998 against unfavorable  
exchange rates, the company's latest annual report to shareholders 
said currency pressures were a ``minimal'' threat to this year's 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall, 3M said it would eliminate 4,500 jobs, or 6 percent  
of its work force, to reduce operating costs. About half of those 
cuts had been made by the end of 1998. 

</P>
</TEXT>
