<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Advance; Dow Up 14.15 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher in early trading today after  
the government reported that inflation remained stable last month. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 14.15 at 9,893.84. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Dow average fell 51.06 to 9,879.41, after  
briefly crossing 10,000 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, broader stock indicators were higher as well, with  
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index up 5.47 at 1,303.29 , and the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index up 10.93 at 2,439.90. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose after the Labor Department reported consumer prices  
rose a tiny 0.1 percent last month, a signal that inflation is 
under control. That news boosted prices in the bond market, where 
the 30-year Treasury bond was up 9/32 point and its yield, which 
moves opposite the price, was at 5.48 percent, down from 5.5 
percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were not bothered by a separate report from the  
Commerce Department that the nation's trade deficit shot up 21 
percent in January. John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist 
at Advest Inc. of Hartford, Conn., said the higher deficit might be 
a good sign, because it means a steady stream of cheap imports can 
keep domestic prices down and contain inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors' main focus, Shaugnessy said, will be Friday's triple  
expiration of options and futures contracts, which typically 
provides an upward bias to trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fundamentals of the market remain solid. Inflation is  
benign, the economy is in good shape, profits will start to pick up 
this quarter,'' Shaughnessy said. He predicts the Dow will rise to 
10,600 by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by 1,172 to 1,110 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 105.64 million 
shares, up from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas stock markets, Japan's Nikkei stock average dropped  
3.38 percent, as sellers rushed in to lock in gains before the 
close of the Japanese fiscal year on March 31. In Europe, The DAX 
index in Frankfurt was down 1.28 percent, the FT-SE 100 in London 
eased 0.66 percent, and the CAC in Paris declined 1.52 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
