<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian-Brit Helicopter Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British engineering group GKN PLC and Finmeccanica  
SpA of Italy signed an agreement today to merge their helicopter 
operations, marking another step in the consolidation of Europe's 
arms industries. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies first announced in April 1998 that they were  
negotiating a merger of the businesses, GKN Westland Helicopters 
and Agusta. Regulatory approval still is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have said that Westland's emphasis on military  
applications would compliment Agusta's performance in the civilian 
aviation market. 
</P>
<P>
	A name for the new company and a site for its headquarters have  
yet to be decided, but neither company envisages having to 
eliminate jobs, said Westland spokesman Peter Baillie. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about building a larger, more competitive business in  
the longer term. If you look at the business profile, Westland's 
production is increasing quite sharply. We are in a recruiting 
mode,'' Baillie said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company would have about $8.5 billion in orders under  
contract, similar to U.S. competitors Bell Helicopter Textron and 
Boeing Co. and more than its main European rival, the Franco-German 
concern Eurocopter, according to Jane's Information Group, a 
British-based defense industry specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50-50 merger awaits regulatory approval, although GKN  
foresees no problems in light of the approval European governments 
have given to consolidation of defense companies. 
</P>
<P>
	GKN's share price ended trading at 9.66 British pounds, or about  
$15.74, Thursday on the London Stock Exchange, down about 35 U.S. 
cents from Wednesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	Finmeccanica's share price finished at 0.97 euros, or $1.07, in  
Milan, Italy, down about 1.1 U.S. cents from Wednesday's level. 
</P>
<P>
	Since British Aerospace PLC scuppered a potential mega-merger  
with Germany's DaimlerChrysler Aerospace earlier this year, defense 
analysts have predicted that further integration in Europe's arms 
industries will take place piecemeal, across different segments of 
the business, rather than in a series of big bangs. 
</P>
<P>
	The new venture's first chairman will be David Wright, managing  
director of GKN's aerospace portfolio. Amedeo Caporaletti, 
president and chief executive of Agusta, has been named chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The backbone of the deal will be the two companies'  
long-standing relationship in development of the three-engined 
EH101 medium-lift helicopter. A total of 98 EH101s have been 
ordered by the Royal Navy, the Royal Air Force, the Italian Navy, 
the Canadian Armed Forces and a customer in Japan. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:32:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Education Spending Examples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The federal government estimates that this year it will spend  
about $702 per child for each student nationwide with a disability 
requiring special education. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools nationwide spend an average of about $6,000 a year per  
student, but about twice that amount on average per student with a 
disability. 
</P>
<P>
	However, such averages often mask low costs, such as the case of  
a student who might need some equipment or occasional help for less 
than $1,000 a year. And they also mask high costs, amounting to 
tens of thousands of dollars for severe or multiply disabled 
children who need steady, personal attention and expensive medical 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal funding has varying effects on state and local spending:  
</P>
<P>
	--Pennsylvania spends about $680 million on special education and  
gets about $83 million in federal money. State officials say a 40 
percent contribution would bring in an additional $343 million. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In the Charlotte-Mecklenburg schools in North Carolina, it  
costs $1,024 a year to provide one student with one hour a week of 
speech and language therapy. The district gets about $539 in 
federal money a year for all services to such a student, even if 
the student needs much more assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
