<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Has Plan To Rescue Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Former Pittsburgh Penguins star Mario Lemieux  
on Thursday promised to raise $50 million as part of his plan to 
buy the team and rescue it from bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	The promise came in a reorganization plan Lemieux submitted to  
U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz, who is overseeing the 
team's Chapter 11 procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's plan valued the Penguins at about $94 million and  
promised to pay off the team's debts, which he estimated at $110 
million to $140 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who led the Penguins to Stanley Cups in the 1991-92 and  
1992-93 seasons, released a statement calling the reorganization 
plan ``the beginning of a new Penguin dynasty in which financial 
commitments are well-negotiated and honored, players are paid and 
fans get their money's worth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins co-owners Howard Baldwin and Roger Marino did not  
immediately return calls for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux did not publicly disclose the names of his financial  
backers, but said he would reveal them to the bankruptcy judge. A 
hearing on Lemieux's reorganization plan was scheduled before 
Markovitz on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins filed for protection from their creditors in U.S.  
Bankruptcy Court just as the NHL season began in October, citing 
debt amounting to as much as $124 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz is expected to rule sometime next month on whether the  
plan paints an honest picture of the team's financial position, 
said Douglas Campbell, Lemieux's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Creditors will then decide whether to accept the plan and award  
Lemieux and his investors ownership of the team. It is up to 
Markovitz to decide whether to affirm their vote, said Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	A history of the bankruptcy filed with the plan says the  
Penguins were ``undercapitalized,'' or didn't have enough money to 
operate, since Baldwin bought the team in 1991. Marino bought into 
the team in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's filing also said the team suffered from negotiating a  
poor lease with SMG, which manages the Civic Arena, and a cheap 
broadcast contract with Fox Sports Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	His plan calls for renegotiating both contracts.  
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said the low lease and broadcast contract made it  
difficult for the Penguins to pay players' salaries, the team's 
greatest expense, and that the 1994-95 lockout only made the team's 
situation more bleak. The plan would pay the deferred salaries owed 
to some former players, as well as banks, insurance companies, 
attorneys and other creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's plan includes a payment schedule for the $32.6 million  
he said he's owed in deferred salary and penalties. The schedule 
calls for a $6 million cash payment, a promissory note for $4.9 
million and a second note for payments of $11.4 million over eight 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wants another $5.2 million when the team's other debts  
are settled, and reserves the right to sue former Penguins owner 
Roger Marino ``or any other third party'' for the remaining $5.1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino's attorney said earlier this month he would walk away  
from the Penguins if Lemieux and his investors shoulder the team's 
annual losses, don't gut the team's high-priced talent, and repay 
$5 million of the $42.5 million Marino invested in the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment consultant Chip Gesner and Michigan trucking company  
owner Harvey Gainey are also interested in buying the team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
