<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Orders Analysis of Lab Threat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today ordered an analysis of  
the counterintelligence security threat at U.S. nuclear labs in the 
wake of suspicions that China stole nuclear weapons designs. 
Clinton directed the President's Foreign Intelligence Advisory 
Board to conduct a review. Former Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., the 
head of the panel, will lead the investigation. ``I am determined 
to do all that is necessary to protect our sensitive national 
security information and to prevent its diversion to foreign 
countries,'' Clinton said in a statement. 

</P>
<P>
	Missile Defense Bill Passes House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill committing the United States to a  
nationwide defense against ballistic missiles easily passed through 
the House of Representatives today. The 317-105 vote came a day 
after the Senate gave strong bipartisan support to similar 
legislation. The House turned to its version after hearing the 
missile threat to the United States outlined in a rare closed-door 
briefing by members of a commission that studied the threat. 
Government officials say that from 25 to 30 nations now have, or 
are in the process of trying to obtain, ballistic-weapons 
capability. 

</P>
<P>
	Potential Amtrak Witness Questioned  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- A motorist who claims to have been  
directly behind the truck involved in the deadly Amtrak collision 
came forward with what federal investigators said today was 
valuable information on the cause of the wreck. Investigators would 
not say what the motorist told them. But they are looking into 
whether the trucker, 58-year-old John Stokes, tried to drive his 
tractor-trailer around the crossing gates and beat the train. 

</P>
<P>
	Balloonists Set Course for Africa  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Two weary balloonists reached the  
Atlantic Ocean today and have made it three-quarters of the way 
around the world in their attempt to conquer one of aviation's most 
elusive goals. Bertrand Piccard of Switzerland and Brian Jones of 
England headed out over the Atlantic Ocean, hoping for a possible 
Sunday morning landing in northwest Africa. By this afternoon, 
Jones, a 51-year-old balloon instructor, and Piccard, a 41-year-old 
physician, had traveled 21,985 miles of the 26,000-mile odyssey 
that began with a March 1 liftoff from the Swiss Alps. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Hits 10,000 But Closes Under  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average today posted a  
record close of 9,997.62, up 118.21 points, after cracking 10,000 
six times but pulling back each time. On Tuesday, the Dow briefly 
traded as high as 10,001.78 before slipping back. A spark for 
today's advance was the report that consumer prices rose 0.1 
percent last month. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,559-1,390. 
The Nasdaq rose 33.99 to 2,462.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com Files for IPO  
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Priceline.com, the Internet travel  
company that allows consumers to name their price for airline 
tickets, disclosed plans today to sell 10 million shares in an 
initial public offering that would raise about $80 million. In a 
filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company 
said it expects the shares to start selling at between $7 and $9. 
The company has applied to trade on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Industry Wins Case  
</P>
<P>
	AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- A federal jury today rejected a $2 billion  
attempt by union health funds to recover the costs of treating 
workers' smoking-related illnesses. The jury ruled for the tobacco 
industry on all counts in the first of at least 14 such lawsuits 
around the country to go to trial. The 114 Ohio union health funds 
argued that the tobacco industry concealed the dangers of smoking 
and went after less-educated blue-collar workers with the Marlboro 
Man and other promotional gimmicks. The tobacco companies contended 
there was nothing illegal about their ad campaigns. 

</P>
<P>
	NCAA Appeals Judge's Rejection  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The NCAA today appealed a federal judge's  
refusal to give it more time to revamp its freshman eligibility 
requirements. U.S. District Judge Ronald Buckwalter declined 
Tuesday to issue a stay that could have delayed enforcement of his 
court order striking down Proposition 16, which mandated that 
freshmen attain a minimum standardized test score to play in 
Division I athletics. In his initial ruling last week, Buckwalter 
declared that minimum score requirements have ``an unjustified 
disparate impact against African-Americans.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
