<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Don't Recognize New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- What's all the fuss over the approaching new  
millennium? Big deal. For lots of people around the world, it's 
pretty much ``been there, done that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The West's way of measuring the passing centuries is by no means  
universal. Under Chinese and Jewish calendars, for example, the 
Year 2000 milestone came and went millennia ago. Still other 
peoples have centuries to wait for the big day. 
</P>
<P>
	And Jan. 1 as New Year's Day is no more absolute -- if you want  
to give New Year's greetings to an Iranian, you should do it this 
Sunday by saying ``Happy Nowrooz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole story of the calendar and how we measure time is  
hugely coincidental,'' says David Ewing Duncan, author of 
``Calendar: Humanity's Struggle to Determine a True and Accurate 
Year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One fluke Duncan cites is how the calendar based on Jesus' birth  
as year one -- even though most scholars agree he was likely born 
between 3 and 5 B.C. -- came to dominate the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just so happens that ours is the calendar the colonists  
used, and that it became common internationally in a technological 
age in which we needed a standard,'' Duncan says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Western standard applies in day-to-day business, but in many  
cases other calendars dictate religious holidays and often how 
peoples view their distinctive pasts. 
</P>
<P>
	``These other calendars are still very much alive wherever  
there's a strong religion or culture,'' Duncan says. ``It's almost 
like having two languages. A lot of people use one language for 
business and speak another language as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So for Jews, the calendar starts with the year the world was  
created according to the Bible. Thus their second millennium began 
in 1761 B.C. by the Western, or Gregorian, calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	For Muslims, time is measured in lunar cycles beginning with  
Prophet Mohammed's founding of the first Islamic community in 
Medina on the Arabian peninsula. Under the Islamic calendar, the 
year 2000 will come in the West's 2562 A.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslims will celebrate New Year's this year on April 17 or, if  
the crescent moon is not sighted by then to signal the start of the 
lunar month, a day later. The Chinese had their New Year's Feb. 17, 
Jews on Sept. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Many peoples -- Iranians, Kurds and some Afghanis -- mark New  
Year's on the spring equinox, usually March 20 or 21. Nowrooz 
predates Islam; Iranians celebrate it by feasting at a table set 
with seven items starting with the letter ``s'' in Farsi, including 
``sonbol'' (flowers) and ``sekkeh'' (coins). 
</P>
<P>
	Americans once marked New Year's in March, too. Britain, and  
American colonists, did not adopt the Gregorian calendar until 
1752, or 170 years after the calendar was reformed at Pope 
Gregory's order. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregory's calendar was one of many attempts to deal with the  
problem of the earth revolving around the sun in a pesky 365.24199 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Leap years, invented millenia earlier by the Egyptians, helped  
solve the problem, but they threatened to put the calendar year 
ahead of the solar year. Gregory's calendar dropped future leap 
years at the turn of most centuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the international frenzy surrounding the Year 2000,  
millennial transitions apparently didn't mean much to those who 
lived through them earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I know the year 5000 was nothing special for Jews,''  
says Benjamin Gampel, a professor of Medieval Studies at the Jewish 
Theological Seminary in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese, whose calendar dates to the 15th or 16th century  
before Christ, account for their years not in centuries but in 
12-year cycles that they do not bother to number, says Irene Bloom, 
a professor of Asian culture at Barnard College in New York. Each 
year is given an animal zodiac sign; this is the year of the hare, 
last year was the tiger, and next year will be the dragon. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayans, parts of whose calendar are still used in remote areas  
of Mexico and Guatemala, had ``great cycles'' of about 5,000 years 
each. According to Duncan, Mayans believed the world will end in a 
huge flood during the next great cycle -- which starts in 2012. 
</P>
<P>
	The Western 2000 could still provide lessons for alternative  
calendars when computers on those systems face the perplexing ``Y2K 
problem,'' the moment when digits turn from 99 to 00 but computers 
mistakenly think it's the beginning of the past century. 
</P>
<P>
	Some computers in Islamic countries may face glitches in 2076,  
when the Islamic year, now 1419, shifts from 1499 to 1500. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a century bug. So any computer ... keeping dates  
on the Islamic calendar will go to 00 in 2076. I think the only 
country with computers on that system, though, might be Saudi 
Arabia,'' says Dr. Imad-Ad-Dean Ahmad, an Islamic astronomer based 
in Bethesda, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	The Y2K bug is unlikely to alter the traditions of other  
calendars. That's why Kani Xulam, who works for the Kurdistan 
American Information Network in Washington, expects to be standing 
in front of the White House listenting to Kurdish music this Sunday 
-- Nowrooz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very much a part of our identity,'' he says. ``It is our  
New Year. For us, Jan. 1 of the year 2000 doesn't signify a great 
deal.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 23:54:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Missile Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate negotiators now must produce  
compromise legislation to commit the United States to a national 
defense against a limited ballistic missile attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The House on Thursday approved its version 317-105, a day after  
the Senate passed similar legislation 97-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House once threatened to veto the legislation -- long a  
GOP priority and part of the Republicans' 1994 ``Contract With 
America.'' But members of the Clinton administration no longer are 
talking that way. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they plan to monitor a House-Senate conference  
committee that will come up with the final version, in hopes the 
finished product will more closely resemble the Senate bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia and China were quick to criticize Congress' action.  
</P>
<P>
	``That poses a serious threat to the whole process of nuclear  
arms control, as well as strategic stability, for which major 
international agreements have been worked out for decades,'' the 
Russian Foreign Ministry said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said the  
measure is counterproductive for arms control and disarmament and 
will ``have an impact on global strategic balance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a bill to become law, both chambers of Congress must pass  
identically worded legislation, which the president must sign. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration favors the Senate bill because it promotes  
continued negotiations with Moscow to reduce nuclear warheads and 
stresses that missile-defense funds must be reviewed annually by 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill also states that the missile defense be deployed  
``as soon as technologically possible,'' a phrase not included in 
the House bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The House measure is but 15 words: ``It is the official policy  
of the United States to deploy a national missile defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a deceptively simple bill. But it speaks volumes to the  
entire planet that we will not shy away from the challenge to make 
the United States and its people safe from ballistic missile 
attack,'' Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., chairman of the House 
intelligence committee, said during House debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no defense today against any missile system. It is a  
national priority that this Congress needs to address,'' Rep. Curt 
Weldon, R-Pa., chief sponsor of the legislation, told colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton vetoed a similar measure in 1995 and Democratic leaders  
previously opposed a commitment to such a system. But lawmakers 
from both parties said recent missile tests by North Korea and Iran 
and reports of nuclear weapons espionage by China helped rally huge 
support for the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the Senate bill, the House measure envisions a scaled-back  
version of the Strategic Defense Initiative proposed in 1983 by 
then-President Ronald Reagan -- and derided by Democrats as ``Star 
Wars'' -- for a space-based defense against ballistic missile 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	While that plan was geared mainly at the former Soviet Union,  
the system now being promoted deals more with an accidental launch 
-- or by the deliberate launch by a rogue or terrorist state. It 
would not be space-based. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has spent over $50 billion on research and limited  
tests on such a system, even though one still has not been 
selected. 
</P>
<P>
	The president put $10.5 billion in his budget for such a program  
over the next five years -- an increase of $6.6 billion -- but wanted 
to wait until June 2000 before deciding whether to actually deploy 
such a system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
