<HEADLINE> Reps. Condemn Conservative Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A resolution condemning the Council of  
Conservative Citizens for ``racism and bigotry'' has drawn the 
support of 138 members of the House, its sponsor said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Council of Conservative Citizens attempts to mask its  
hateful ideology by posing as a mainstream conservative think tank 
but the racist agenda of this group is undeniable,'' Rep. Robert 
Wexler, D-Fla., told a news conference. Among his co-sponsors are 
11 Republicans, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Council of Conservative Citizens has an insidious and  
treacherous agenda,'' Wexler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Formed 13 years ago and claiming a membership of 15,000, the St.  
Louis-based council gained national attention this year when it was 
revealed Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Rep. Bob 
Barr, R-Ga., had addressed the group. 
</P>
<P>
	The council advocates an end to school busing, the right to bear  
arms, stricter immigration restrictions and ``preserving our 
heritage by fighting efforts to destroy America's honored cultural 
traditions'' citing the Confederate flag. 
</P>
<P>
	Jared Taylor, a council board member, talking to reporters  
later, said his group unfairly is being targeted. 
</P>
<P>
	``They haven't censured the KKK or the Symbionese Liberation  
Army or other groups. The reason they are coming after us is that 
we have had a number of people from Congress to our group,'' Taylor 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
