<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. 2, Norway 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUFEIRA, Portugal (AP) -- Kristine Lilly's second-half goal  
lifted the United States women's soccer team to a 2-1 victory over 
world champion Norway on Thursday and into the Algarve Cup 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans, who have never won the tournament, will play  
China on Saturday. The U.S. team finished 2-0-1 in its group and 
had to beat Norway to advance. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory also avenged a 4-1 loss to Norway in the tournament  
last year, the only loss of 1998 for the U.S. team. 
</P>
<P>
	China beat Australia 2-0 in the other group, but had already  
clinched the spot in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	Norway took a 1-0 lead just 11 minutes into the match on a goal  
by Ann Kristin Aarones off a corner kick. That lead lasted one 
minute before Julie Foudy tied it. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal ended goalkeeper Briana Scurry's streak of 740  
scoreless minutes, but it took less than 60 second for the 
Americans to equalize. 
</P>
<P>
	They worked the ball into Norway's penalty box off the kickoff.  
Lilly ran onto a bouncing ball on the right side. With her back to 
the goal, she popped the ball back over her head to Foudy, who sent 
a left-footed shot just inside the right post. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so angry that we let in a goal, I was on a rampage,''  
Foudy said. ``The games with Norway are always such physical 
battles, but our defense did a great job and we were really solid 
in the air.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women, who will be hosts of the World Cup this summer,  
almost scored just two minutes later. Mia Hamm's shot from a sharp 
angle in the left side of the penalty box skimmed off the crossbar. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly got the winning goal in the 55th minute on a  
counter-attack. The ball was cleared by the U.S. defense, and when 
Hamm got it at midfield, she sidestepped a defender and embarked on 
a 50-yard run. 
</P>
<P>
	She then fed the cutting Tiffeny Milbrett in the left side of  
the penalty box. Milbrett beat her defender to the end line and 
crossed on the ground to the far post, where Lilly put it home from 
7 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a match that we had to win against the best,'' said  
U.S. coach Tony DiCicco. ``We had more chances to score, we had 
better chances, and I think we deserved to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Defender Carla Overbeck had to leave the game in the 62nd minute  
after injuring her neck while challenging for a header. The U.S. 
captain was sore after the game, but is listed as probable for the 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamm suffered a mild shoulder separation in the first half, but  
also should be ready for the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
