<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Low Prices Hurt Cranberry Growers / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONGVIEW, Wash. (AP) -- Cranberry growers have become bogged down  
by overproduction, victims of their own success. 
</P>
<P>
	Small farmers once had the cranberry market mostly to  
themselves, and for decades berry prices increased or at least held 
steady. 
</P>
<P>
	But now, supply has outgrown demand. Cranberries are pouring in  
from huge farms in Chile, Ireland, Eastern Europe and especially 
Canada. That is good for consumers looking for low juice prices, 
but not so good for U.S. farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a tough year,'' said Malcolm McPhail, who  
farms 63 acres of bogs near Ilwaco in southwest Washington. ``There 
will be some people who go bankrupt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His farm is part of the Ocean Spray Cranberries cooperative, a  
group of 750 growers who control about 70 percent of the U.S. crop 
and nearly all of the cranberries grown in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The cranberry bog business has not grown much recently in  
Washington, where the average farm measures 10 acres. The 
difficulty and expense of dealing with the loss of wetlands has 
dampened bog growth in the United States -- and encouraged foreign 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Huge new plantings have flooded the market. Also, new cranberry  
plantings yield double or triple the amount per acre that old bogs 
produce. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic growers say they saw the price drop coming. Still, some  
were shocked when Ocean Spray announced it overpaid farmers in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocean Spray cooperative farmers deliver their crops in October  
and are paid periodically as the company sells berries through the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the going rate was 61 cents a pound. Late in the fall,  
the price dropped to 55 cents a pound. The price continues to 
plummet, and Ocean Spray estimates farmers will get 42 to 48 cents 
per pound this year. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Ocean Spray suspended payments to former co-op  
growers who were required to buy shares in the company. The shares 
are redeemed over a six-year period when the grower leaves the 
co-op. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Hatton, a Grayland cranberry farmer and chairman of Ocean  
Spray's board of directors, says the company will resume payments 
when the market improves. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the decision leaves some cranberry farmers with a bitter  
taste in their mouths. 
</P>
<P>
	``The arrogance of the company is just unreal,'' said former  
Ocean Spray grower Roy Peters of Bandon, Ore. ``We have been 
wronged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is not the first time cranberries have taken a slide.  
</P>
<P>
	Old-timers remember the big Army contract that fell through  
during World War II and hurt prices. Then there was the infamous 
1959 scare, when cranberries briefly and falsely were linked to 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The current price woes are the worst in many farmers' memories,  
though. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a fun time for us,'' said Hatton, a cranberry grower  
since 1972. ``But we've had some good times, and we expect more in 
the future.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
