<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seating for Oscar Is a Real Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Forget Steven Spielberg, Michael Eisner and  
Michael Ovitz. The most powerful person in Hollywood these days is 
a guy named Otto. 
</P>
<P>
	You know, Otto Spoerri.  
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, yes. I am the most powerful,'' chuckles the  
66-year-old financial controller of the Academy of Motion Picture 
Arts and Sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	It is Spoerri's job to ration out Oscar tickets when the  
ceremony squeezes into the 2,850-seat Dorothy Chandler Pavilion on 
Sunday after the last two years at the cavernous Shrine Auditorium, 
which seats 6,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Let the whining begin.  
</P>
<P>
	``You hear it every year,'' Spoerri says with a sigh. ``You  
know, `My mother is dying of cancer' or `My parents are flying in 
from New Zealand.' I've heard it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For 23 years, Spoerri has decided who gets in, who sits where  
and who gets left out. With fewer than half as many seats available 
this year as in 1998, there's a lot of arm-twisting to get into the 
71st Academy Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just say, `Guess what? Each nominee is offered two  
tickets,''' he says. That means there are 157 people eligible for 
the $250 tickets, and Spoerri is willing to listen to pleas for 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some nominees ask for extra seats for parents, grown-up kids,  
whatever it might be. If you can accommodate them, you do. But it's 
tight this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six staffers handle all ticket-related calls, but Spoerri  
usually becomes the target of the dissatisfied since his signature 
is on each rejection letter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been threatened, but they can get angry and let  
their steam out. I'll listen. I really feel for these people,'' he 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Spoerri admits he was ``pretty awed by the star power'' when he  
first took over the job. Now, denying an A-list phenom is almost 
routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have said `no' to stars,'' he says, refusing to identify  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, ever vigilant  
about interlopers to their ultra-private party, pounces on brokers 
who sell Oscar tickets to non-sanctioned guests. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets found in the wrong hands are traced and offending  
Academy members forever blacklisted from the Oscars. There are two 
or three such expulsions each year. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason is simple: ``If we have a member whose ticket request  
is rejected, then he looks on the TV and sees somebody's 
hairdresser in a seat, they are unhappy,'' Spoerri says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Academy has 6,000 members, yet only 300 seats are dedicated  
for them. Members are picked by lottery and ``people who are a name 
sometimes don't get picked,'' Spoerri says. 
</P>
<P>
	Presenters, of course, get tickets and so do their dates.  
Studios, telecast advertisers, performers, past Academy governors, 
Academy friends and the news media get still more. 
</P>
<P>
	California Gov. Gray Davis, Mayor Richard Riordan and police  
Chief Bernard Parks got tickets this year, as did the mayor and 
fire chief of Beverly Hills. 
</P>
<P>
	Deciding who sits where is yet another ordeal for Spoerri, who  
must decide if guests sit on the more prestigious main floor or in 
the balcony. Separating feuding stars is another headache. 
</P>
<P>
	So where will the most powerful man in Hollywood be Sunday  
evening? 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife and I have tickets,'' he says. ``I can enjoy the show  
once it starts.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 06:35:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Sites To Play Role in 2000 Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to capitalize on the Internet craze,  
presidential hopefuls are building Web sites that offer everything 
from candidate biographies and issue papers to online chats and 
information on how to volunteer. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 2000 campaign Web sites are remarkably similar, both  
in layout and content. But Steve Forbes and Rep. John Kasich offer 
a bit more, giving voters daily reports and photos from the 
campaign trail and mass e-mail updates on the candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes declared his candidacy for the GOP presidential  
nomination Tuesday in an announcement carried first on his Web 
site. Lamar Alexander made a similar declaration during the 1996 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet combines the best of American ingenuity,  
innovation and high tech,'' Forbes said at a New Hampshire campaign 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the presidential hopefuls who have formed exploratory  
committees, Vice President Al Gore and Gary Bauer are the only ones 
without active campaign Web sites. Both plan to have sites on the 
World Wide Web soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's site will be ``fresh and dynamic'' and should be up  
before the end of March, said Roger Salazar, spokesman for Gore's 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The implications of Internet campaigning could be significant,  
bringing voters and candidates together in a way previously 
unimaginable. Some think that the power of the Internet will come 
to rival other mediums. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet will be to the 2000 campaign what television was  
to the 1960 campaign,'' says Todd Harris, communications director 
for Kasich. ``It is a crucial medium that you have to employ to get 
your message out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the focal point for campaign activity in a high-tech  
world,'' said Jonathan Baron, communications director for former 
Vice President Dan Quayle. ``Any campaign that makes full use of 
the Internet will have a competitive advantage over those who 
don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George W. Bush of Texas inaugurated his campaign Web site  
the day he announced formation of a presidential exploratory 
committee. Computers were set up at the announcement site and 
people were able to log on to his page -- offered both in English 
and Spanish. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign Web sites are designed to cater to activist voters  
-- ones who will take the initiative to seek out a candidate and 
vote in the crucial party primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who use the Internet to garner information on  
candidates are much more invested in the political process,'' 
Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 3,000 people have signed up with Kasich on the World  
Wide Web and are ``now in a dialogue with the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Web sites give candidates an advantage in building and  
organizing a grass-roots organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. Bill Bradley's campaign site has an extensive ``get  
involved'' section that garners information such as age, job and 
e-mail address -- all voluntarily submitted. It will undoubtedly 
help the campaign to organize its volunteers in ways previously 
untapped before the Internet became such a force. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a great way to put an instant organization together,''  
says Larry Sabato, a professor at the University of Virginia. He 
points to Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura's successful campaign as the 
model for using Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ventura used his Web site to build his organization and get  
people to his events,'' says Sabato. 
</P>
<P>
	``The technology is there for grass-roots efforts,'' said Mark  
Smith, spokesman for Bauer. ``You might as well take advantage of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Web sites also allow the campaigns to communicate with  
voters directly. Candidates can offer a range of policy positions, 
statements, speeches and information without editing or 
interpretation by the news media. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole's site, for example, has video of her entire  
speech announcing her formation of an exploratory committee. Her 
campaign will eventually allow voters to ``customize'' the site, 
giving them the speeches, issue positions and other information 
they are most interested in. 
</P>
<P>
	One thing the Web sites cannot do is directly raise money for  
candidates through credit card donations, which are prohibited 
under Federal Election Commission rules. They, however, can take 
pledges and tell voters where to send checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabato thinks that the Internet's role is being somewhat  
overestimated and that it will be a tool primarily of underdog 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real revolution will be when we have Internet voting,''  
says Sabato, a phenomenon he thinks will occur within 10 years -- 
changing the face of politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:42:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pasadena Is Not Wooing Raiders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- A Pasadena councilman says the city is  
making no effort to lure the Oakland Raiders, who played at the Los 
Angeles Coliseum from 1982-94, to the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Raiders owner Al Davis said Wednesday during the NFL owners  
meetings in Phoenix he isn't currently in negotiations with anyone 
about a return by the team. 
</P>
<P>
	However, when asked by The Associated Press if the Pasadena City  
Council had contacted the Raiders, he replied, ``Oh, you heard 
about that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I know, there has been no contact between the City  
of Pasadena, the Pasadena City Council, or any of the Pasadena city 
council members,'' city councilman Paul Little told The AP. ``As 
far as I know, there's certainly no effort to try to bring Mr. 
Davis and his team to Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hoping the city of Pasadena will support the Los Angeles  
Coliseum effort to bring an expansion team there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL gave Los Angeles a conditional expansion franchise  
earlier this week during its winter meetings. Davis, who moved the 
Raiders back to Oakland before the 1995 season, reiterated he 
believes that he owns the rights to the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really don't have an interest in permanently housing a  
professional football team,'' Little said. ``Temporarily, I think 
that's something we would look at, but I think we'd look at it very 
closely with an eye toward the bottom line for Pasadena and if it 
would help support the Coliseum effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy to do a service by temporarily housing a team, but  
I think that's as far as it would go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Los Angeles mayor Richard Riordan urged the two  
groups competing for the expansion franchise to get together behind 
one proposal that would have the team play at a renovated Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Coliseum is head and shoulders above any other venue,''  
Riordan said. ``We're going to have a team here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riordan has already talked to members of both camps, and is  
setting up meetings intended to end competition, the Los Angeles 
Times reported Thursday, citing sources it did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our door is open,'' said Eli Broad, a leader in the Coliseum  
bid. ``We'd be delighted to get together and talk about it. I would 
hope that we would end up with a unified bid behind the Coliseum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood dealmaker Michael Ovitz, who heads the group backing a  
stadium in Carson, said it was too soon to determine if his group 
would be willing to give up its original plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to assess that right now,'' he said. ``We're  
thrilled that LA is in the running.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:47:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Adams Can't Deliver IRA Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The leader of the Irish Republican Army's  
affiliated political party said today he ``simply can't deliver'' a 
start now to the outlawed group's disarmament, one of the 
long-postponed goals of the Northern Ireland peace process. 
</P>
<P>
	The blunt talk from Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams came on Capitol  
Hill after a particularly candid half-hour meeting Wednesday night 
inside the White House with his political nemesis, Ulster Unionist 
Party leader David Trimble. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said Trimble had asked him for ``an event'' in which a  
substantial range of IRA weaponry would be handed over to Northern 
Ireland's disarmament commission, which has waited nearly a year 
for the IRA to move. While Adams said he welcomed Trimble's 
``clearest definition yet of what he requires,'' he called the 
demand ``a complete hindrance and precondition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And I can't stress enough, as I stand here, that I simply  
can't deliver that,'' said Adams, who was flanked by three 
congressional supporters, Reps. Peter King, R-N.Y., Joe Crowley, 
D-N.Y., and Richard Neal, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble, the Protestant assigned to form a new  
Protestant-Catholic government for Northern Ireland, is refusing to 
support Sinn Fein's eligibility for office unless the IRA starts 
disarming first. Their deadlock has jeopardized that central goal 
of last year's Good Friday peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton brought the quarreling leaders together  
Wednesday night after a ceremony honoring negotiator George 
Mitchell. The president asked prayers for victims of the violence 
in Northern Ireland, including Catholic lawyer Rosemary Nelson, who 
was being buried today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mood of my meeting with Gerry Adams was very serious,''  
Trimble said in an interview before Adams' press conference. 
``While nothing was resolved, it was a good talk. I was glad to see 
that Adams this time was seriously thinking about the issue of 
decommissioning (weapons), rather than just repeating his old 
script.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel quite optimistic that, in the end, we will overcome  
this difficulty -- because there really is no alternative,'' said 
Trimble, calling the IRA's gradual disarmament and dissolution ``a 
question now not of whether, but when.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in a comment suggesting he had little influence over IRA  
policy, Adams said Trimble's position was leaving the supporters of 
both their parties ``dependent on an organization over which they 
have no influence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The British government has set this year's Good Friday, April 2,  
as a potential make-or-break deadline for a deal. Trimble's hold on 
Protestant opinion is so shaky he presumes he would be ousted as 
Ulster Unionist leader if he offers Sinn Fein an olive branch 
without getting something concrete in return. Adams emphasizes this 
isn't an explicit condition for his party to hold office. 
</P>
<P>
	At Wednesday night's St. Patrick's Day reception on the White  
House's South Lawn, Trimble and Adams sat 10 seats apart in the 
audience as former Senator Mitchell, chairman of the peace talks, 
warned them and other key negotiators: ``What you do, or don't do, 
could mean life or death for many of your fellow citizens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Clinton asked the several hundred guests -- most of  
the key Irish, British and Northern Irish peacemakers among them -- 
to say prayers for those hundreds of people slain and maimed by 
dissident terrorists trying to tear apart the Good Friday 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The reception also featured a brief piano appearance by Claire  
Gallagher, 17, who was blinded in the IRA dissident car-bombing of 
the Northern Ireland town of Omagh in August. That blast killed 29 
and wounded 370. The Clintons originally met Claire while visiting 
the shattered town in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:47:32 </DATE_TIME>
