<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Honored at White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Remembering Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak  
Rabin at a White House ceremony, President Clinton on Thursday 
called for new champions of Middle East peace to fill the gap left 
by the deaths of Rabin and Jordan's King Hussein. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can still here the strong voice of Yitzhak Rabin and King  
Hussein speaking to us today,'' Clinton said at a ceremony at the 
South Lawn pavilion. ``Today their voices must be embodied by 
others all across the Middle East.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We need friends of peace,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton were awarded the  
inaugural Shalom Chaver Award for International Leadership by 
Rabin's widow, Lea, and daughter, Dalia Rabin-Pelossof, who also 
announced that two gardens at the Yitzhak Rabin Center for Israel 
Studies in Tel Aviv will be named for the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	The award, the name of which means ``godbye friend,'' takes its  
name from Clinton's farewell after Rabin was assassinated. It was 
created to honor people who have worked for peace in the Middle 
East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
