<DOCNO> APW19990318.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 00:42:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miami's Coles Savors Tournament Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	One year after coach Charlie Coles collapsed on the court from  
cardiac arrest, his Miami Redhawks are in the NCAA tournament's 
round of 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles is smiling a lot as the Redhawks prepare to play defending  
champion Kentucky on Friday. It's not just because his team has 
done something that no other Miami team could -- win two NCAA 
tournament games. 
</P>
<P>
	There's more to it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just feel blessed,'' Coles said. ``But you know, I would  
have felt blessed regardless because I get a chance to spend time 
with kids I truly love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bond between coach and players deepened last year, when  
Coles collapsed during the first half of a Mid-American Conference 
tournament quarterfinal on Feb. 28. Doctors worked on him for 20 
minutes on court before he was taken to a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors determined there was no lasting damage to his heart and  
he would be able to coach again. Coles, 57, never hesitated to go 
back to doing what he loves and working with a senior-laden team 
that he had nurtured to the verge of national prominence. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really builds around the seniors and senior pride and  
leadership,'' Wally Szczerbiak said. ``He was really looking 
forward to the senior class coming in this year and us going out 
with a bang like we have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After beating Washington in the first round -- Szczerbiak scored  
43 of Miami's 59 points -- the 10th-seeded RedHawks upset Utah to 
reach the round of 16 and set their southwest Ohio campus buzzing. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has tried to be calmer at courtside this season, a  
resolution he admits he cannot always keep. But there's been no 
change in the way he coaches -- and his players are thankful. 
</P>
<P>
	``Charlie is a perfectionist,'' Szczerbiak said. ``That's how he  
lives. That's how he is. He never takes anything for granted and he 
always works really hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think that's the main reason we've come so far, with  
him driving us to be the best we could possibly be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His coaching in the tournament has been impressive. He gave his  
struggling team some time off after it lost in this year's MAC 
tournament, and that helped put players in the right frame of mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach gave us two days off to totally get away from basketball  
and take our minds off the game. That really helped everyone,'' 
Szczerbiak said. 
</P>
<P>
	The game plans for the NCAA tournament have worked. The idea  
against Washington's man-to-man defense was to get Szczerbiak the 
ball and set screens to give him some room. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't mind when Wally scores a lot of points,'' Coles said.  
``The screens we set were the best I've ever been associated with 
as a coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Szczerbiak scored 24 against Utah and often drew a crowd,  
leaving others open to score. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as important, the RedHawks didn't crumble when times got  
tough. That's at least partly a tribute to Coles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we've handled it pretty well,'' Szczerbiak said.  
``After the first game, we got better and played better in the next 
game. That's a tribute to guys not letting the attention affect 
them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 16:15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L. Taylor's Ex-Partner Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- The onetime business partner and lawyer for  
retired All-Pro linebacker Lawrence Taylor was convicted by a 
federal jury Thursday of embezzlement, money laundering, bank fraud 
and tax evasion charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict against Alfred Porro Jr. came after three days of  
deliberations. It followed nine weeks of testimony, highlighted by 
Taylor's appearance on the witness stand last month just three days 
after being he was elected to the pro football Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a plea bargain that he hopes will help him avoid  
prison, Taylor, 39, testified for the prosecution. Taylor had 
pleaded guilty in June 1997 to tax charges that surfaced during the 
investigation of Porro, 64, and his wife, Joan, 51, who was also 
convicted Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor was not charged with the couple, who are both lawyers  
from Lyndhurst in Bergen County. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trial presented proofs of a seamless web of fraud,'' said  
U.S. Attorney Faith S. Hochberg, whose office prosecuted the case. 
``When the frauds were finally catching up with Al and Joan Porro, 
the evidence proved that they tried to pervert justice by 
submitting phony and backdated documents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Porros represented themselves and were convicted on all  
charges, 17 against him and eight against her. Among the charges: 
stealing $276,000 in client trust funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of that money was used to salvage their failing businesses,  
including the Lawrence Taylor Golf Center in East Rutherford. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor and Porro were partners in a company that built the  
driving range, but Taylor said he was not involved in the 
construction or financing. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor told jurors that his signature was falsified on a bogus  
financial guarantee that Porro submitted to a bank that lent Porro 
$850,000 to develop a Meadowlands tract. Under cross-examination by 
Porro, Taylor said he did not know who forged his name and that it 
did not appear to be Porro's signature. 
</P>
<P>
	The Porros had been municipal attorneys for two Bergen County  
towns, Carlstadt and East Rutherford. They could be disbarred 
because of the felony convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Each also faces dozens of years in prison and millions of  
dollars in fines when sentenced Aug. 13 by U.S. District Judge 
Joseph H. Rodriguez, although the actual penalties would be far 
lower under federal sentencing guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors asked that the Porros be held without bail, but  
Rodriguez decided on house arrest with electronic monitoring 
pending a bail hearing on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor will probably be sentenced after the Porros.  
</P>
<P>
	Considered the dominant defensive player of his time, Taylor  
played 13 seasons at linebacker with the Giants, leading the team 
to two Super Bowl titles. He is also known for trouble off the 
field, including two drug arrests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:29:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lewis: I'm Victim of Conspiracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lennox Lewis returned home today endorsing the  
investigations into his disputed draw with Evander Holyfield in 
their heavyweight title fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after touching down at London's Heathrow Airport, Lewis  
maintained was the victim of a ``conspiracy'' and that the judges 
had been ``incompetent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everything should be looked into,'' he said. ``There  
was definitely something going on, some kind of conspiracy we don't 
know about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's Holyfield-Lewis showdown at Madison Square Garden in  
New York created an outcry when it was called a draw. Most in the 
sellout crowd felt Lewis had won comfortably. 
</P>
<P>
	Referee Arthur Mercante Jr. agreed, as did most boxing writers  
who covered the 12-rounder 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the three judges saw the outcome differently. South  
African Stan Christodoulou scored it 116-113 for Lewis, Eugenia 
Williams of Atlantic City, N.J., voted 115-113 for Holyfield and 
Britain's Larry O'Connell scored it 115-115. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' manager, Frank Maloney, said he didn't believe bribes had  
been paid, but he questioned Williams' competence as a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe there was any illegal payment, they wouldn't  
have been that stupid,'' Maloney said. ``They may not find money in 
her bank account, but there was definitely something wrong with her 
judging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigations by state authorities are being held in New York,  
and the Manhattan district attorney is looking into possible 
criminal activity regarding the bout. 
</P>
<P>
	One source close to the investigation, who asked not to be  
identified, said: ``We could be looking at tampering or illegal 
payments. Then again, maybe we're looking at lousy judging, which 
is not a crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said Holyfield should hand over the WBA and IBF titles,  
although the British fighter doesn't expect that to happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Evander's a man, he should admit that he got beat and give  
me my belts,'' said Lewis, who is the WBC champion. ``But he's not 
that kind of character. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say that Evander Holyfield is holding my belts right  
now for me. They're actually my belts but he's holding them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Looking ahead to a possible rematch, Lewis' promoter, Panos  
Eliades, said he was looking at ways of removing Don King as a 
promoter of the fight, although he conceded it would be very 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	Maloney said he would prefer the rematch to be in the United  
States or Britain while Eliades said he had been contacted by 
President Nelson Mandela who wanted the fight in South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis took consolation from one thing. He believes he won over  
Americans who had been skeptical about his ability. 
</P>
<P>
	``People stopped me in the streets and said 'you got robbed'.  
It's weird getting so many people coming up to me and saying 
that,'' Lewis said. ``When I go out on the streets a lot of people 
know me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:29:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
