<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blue Jays Fire Johnson As Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNEDIN, Fla. (AP) -- Tim Johnson's lies about his Marine service  
in Vietnam did too much damage to save his job with the Toronto 
Blue Jays. 
</P>
<P>
	In a rare spring training move, the Blue Jays fired Johnson as  
manager Wednesday and replaced him with Jim Fregosi. 
</P>
<P>
	``The unsettledness and the distractions had become the issue,''  
general manager Gord Ash said. ``It had become apparent it wasn't 
going to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson never saw combat, but supposedly made up stories --  
including a tale about shooting a young girl -- to motivate the 
team. Instead, it cost him his job. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson taught mortar training to recruits going to Vietnam, yet  
never served there. The truth was revealed last year, causing 
conflicts with several players and pitching coach Mel Queen, and 
even an apology to the club this spring could not quell the 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was always a distraction, we can't lie about that,'' first  
baseman Carlos Delgado said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was fired at 1 a.m. after a 2-1 loss to the New York  
Yankees left the Blue Jays at 3-12 in exhibitions. The move came a 
few days after former Toronto third baseman Ed Sprague called 
Johnson a ``liar'' and a ``back stabber.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't going to fade into the background as quickly as I  
hoped,'' Ash said. ``It had become a preoccupation and was making 
it hard to focus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't any one thing, just an accumulation of things,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firing a manager in spring training is not unprecedented.  
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego Padres fired Alvin Dark and hired Roger Craig on  
March 21, 1978. Dark had managed the Padres for the final 114 games 
the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Cavaretta was fired by the Chicago Cubs on March 29, 1954.  
He was let go when, with a 5-15 record, he told owner P.K. Wrigley 
he thought the Cubs were doomed to a bad season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were looking for leadership,'' Fregosi said. ``We've got  
18 games. We'll be ready by opening day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 49, was offered a job as a scout, and it was not known  
whether he would take it. He was driving to visit family in Kansas 
and was unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays went 88-74 and finished third in the AL East in  
Johnson's only season as a major league manager. Fregosi also 
interviewed for the spot before Ash picked Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Fregosi, 56, managed the Philadelphia Phillies when they lost  
the 1993 World Series to Toronto. Fired after the 1996 season, he 
was with the San Francisco Giants as a special assistant to the 
general manager when Ash sought permission Friday to talk to him. 
</P>
<P>
	They reached agreement Sunday and Fregosi signed a two-year  
deal. He had an 861-937 record while managing Philadelphia, the 
Chicago White Sox and California Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have always wanted to manage,'' Fregosi said. ``I missed the  
action, I missed the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his first exhibition game for Toronto on Wednesday, he faced  
the Phillies and shook hands with manager Terry Francona, who 
replaced Fregosi in 1996. The Blue Jays stole a run with a double 
steal in the first inning, then Fregosi came on the field to argue 
a ground-rule double call in the fifth of a 10-6 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was exciting,'' Fregosi said. ``It was fun to be back a  
part of the action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson almost didn't make it to spring training.  
</P>
<P>
	Last November, he was given the choice of being dismissed,  
resigning to become a coach or apologizing. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson made a public apology, then came to camp and apologized  
to his players. He also cleared up another lie -- his official Blue 
Jays bio said he was a high school All-American basketball player 
who turned down a chance to play for UCLA, but none of it was true. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe people deserve second chances, and I think Tim  
deserved that,'' Ash said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ash said the move to change managers began last week when he met  
with the Toronto's owners and ``expressed some concern about our 
ability to move forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays stumbled at the start of last year before  
finishing strong. Still, Johnson's lies about his service in the 
U.S. Marines became the story of their season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, that had something to do with it,'' infielder Tony  
Fernandez said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a key series last season at Boston, Johnson said he  
planned to pitch Roger Clemens instead of Pat Hentgen in the final 
game. When Hentgen complained, Johnson sharply told the pitcher he 
didn't know anything about tough spots, adding ``pressure is 
Vietnam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hentgen, one of Johnson's critics, had little to say after the  
firing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a front-office decision and Gord Ash made it,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 06:24:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Criticizes US for Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China today criticized a U.S. missile-defense  
bill that was passed with overwhelming support by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said the missile defense  
programs the United States is considering are counterproductive for 
arms control and disarmament and will ``have an impact on global 
strategic balance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``China expresses its grave concern,'' Sun said.  
</P>
<P>
	The bill, passed by the Senate 97-3 on Wednesday, would commit  
the United States to building a national defense against limited 
ballistic missile attack ``as soon as technologically possible.'' A 
version of the bill was scheduled to be taken up today by the House 
of Representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The national missile defense program supported by the Senate  
would use similar technology to a theater missile defense system 
that the United States and Japan are studying for East Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	China fears the system could spark a costly arms race, would  
strengthen U.S. military alliances with Japan and South Korea and 
may be used to protect Taiwan, thereby obstructing reunification. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past month, senior Chinese leaders have spoken out  
against the proposed regional anti-missile system. On Monday, 
Premier Zhu Rongji said China was firmly opposed to it. 
</P>
<P>
	China views the island of Taiwan as part of its territory and  
considers reunification a strategic goal. Taiwan and the mainland 
have been ruled separately since the end of the Chinese civil war 
in 1949. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:24:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Court Clears Way for Probe for Starr  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court cleared the way today  
for the Justice Department to investigate the official conduct of 
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. The special court that names 
independent counsels dismissed a challenge by Landmark Legal 
Foundation, a conservative group that sought an order to block the 
Justice Department investigation. The court said it had limited 
jurisdiction and could not go beyond the powers set out in the 
Ethics In Government Act. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians Sign Peace Deal  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The ethnic Albanian delegation at the Kosovo peace  
talks unilaterally signed a U.S.-sponsored peace accord today, but 
the Serbs still refused to sign the deal, and the peace talks 
appeared headed toward collapse. The Albanian delegation said it 
was leaving after the signing, with some members going to 
Washington and others returning to Kosovo, where Yugoslav forces 
were reported to be massing and NATO has threatened airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	Tire Marks Key to Train Probe  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- Federal authorities are analyzing two  
tire tracks in the mud at the crossing where an Amtrak train 
slammed into a semitrailer loaded with steel bars Monday night. 
John Goglia, a member of the National Transportation Safety Board, 
said the marks ``would indicate that somebody tried to go around 
the gates.'' Last night investigators re-enacted the accident, 
which killed at least 11 people and injured more than 100. 

</P>
<P>
	House Considers Own Pay Raise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top House leaders are weighing a plan to give  
legislators a cost of living increase, an increase that could add 
about $5,000 to an annual salary of $136,673. Speaker Dennis 
Hastert, R-Ill., raised the issue at a meeting earlier this year 
with Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, according to aides to the 
two men. Under a 1989 law, lawmakers are entitled to a cost of 
living increase that is pegged to the pay raise the president 
proposes each year for federal workers. Members of Congress last 
got an increase two years ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Whitewater Defense Gets Order  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal judge ruled today that  
lawyers for Susan McDougal must first specify what questions they 
want to ask of Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr's top deputy 
before he takes the witness stand. Acting on a request from Starr's 
office, U.S. District Judge George Howard ordered Mrs. McDougal's 
lawyers to provide a better summary of their questions for Deputy 
Independent Counsel Hickman Ewing and told the two sides to try to 
reach an agreement on Ewing's testimony. Court papers filed earlier 
by Starr's office suggested the defense lawyers' summary might be 
used to fight an appearance by Ewing or to try to block some 
questions. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Unveils New Internet Explorer  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is releasing a new Internet  
Explorer today that offers a number of minor improvements that 
range from faster viewing of Web pages to a reduced tendency to 
``crash'' when retrieving Internet information. A Microsoft 
official rejected observations by some that the new software is 
less closely integrated with Windows. The government, in an ongoing 
suit, accuses Microsoft of using its dominance of the personal 
computer market illegally to force consumers who use Windows also 
to use its browser. 

</P>
<P>
	Trade Deficit Surges to Record High  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. trade deficit soared to an all-time  
high of $17 billion in January as global financial troubles pushed 
U.S. exports down further while imports of autos, consumer goods 
and food were climbing to record highs. The Commerce Department 
reported that the trade deficit shot up 21 percent from December's 
$14.1 billion level and surpassed the old monthly record of $16.7 
billion set last August. In other reports, the government announced 
that new claims for unemployment insurance were up 6,000 to 298,000 
last week, and that consumer prices rose just 0.1 percent in 
February. 

</P>
<P>
	Balloonists Cross Dominican Rep.  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A pair of Swiss-English adventurers  
today soared over the Dominican Republic in a final push to become 
the first balloonists to circle the globe nonstop. The team has 
flown further than any balloonist before, traveling more than 
21,625 miles after leaving the Swiss Alps on March 1. The 
balloonists raced across the Pacific in six days and scooted over 
Mexico yesterday, with winds pushing them to speeds of 115 mph. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 31  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones  
industrials were up 31.08 at 9,910.49. New York Stock Exchange 
advancers led decliners 1,429-1,325. The Nasdaq Composite Index was 
up 16.72 at 2,445.69. 

</P>
<P>
	Joe Torre Undergoes Prostate Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- New York Yankees manager Joe Torre is  
recovering from what doctors call a successful removal of his 
cancerous prostate gland earlier today. The operation was performed 
at Barnes-Jewish hospital by Dr. William Catalona. Doctors say the 
58-year-old Torre is expected to be hospitalized for three or four 
days. Torre disclosed the illness last week and has taken leave 
from the team for the surgery and an undisclosed period of 
recovery. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
