<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency Defends Business Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Development Program responded  
Thursday to criticism of a new economic partnership with 
corporations, saying any joint program will meet U.N. standards on 
labor, human rights and the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	UNDP chief James Gustav Speth also accused a human rights  
organization, Transnational Resource and Action Center, of having 
misled the media by suggesting the new program was being kept 
secret because some of the corporations had been accused of human 
rights or environmental abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations has been very open about the plans for the  
partnership, even holding a workshop on it in South Africa, but 
hasn't widely publicized it because the initiative was still in the 
works, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is indeed much information that you do not have, and it  
would have been far preferable to do us the courtesy of seeking out 
accurate information, and all of it, and engaging in a dialogue 
with us on your concerns,'' Speth wrote the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	An internal U.N. document leaked by TRAC to the media last week  
detailed a new Third World economic development effort in which 
multinational companies contribute $50,000 for new U.N. development 
projects. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, the United Nations is considering creating a logo  
incorporating its name that corporate sponsors could use. TRAC 
claims the partnership, and the logo, will allow companies an easy 
opportunity to use the highly valuable U.N. name to help build new 
businesses and improve their reputations. 
</P>
<P>
	Speth acknowledged that some of the corporations involved had  
been accused of rights abuses, but said the United Nations wasn't 
in a position to certify the companies' compliance with 
international rights standards. 
</P>
<P>
	He stressed, however, that any cooperation between corporations  
and the United Nations ``will have to meet United Nations standards 
in human rights, environmental sustainability and labor rights.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
