<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Warns About Unsafe Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Water is becoming the ``climate change''  
issue of the next quarter century, when the number of people 
without access to clean, safe water is expected to jump by about a 
billion people, a top U.N. official says. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of ``water wars'' between countries vying for  
dwindling water supplies will only increase as the world's 
population grows and governments squander opportunities to manage 
the finite amount of freshwater that exists, Klaus Topfer, the head 
of the U.N. Environment Program, said in an interview Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 47 percent of the world's land area, excluding  
Antarctica, falls within international water basins shared by two 
or more countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations is trying to drive home the threat of future  
conflicts over water -- and the humanitarian consequences of unsafe 
water -- ahead of the World Day for Water, which will be marked 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's focus is to draw attention to the impact of the  
world's water shortage on regions where the water supply is 
adequate, primarily the developed world. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people are convinced water is a regional topic,'' Topfer  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.N. analysis, sponsored by Topfer's agency and the U.N.  
University, found that clean, safe water can be brought to the 1.4 
billion people around the world without it for as little as $50 per 
person in rural areas and $105 per person in urban areas. 
</P>
<P>
	That can prevent many of the 3 billion cases of illness and 5  
million deaths caused each year by unsafe water, U.N. experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, a child dies every eight seconds from a water-related  
disease and 20 percent of freshwater fish species are near 
extinction because of contaminated water, U.N. figures show. 
</P>
<P>
	The study warned that the number of people without access to  
safe water would jump from 1.4 billion today to 2.3 billion by 
2025, with the number of those who die from contaminated water 
expected to jump sharply as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
