<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasure Hunters Win Fortune </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A band of treasure hunters who found the  
wreck of the ill-fated Brother Jonathan -- California's deadliest 
shipwreck -- have come out the big winners in a fight over a fortune 
in lost gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Deep Sea Research Inc. of El Cajon will get to keep more than  
1,000 coins it recovered from the sunken hulk. The ship went down 
in 1865, taking scores of sailors, miners, prostitutes and 
politicians to the bottom about four miles off Crescent City. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's settlement in U.S. District Court in San Francisco  
upheld an agreement between DSR and the state which will allow the 
company to continue retrieving objects and keep 80 percent of what 
it finds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The settlement brought to a close 5 1/2 years in court,'' said  
David Flohr, one of DSR's founders. ``We're very pleased and 
gratified, after this long and very expensive struggle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DSR expects to make $5 million to $10 million when the coins --  
$5, $10 and $20 gold pieces -- are auctioned in Los Angeles May 
29-31. Part of the payoff will go to about 100 small investors who 
bankrolled the project. 
</P>
<P>
	DSR divers will be back on the wreck later this year and again  
next summer. Among the items they will be seeking are a safe which 
may contain $200,000 in greenbacks from an army payroll, a circus 
payroll and more gold in coins and bullion. 
</P>
<P>
	It sounds like a lot of money, but the hunt for the Brother  
Jonathan and the salvage operation is a complex and costly project. 
More than $1 million was spent finding and retrieving the booty. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvey Harrington, DSR's vice president and director of offshore  
operations, visited the wreck in a small submarine. The picture he 
recalls is far from glamorous. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no panoramic view,'' he said. ``In most cases, ships like  
this have deteriorated to the waterline or are covered over. It's 
murky and muddy. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's still quite a sight.''  
</P>
<P>
	In July 1865, the Brother Jonathan, a three-masted, side-wheel  
steamer was heading north along the California coast when it 
encountered stormy weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Pushed out of control, it slammed into a hidden rock, now called  
Jonathan Rock. The rock ripped a gaping hole in the hull, and 
terrified passengers had just 45 minutes to save themselves before 
the ship vanished in 250 feet of water. 
</P>
<P>
	One lifeboat, with 21 people aboard, made it to shore.  
Researchers think some 200 others perished. Among the victims was 
James Nesbit, editor of the San Francisco Bulletin, whose hastily 
scribbled will and notes to loved ones washed ashore wrapped in 
oilskin. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Lands Commission gets 20 percent of whatever DSR finds  
and will have an expert on board the salvage ship to supervise the 
recovery of historic items. The 200 coins already due to the state, 
worth $1 million, will be distributed to museums in Crescent City 
and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	DSR has already bought title to the ship and its contents from  
insurance companies that paid claims. Descendants of the wreck's 
victims who can prove a relationship to an item will be able to 
keep it, minus recovery costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement brings to an end more than a quarter century of  
research and legal squabbling. The case went to the Supreme Court, 
where a year ago the state, with 17 states supporting it, argued -- 
unsuccessfully -- that they should control whatever came off the 
ship. The court ruled that salvage cases must be considered on a 
case-by-case basis in lower courts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
