<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Remain in Limbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Joe Gibbs can concentrate solely on NASCAR  
for another couple of weeks. Vinny Cerrato has to keep cooling his 
heels in his hotel room a few miles from Redskin Park, where 
current management won't let him have an office. 
</P>
<P>
	With the sale of the Washington Redskins postponed again, the  
people who plan to be a part of the new regime remain in limbo -- as 
do the people who still run the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think all of us thought it would get voted upon this week,''  
general manager Charley Casserly said Thursday. ``It didn't, so we 
just keep going. That's all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casserly represented the Redskins at the NFL meetings in  
Phoenix, where the team's prospective new owners, Howard and Edward 
Milstein and Dan Snyder, had to ask for a postponement on a vote to 
approve their $800 bid because they realized it wouldn't pass. The 
NFL said Thursday the owners will reconvene and vote on the matter 
at a special meeting April 7 in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Howard Milstein will travel around the country  
for some one-on-one lobbying to get the four or five votes it's 
believed he needs to reach the necessary three-fourths majority of 
24. It's thought that a hard-core group of four owners -- Denver's 
Pat Bowlen, New Orleans' Tom Benson, Pittsburgh's Dan Rooney and 
Cleveland's Al Lerner -- are firmly opposed and cannot be won over, 
while others are more flexible. 
</P>
<P>
	The reasons for opposition to the Milstein-Snyder bid vary, but  
they all concern the Milstein part of the bid, which was originally 
to be financed with an unsecured loan. The Milsteins have adjusted 
their financing several times over the past few weeks, and they 
will use the extra time to put together a proposal that satisfies 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, some owners, wary of Howard Milstein's contentious  
reign as part-owner of the New York Islanders, worry that he may 
become an Al Davis-like maverick owner in the NFL. Several owners 
even suggested Wednesday that Snyder should be the majority owner 
of the Redskins' group because he has the ready cash in the bank, a 
proposal Milstein isn't ready to consider. 
</P>
<P>
	But where does this leave the team? Free agents have been  
skittish about signing with the Redskins because of the 
uncertainty. Casserly and coach Norv Turner are preparing for the 
April 17-18 draft, even though there's no guarantee they'll still 
have jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's killing us,'' guard Tre Johnson told The Washington Post  
even as the owners were meeting. ``This is my sixth year (with the 
Redskins) and it looks like it's going to be the worst one. ... A 
lot of guys have to be skeptical -- like free agents. They've got be 
wary of coming here. They don't know who they're going to play 
for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Milsteins and Snyder have been preparing for the changeover  
as best they can. Cerrato, the former director of player personnel 
with the San Francisco 49ers, has been hired as a consultant. The 
Redskins said there wasn't room for him to have office space at 
Redskin Park, so he's working out of a hotel, keeping tabs on 
players throughout the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibbs, who coached the Redskins to three Super Bowl titles  
before resigning after the 1992 season, would serve as an adviser 
to the new owners while continuing to run his NASCAR team in 
Charlotte, N.C. Milstein and Snyder plan to have their first 
face-to-face meetings with Turner and Casserly -- if the sale is 
approved -- before any decision is announced concerning the coach or 
general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the repeated delays were starting to wear on him,  
Casserly said: ``It's like a football game. You lose yardage on 
first down, you still got to play second down. We'll keep doing 
what we're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Redskins signed two players Thursday. Unrestricted free  
agent tackle Jamie Brown, who has played for Denver and San 
Francisco over four NFL seasons, signed a one-year, $500,000 
contract. Exclusive rights free agent guard Lamont Burns, a late 
addition last season, signed for one year at $325,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
