<DOCNO> APW19990318.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 06:15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tandy Settles Hearing Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Radio Shack's parent company has settled a  
lawsuit brought by a hearing-impaired man who was assaulted by a 
store clerk because he couldn't understand what the clerk said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tandy Corp. said Wednesday it also has agreed to launch a  
nationwide program to teach its employees how to better serve the 
needs of hearing-impaired customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Gannon, 39, said he was attacked at a Radio Shack in  
suburban Virginia in August 1995 during a misunderstanding 
aggravated by his lack of hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannon said the clerk ringing up the sale questioned his  
signature on his credit card receipt, but Gannon couldn't read the 
clerk's lips because the clerk wasn't facing him. 
</P>
<P>
	After Gannon impatiently snatched his receipt back, the clerk  
came around the counter, punched Gannon in the face and tackled him 
onto a glass display case. Gannon was cut and bruised. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio Shack fired the clerk, Donald M. Boseman, who was later  
convicted of assault, sentenced to 10 days in jail and fined 
$1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannon said he went to court after Tandy refused to apologize or  
help with his $10,000 medical bills. He also launched a picketing 
campaign outside area Radio Shack stores urging customers to 
boycott the electronics chain. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side would disclose the amount of the settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	Tandy officials said the Fort Worth, Texas-based company  
``regrets the experience of Mr. Gannon.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
