<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation All but Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inflation all but disappeared -- again -- in  
February, allowing increased wages to flow directly into more 
purchasing power for American workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Price Index edged 0.1 percent higher last month,  
for the third consecutive month, despite a few scattered trouble 
spots such as meat, oranges, school books and airline fares, the 
Labor Department said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	World economic weakness continued to deliver dividends to U.S.  
buyers, with prices falling for clothing, cars and computers, 
reflecting the influence of imports manufactured in countries with 
devalued currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the department said average weekly earnings for  
American workers, adjusted for inflation, jumped 0.7 percent in 
February, the biggest increase in 18 months. During the past year, 
they have risen 3.6 percent to $452.49, before inflation, and 1.9 
percent after inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Increased imports have had a positive effect on the economy by  
keeping prices down, and real consumer purchasing power up,'' said 
economist Dave Huether of the National Association of 
Manufacturers. ``There is no inflation-creep in sight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The seasonally adjusted inflation rate for the first two months  
of the year was just 1.1 percent, compared with a 12-year low of 
1.6 percent for all of 1998. That means Federal Reserve 
policy-makers meeting March 30 probably will feel comfortable 
leaving short-term interest rates unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``Low inflation will keep the Fed on hold throughout 1999,''  
said economist Stan Shipley of Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy costs were unchanged last month, with declines for fuel  
oil and gasoline offsetting increases for electricity and natural 
gas. Energy is down 5.7 percent from a year ago, but analysts 
warned recent big increases for crude oil mean prices at the pump 
will head higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll probably see a 3 percent to 4 percent increase in  
gasoline prices. ... It will be noticed but it won't be huge,'' 
said economist Donald Ratajczak of Georgia State University. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices, meanwhile, rose only 0.1 percent after a  
substantial 0.5 percent increase in January. Fruit costs went up, 
pushed by a 5.3 percent increase for oranges on top of a 24.1 
percent gain the previous month, reflecting a December freeze in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef rose 1.3 percent, the most in six years, and pork, 1.4  
percent. Still, pork remained 5.3 percent cheaper than a year ago 
and vegetable costs fell 3.4 percent, pulled down by a 20 percent 
drop for tomatoes, the most in almost three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices excluding the volatile food and energy components edged  
up 0.1 percent in February. Airline fares jumped 2.4 percent. 
Hospital services and textbooks rose, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Further airfare increases probably will appear in the March  
price index, due out next month. Over the weekend, the airline 
industry raised business fares about 1 percent and leisure fares by 
about 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	However, clothing costs fell 0.2 percent in February, and new  
cars and trucks, 0.3 percent. Computer prices declined 2.8 percent 
and were 34.6 percent lower than a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, tobacco costs declined 1.4 percent but were still 33.5  
percent higher than a year earlier, reflecting tobacco companies' 
efforts to recoup the cost of multimillion-dollar liability 
settlements. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 23:24:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle Says China Is World Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Vice President Dan Quayle, making his  
first major foreign policy speech as a potential presidential 
candidate in 2000, suggested the Bush administration may have been 
too easy on China. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying it was time to ``speak some truths,'' Quayle said former  
President Bush and he believed encouraging trade ``with a minimum 
of sanctions and sanctimony'' would move China toward allowing more 
freedoms for its people while improving U.S.-China ties. 
</P>
<P>
	But the strategy didn't work and things have worsened under an  
even friendlier Clinton administration, Quayle said, according to a 
draft copy of a speech he was delivering today in Los Angeles to 
the World Affairs Council. The Associated Press obtained an advance 
copy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was a worthy objective, but upon reflection it is  
clear to me that the Chinese took advantage of that opportunity,'' 
Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said the Bush administration was ``firm when we had to  
be,'' however, imposing stiff economic sanctions against China 
after the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre of pro-democracy 
demonstrators by Chinese military troops. Some sanctions remain in 
effect. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush administration also used an annual international human  
rights convention in Geneva to condemn China -- something President 
Clinton refused to do last year for the first time since Tiananmen, 
Quayle said in a broad attack of the administration's China policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle criticized Clinton for removing the link between human  
rights and U.S. trade policy in 1994, saying the administration 
went further than Bush in promoting trade. Still, Bush granted 
China most-favored nation status to China every year, as has 
Clinton, allowing normal trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``President Clinton has consistently supported granting China  
most-favored nation status, no matter how egregious the human 
rights abuses documented by his own State Department,'' Quayle 
charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle also slammed Vice President Al Gore, the likely 2000  
Democratic candidate, for blaming past Republican administrations 
for lax security at federal weapons labs that may have allowed 
China to steal nuclear secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	``How dare Al Gore blame Presidents Reagan and Bush for  
negligence that clearly happened on his and President Clinton's 
watch,'' Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI and CIA since 1995 have been investigating possible  
espionage at the Los Alamos National Laboratories in the 1980s that 
may have helped modernize Chinese nuclear warheads. The Clinton 
administration has been accused of dragging its feet in responding 
to the allegations as U.S. officials just this week announced 
tighter lab security. Clinton on Thursday ordered an analysis of 
the security threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle, who has visited China three times since leaving office  
and has met Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Prime Minister Zhu 
Rongji, said he doesn't perceive China as a U.S. enemy and he 
believes that working with Beijing will promote development of a 
``free and prosperous China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the fall of the Soviet Union and the growing U.S.  
military technological advantage over other countries, among other 
events, have caused China to see the United States as a potential 
enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to recognize the emergence of a new China,'' Quayle  
said. ``China is much different than it was 10 or even five years 
ago. The new China is increasingly assertive and aggressive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said the Clinton administration should move cautiously on  
making a deal with China to join the World Trade Organization, 
which would require Beijing to lower more tariffs on goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, he said Taiwan, which China considers a renegade  
province, is ready to join the WTO now, although the Clinton 
administration doesn't want to anger by Beijing by making a deal 
with Taipei first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 10:24:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Via Dolorosa' Is Masterful Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Most playwrights reveal themselves through their  
work. David Hare is no exception. 
</P>
<P>
	But the British writer, author of ``Plenty,'' ``Racing Demon,''  
``Skylight'' and other works, has done one better. He has put 
himself on stage in ``Via Dolorosa,'' a masterful meditative 
monologue on his 1997 visit to Israel and the Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a fascinating journey, not only for what it reveals about  
Hare, but for what it says about a situation that has defied 
solutions for thousands of years. 
</P>
<P>
	At Broadway's Booth Theater, Hare paints his picture from scores  
of interviews with Jews and Palestinians alike. It is a fragmented, 
often surreal portrait, made up of contradicting ideas hurled at 
him with a ferocity that could make one despair for any resolution 
of the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	The 51-year-old Hare, a gangly gentleman casually dressed in a  
white shirt and charcoal gray slacks, is no actor. ``I've always 
tried to get Judi Dench to do this sort of thing,'' he says of the 
profession he abandoned at age 15 after a school production of ``A 
Man for All Seasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet his slow, almost stiff delivery contributes to the  
effectiveness of the evening. His speech is deliberate, carefully 
measured as he moves across the nearly barren stage of the Booth, 
which is filled only with a wooden playing area, two desks and two 
chairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The author reveals that he finally has discovered the subject of  
his many plays (there are more than a score). Faith, the need for 
belief, dominates most of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Israel is, first and foremost, a cause ... the cause being a  
patch of land ... lying like a small brown anchovy set down on a 
school atlas,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause has created intractable conflict, battles that are  
championed by an astonishing parade of characters in ``Via 
Dolorosa.'' The author re-creates some vivid interviews in his 
90-minute lecture. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare starts in Israel, visiting settlers in Hebron, a Jewish  
settlement surrounded by Arabs. He stays with Danny and Sarah 
Weiss, American Jews who came to Israel to reconnect with their 
spiritual values. As for their living on disputed land, Danny 
contends Israel must have roots. ``It has to be the place where 
life goes right down deep into the soil,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	That soil is claimed just as defiantly by the Palestinians,  
although there are as many shades of opinion among the Arabs as 
there are in Tel Aviv. 
</P>
<P>
	Haider Abdel Shafi, the most popular politician in Gaza,  
declares, ``Our most urgent task is to reform ourselves.'' Shafi 
laments the lack of principles in his society and criticizes Yasser 
Arafat for being ``a man who buys peoples' allegiance,'' creating a 
corrupt society. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone has an opinion, including Hare who celebrates the  
argumentative environments in which he finds himself. He discovers 
joy in the fact that people stand for something, unlike folks in 
his own country. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare chides British Prime Minister Tony Blair for being ``all  
things to all men'' and thus not letting people know what he really 
stands for. 
</P>
<P>
	The title of the evening comes from Hare's need to walk the Via  
Dolorosa in Jerusalem, ``to follow the Stations of the Cross, which 
represent the steps on Christ's journey to his death.'' The 
playwright is bewildered by the narrow unimpressive walkway, its 
postcard shops and the hordes of ``American evangelicals dressed in 
shell suits and baseball caps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wants more, but gradually realizes it is not the stones that  
are important but the ideas they represent that matter, ideas that 
have led to the life-and-death struggle in the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	Hare has become something of a growth industry on Broadway. Last  
year, New York saw ``The Judas Kiss,'' the author's drama about 
Oscar Wilde starring Liam Neeson. Earlier this season, Nicole 
Kidman, riding waves of publicity, sold out in ``The Blue Room.'' 
Next month could be the best of all, Dench, returning to Broadway 
after more than 30 years, in ``Amy's View.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But for now, we have the playwright in the flesh, courtesy of  
Lincoln Center Theater. ``Via Dolorosa'' makes a plea for 
understanding or, at the least, attempting to understand. It is a 
lively, literate evening that like the rest of Hare's plays, 
celebrates belief, even if no agreement is in sight on what belief 
is the one true faith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
