<HEADLINE> Sabres Need Hasek for Playoff Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres avoided losing much  
ground without Dominik Hasek. Now they're looking forward to going 
places with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek is close to returning from a strained groin that has  
sidelined him since Feb. 17. The goalie has resumed practicing with 
the team and might play Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a good practice,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said  
Wednesday. ``He went a little bit longer today, a few more shots. I 
thought at times he was still a little tentative, but he got 
through it OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff said Hasek might start against the New York Rangers on the  
first stop of the team's four-game road trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today I could go even harder from post to post, more splits,''  
Hasek said. ``I hope it feels the same tomorrow. I'll have one more 
practice and I hope I'll play in New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres did their part to get Hasek in shape when Curtis  
Brown took a blistering slap shot that dented the goalie's face 
mask. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres are loose after wins over Boston and the New York  
Islanders. They are seventh in the Eastern Conference playoff race, 
within two points of sixth-place Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a logjam in the middle of our conference,'' Sabres  
captain Michael Peca said. ``You put some wins together and you're 
going to put yourself in a better position in the playoffs and 
possibly get home-ice advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres are in the thick of the playoff race despite their  
recent struggles. They tumbled from the top of the conference after 
a strong start and looked at last Thursday's loss to Tampa Bay as 
their season low. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe for awhile there we weren't doing the small things, and  
sometimes it's tough to even notice what those are,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as teams make a playoff push, Tuesday's trade deadline has  
players around the league a little edgy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a nervous time,'' Ruff said. ``Any time there's a  
possibility that players might get moved, there's some anxiety 
around the team. There's nothing you can do about it. You worry 
about how you play and your effort on the ice, and that's all you 
can control really.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The arrival of Stu Barnes, sent from Pittsburgh in a recent  
trade for Matthew Barnaby, has provided a lift. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gets a lot of chances and he creates a lot of chances for  
guys around him, so he's a welcome addition to this team,'' said 
Barnes' linemate Geoff Sanderson, who is trying to break out of a 
scoring slump. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting the chance play a lot, which is something that I  
wasn't getting in Pittsburgh this year,'' Barnes said. ``I'm 
playing center now, which is a little bit different, too, because 
I'm handling the puck a little more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The return of Hasek would be another boost, even though Dwayne  
Roloson and rookie Martin Biron have played well. ``No disrespect 
to Dwayne or Marty, but when you're adding the best goaltender that 
possibly ever played the game, you've got to feel better about your 
chances,'' Peca said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
