<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Seeks To Restructure FCC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Long-distance companies would have to post  
information about current rates on the Internet under a plan 
federal regulators are considering. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint say they already voluntarily  
provide information about rates on their corporate Web sites. But 
the FCC plan, expected to be adopted today, would force the 
companies to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies would have to provide information on domestic  
rates -- including the terms and conditions of service -- in a 
``timely manner and updated regularly,'' said FCC officials, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	If rates or services are changed, that would have to be posted,  
too. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond that, the FCC would not specify when information must be  
posted, how often it must be updated or where it would appear on 
the companies' corporate Web sites, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's requirement would cover a wide range of services, from  
domestic long-distance calls to calling card calls to directory 
assistance. It would not include information on international 
calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's expected requirement goes hand-in-hand with a 1996  
order, which never took effect, intended to free long-distance 
companies from having to file federal tariffs outlining their rates 
or service changes to the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, long-distance companies continue to file that  
information to the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's expected action today would not affect that 1996  
order, which is being challenged by MCI WorldCom and others at a 
federal court here. But the public disclosure requirement would not 
take effect until the court resolves the larger matter involving 
federal tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Consumers Union's Washington  
office, said the public disclosure requirement would help make 
consumers more aware of rate changes. But he noted it would not 
help those who do not own computers. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, the FCC also was expected to require long-distance  
companies to post current rate information in some of their 
offices, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T said they are not opposed to the public  
disclosure, but repeated their opposition to getting rid of federal 
tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the century-old doctrine, long-distance companies may  
charge only the rates for services they have filed with the FCC. 
The tariff trumps all other agreements with customers, verbal or 
otherwise. Some critics contend the arrangement lets companies slip 
rate changes by customers. 
</P>
<P>
	But MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T contend that in the absence of  
tariffs, companies would have to enter into some other contract 
with customers each time rates or service were changed. 
</P>
<P>
	That would make it harder for them to offer new discount plans  
or promotions featuring free or cheap calls, they note. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kimmelman and other critics said that consumers would be  
better served by posting rate information online than by putting it 
in tariffs, which the average long-distance customer does not see. 
</P>
<P>
	Assuming the court upholds the FCC on its decision to eliminate  
tariffs, officials contemplate that long-distance companies 
voluntarily would move toward a more ``contractual relationship'' 
with customers -- along the lines of credit card companies who 
provide notice in the mail when terms change. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the FCC was expected:  
</P>
<P>
	-- To tighten rules making it easier for companies to install  
equipment at major local phone companies' central offices to 
provide high-speed Internet and data services. The ruling would 
help companies including Covad Communications and NorthPoint 
Communications, which provide connections letting businesses access 
information from computers at speeds considerably faster than 
regular phone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Earmark a portion of the airwaves for satellite delivery of  
telephone and data services. Nine companies, including Iridium, 
Globalstar and Boeing are interested. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990318.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 08:15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Team Eyes Starr Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Attempting to put Kenneth Starr's  
tactics on trial, lawyers for Susan McDougal plan to call the 
Whitewater prosecutor's top deputy to the witness stand. Starr's 
office demanded today that the defense first spell out in detail 
what questions will be asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office made the demand in a letter after Starr deputy  
Hickman Ewing was subpoenaed in the courtroom where Mrs. McDougal 
is on try for criminal contempt and obstruction of justice. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter to Mrs. McDougal's lawyer, Mark Geragos, said federal  
regulations require that when a U.S. attorney is called to testify, 
the defense must disclose ahead of time what information is being 
sought. Geragos showed the letter to reporters today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We already told them what we wanted to talk to Ewing about,''  
Geragos said. ``Now they want more detail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge George Howard will have to decide what level  
of specificity Geragos must provide to the court before 
questioning. The judge could decide not to allow some questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony from defense witnesses was expected to start today,  
beginning with Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing watched from the rear of the courtroom Wednesday as the  
prosecution closed its case by summoning three former members of 
the Whitewater grand jury before whom Mrs. McDougal had refused to 
testify. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the day, Bill Henley, Mrs. McDougal's brother,  
reached through a crowd of reporters and handed Ewing a subpoena, 
saying, ``Hick, I've got something for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt really good,'' Bill Henley said a few moments later.  
``It's about time we got to ask them a few questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said later he didn't think prosecutors would try to block  
his appearance at the behest of the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have nothing to hide,'' Ewing said.  
</P>
<P>
	But he hinted at a possible legal dispute ahead over how far  
afield Mrs. McDougal's lawyers should be allowed to range in 
questioning the Whitewater prosecutor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos would not rule out summoning Starr as well. ``First let  
me deal with Hick Ewing,'' he said. ``One at a time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Making a prosecutor a defense witness was the second unusual  
turn of the day. The first was putting on the witness stand three 
members of the grand jury that indicted Mrs. McDougal after she 
refused to answer their questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing said that in 25 years as a federal prosecutor he had never  
seen grand jurors testify at a criminal trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand jury foreman John Washam testified that the death of Mrs.  
McDougal's former husband, James McDougal, in 1998 made her 
testimony even more crucial than it had been before. 
</P>
<P>
	With James McDougal's death, ``one link of the chain was gone''  
of people who knew what went on in Whitewater, said Washam. 
McDougal had been Starr's chief cooperating witness in his 
investigation of the Whitewater land deal in which the Clintons and 
McDougals were partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Geragos focused on the fact that Starr's office didn't tell  
grand jurors James McDougal had changed his story a number of 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wouldn't you have wanted to hear that?'' Geragos asked grand  
juror Marsha High. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' she responded.  
</P>
<P>
	Geragos argues that his client didn't want to answer questions  
because overzealous prosecutors were trying to force her to give 
false testimony against the president and first lady Hillary Rodham 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Grand juror Jennifer Castleberry said she believed prosecutors  
were simply trying to gather the facts, not go after the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say they wanted to ask Mrs. McDougal about her  
Whitewater business partnership with the Clintons, including a 
$27,600 loan for the land development taken out in Bill Clinton's 
name from the savings and loan owned at the time by the McDougals. 
The president has testified he never borrowed money from the S&AMP;L. 
</P>
</TEXT>
