<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Saves Ind. Counsel Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate on Thursday killed a Democratic  
effort to cut off funding for most independent counsels by year's 
end, sparing Kenneth Starr's investigation of President Clinton for 
the time being. 
</P>
<P>
	The authors of the amendment, which lost on a voice vote, made  
their aims clear. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a mistake to let the Starr investigation continue  
indefinitely, without any ending date,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, 
D-Iowa. ``Mr. Starr has had long enough to investigate Whitewater 
and Monica Lewinsky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Watergate-inspired independent counsel law is set to expire  
June 30 unless Congress renews it. But with three months left and 
no consensus for how to fix the law, there is little sentiment for 
saving it, especially after investigations of Republican and 
Democratic presidents have irritated lawmakers from both parties. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic proposal, which supporters tried to add to a  
spending bill, would have cut off federal money for Starr's 
investigation of Clinton and for four other independent counsels on 
Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The matters under investigation would have reverted to the  
Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Letting the law lapse would allow the ongoing investigations to  
continue to their conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	With no Republican co-sponsors, the measure had little chance of  
passing. Senate Governmental Affairs Chairman Fred Thompson, 
R-Tenn., called the amendment ``a very very bad idea,'' and pointed 
out that even Attorney General Janet Reno opposed the Democratic 
proposal a day earlier. The attorney general, he said, can 
terminate investigations without direction from Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress should not be interjecting itself to terminate  
investigations in midstream when there is already a mechanism,'' to 
do that if warranted, Thompson told the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to the amendment crossed party lines. Sen. Joe  
Lieberman, the ranking Democrat on Thompson's committee, said the 
measure would set a bad precedent for congressional interference. 
</P>
<P>
	``This amendment is not just a preemptive attack on the  
statute...it's what might be called a personal attack on the most 
controversial independent counsels,'' said Lieberman, D-Conn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
