<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Smog May Damage Kids' Lungs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Children who grow up breathing dirty air may  
suffer lung damage into adulthood, according to early results of a 
long-term study of the effects of Southern California smog. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at the University of Southern California also found  
that girls may be at a higher risk than boys of suffering the ill 
effects from air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary results of the 10-year study were published  
today in the American Journal of Respiratory and Critical Care 
Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists monitored the air in 12 California communities for  
ozone, nitrogen dioxide, microscopic airborne particles and acid 
vapor. Researchers also monitored the breathing capacity of about 
5,000 children from grades four to 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The children filled out questionnaires about their daily  
activities and surroundings. They also were asked to blow into a 
machine that measured their lung capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	Boys showed a lower breathing capacity if they lived in  
communities with high ozone levels and spent a lot of time 
outdoors, said research leader John Peters, professor of preventive 
medicine at the USC School of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Girls who spent more time outdoors showed an even higher  
percentage of diminished breathing capacity, the study found. 
Nitrogen dioxide and particulate matter appeared to have the most 
effect on girls. 
</P>
<P>
	The scientists aren't sure why girls are more at risk, Peters  
said, especially since most indicated they spent less time outdoors 
than boys, and thus presumably had less exposure to smog. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were taken from the first year of the $15 million  
study, 1993-94. Researchers will continue tracking the children 
through high school, and more comprehensive results were expected 
in 2003, Peters said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
