<HEADLINE> Cities Celebrate St. Patrick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Led by actress Maureen O'Hara, the 238th annual  
St. Patrick's Day Parade filled Fifth Avenue with some 200,000 
marchers Wednesday as people here and across the country saluted 
Irish heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Irish-born Ms. O'Hara, the parade's grand marshal and star  
of such movies as ``The Quiet Man,'' celebrated the Irish 
connection ``that I feel so strongly in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irish-accented Boston held its St. Patrick's Day Parade on  
Sunday, but Wednesday was another opportunity for celebration as 
government workers got the day off for Evacuation Day, the 
anniversary of the day when the British left Boston Harbor in 1775 
and Loyalists fled the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people filled downtown Kansas City, Mo., for a  
parade that included an Elvis impersonator in a green 
rhinestone-studded suit, a Dixieland Jazz band and an Old West 
stagecoach. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinal Bernard Law, the archbishop of Boston, celebrated a  
noon Mass in honor of St. Patrick, and Guinness flowed freely in 
crowded bars with names like Dooley's Tavern, The Purple Shamrock 
and Tiernan's. 
</P>
<P>
	In Savannah, Ga., a beautiful spring day led to a  
higher-than-average attendance for the city's 175th St. Patrick's 
Day parade that wound for nearly four hours through the city's 
famed squares. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York crowds also enjoyed high temperatures, nearing 60  
degrees at one point, after a chilly weekend filled with rain and 
snow. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's too many firemen here. If you had a fire, there  
wouldn't be anyone to put it out,'' said Tom Walsh, 31, visiting 
along with fellow London bus drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw lots of people with green hair,'' said Susan Kelly, 53,  
of Alexandria, Va., who wore a shamrock scarf, ``and people wearing 
`Kiss me, I'm Irish' shirts who didn't look Irish at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd was mostly peaceful, although police made three  
arrests for unruly behavior. A 20-year-old man was arrested after a 
fight in Central Park in which another man was stabbed in the 
chest. 
</P>
<P>
	The parade also was marked by the annual protest by the Irish  
Lesbian &AMP; Gay Organization, which has repeatedly been barred from 
marching under its own banner by the parade sponsor, the Ancient 
Order of Hibernians. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen members of the gay group were arrested for disorderly  
conduct during a pre-parade demonstration on 42nd Street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
