<DOCNO> APW19990318.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-18 13:23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior PGA Return to Roots  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla. (AP) -- Had there been no money, no  
television cameras, no legacy on the line, the four men involved 
still would have remembered it as a wonderful afternoon -- and 
evening -- of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	As it turned out, the amazing show put on by Tommy Bolt, Roberto  
De Vicenzo, Art Wall and the late Julius Boros 20 years ago in the 
Legends of Golf tournament was not only exciting, it was important. 
</P>
<P>
	Their six-hole playoff, one seen by a good-sized TV audience for  
a few, magical hours on a Sunday evening, stands as the critical 
moment in the formation of the Senior PGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``It had everything to do with the tour starting, in my  
estimation,'' Bolt said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tour, now with 42 tournaments and more than $51 million  
annually in prize money, returns to its roots Friday, with the 
first round in the two-man, best-ball format at the World Golf 
Village Slammer and Squire Course. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending champions are Charles Coody and Dale Douglass, who  
needed a two-hole playoff last year to become rare 60-something 
winners on this increasingly competitive, 50-and-over tour. 
</P>
<P>
	That playoff brought back faint memories of 1979 at Onion Creek  
Country Club, when Bolt, De Vicenzo, Wall and Boros combined for 11 
birdies -- five from De Vicenzo himself -- over a six-hole playoff 
that lasted well into the twilight. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were making birdies,'' Bolt said. ``I holed one, then I'd  
point my finger at Roberto and say, `Top that one.' He'd hole his 
putt on top of it and point his finger back at me. We had a lot of 
fun playing that day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boros and De Vicenzo eventually split the $70,000 first prize,  
but the real reward was the attention the entire foursome drew to 
seniors golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Their playoff ran so long, it preempted the nightly news and the  
beginning of prime time through most markets in the East, something 
rarely heard of even these days for a golf tournament. It drew 
nearly double the TV audience of a normal PGA event and sent the 
message that, yes, these old guys could still put on quite a show. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Raphael, the creator of the Legends of Golf, said he was  
overwhelmed by the reaction when he walked into one of his favorite 
New York restaurants the next afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all people were talking about,'' he said. ``They were  
saying, `Did you see that finish? Did you see them putting and 
playing?' I thought it was going to be the greatest thing to happen 
to these senior players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The timing was perfect. A year later, Arnold Palmer turned 50,  
and the Senior Tour was up and running with two events and a total 
of $250,000 in prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of its best-ball format and the fact that it's an  
unofficial event, the Legends has drifted back somewhat in 
prominence on the increasingly crowded schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's a nice break from the grind, and an opportunity to  
see some players that longtime golf fans may not have seen in 
action in a while. Players like Bob Goalby and Sam Snead will 
compete in the over-70 Demaret Division, a 36-hole competition 
played over the first two days. 
</P>
<P>
	De Vicenzo, Wall and Bolt will all be back to play and celebrate  
the 20th anniversary of the tournament that started it all. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the tour started, I thought maybe they would have 12 to  
15 tournaments at the very most,'' Wall said. ``I had no idea it 
could grow into this. It totally boggles my mind.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
